  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Crush injury: when muscles scream, kidneys weep, and limbs seize.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers highlight two critical complications of severe muscle damage within a fascial compartment: acute renal failure from rhabdomyolysis and contracture from ischemic necrosis. Crushing injuries can lead to compartment syndrome and extensive muscle breakdown, triggering these systemic and local sequelae.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSevere muscle damage, as seen in crushing injuries, releases myoglobin into the bloodstream. This myoglobin is nephrotoxic, precipitating in renal tubules and causing acute tubular necrosis, leading to acute renal failure. Concurrently, increased pressure within a fascial compartment compromises microvascular perfusion, leading to muscle ischemia and necrosis. If untreated, this necrotic muscle is replaced by fibrous tissue, which contracts and shortens, resulting in a fixed deformity known as Volkmann's ischemic contracture.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Loss of peripheral pulses is a very late and ominous sign of compartment syndrome, as arterial pressure often exceeds compartment pressure until severe ischemia. Early signs include pain out of proportion, paresthesia, and pain with passive stretch.\nOption B (Incorrect): Methaemoglobinaemia is a condition where the iron in hemoglobin is oxidized, impairing oxygen transport. Muscle damage causes rhabdomyolysis and myoglobinuria, not methaemoglobinaemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Multiple skin incisions (fasciotomies) are a surgical treatment for compartment syndrome to relieve pressure, not a cause or mediator of the initial muscle damage from a crushing injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Compartment Syndrome | Rhabdomyolysis | Volkmann's Ischemic Contracture |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Increased intracompartmental pressure | Muscle cell lysis, myoglobin release | Untreated compartment syndrome, muscle necrosis |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Pain out of proportion, paresthesia, pain on stretch | Muscle pain, weakness, dark urine | Fixed flexion deformity, claw hand/foot |\n| **Major Complication** | Muscle necrosis, nerve damage, contracture | Acute Kidney Injury (AKI), hyperkalemia, arrhythmia | Permanent functional impairment, limb deformity |\n| **Treatment** | Fasciotomy | IV fluids, urine alkalinization, dialysis | Surgical release, tendon transfers, osteotomies |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Crushing injury = rhabdo + compartment syndrome = AKI + contracture.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, affected muscles appear pale, edematous, and non-contractile. On MRI, T2-weighted images show muscle edema and signal changes consistent with necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends aggressive fluid resuscitation for crush injuries to prevent rhabdomyolysis-induced renal failure and emphasizes early recognition and management of compartment syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | inevitably results in loss of peripheral pulses. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | causes methhaemoglobinaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | can cause acute renal failure. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | leads to contracture. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | is mediated simply by multiple skin incisions. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) can cause acute renal failure.; leads to contracture.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
