  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, O negative saves the day!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Group O RhD -ve. This blood type is considered the universal donor because its red blood cells lack A, B, and RhD antigens, minimizing the risk of an acute hemolytic transfusion reaction when immediate transfusion is required without full cross-matching.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe immunological basis for Group O RhD -ve being the universal donor lies in the absence of major red blood cell surface antigens. Group O red blood cells lack both A and B antigens, preventing recipient anti-A or anti-B antibodies from causing agglutination. Additionally, RhD -ve blood lacks the RhD antigen, which is highly immunogenic. This dual absence of A, B, and RhD antigens makes it the safest option for emergency transfusions, particularly for females of childbearing potential where RhD sensitization must be avoided.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Group O RhD +ve contains the RhD antigen, which can sensitize RhD-negative recipients, especially females of childbearing potential, leading to potential hemolytic disease of the newborn in future pregnancies.\nOption C (Incorrect): Group AB RhD -ve red blood cells express both A and B antigens, making them incompatible with recipients who have anti-A or anti-B antibodies (i.e., anyone who is not AB).\nOption D (Incorrect): Group AB RhD +ve red blood cells express A, B, and RhD antigens, making them incompatible with most recipients due to the presence of anti-A, anti-B, or anti-RhD antibodies.\nOption E (Incorrect): Group B RhD +ve red blood cells express the B antigen, making them incompatible with recipients who have anti-B antibodies (i.e., Group A or Group O individuals).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Blood Type | RBC Antigens | Plasma Antibodies | Emergency RBC Transfusion |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| O RhD -ve | None | Anti-A, Anti-B | Safest Universal Donor |\n| O RhD +ve | RhD | Anti-A, Anti-B | Universal Donor (caution in RhD-ve females) |\n| AB RhD +ve | A, B, RhD | None | Universal Recipient |\n| Any other | Specific A/B/RhD | Specific Anti-A/B/RhD | Requires cross-match |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: O negative blood: the universal donor, always safe in a pinch.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn a massive transfusion protocol, you'd see multiple units of O RhD -ve blood being rapidly infused, often through large bore IVs or central lines, with close monitoring for signs of transfusion reaction or coagulopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAABB (formerly American Association of Blood Banks) Guidelines, Technical Manual, 20th Edition (2020). It recommends O RhD-negative red blood cells for emergency transfusion when the recipient's blood type is unknown, especially for females of childbearing potential.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Group O RhD -ve. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Group O RhD +ve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Group AB RhD -ve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Group AB RhD +ve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Group B RhD +ve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Group O RhD -ve.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
