  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 NGT feeding: a lifeline with a long list of potential pitfalls.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer is ACCEPT because all listed options (pulmonary aspiration, nausea, diarrhoea, disturbed liver function, and hyponatraemia) are well-recognized and common unwanted effects associated with nasogastric tube feeding. NGT feeding, while vital for nutritional support, carries a broad spectrum of potential complications affecting multiple organ systems.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNasogastric tube feeding bypasses normal oral intake and digestion, leading to several physiological disruptions. Pulmonary aspiration can occur due to impaired gag reflex, tube misplacement, or reflux. Nausea and diarrhoea are common gastrointestinal side effects, often related to feed composition, rate, or bacterial contamination. Disturbed liver function, particularly cholestasis or steatosis, can result from altered nutrient metabolism or overfeeding. Hyponatraemia may develop from inappropriate free water administration or syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) in critically ill patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options (A, B, C, D, E) are correct and represent recognized unwanted effects of nasogastric tube feeding. Therefore, there are no incorrect options to address.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Specific Effect | Mechanism/Cause | Management Principle |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pulmonary | Aspiration | Tube misplacement, reflux, impaired gag reflex | Confirm tube position, elevate head of bed, slow infusion |\n| Gastrointestinal | Nausea/Diarrhoea | Rapid infusion, high osmolality, bacterial contamination | Adjust rate/concentration, consider prokinetics, hygiene |\n| Metabolic | Hyponatraemia | Excess free water, SIADH, renal dysfunction | Monitor electrolytes, adjust fluid/feed composition |\n| Hepatic | Disturbed Liver Function | Overfeeding, altered nutrient metabolism, cholestasis | Optimize caloric intake, monitor LFTs, consider cyclic feeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NGT feeding is a double-edged sword; anticipate systemic complications beyond the gut.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, malposition of an NGT into the trachea or bronchus is a critical finding, requiring immediate repositioning. Intraoperatively, if an NGT is placed, ensure its tip is beyond the pylorus for post-pyloric feeding or correctly positioned in the stomach, confirming no perforation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN/SCCM Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016). Recommends early enteral nutrition via NGT, but emphasizes monitoring for complications and appropriate tube placement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | pulmonary aspiration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | nausea. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | diarrhoea. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | disturbed liver function. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | hyponatraemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABCDE) pulmonary aspiration., nausea., diarrhoea., disturbed liver function., hyponatraemia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
