  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Amoebiasis cutis: Liver's skin breakout, steroids are a no-go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A and D are correct. Amoebiasis cutis is indeed an infection of the dermis caused by *Entamoeba histolytica*, and it is frequently recognized as a complication arising from a ruptured amoebic liver abscess or direct extension from other visceral sites.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAmoebiasis cutis represents an extraintestinal manifestation of *Entamoeba histolytica* infection. The parasite, typically acquired via the fecal-oral route, first colonizes the colon, leading to intestinal amoebiasis. In some cases, trophozoites can invade the colonic wall, enter the portal circulation, and establish an amoebic liver abscess. Cutaneous amoebiasis often develops when such an abscess ruptures and drains externally, or when amoebae directly invade the skin from an adjacent infected organ or through a fistula. The skin lesions are characterized by progressive, destructive ulceration due to the proteolytic enzymes produced by the amoebae.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Amoebiasis cutis lesions are typically progressive, destructive, and often irregular or serpiginous, not circumscribed. They tend to spread rapidly.\nOption C (Incorrect): While trophozoites can sometimes be seen on a smear, definitive diagnosis usually requires a biopsy with histopathological examination (showing trophozoites and inflammatory infiltrate), culture, or PCR. Simple slide smear alone is often insufficient for a reliable diagnosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Steroid therapy is contraindicated in amoebic infections as it can suppress the host's immune response, leading to worsening disease, dissemination, and increased mortality. Specific anti-amoebic agents are required for treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intestinal Amoebiasis | Amoebic Liver Abscess | Amoebiasis Cutis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Site** | Colon | Liver | Skin (dermis) |\n| **Symptoms** | Dysentery, abdominal pain | Fever, RUQ pain, hepatomegaly | Painful, progressive skin ulcerations |\n| **Diagnosis** | Stool microscopy, PCR | Imaging (US/CT), serology, aspiration | Biopsy (histopathology), culture, PCR |\n| **Treatment** | Metronidazole + luminal agent | Metronidazole + luminal agent (drainage if needed) | Metronidazole + luminal agent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Amoebiasis cutis: *E. histolytica* skin infection, often from liver abscess, avoid steroids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/US), an amoebic liver abscess typically appears as a well-defined, hypodense or hypoechoic lesion, often solitary and in the right lobe. Intraoperatively, amoebiasis cutis presents as a rapidly progressive, painful, necrotic ulcer with undermined edges, often with purulent or 'anchovy paste' like discharge if associated with a ruptured liver abscess or fistula.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nIDSA Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Amebiasis (2017) recommend metronidazole as the drug of choice for invasive amoebiasis (including liver abscess and cutaneous forms), followed by a luminal agent to eradicate intestinal cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is infection of the dermis with Entamoeba histolytica. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | tends to be circumscribed. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is diagnosed simply by slide smear. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | is recognised as a complication of liver abscess. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | readily clears up with steroid therapy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: AD) is infection of the dermis with Entamoeba histolytica., is recognised as a complication of liver abscess.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
