  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Syphilis: The great imitator, leaving its mark on bone, nerve, and cartilage.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A, C, and E are correct, representing classic manifestations of late-stage acquired syphilis. These features highlight the systemic and destructive nature of chronic Treponema pallidum infection, affecting various organ systems including the nervous system, bone, and cartilage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcquired syphilis, particularly in its tertiary stage, can lead to significant tissue destruction and organ dysfunction. Eighth nerve bilateral deafness (A) is a manifestation of neurosyphilis, where the spirochete directly damages the vestibulocochlear nerve, leading to sensorineural hearing loss. Saddle nose (C) results from gummatous destruction of the nasal septum and cartilage, causing collapse of the nasal bridge. Sabre tibia (E) is due to chronic periostitis and osteitis, leading to anterior bowing and thickening of the tibia. These features underscore the chronic inflammatory and destructive processes initiated by the spirochete.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Moon's molars are a characteristic feature of congenital syphilis, not acquired syphilis. They are hypoplastic first molars with multiple cusps.\nOption D (Incorrect): Salmon patches on the cornea, also known as interstitial keratitis, are a hallmark of congenital syphilis, not acquired syphilis. They represent corneal inflammation and neovascularization.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acquired Syphilis | Congenital Syphilis | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Eighth nerve deafness | Yes (tertiary) | Yes (late) | Neurosyphilis manifestation |\n| Moon's molars | No | Yes | Dental hypoplasia |\n| Saddle nose | Yes (tertiary) | Yes (late) | Cartilage destruction |\n| Salmon patches (cornea) | No | Yes | Interstitial keratitis |\n| Sabre tibia | Yes (tertiary) | Yes (late) | Periostitis/osteitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acquired syphilis: Think late-stage destruction, not developmental anomalies.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a saddle nose deformity would show destruction of the nasal septum and possibly the nasal bones on a CT scan. Sabre tibia would appear on X-ray as anterior bowing and cortical thickening of the tibia, indicative of chronic periostitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Sexually Transmitted Infections Treatment Guidelines, 2021. These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of syphilis, including management of late-stage manifestations like neurosyphilis and gummatous lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | eighth nerve bilateral deafness. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Moon’s molars. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | saddle nose. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | salmon patches on the cornea. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | sabre tibia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) eighth nerve bilateral deafness., saddle nose., sabre tibia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
