  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Yaws: Tropical skin contact, not sex, same serology as syphilis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key characteristics of Yaws: its causative agent (*Treponema pertenue*), its serological cross-reactivity with syphilis, and its typical presentation in children on the legs. These points accurately describe the microbiology, diagnostic features, and epidemiology of this treponemal infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nYaws is a chronic, non-venereal treponemal infection caused by *Treponema pertenue*, a spirochete closely related to *T. pallidum* (syphilis). This close genetic and antigenic relationship explains why serological tests for syphilis (e.g., VDRL, RPR, FTA-ABS) are also reactive in Yaws, making differentiation challenging without clinical context or molecular testing. The disease is primarily transmitted through direct skin-to-skin contact, often among children in warm, humid, tropical climates, with initial lesions frequently appearing on the lower extremities due to minor trauma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Yaws is characteristically prevalent in warm, humid, tropical regions, not dry desert lands, as it thrives in environments conducive to skin-to-skin contact and poor hygiene.\nOption D (Incorrect): Yaws is primarily transmitted by direct skin-to-skin contact, making it a non-venereal disease, unlike syphilis which is predominantly sexually transmitted.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature          | Yaws                               | Syphilis                               | Pinta                                  |\n| :--------------- | :--------------------------------- | :------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------- |\n| Causative Agent  | *Treponema pertenue*               | *Treponema pallidum* subsp. *pallidum* | *Treponema carateum*                   |\n| Transmission     | Non-venereal (skin-to-skin contact)| Sexual, congenital                     | Non-venereal (skin-to-skin contact)    |\n| Primary Lesion   | Papule/framboesia                  | Chancre                                | Papule, evolving to dyschromic macules |\n| Serology         | Reactive to syphilis tests         | Reactive to syphilis tests             | Reactive to syphilis tests             |\n| Endemic Areas    | Warm, humid tropics (children)     | Worldwide (adults)                     | Central/South America (adults)         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Treponematoses share serology but differ in transmission and primary lesions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn examination, early Yaws lesions (framboesias) appear as raspberry-like papules or nodules, often ulcerated, typically on the legs or feet. Later stages can involve destructive bone lesions (gangosa, saber shins) or juxta-articular nodules, visible on X-ray.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the management of endemic treponematoses (2017). These guidelines recommend single-dose oral azithromycin for mass treatment and individual cases of Yaws.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is characteristically prevalent in dry desert lands. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is caused by Treponema pertenue. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | produces serological reactions identical with syphilis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | is a sexually transmitted disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | occurs primarily on the legs of children. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCE) is caused by Treponema pertenue., produces serological reactions identical with syphilis., occurs primarily on the legs of children.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
