  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Candida: The opportunistic yeast that loves a weak host.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer options ACD accurately describe Candidiasis. This common fungal infection is indeed caused by a yeast, can manifest as intertrigo in skin folds, and is a well-recognized opportunistic infection in patients with AIDS due to their compromised immune systems.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCandidiasis is primarily caused by *Candida albicans*, a dimorphic fungus that typically exists as a commensal yeast on mucosal surfaces. Its opportunistic nature means it thrives when host defenses are weakened, such as in immunosuppression (e.g., AIDS, diabetes, broad-spectrum antibiotic use). The fungus's ability to colonize moist, occluded skin areas leads to intertrigo, characterized by erythematous, macerated plaques with satellite lesions. In AIDS patients, candidiasis, particularly oral thrush or esophageal candidiasis, is a common early indicator of immune deterioration and a significant cause of morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Framboesia, also known as yaws, is a chronic bacterial infection caused by *Treponema pallidum pertenue*, a spirochete, not a yeast. It produces granulomatous lesions, not related to candidiasis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Penicillin is an antibiotic effective against bacteria by interfering with cell wall synthesis. It has no antifungal activity and would be completely ineffective against *Candida* species, which require specific antifungal agents like azoles or echinocandins for treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organism | Type | Common Manifestation in AIDS | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| *Candida albicans* | Yeast | Oral thrush, esophagitis, vaginitis | Antifungals (e.g., fluconazole) |\n| *Pneumocystis jirovecii* | Fungus | Pneumonia (PCP) | Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole |\n| *Mycobacterium avium* complex (MAC) | Bacteria | Disseminated infection, lymphadenitis | Macrolides (e.g., azithromycin) |\n| Toxoplasma gondii | Parasite | Encephalitis | Pyrimethamine + sulfadiazine |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Yeast, immunocompromise, and moist skin folds often point to Candida.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, esophageal candidiasis appears as white, adherent plaques or pseudomembranes. Clinically, oral thrush presents as white, creamy patches on the tongue and oral mucosa that can be scraped off.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guidelines for the Prevention and Treatment of Opportunistic Infections in HIV-Infected Adults and Adolescents (2023) recommend fluconazole as the primary treatment for oropharyngeal and esophageal candidiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is caused by a yeast. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | produces ulcerated raspberry-like swellings (framboesia). | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | can cause intertrigo. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | has a recognised association with AIDS. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is cured with penicillin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACD) is caused by a yeast., can cause intertrigo., has a recognised association with AIDS.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
