  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HIV: A master of immune evasion, a host of complications.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key clinical manifestations and opportunistic infections associated with HIV. Lymphadenopathy is a common early and persistent sign, encephalopathy represents neurological involvement, and Pneumocystis carinii infection (PCP) is a classic AIDS-defining illness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHIV primarily targets CD4+ T lymphocytes, leading to progressive immunosuppression. Lymphadenopathy results from chronic immune activation and follicular hyperplasia in response to persistent viral replication. HIV-associated encephalopathy (now part of HIV-associated neurocognitive disorders, HAND) is caused by direct viral effects on CNS cells (e.g., microglia, astrocytes) and chronic inflammation, leading to neuronal dysfunction and damage. Pneumocystis carinii (now *Pneumocystis jirovecii*) pneumonia (PCP) is an opportunistic infection that occurs when the CD4+ T cell count drops significantly, typically below 200 cells/µL, compromising the host's ability to clear this ubiquitous fungus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): B lymphocytes are part of the immune system and are involved in the antibody response to HIV, but HIV primarily targets T cells. While HIV can cause B cell dysfunction (e.g., hypergammaglobulinemia, increased lymphoma risk), 'B lymphocytes' themselves are not a direct *association* or *manifestation* of HIV infection in the same way as the other options. \nOption D (Incorrect): Buerger’s disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) is a non-atherosclerotic, segmental inflammatory vasculitis strongly associated with heavy tobacco use, not HIV infection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | System Affected | Pathophysiology/Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lymphadenopathy | Lymphatic/Immune | Chronic immune activation, follicular hyperplasia; often early sign |\n| Encephalopathy | Central Nervous System | Direct viral effects on CNS cells, chronic inflammation, neuronal damage |\n| Pneumocystis carinii infection (PCP) | Respiratory | Opportunistic fungal infection due to severe CD4+ T cell depletion (<200 cells/µL) |\n| Kaposi's Sarcoma | Skin, Mucosa, Organs | AIDS-defining cancer caused by Human Herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8) in immunosuppressed individuals |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think systemic, neurologic, and opportunistic when considering HIV complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn chest CT, PCP typically presents as diffuse ground-glass opacities, often with septal thickening. Brain MRI in HIV encephalopathy may show diffuse cerebral atrophy, white matter abnormalities, and sometimes calcifications. Enlarged lymph nodes are visible on CT scans for lymphadenopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNIH Guidelines for the Prevention and Treatment of Opportunistic Infections in Adults and Adolescents with HIV (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, treatment, and prophylaxis of opportunistic infections, including PCP, in individuals with HIV.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | lymphadenopathy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | B lymphocytes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | encephalopathy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Buerger’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Pneumocystis carinii infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) lymphadenopathy., encephalopathy., Pneumocystis carinii infection.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
