  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Immunity's sentinels and alarm-sounders are just as vital as the soldiers!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies dendritic cells, mast cells, and Langerhans’ cells as key components of the immune response. These cells play distinct but crucial roles in recognizing pathogens, initiating inflammation, and presenting antigens to orchestrate adaptive immunity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDendritic cells are professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs) that bridge innate and adaptive immunity by capturing antigens, processing them, and migrating to lymph nodes to activate T cells. Mast cells are granulocytes found in connective tissues, playing a central role in allergic reactions and inflammation by releasing histamine and other mediators upon activation. Langerhans’ cells are specialized dendritic cells residing in the epidermis, acting as the skin's primary APCs, capturing antigens and migrating to regional lymph nodes to initiate immune responses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Reticulocytes are immature red blood cells primarily involved in oxygen transport, not immune function.\nOption B (Incorrect): Oligodendrocytes are glial cells in the central nervous system responsible for myelin formation, not direct immune responses.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Primary Function | Immune System Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| Dendritic Cell | Antigen presentation | Initiates adaptive immunity |\n| Mast Cell | Mediator release (histamine) | Allergic reactions, inflammation |\n| Langerhans’ Cell | Antigen presentation (skin) | Skin immunity, T-cell activation |\n| Reticulocyte | Oxygen transport | None (hematopoietic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Immune cells extend beyond lymphocytes; consider antigen presenters and inflammatory mediators.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, severe mast cell degranulation can manifest as sudden hypotension, bronchospasm, and urticaria during anaphylaxis, requiring immediate recognition and treatment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAAAI/ACAAI Anaphylaxis Practice Parameter (2020) provides comprehensive guidelines for the diagnosis and management of mast cell-mediated severe allergic reactions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | reticulocytes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | oligodendrocytes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | dendritic cells. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | mast cells. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Langerhans’ cells. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D, E) ['dendritic cells.', 'mast cells.', 'Langerhans’ cells.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
