  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Immunosuppression: A double-edged sword, preventing rejection but demanding vigilance for unique toxicities.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options highlight critical and distinct side effects of commonly used immunosuppressants. Steroids are notorious for inducing bone avascular necrosis, particularly in weight-bearing joints, while OKT3 (muromonab-CD3) is well-known for triggering a severe cytokine release syndrome that can manifest as life-threatening pulmonary edema.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGlucocorticoids, like prednisone, can disrupt bone microcirculation and osteocyte viability through various mechanisms including fat emboli, increased intraosseous pressure, and direct osteocyte toxicity, leading to avascular necrosis. OKT3, a monoclonal antibody targeting CD3 on T-cells, causes rapid T-cell activation and lysis upon initial administration. This massive T-cell destruction releases a flood of cytokines (e.g., TNF-alpha, IL-2, IFN-gamma) into the systemic circulation, leading to a 'cytokine storm' or cytokine release syndrome, which can cause capillary leak syndrome and subsequent pulmonary edema.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Azathioprine is associated with bone marrow suppression, hepatotoxicity, and pancreatitis, not gum hyperplasia. Gum hyperplasia is a classic side effect of cyclosporine.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cyclosporine commonly causes hirsutism, nephrotoxicity, hypertension, and gum hyperplasia. Skin thinning is a well-known side effect of chronic steroid use.\nOption D (Incorrect): Antithymocyte globulin (ATG) can cause infusion reactions and cytokine release syndrome, but severe pulmonary edema is more specifically and severely associated with OKT3 due to its potent T-cell activation and cytokine storm. ATG's CRS is generally milder.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Immunosuppressant | Major Side Effects |\n|---|---|\n| Steroids | Avascular Necrosis, Hyperglycemia, Osteoporosis, Skin thinning |\n| Cyclosporine | Nephrotoxicity, Hypertension, Hirsutism, Gum hyperplasia |\n| Tacrolimus | Nephrotoxicity, Neurotoxicity, Hyperglycemia, Alopecia |\n| Azathioprine | Bone marrow suppression, Hepatotoxicity, Pancreatitis |\n| OKT3 (Muromonab-CD3) | Cytokine Release Syndrome (Pulmonary Edema, Fever, Hypotension) |\n| Antithymocyte Globulin (ATG) | Infusion reactions, Cytokine Release Syndrome (milder than OKT3), Serum sickness |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the signature side effects of each major immunosuppressant.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, avascular necrosis (AVN) typically appears as a serpiginous low-signal line on T1-weighted images, representing the necrotic bone margin, often with a 'double-line sign' on T2-weighted images in the femoral head.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Transplantation (AST) Guidelines (various years, e.g., 2019 for kidney transplant) provide comprehensive recommendations on immunosuppression regimens and management of their side effects.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | steroids causing bone avascular necrosis. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | azathioprine causing gum hyperplasia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | cyclosporine causing thinning of the skin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | antithymocyte globulin causing pulmonary oedema. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | antibody OKT3 causing pulmonary oedema. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, E) ['steroids causing bone avascular necrosis.', 'antibody OKT3 causing pulmonary oedema.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
