  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Match, cross-match, and bug check: Your kidney transplant trifecta!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights essential screening tests for cadaveric kidney donors, focusing on immunological compatibility and infectious disease status to ensure graft survival and recipient safety. These tests are fundamental to preventing immediate graft failure and significant post-transplant complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nABO blood group compatibility is paramount to prevent hyperacute rejection mediated by pre-formed antibodies against donor ABO antigens. Lymphocyte cross-match detects pre-existing recipient antibodies against donor HLA antigens, which is critical to avoid hyperacute or accelerated acute rejection. CMV status is vital for guiding antiviral prophylaxis or preemptive therapy in the recipient, significantly reducing the risk of severe post-transplant cytomegalovirus disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Retrograde urography is an invasive procedure primarily used to evaluate the recipient's urinary tract or specific donor ureteral anomalies if suspected, not a routine screening test for cadaveric kidney donors.\nOption E (Incorrect): Bone marrow biopsy is a diagnostic procedure for hematologic conditions and is entirely irrelevant for routine screening of kidney donors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Screening Test | Purpose in Kidney Transplantation |\n|---|---|\n| ABO Blood Group | Prevent hyperacute rejection |\n| Lymphocyte Cross-match | Detect donor-specific antibodies |\n| HLA Typing | Assess immunologic match, guide immunosuppression |\n| CMV Status | Guide antiviral prophylaxis/monitoring |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Immunologic and infectious screening are non-negotiable for donor kidney viability and recipient safety.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring organ recovery, the kidneys are visually inspected for gross abnormalities. Post-perfusion, the kidney should appear pink and turgid. In the recipient, a successful transplant will show immediate urine output and good perfusion on Doppler ultrasound.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nUnited Network for Organ Sharing (UNOS) Policy 3.5: Donor Evaluation (most recent version) provides comprehensive recommendations for donor screening and organ allocation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ABO blood group compatability. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | lymphocyte cross-match. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | CMV status | ✅ Correct |\n| D | retrograde urography. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | bone marrow biopsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) ['ABO blood group compatability.', 'lymphocyte cross-match.', 'CMV status']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
