  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-transplant complications demand swift, decisive surgical action.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies common and critical surgical complications after renal transplantation that necessitate prompt surgical intervention. These interventions are crucial for preserving graft function and ensuring patient safety.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPost-transplant haemorrhage requires immediate re-exploration to identify and ligate bleeding vessels, preventing hypovolemic shock and graft ischemia. Symptomatic lymphocoeles, especially those causing ureteric compression or pain, are effectively treated by surgical fenestration into the peritoneal cavity, allowing for fluid reabsorption. Urinary leaks, often due to anastomotic dehiscence or ureteric injury, mandate re-exploration and repair to prevent urinoma formation, infection, and potential graft loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Re-exploration alone does not treat ureteric necrosis; it's part of the diagnostic or access phase. Definitive treatment involves excision of the necrotic segment and reconstruction (e.g., re-anastomosis, ureteroneocystostomy, or pyeloureterostomy). \nOption C (Incorrect): Nephrectomy for graft artery thrombosis is a last resort. The initial appropriate treatment is urgent re-exploration and thrombectomy to attempt graft salvage, especially if detected early. Nephrectomy is reserved for irreversible ischemia or failed salvage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication           | Presentation                                  | Initial Management                               | Definitive Surgical Treatment                               |\n|------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Haemorrhage            | Hypotension, decreasing Hgb, expanding hematoma | Resuscitation, urgent re-exploration             | Ligation of bleeding vessel(s)                              |\n| Urinary Leak           | Decreased urine output, pain, fever, urinoma  | Foley catheter, percutaneous drainage            | Re-exploration, repair of leak, re-anastomosis              |\n| Lymphocoele (symptomatic)| Pain, graft dysfunction, ureteric compression | Percutaneous drainage (temporary)                | Surgical fenestration into peritoneum                       |\n| Graft Artery Thrombosis| Anuria, sudden graft dysfunction, pain        | Urgent Doppler US/CT angio, anticoagulation      | Urgent re-exploration, thrombectomy (if viable), or nephrectomy (if irreversible)\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early recognition and aggressive surgical management save renal grafts.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, haemorrhage appears as an expanding hematoma on CT. Urinary leaks show extravasation on CT urogram or cystogram. Lymphocoeles are well-defined fluid collections on ultrasound or CT. Intraoperatively, active bleeding, direct visualization of urine extravasation, or a tense fluid collection would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009). It recommends prompt evaluation and management of surgical complications to optimize graft and patient outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | re-exploration for haemorrhage. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | re-exploration for ureteric necrosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | nephrectomy for graft artery thrombosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | surgical fenestration for lymphocoele. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | re-exploration for urinary leak. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) ['re-exploration for haemorrhage.', 'surgical fenestration for lymphocoele.', 're-exploration for urinary leak.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
