  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Late graft loss: chronic foes, not sudden blows.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies cyclosporine toxicity and graft neoplasm as recognized causes of late kidney graft loss. These conditions typically manifest months to years after transplantation, leading to chronic dysfunction and eventual graft failure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLate graft loss refers to complications occurring well after the initial post-operative period, often due to chronic processes. Cyclosporine, a calcineurin inhibitor, is a potent immunosuppressant but is well-known for its nephrotoxic effects, causing chronic interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy over time, leading to progressive graft dysfunction. Graft neoplasm, particularly post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder (PTLD) or de novo malignancies, arises from chronic immunosuppression which impairs immune surveillance, allowing oncogenic viruses (like EBV) or spontaneous mutations to lead to uncontrolled cell growth within or affecting the graft, ultimately compromising its function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Graft rupture is an acute, often catastrophic event, typically occurring in the immediate post-operative period due to hyperacute rejection, trauma, or severe acute rejection, not a cause of late loss.\nOption B (Incorrect): Renal vein thrombosis is an early surgical complication, usually presenting within days to weeks post-transplant with acute graft dysfunction or anuria, not a late cause.\nOption D (Incorrect): Anastomotic dehiscence refers to the breakdown of the surgical connection, leading to urine leak or hemorrhage, and is an early surgical complication, not a cause of late graft loss.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Early Graft Loss (Days-Weeks) | Late Graft Loss (Months-Years) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Surgical/Vascular** | Renal artery/vein thrombosis, anastomotic leak/dehiscence, graft rupture | Ureteral stricture, lymphocele, recurrent stone disease |\n| **Immunological** | Hyperacute rejection, acute cellular/antibody-mediated rejection | Chronic active antibody-mediated rejection, chronic allograft nephropathy |\n| **Medical/Other** | Acute tubular necrosis, initial drug toxicity, infection | Calcineurin inhibitor nephrotoxicity, graft neoplasm, recurrent primary disease, infection |\n| **Example** | Graft thrombosis, urine leak | Cyclosporine toxicity, PTLD |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Late graft loss equals chronic problems: think immunosuppression side effects and malignancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor cyclosporine toxicity, imaging may show a small, echogenic kidney, but biopsy is definitive, revealing interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy. For graft neoplasm, ultrasound or CT may reveal a new mass within or adjacent to the graft, often requiring biopsy for definitive diagnosis and staging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO (Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009, with subsequent updates) recommends lifelong monitoring for drug toxicity and malignancy in transplant recipients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a graft rupture. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | renal vein thrombosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | cyclosporine toxicity. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | anastomotic dehiscence. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | graft neoplasm. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, E) ['cyclosporine toxicity.', 'graft neoplasm.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
