  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-transplant complications: Act fast, save the graft!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct options represent critical and common post-liver transplant surgical complications that require specific, often urgent, interventions to preserve graft function and patient survival. These include infectious, anastomotic, and vascular issues.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatic artery thrombosis (HAT) is a surgical emergency requiring prompt thrombectomy or re-transplantation to prevent graft ischemia and failure. Bile leaks, often due to anastomotic breakdown, necessitate re-exploration for repair and drainage to prevent peritonitis and sepsis. Cholangitis, frequently associated with biliary strictures, requires aggressive antibiotic therapy and often endoscopic or percutaneous drainage to manage infection and prevent graft loss. These interventions are crucial for managing the immediate threats to the transplanted liver.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Exploration for preservation damage is not a direct management strategy for the damage itself. Preservation injury manifests as poor graft function or specific complications (e.g., biliary strictures), which are then managed, but the \"damage\" itself isn't surgically explored post-transplant.\nOption D (Incorrect): While portal vein thrombosis can occur, acute thrombectomy is not as universally indicated or as immediately critical as for hepatic artery thrombosis. PVT is often managed medically with anticoagulation, or with shunting procedures, and its acute surgical intervention is less common than for HAT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Type | Common Cause | Primary Management | Urgency |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Hepatic Artery Thrombosis (HAT) | Vascular | Technical error, hypercoagulability | Urgent thrombectomy/re-transplant | High |\n| Bile Leak | Biliary/Anastomotic | Anastomotic breakdown, ischemia | Re-exploration, repair, drainage | High |\n| Cholangitis | Infectious | Biliary stricture, anastomotic issues | Antibiotics, drainage (ERCP/PTC) | Medium-High |\n| Portal Vein Thrombosis (PVT) | Vascular | Technical error, hypercoagulability | Anticoagulation, shunting, thrombectomy (less common) | Medium |\n| Preservation Injury | Graft Dysfunction | Cold ischemia time, donor factors | Supportive care, manage sequelae | Variable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HAT and bile leaks demand immediate surgical attention post-LT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nHAT: Doppler ultrasound shows absent hepatic artery flow. CT angiography confirms occlusion. Intraoperatively, the hepatic artery will be pulseless and thrombosed.\nBile Leak: CT scan with contrast may show perihepatic fluid collection. HIDA scan or ERCP/PTC can localize the leak. Intraoperatively, bile staining and active leakage will be evident at the anastomotic site or T-tube exit.\nCholangitis: Ultrasound/CT may show dilated bile ducts, periductal edema. ERCP/PTC can show strictures and purulent bile.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) 2018 Practice Guidance: Liver Transplantation. Recommends prompt diagnosis and management of vascular and biliary complications to optimize outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | antibiotics for cholangitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | re-exploration for bile leak. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | exploration for preservation damage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | thrombectomy for portal vein thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | thrombectomy for hepatic artery thrombosis. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) ['antibiotics for cholangitis.', 're-exploration for bile leak.', 'thrombectomy for hepatic artery thrombosis.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
