  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 NF1: More than just spots, it's a plexiform problem.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key features of generalized neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1). Plexiform neurofibromas are pathognomonic for NF1 and can lead to massive soft tissue overgrowth, often termed elephantiasis. Cirsoid lesions, which are vascular malformations, are also recognized, albeit less common, associations with NF1.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeurofibromatosis type 1 is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by a mutation in the NF1 gene, leading to a loss of function of neurofibromin, a tumor suppressor. This results in uncontrolled proliferation of cells derived from the neural crest, particularly Schwann cells and fibroblasts. Plexiform neurofibromas are diffuse, infiltrative tumors that grow along nerve sheaths and into surrounding tissues, causing significant disfigurement and often leading to the massive tissue hypertrophy characteristic of elephantiasis. The vascular anomalies, including cirsoid lesions, are thought to arise from dysregulation of vascular smooth muscle cells and endothelial cells, also influenced by the NF1 gene mutation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Port wine stains are capillary malformations typically associated with Sturge-Weber syndrome, not NF1. NF1 is characterized by café-au-lait spots and axillary/inguinal freckling.\nOption E (Incorrect): Vitiligo is an autoimmune condition causing depigmentation of the skin, which is not a feature of NF1. NF1 is associated with hyperpigmented lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1) | Sturge-Weber Syndrome | Tuberous Sclerosis Complex (TSC) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Genetic Basis | NF1 gene (Chr 17), neurofibromin | GNAQ gene (somatic mutation) | TSC1/TSC2 genes |\n| Skin Lesions | Café-au-lait spots, axillary/inguinal freckling, neurofibromas (cutaneous, plexiform) | Port-wine stain (facial capillary malformation) | Hypomelanotic macules (ash-leaf spots), facial angiofibromas, shagreen patches |\n| Neurological | Optic pathway gliomas, Lisch nodules (iris hamartomas), learning disabilities, seizures | Leptomeningeal angioma, seizures, intellectual disability, glaucoma | Cortical tubers, subependymal nodules, subependymal giant cell astrocytomas (SEGA), seizures, intellectual disability |\n| Other | Skeletal dysplasia (scoliosis, pseudoarthrosis), pheochromocytoma, renal artery stenosis | Glaucoma, vascular malformations | Renal angiomyolipomas, cardiac rhabdomyomas, pulmonary lymphangioleiomyomatosis (LAM) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Plexiform neurofibromas are the hallmark of NF1's disfiguring potential.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, plexiform neurofibromas appear as diffuse, often ill-defined masses with T2 hyperintensity and can show a 'bag of worms' appearance. Intraoperatively, they are infiltrative, highly vascularized, and often difficult to completely resect due to their diffuse nature and involvement of vital structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (2023): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, surveillance, and management of NF1, including treatment strategies for plexiform neurofibromas and associated complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | elephantiasis. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | plexiform lesions. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | cirsoid lesions. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | port wine stains. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | vitiligo. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) ['elephantiasis.', 'plexiform lesions.', 'cirsoid lesions.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
