  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Glomus: Small pain, big relief with excision!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key characteristics of glomus tumours. These are benign neoplasms originating from glomus bodies, which are specialized neuromyoarterial structures involved in thermoregulation. The correct options highlight their common location and distinctive cellular morphology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGlomus tumours arise from glomus bodies, which are arteriovenous anastomoses found predominantly in the dermis, particularly in the digits. These tumours are classically associated with a triad of severe paroxysmal pain, cold sensitivity, and pinpoint tenderness, especially when subungual. Histologically, they are characterized by nests of uniform, round to cuboidal glomus cells, which are modified smooth muscle cells, surrounding vascular channels. Their common occurrence in the nail beds makes them a significant cause of subungual pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): are renal tumours. Glomus tumours are not typically found in the kidney; renal tumours are a distinct category (e.g., renal cell carcinoma).\nOption B (Incorrect): are cylindromas. Cylindromas are benign adnexal tumours of the skin, originating from sweat glands, and are histologically distinct from glomus tumours.\nOption C (Incorrect): contain neural tissue. While glomus bodies are innervated (neuromyoarterial), the neoplastic glomus cells themselves are modified smooth muscle cells, not neural tissue.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Glomus Tumour | Hemangioma | Cylindroma |\n| :------ | :------------ | :--------- | :--------- |\n| Origin | Glomus body (modified smooth muscle) | Endothelial cells | Adnexal (sweat gland differentiation) |\n| Location | Subungual (most common), digits, extremities | Anywhere (skin, internal organs) | Scalp, face (\"turban tumor\") |\n| Cell Type | Uniform cuboidal/polygonal glomus cells | Endothelial cells forming vascular channels | Basaloid cells in jigsaw puzzle pattern |\n| Key Symptom | Paroxysmal pain, cold sensitivity, pinpoint tenderness | Often asymptomatic, may bleed or ulcerate | Slow-growing nodule, often multiple |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Glomus: Painful, cold-sensitive subungual nodule of modified smooth muscle cells.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI or ultrasound, a glomus tumour appears as a small, well-circumscribed, often hypervascular lesion. Intraoperatively, it is typically a small, reddish-blue nodule, often found directly beneath the nail plate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific dedicated guideline for glomus tumors exists from major surgical societies due to their rarity and benign nature. Management typically follows general principles of benign tumor excision.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are renal tumours. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | are cylindromas. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | contain neural tissue. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | occur in the nail beds. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | contain large cuboidal cells. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D, E) ['occur in the nail beds.', 'contain large cuboidal cells.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
