  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fibrosarcoma: Mesenchymal menace, wide excision is your best defense.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies fibrosarcomas as mesenchymal tumors that necessitate wide surgical excision with clear margins. Understanding their tissue origin and primary treatment modality is fundamental for managing these aggressive soft tissue sarcomas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibrosarcomas originate from fibroblasts, which are connective tissue cells of mesenchymal lineage, distinguishing them from epithelial (carcinomas) or glandular (adenomas) tumors. The principle of wide local excision with surrounding healthy tissue is paramount for soft tissue sarcomas to achieve R0 resection, minimizing local recurrence. These tumors often lack a true capsule and can infiltrate surrounding tissues microscopically, making clear margins critical for long-term disease control.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fibrosarcomas are mesenchymal, not adenomatous. Adenomatous refers to tumors of glandular epithelial origin. \nOption C (Incorrect): Soft tissue sarcomas, including fibrosarcomas, primarily spread hematogenously (e.g., to lungs) and locally, not typically via lymphatic permeation like many carcinomas. \nOption D (Incorrect): An epulis is a general term for a gingival mass, often inflammatory or reactive. While rare oral fibrosarcomas can occur, they are not characteristically described as 'an epulis,' which is more commonly associated with benign or reactive lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Fibrosarcoma | Carcinoma | Liposarcoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tissue Origin | Mesenchymal (fibroblasts) | Epithelial (glandular/lining) | Mesenchymal (adipocytes) |\n| Primary Spread | Hematogenous, Local | Lymphatic, Hematogenous | Hematogenous, Local |\n| Treatment Principle | Wide Excision | Wide Excision +/- Lymphadenectomy | Wide Excision |\n| Lymph Node Involvement | Rare | Common | Rare |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fibrosarcomas: mesenchymal, hematogenous spread, wide excision for local control.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, fibrosarcomas often appear as ill-defined, heterogeneous masses with variable enhancement. Intraoperatively, they may lack a distinct capsule, appearing infiltrative into surrounding muscle or fascia, necessitating careful margin assessment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (latest version, e.g., 2023/2024) recommend wide local excision with negative margins as the cornerstone of treatment, often supplemented by adjuvant radiation therapy for high-grade or large tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are adenomatous. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | are mesenchymal. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | spread primarily by lymphatic permeation: | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | occur as an epulis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | are treated by a wide excision with surrounding healthy tissues. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, E) ['are mesenchymal.', 'are treated by a wide excision with surrounding healthy tissues.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
