  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 False cysts: Just a fluid party, no epithelial bouncer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers B and C accurately describe a false cyst (pseudocyst). A false cyst is characterized by the absence of an epithelial lining, instead having a fibrous or inflammatory wall. It typically forms from the accumulation of fluid, often inflammatory exudate or blood, such as within a liquefying hematoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe fundamental distinction between a true cyst and a false cyst lies in the histological nature of its wall. A true cyst is lined by epithelium or endothelium, which is a hallmark of its developmental origin or specific pathological process. In contrast, a false cyst, or pseudocyst, lacks this specialized lining, instead being encapsulated by a fibrous capsule, granulation tissue, or inflammatory cells. The fluid within a false cyst is often a collection of inflammatory exudate, necrotic debris, or blood products, which explains why it can form in a hematoma as the blood clot liquefies and becomes walled off.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"has an epithelial lining.\" This statement describes a true cyst, which is defined by the presence of an epithelial or endothelial lining. A false cyst, by definition, lacks this characteristic.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"arises in an embryonic remnant.\" Cysts originating from embryonic remnants (e.g., thyroglossal duct, branchial cleft) are typically true cysts, possessing an epithelial lining derived from the embryonic tissue.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"is a characteristic of hydatid cyst.\" A hydatid cyst is a parasitic cyst caused by *Echinococcus granulosus* and is a true cyst with a distinct germinal layer and laminated membrane, not a false cyst.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | True Cyst | False Cyst (Pseudocyst) | Hydatid Cyst |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lining** | Epithelial or Endothelial | Fibrous capsule, granulation tissue, or inflammatory cells (no epithelium) | Germinal layer and laminated membrane (parasitic) |\n| **Contents** | Serous fluid, mucus, sebum, etc. | Inflammatory exudate, necrotic debris, blood, pancreatic fluid | Hydatid fluid, protoscolices, daughter cysts |\n| **Etiology** | Developmental, neoplastic, retention | Trauma, inflammation (e.g., pancreatitis), hemorrhage (hematoma) | Parasitic infection (*Echinococcus*) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: No epithelium, no true cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT, MRI, US), a false cyst typically appears as a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic fluid collection, often with internal debris or septations, and a variable wall thickness that may or may not enhance. Intraoperatively, it presents as a fluid-filled sac with a dull, fibrous, or inflammatory wall, lacking the glistening, smooth appearance of an epithelial lining.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013). These guidelines discuss the diagnosis and management of pancreatic pseudocysts, a common type of false cyst.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | has an epithelial lining. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | contains exudate. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can form in a haematoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | arises in an embryonic remnant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is a characteristic of hydatid cyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) ['contains exudate.', 'can form in a haematoma.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
