  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Leishmania: Sandfly's bite, a global skin blight!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies Delhi boil, Baghdad sore, and Lahore sore as manifestations of Leishmania infection. These terms are classic geographical eponyms for cutaneous leishmaniasis, a common form of the parasitic disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeishmaniasis is a parasitic disease caused by protozoa of the genus Leishmania, transmitted by the bite of infected female phlebotomine sandflies. Cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) is the most common form, characterized by skin lesions, typically papules, nodules, or ulcers, which can be self-healing or chronic. The historical recognition and geographical prevalence of these lesions led to their naming after the regions where they were endemic, such as Delhi, Baghdad, and Lahore, reflecting the global distribution and varied clinical presentations of the disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Singapore ear) (Incorrect): This is not a recognized clinical manifestation or eponym for Leishmania infection. It does not correspond to any known form of leishmaniasis.\nOption D (Malta fever) (Incorrect): Malta fever is an alternative name for Brucellosis, a bacterial infection caused by Brucella species, not a parasitic infection like Leishmaniasis. It is a systemic febrile illness, distinct from the skin lesions of cutaneous leishmaniasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Leishmaniasis | Key Features | Causative Species (Examples) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cutaneous Leishmaniasis (CL) | Skin lesions (papules, nodules, ulcers), often self-healing or chronic. | L. major, L. tropica, L. mexicana |\n| Mucocutaneous Leishmaniasis (MCL) | Destructive lesions of mucous membranes (nose, mouth, throat), often secondary to CL. | L. braziliensis |\n| Visceral Leishmaniasis (VL) (Kala-azar) | Systemic disease affecting spleen, liver, bone marrow; fever, weight loss, hepatosplenomegaly. | L. donovani, L. infantum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think sandfly, think Leishmania, think geographical skin sores.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nHistopathology of a skin biopsy from a cutaneous lesion would reveal intracellular amastigotes (Leishman-Donovan bodies) within macrophages.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the treatment of leishmaniasis (2010). It provides comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis and management of all forms of leishmaniasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Delhi boil. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Baghdad sore. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Singapore ear. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Malta fever. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Lahore sore. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) ['Delhi boil.', 'Baghdad sore.', 'Lahore sore.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
