  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Punctum present? It's a cyst, not a mystery!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights a key diagnostic feature of common cutaneous cysts. The presence of a punctum, which is the opening of the blocked follicular infundibulum, is characteristic of epidermoid or pilar cysts, often colloquially referred to as sebaceous cysts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe punctum is a crucial clinical sign, often appearing as a small, dark pore on the surface of the cyst. It represents the original follicular opening from which the cyst developed due to obstruction and accumulation of keratinous debris. This central punctum can sometimes be expressed, releasing malodorous, cheesy material, which is pathognomonic for these types of cysts.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While \"sebaceous cyst\" is a common misnomer, most such lesions are epidermoid cysts (derived from epidermal cells) or pilar cysts (derived from hair follicle sheath cells), not true sebaceous cysts which are rare and originate from sebaceous glands.\nOption B (Incorrect): These cysts are indeed common on the face and scalp, but they can occur almost anywhere on the body where hair follicles are present, including the trunk, neck, and extremities.\nOption C (Incorrect): A sebaceous horn is a misnomer for a cutaneous horn, which is a hyperkeratotic lesion, often precancerous or cancerous, and not typically formed from an ulcerated cyst. Cysts can ulcerate but do not transform into horns.\nOption E (Incorrect): Pott's puffy tumor is a rare complication of frontal sinusitis, characterized by a subperiosteal abscess of the frontal bone, and is unrelated to chronically infected sebaceous cysts.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Epidermoid Cyst | Pilar Cyst (Trichilemmal Cyst) | True Sebaceous Cyst (Steatocystoma) | Dermoid Cyst |\n| :--------------- | :-------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------- |\n| **Origin** | Epidermal infundibulum | Outer root sheath of hair follicle | Sebaceous gland duct | Trapped ectodermal and mesodermal elements |\n| **Location** | Anywhere, common on face, neck, trunk | Scalp (90%), less common elsewhere | Trunk, proximal extremities | Congenital, often periorbital, neck, sacrum |\n| **Punctum** | **Characteristic** | Usually absent | Absent | Absent |\n| **Contents** | Keratin, cheesy, malodorous | Keratin, often pasty, less malodorous | Oily, yellow liquid | Keratin, hair, sebaceous material, sometimes teeth/bone |\n| **Lining** | Stratified squamous epithelium (like epidermis) | Stratified squamous epithelium (no granular layer) | Sebaceous gland cells | Stratified squamous epithelium with skin appendages |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A punctum points to an epidermoid or pilar cyst, not a true sebaceous one.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a sebaceous cyst (epidermoid/pilar) typically appears as a well-circumscribed, anechoic or hypoechoic lesion with posterior acoustic enhancement. Intraoperatively, after incision, a distinct capsule is usually visible, and the cyst can often be \"shelled out\" intact, revealing its characteristic cheesy or pasty contents.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines for the Management of Benign Skin Lesions (2019) recommends surgical excision for symptomatic or bothersome cutaneous cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is called as an epidermoid cyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | only occurs on the face or scalp. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | can, if ulcerated, become a sebaceous horn. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | characteristically displays a punctum. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | if chronically infected is called a Pott’s puffy tumour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ['characteristically displays a punctum.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
