  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse rapid growth with eternal doom; some lesions just like to bloom and then zoom!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies molluscum sebaceum as a keratoacanthoma, a benign epithelial tumor known for its characteristic rapid growth followed by spontaneous regression. This understanding is crucial for accurate diagnosis and management, differentiating it from more aggressive skin cancers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKeratoacanthoma is a unique cutaneous lesion characterized by its rapid development over weeks to months, forming a dome-shaped nodule with a central keratin-filled crater. Histologically, it shows well-differentiated squamous cells with a characteristic crateriform architecture. The most distinguishing feature is its tendency for spontaneous involution and complete resolution, often leaving a scar, which differentiates it from squamous cell carcinoma despite its initial aggressive growth pattern. This self-limiting nature is a key diagnostic and management consideration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"a sebaceous cyst.\" Sebaceous cysts (epidermoid cysts) are slow-growing, benign epidermal inclusion cysts filled with keratin and sebum, and do not spontaneously regress like a keratoacanthoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"called Bowen’s disease.\" Bowen's disease is squamous cell carcinoma in situ, a malignant condition requiring treatment and not known for spontaneous resolution.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"an epithelioma.\" While a keratoacanthoma is an epithelial tumor, \"epithelioma\" is a broad, non-specific term that doesn't capture the unique spontaneous healing characteristic of a keratoacanthoma. Many malignant skin cancers are also epitheliomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Keratoacanthoma                                | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC)                  | Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC)                     |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- |\n| **Growth Pattern**  | Rapid growth, then spontaneous regression      | Slow, progressive growth                        | Slow, progressive growth                       |\n| **Appearance**      | Dome-shaped nodule, central keratin plug       | Erythematous, scaly patch, nodule, or ulcer    | Pearly nodule, rolled border, telangiectasias  |\n| **Prognosis**       | Benign, self-resolving (can leave scar)        | Malignant, metastatic potential                | Malignant, locally invasive, rarely metastasizes |\n| **Management**      | Observation (if confident), excision, curettage | Excision, Mohs surgery, radiation, systemic therapy | Excision, Mohs surgery, curettage, topical therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Molluscum sebaceum = Keratoacanthoma. Rapid growth, spontaneous regression.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, a keratoacanthoma appears as a rapidly growing, firm, dome-shaped nodule with a characteristic central crater filled with a keratin plug. Histologically, it shows a crateriform architecture with well-differentiated squamous cells and often a prominent inflammatory infiltrate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for the management of cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (2021) often discuss keratoacanthoma within this context, recommending that while spontaneous regression is common, surgical excision is frequently preferred to confirm diagnosis and prevent scarring, especially for larger lesions or those in cosmetically sensitive areas, due to the clinical difficulty in distinguishing it from well-differentiated SCC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a sebaceous cyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | called Bowen’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | an epithelioma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | a keratoacanthoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | known to heal spontaneously. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D, E) ['a keratoacanthoma.', 'known to heal spontaneously.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
