  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bleeding bump? Cut it out, don't just dab it.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, excision. Pyogenic granuloma, despite its name, is a benign vascular lesion, not an infection, and requires complete surgical removal for definitive treatment and to prevent recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPyogenic granulomas are rapidly growing, friable, vascular lesions that often bleed easily. They are essentially lobular capillary hemangiomas. Complete surgical excision, including the base and a small margin of normal tissue, is crucial because incomplete removal frequently leads to recurrence. The specimen should always be sent for histopathological examination to confirm the diagnosis and rule out other more serious conditions, such as amelanotic melanoma or squamous cell carcinoma, which can mimic its appearance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cauterisation alone is often insufficient to remove the entire lesion, especially its base, leading to a high recurrence rate.\nOption B (Incorrect): Antibiotic ointment treats infection, but pyogenic granuloma is a vascular proliferation, not primarily an infection. Antibiotics would only be palliative for secondary infection, not definitive treatment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is generally not indicated for benign skin lesions like pyogenic granuloma due to potential side effects and the availability of simpler, effective surgical treatments.\nOption E (Incorrect): Incision implies cutting into or draining, which is inappropriate for a solid vascular lesion. It would likely cause significant bleeding and not achieve definitive removal, leading to recurrence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pyogenic Granuloma | Capillary Hemangioma | Basal Cell Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appearance | Rapidly growing, friable, red/purple nodule, often pedunculated | Red, raised, 'strawberry mark', present at birth/infancy | Pearly nodule, rolled border, telangiectasias, central ulceration |\n| Etiology | Trauma, hormonal changes, medications | Congenital vascular malformation | UV radiation exposure |\n| Treatment | Surgical excision | Observation, laser, topical/oral beta-blockers | Surgical excision (Mohs), cryotherapy, topical chemotherapy |\n| Recurrence | High if incomplete excision | Low (most involute spontaneously) | Low if complete excision |\n| Malignancy | Benign | Benign | Malignant (locally invasive) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyogenic granuloma: Excise completely to prevent recurrence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, a pyogenic granuloma appears as a soft, often pedunculated, reddish-purple to dark red nodule that is highly vascular and bleeds profusely with minimal manipulation. Its base may be narrow or broad.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines (various years) recommend surgical excision as the primary treatment for symptomatic, persistent, or recurrent pyogenic granulomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | cauterisation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | antibiotic ointment. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | excision. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | radiotherapy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | incision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ['excision.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
