  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 PWS: Permanent purple, not proliferative.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. A port wine stain (naevus flammeus) is a type of vascular anomaly, specifically a capillary malformation. While technically distinct from a true hemangioma (which is a proliferative tumor), in broader clinical terminology, vascular malformations are sometimes grouped under the umbrella of 'hemangiomas' or 'vascular birthmarks,' making 'type of haemangioma' the best fit among the given options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPort wine stains are congenital vascular malformations characterized by abnormally dilated capillaries in the superficial dermis. Unlike infantile hemangiomas, they are not proliferative tumors; rather, they represent a developmental error in vascular morphogenesis. They are present at birth, grow proportionally with the child, and do not involute spontaneously. The characteristic reddish-purple color is due to the stagnant blood within these ectatic capillaries, and the lesion typically darkens and thickens with age.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Port wine stains are benign vascular malformations and do not carry a risk of malignant transformation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Melanoma is a malignant tumor of melanocytes, which are pigment-producing cells. Port wine stains are vascular in origin.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bruising is a temporary extravasation of blood into tissues due from trauma. Port wine stains are permanent, congenital vascular anomalies.\nOption E (Incorrect): A tattoo is an exogenous deposition of pigment into the skin. A port wine stain is an endogenous vascular anomaly.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Port Wine Stain (Capillary Malformation) | Infantile Hemangioma | Venous Malformation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nature | Congenital vascular malformation | Benign vascular tumor (proliferative) | Congenital vascular malformation |\n| Presentation | Present at birth, flat, red/purple | Appears weeks after birth, grows rapidly, involutes | Present at birth, soft, compressible, blue |\n| Histology | Dilated capillaries, no endothelial proliferation | Endothelial cell proliferation | Dilated venous channels |\n| Prognosis | Permanent, darkens with age | Spontaneous involution (5-10 years) | Permanent, grows slowly, does not involute |\n| Treatment | Pulsed dye laser | Observation, beta-blockers (propranolol) | Sclerotherapy, surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Port wine stains are capillary malformations, present at birth, and do not involute.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, a port wine stain appears as a flat, erythematous to violaceous patch. Imaging (MRI) is typically reserved for suspected associated syndromes, such as Sturge-Weber syndrome (leptomeningeal angiomatosis) or Klippel-Trenaunay syndrome (limb hypertrophy and venous malformations), where it would show characteristic findings like pial angiomas or soft tissue/bone overgrowth.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe International Society for the Study of Vascular Anomalies (ISSVA) Classification of Vascular Anomalies (2018) is the most relevant guideline. It classifies port wine stains as 'Capillary Malformations,' distinguishing them from 'Vascular Tumors' like hemangiomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | premalignant lesion of the skin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | type of melanoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | type of bruising of the skin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | type of haemangioma. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | tattoo. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ['type of haemangioma.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
