  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma types: Know their spots, know their stripes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies three distinct types of malignant melanoma: superficial spreading, nodular, and acral lentiginous. Each of these types possesses unique clinical and pathological characteristics that are crucial for diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSuperficial spreading melanoma (SSM) is the most common type, typically presenting as a flat or slightly raised lesion with irregular borders and variegated pigmentation, often arising from a pre-existing nevus. Nodular melanoma (NM) is characterized by rapid vertical growth, often appearing as a dark, raised nodule that frequently ulcerates and bleeds due to its aggressive nature. Acral lentiginous melanoma (ALM) is less common but significant, particularly in individuals with darker skin types, and is found on the palms, soles, and nail beds, often presenting as a dark streak under the nail (melanonychia striata) or a pigmented lesion on acral surfaces.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The melanotic freckle, or lentigo maligna, is melanoma in situ, meaning it is confined to the epidermis. While it has the potential to progress to invasive lentigo maligna melanoma, it is not inherently \"very malignant\" in its initial, non-invasive stage.\nOption E (Incorrect): Amelanotic melanoma is a variant of other melanoma types (e.g., superficial spreading, nodular, acral lentiginous) where there is a lack of pigment. It is often aggressive and *does* metastasize, sometimes with a worse prognosis due to delayed diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Melanoma Type | Key Features | Common Location |\n|---|---|---|\n| Superficial Spreading | Most common, irregular borders, variegated color, radial growth phase | Trunk, extremities |\n| Nodular | Rapid vertical growth, raised, often ulcerates/bleeds, aggressive | Any site, often head/neck, trunk |\n| Acral Lentiginous | Palms, soles, nail beds, often in darker skin types, Hutchinson's sign | Palms, soles, subungual |\n| Lentigo Maligna | Melanoma in situ, sun-damaged skin, slow radial growth | Face, neck, sun-exposed areas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the ABCDEs and the distinct features of melanoma types.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDermoscopy is crucial for evaluating pigmented lesions, revealing characteristic patterns for each melanoma type, such as atypical pigment networks, streaks, or blue-white veil. Biopsy (excisional preferred) confirms diagnosis and determines Breslow depth.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Melanoma (2023) provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the spreading superficial type, which is the commonest and has an irregular | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the melanotic freckle, which is very malignant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the nodular type which ulcerates and bleeds. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | the acral-lentiginous type, which occurs chiefly on the dorsum of the hands | ✅ Correct |\n| E | the amelanotic type, which does not metastasise. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) ['the spreading superficial type, which is the commonest and has an irregular edge.', 'the nodular type which ulcerates and bleeds.', 'the acral-lentiginous type, which occurs chiefly on the dorsum of the hands and the feet.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
