  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma: Not always dark, always dangerous.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This answer is correct because malignant melanoma, while often pigmented, can also present without melanin, making its diagnosis challenging. Recognizing both melanotic and amelanotic forms is crucial for early detection and appropriate management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant melanoma originates from melanocytes, cells responsible for producing melanin. While many melanomas retain this function, appearing dark (melanotic), a significant subset loses or never develops the ability to produce melanin, resulting in amelanotic melanoma. These amelanotic lesions can be pink, red, skin-colored, or even bluish, often mimicking benign lesions like basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, or even inflammatory processes. This variability underscores the importance of a high index of suspicion and biopsy for any suspicious skin lesion, regardless of pigmentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Melanoma can arise de novo (from normal skin) in a significant percentage of cases, not exclusively from pre-existing nevi.\nOption B (Incorrect): Melanoma is exceedingly rare before puberty; its incidence significantly increases with age, particularly after adolescence.\nOption C (Incorrect): A halo surrounding a lesion is characteristic of a benign halo nevus, where the body's immune system attacks the nevus cells. Melanoma typically does not present with a halo.\nOption E (Incorrect): Malignant melanoma is highly aggressive and spreads via both the lymphatic system (leading to regional lymph node metastases) and the bloodstream (hematogenous spread, leading to distant metastases).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Malignant Melanoma | Benign Nevus | Amelanotic Melanoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pigmentation | Variable (dark, brown, black, red, blue, white) | Uniformly tan to dark brown | Absent or minimal (pink, red, skin-colored) |\n| ABCDE Criteria | Often positive (Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Color variation, Diameter >6mm, Evolving) | Often negative (Symmetric, regular border, uniform color, stable) | Challenging (lack of color variation), focus on ABE |\n| Growth Pattern | Rapid, often asymmetric, irregular borders | Slow, symmetric, regular borders | Rapid, often asymmetric, irregular borders |\n| Metastatic Potential | High (lymphatic & hematogenous) | None | High (lymphatic & hematogenous) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't let lack of pigment lull you; amelanotic melanoma is a wolf in sheep's clothing.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn dermoscopy, amelanotic melanoma may show atypical vascular patterns (e.g., milky-red areas, dotted vessels, linear irregular vessels) and white structureless areas, lacking the typical pigment network. Intraoperatively, sentinel lymph node biopsy is crucial for staging, even if the primary lesion is amelanotic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Melanoma (latest version). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and management, emphasizing the importance of complete excisional biopsy for suspicious lesions and sentinel lymph node biopsy for appropriate T-stages.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | only arises in a pre-existing pigmented naevus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is common before puberty. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | may be surrounded by a halo. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | may be both melanotic and amelanotic. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | spreads by the lymphatics and not by the blood stream. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ['may be both melanotic and amelanotic.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
