  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HHV-8: The vascular villain of immunosuppression.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies key characteristics of Kaposi's sarcoma (KS), a multifocal vascular tumor. It accurately points out its endothelial origin, association with immunosuppression and related malignancies, and common initial presentation sites.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKaposi's sarcoma is a low-grade vascular tumor caused by Human Herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8), also known as Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus (KSHV). It arises from lymphatic endothelial cells, which are specialized endothelial cells lining lymphatic vessels, closely related to capillaries. The disease is strongly associated with immunosuppression, particularly in HIV/AIDS patients, who are also at increased risk for other opportunistic infections and malignancies like lymphoma. Classic Kaposi's sarcoma, an indolent form, typically manifests as purplish-red macules, plaques, or nodules, most commonly beginning on the lower extremities, especially the feet and ankles.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Kaposi's sarcoma is caused by Human Herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8), not malaria. Malaria is a parasitic infection transmitted by mosquitoes.\nOption D (Incorrect): While Kaposi's sarcoma can affect internal organs (e.g., gastrointestinal tract, lungs, lymph nodes), skin lesions are the most common and often the initial manifestation. Visceral involvement without any skin manifestations is rare.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of KS | Associated Population | Key Features | Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Classic | Elderly men, Mediterranean/Eastern European descent | Indolent, lower extremity lesions | Good, slow progression |\n| Endemic (African) | Young African adults/children | Aggressive, often lymphadenopathic | Variable, can be aggressive |\n| Iatrogenic | Organ transplant recipients on immunosuppressants | Variable, can regress with reduced immunosuppression | Improves with immunosuppression reduction |\n| Epidemic (AIDS-related) | HIV-positive individuals | Widespread skin and visceral involvement, aggressive | Linked to CD4 count, improves with ART |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HHV-8, endothelial origin, immunosuppression, lower extremity lesions are classic KS hallmarks.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), Kaposi's sarcoma can appear as nodular lesions, lymphadenopathy, pulmonary infiltrates, or bowel wall thickening. Intraoperatively, lesions are typically purplish-red, often friable, and highly vascular, sometimes bleeding easily.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Kaposi Sarcoma (2023) recommends antiretroviral therapy (ART) for HIV-associated KS and various local or systemic therapies based on disease extent.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is derived from capillaries. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is associated with lymphoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | is associated with malaria. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | can run its course in other organs without skin manifestations. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | commonly begins on the feet. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) ['is derived from capillaries.', 'is associated with lymphoma.', 'commonly begins on the feet.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
