  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Partial thickness burns: sensitive, progressive, and sloughing – don't underestimate them!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies key characteristics and potential outcomes of a partial thickness burn. These burns are known for their sensitivity, potential for progression, and a natural healing process involving sloughing of damaged tissue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPartial thickness burns, also known as second-degree burns, involve the epidermis and a portion of the dermis. The presence of intact nerve endings within the remaining dermis accounts for their characteristic sensitivity and pain. The dermal injury can deepen due to ongoing inflammation, infection, or inadequate resuscitation, leading to conversion to a full thickness burn. The healing process for deeper partial thickness burns often involves the separation of necrotic dermal tissue as a slough, which then allows for re-epithelialization from remaining adnexal structures or wound contraction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): A split skin graft is typically reserved for deep partial thickness burns that are unlikely to heal spontaneously or for full thickness burns. Superficial partial thickness burns usually heal without grafting.\nOption E (Incorrect): Tangential excision is a surgical debridement technique used for deep partial thickness or full thickness burns to remove non-viable tissue and prepare the wound bed for grafting. It is not indicated for superficial partial thickness burns.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Depth | Appearance | Sensitivity | Healing Time | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Superficial (1st degree) | Red, dry, no blisters | Painful | 3-6 days | Symptomatic relief |\n| Superficial Partial (2nd degree) | Red, moist, blisters, blanches | Very painful | 1-3 weeks | Wound care, pain control |\n| Deep Partial (2nd degree) | Red/white, wet/dry, less blanching, blisters | Less painful, pressure sensation | 3-8 weeks | Excision, grafting often needed |\n| Full Thickness (3rd degree) | White, leathery, charred, no blanching | Insensate | Never (without intervention) | Excision, grafting required |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Partial thickness burns hurt, can worsen, and often slough before healing.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, a partial thickness burn appears red, often with blisters, and is exquisitely painful to touch. The wound bed may be moist and will blanch with pressure, indicating some preserved dermal perfusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (updated periodically). These guidelines recommend appropriate wound care, pain management, and surgical intervention strategies based on burn depth and extent.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is sensitive. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | can become a full thickness burn. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | will separate as a slough in two to three weeks. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | requires a split skin graft. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is likely to benefit from tangential excision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) ['is sensitive.', 'can become a full thickness burn.', 'will separate as a slough in two to three weeks.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
