  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Excise and graft deep burns; don't delay, or you'll pay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is excision and applying a split skin graft. For a 10cm deep burn, early excision of non-viable tissue followed by immediate wound closure with a split-thickness skin graft is the gold standard to prevent infection, minimize fluid loss, and promote optimal healing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDeep burns, often implying full-thickness injury, require surgical intervention because the dermal elements necessary for spontaneous re-epithelialization are destroyed. Early excision removes necrotic tissue, which is a nidus for infection and inflammation, and prepares a healthy wound bed. A split-thickness skin graft (STSG) is then applied to achieve definitive wound closure. STSGs are preferred for large surface areas like a 10cm burn on the leg due to their ability to cover extensive defects, ease of harvest, and good take rates, providing durable coverage and reducing contracture risk compared to secondary intention healing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Awaiting desloughing and secondary suture is inappropriate for a 10cm deep burn. Deep burns do not reliably deslough spontaneously, and secondary suture is not feasible for such a large defect due to tissue loss and tension, leading to prolonged healing and increased complications.\nOption B (Incorrect): Using a split skin graft as a dressing, stat, is incorrect. A split skin graft is a definitive surgical cover, not a temporary dressing, and requires a clean, excised wound bed for successful take.\nOption D (Incorrect): Excision and using a flap graft is generally overkill for a 10cm deep burn on the back of the leg unless critical structures (e.g., exposed bone, joint) are involved. Flap grafts are more complex, have higher donor site morbidity, and are typically reserved for smaller, deeper defects requiring bulk or specialized tissue.\nOption E (Incorrect): Performing tangential excision is primarily for deep partial-thickness burns, not typically for 'deep burns' which often implies full-thickness injury requiring full-thickness excision. While tourniquet control is often used, the type of excision is the key differentiating factor here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Depth             | Treatment Strategy                                     | Rationale                                                                                                 |\n|------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Superficial/Partial    | Conservative (dressings, topical agents)               | Dermal elements intact; spontaneous healing expected.                                                     |\n| Deep Partial Thickness | Tangential excision + Skin Graft (often STSG)          | Removes non-viable dermis; preserves viable dermis; accelerates healing; reduces scarring.                 |\n| Full Thickness         | Full Excision + Skin Graft (STSG or FTSG/Flap)         | All dermal elements destroyed; requires removal of necrotic tissue and definitive closure.                |\n| Small, Deep, Critical  | Full Excision + Flap Graft (or FTSG)                   | Provides robust coverage, padding, and vascularity over exposed vital structures (bone, tendon, joint). |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Deep burns need early excision and definitive closure, usually with a split skin graft.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, after excision, the wound bed would appear uniformly viable, often with punctate bleeding, indicating adequate debridement. The harvested split-thickness skin graft would be thin, often meshed, and laid directly onto this prepared bed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (2018): Recommends early excision and grafting for full-thickness burns to reduce morbidity and mortality.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | awaiting desloughing and performing secondary suture. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | using a split skin graft as a dressing, stat. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | excision and applying a split skin graft. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | excision and using a flap graft. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | performing tangential excision and applying a split skin graft under tourni | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) excision and applying a split skin graft.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
