  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Listen for the hum, then scan the flow – arterial disease will show!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers are A (auscultation) and B (duplex imaging). These options represent fundamental and commonly employed methods for the initial investigation and diagnosis of arterial disease, ranging from basic physical examination to advanced non-invasive imaging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAuscultation is a crucial component of the physical exam, where listening for bruits (turbulent flow sounds) over arteries can indicate underlying stenosis or aneurysm. Duplex imaging, combining B-mode ultrasound with Doppler flow analysis, is a cornerstone non-invasive diagnostic tool. It allows for direct visualization of arterial walls, plaque morphology, and measurement of blood flow velocities, providing detailed information about the presence, severity, and location of arterial stenoses or occlusions without the risks associated with invasive procedures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Angioplasty is an interventional therapeutic procedure used to treat arterial stenosis, not a method for investigation or diagnosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Digital subtraction angiography (DSA) is an invasive imaging technique that provides detailed visualization of arterial anatomy and pathology. While diagnostic, it is typically reserved for cases where non-invasive imaging is inconclusive or when intervention is planned, due to its associated risks (e.g., radiation, contrast nephropathy, access site complications). It is not considered a primary or initial investigative method in the same category as auscultation or duplex imaging for routine screening or diagnosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Myelography is a diagnostic procedure used to visualize the spinal cord and nerve roots, primarily for neurological conditions, and has no role in the investigation of arterial disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Method             | Type          | Role in Arterial Disease Investigation                                                              | Advantages                                   | Disadvantages                                     |\n|--------------------|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Auscultation       | Physical Exam | Initial screening for bruits (turbulent flow) indicating stenosis or aneurysm.                      | Non-invasive, quick, no equipment needed.    | Subjective, low sensitivity/specificity.          |\n| Duplex Ultrasound  | Non-invasive  | First-line imaging for visualizing vessel anatomy, plaque, and assessing blood flow dynamics.     | Non-invasive, real-time, no radiation/contrast.  | Operator-dependent, limited by body habitus.      |\n| CTA/MRA            | Non-invasive  | Detailed anatomical mapping, 3D reconstruction, pre-operative planning.                           | High resolution, comprehensive view.         | Radiation (CTA), contrast (both), cost, MRI contraindications. |\n| DSA                | Invasive      | Gold standard for luminal imaging, often performed immediately prior to or during intervention.   | Highest resolution, dynamic flow assessment. | Invasive, radiation, contrast nephropathy, access site risks. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Initial arterial disease workup: auscultation, then non-invasive duplex ultrasound.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn duplex ultrasound, arterial disease manifests as focal plaque, increased peak systolic velocities at stenoses, post-stenotic turbulence, and dampened waveforms distal to significant lesions. DSA would show luminal narrowing, occlusions, and collateral vessel formation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease: Recommends ankle-brachial index (ABI) as an initial screening tool and duplex ultrasound as the primary non-invasive imaging modality for diagnosis and surveillance.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | auscultation. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | duplex imaging. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | angioplasty. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | digital subtraction angiography. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | myelography. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B) auscultation., duplex imaging.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
