  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Occlude with intent, not by accident!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis answer is correct as it accurately identifies multiple common materials employed in therapeutic embolization procedures. Therapeutic embolism aims to intentionally occlude blood vessels to treat various conditions, and the choice of material depends on the desired permanence and target vessel characteristics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTherapeutic embolization relies on diverse materials to achieve vessel occlusion. Gel foam sponge is a temporary particulate agent that provides mechanical occlusion and promotes thrombosis. Detachable balloons offer temporary or permanent occlusion, often used for flow arrest or vessel sacrifice. Stainless steel coils are permanent mechanical occlusive devices, inducing thrombosis and fibrosis. Ethyl alcohol is a potent liquid sclerosant, causing endothelial damage, thrombosis, and permanent vessel obliteration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A blood clot is a naturally occurring embolus, not a material *used* or intentionally introduced for therapeutic embolization. Introducing a patient's own blood clot would be uncontrolled and carry significant risks.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Embolic Agent Type | Examples | Mechanism | Permanence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Particulate | Gelfoam, PVA, Microspheres | Mechanical occlusion, thrombosis | Temporary to Permanent |\n| Liquid | Absolute Ethanol, Onyx, Glubran | Sclerosis, polymerization, thrombosis | Permanent |\n| Mechanical | Coils, Plugs, Balloons | Mechanical occlusion, thrombosis | Permanent (Coils/Plugs), Temporary/Permanent (Balloons) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Embolic agents vary by permanence, mechanism, and target vessel size.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn fluoroscopy, coils are radiopaque and immediately visible. Liquid embolics like Onyx are often mixed with tantalum for radiopacity. Gelfoam is radiolucent but its effect is seen by flow cessation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety of Interventional Radiology (SIR) Clinical Practice Guidelines (e.g., 2017) recommend specific embolic agents based on the clinical indication and target vessel characteristics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | blood clot. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | gel foam sponge. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | balloons. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | stainless steel coils. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | ethyl alcohol. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D, E) gel foam sponge., balloons., stainless steel coils., ethyl alcohol.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
