  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let GCA steal their sight; biopsy and treat with all your might!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, D, and E. Temporal arteritis, also known as Giant Cell Arteritis (GCA), is a systemic vasculitis primarily affecting large and medium-sized arteries. It is considered a collagen disease due to its inflammatory nature affecting the vessel wall, carries a significant risk of blindness, and requires surgical biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGCA is a granulomatous vasculitis characterized by inflammation of the arterial wall, often involving the internal elastic lamina and media, leading to intimal hyperplasia and luminal narrowing. This process can affect the ophthalmic artery, causing irreversible vision loss, making prompt diagnosis and treatment critical. The gold standard for diagnosis remains a temporal artery biopsy, which typically reveals inflammatory infiltrates, giant cells, and disruption of the internal elastic lamina. It is often associated with polymyalgia rheumatica.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Takayasu’s arteritis is a distinct large-vessel vasculitis primarily affecting the aorta and its major branches, typically in younger women, and is not a feature or variety of GCA.\nOption C (Incorrect): Buerger’s disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) is a segmental, inflammatory, non-atherosclerotic vasculitis affecting small and medium-sized arteries and veins of the extremities, distinct from GCA.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Temporal Arteritis (GCA) | Takayasu's Arteritis | Buerger's Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Affected Vessels** | Large/medium arteries (temporal, ophthalmic, aorta) | Aorta & major branches | Small/medium arteries/veins (extremities) |\n| **Demographics** | Elderly (>50, F>M) | Young adults (<40, F>M) | Young/middle-aged male smokers |\n| **Key Complications** | Blindness, stroke, aortic aneurysm | Claudication, stroke, hypertension | Ischemic ulcers, gangrene, autoamputation |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Granulomatous vasculitis | Granulomatous vasculitis | Inflammatory, non-atherosclerotic vasculitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: GCA: Old, blind, biopsy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a 'halo sign' (hypoechoic thickening of the vessel wall) can be seen. In the OR, the temporal artery may appear thickened, nodular, and non-pulsatile.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) 2021 Guideline for the Management of Giant Cell Arteritis. It recommends prompt initiation of high-dose glucocorticoids and consideration of adjunctive therapies like tocilizumab, along with temporal artery biopsy for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a local collagen disease. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | a feature of Takayasu’s arteriopathy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | a variety of Buerger’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | associated with blindness. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | confirmed by surgical biopsy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) a local collagen disease., associated with blindness., confirmed by surgical biopsy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
