  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let DIY efforts lead to a thrombotic dilemma!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer (A, C, E) is correct. Axillary vein thrombosis, often seen in active individuals, can result from repetitive arm movements (DIY activities), leading to local pain and swelling. Early anticoagulation is crucial to prevent propagation and complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAxillary vein thrombosis (AVT), particularly Paget-Schroetter syndrome, is an \"effort thrombosis\" of the upper extremity. It commonly affects young, otherwise healthy individuals involved in strenuous or repetitive overhead arm activities, such as DIY, sports, or occupational tasks, leading to compression of the subclavian-axillary vein at the thoracic outlet. This compression, combined with endothelial injury and hypercoagulability, precipitates thrombus formation. Symptoms include arm pain, swelling, and discoloration. Early diagnosis and prompt initiation of anticoagulation are vital to prevent thrombus propagation, reduce post-thrombotic syndrome, and facilitate potential thrombolysis or surgical decompression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Homan's sign is a clinical sign for deep vein thrombosis (DVT) of the lower extremity, involving pain in the calf upon dorsiflexion of the foot. It is not applicable to upper extremity thrombosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Raynaud's phenomenon is a vasospastic disorder affecting small arteries and arterioles, typically in the fingers and toes, causing color changes. While thoracic outlet syndrome can sometimes be associated with neurogenic or arterial symptoms, axillary vein thrombosis itself does not directly cause Raynaud's phenomenon.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Upper Extremity DVT (UEDVT) | Lower Extremity DVT (LEDVT) | Raynaud's Phenomenon |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Common Cause | Effort/Thoracic Outlet Syndrome | Immobility/Surgery/Malignancy | Vasospasm/Connective Tissue Disease |\n| Symptoms | Arm swelling, pain, discoloration | Leg swelling, pain, tenderness | Digital pallor, cyanosis, rubor |\n| Diagnostic Test | Duplex Ultrasound | Duplex Ultrasound | Cold stimulation test, nailfold capillaroscopy |\n| Treatment | Anticoagulation, +/- thrombolysis/decompression | Anticoagulation | Avoidance of cold, vasodilators |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Upper extremity DVT often means \"effort thrombosis\" in active patients.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is the first-line imaging, showing non-compressible, echogenic thrombus within the axillary vein. Venography can confirm diagnosis and delineate extent, often revealing extrinsic compression at the thoracic outlet.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 Guidelines for the Management of Venous Thromboembolism: Treatment of Deep Vein Thrombosis and Pulmonary Embolism. Recommends anticoagulation for UEDVT and considers thrombolysis or surgical decompression for Paget-Schroetter syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is associated with DIY activities. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | gives a positive Homan’s sign. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | causes pain in the forearm. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is a recognised cause of Raynaud’s phenomenon. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | can be limited by early anticoagulant therapy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) is associated with DIY activities., causes pain in the forearm., can be limited by early anticoagulant therapy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
