  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let filariasis worm its way into your blind spots!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Options C and D are correct. Lymphatic filariasis, primarily caused by Wuchereria bancrofti and Brugia malayi, is diagnosed by detecting microfilariae in blood, often requiring nocturnal sampling due to their periodicity. The lymphatic obstruction caused by these parasites can lead to chylous reflux.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe microfilariae of Wuchereria bancrofti and Brugia malayi exhibit nocturnal periodicity, meaning they are most abundant in peripheral blood between 10 PM and 2 AM, making a nocturnal blood smear the most effective diagnostic method. The adult worms reside in lymphatic vessels, causing inflammation and obstruction. This chronic obstruction leads to lymphatic dilation and rupture, allowing chyle (lymph rich in triglycerides) to leak into various body cavities or organs, manifesting as chylous ascites, chyluria, or chylous reflux.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Filariasis is caused by nematodes (roundworms), not cestodes (tapeworms).\nOption B (Incorrect): While Anopheles mosquitoes can transmit Wuchereria bancrofti in some regions, Culex and Aedes mosquitoes are also significant vectors for lymphatic filariasis. The statement is not exclusively true.\nOption E (Incorrect): Elephantiasis is severe lymphedema and skin thickening due to lymphatic obstruction. Elephantiasis neuromatosa refers to nerve tissue overgrowth, typically seen in neurofibromatosis, and is unrelated to filariasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Filarial Worm | Vector | Key Manifestations | Diagnostic Timing |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Wuchereria bancrofti | Culex, Anopheles, Aedes | Elephantiasis, hydrocele, chyluria | Nocturnal |\n| Brugia malayi | Mansonia, Anopheles | Elephantiasis (distal limbs) | Nocturnal |\n| Loa loa | Chrysops (deer fly) | Calabar swellings, eye worm | Diurnal |\n| Onchocerca volvulus | Simulium (blackfly) | River blindness, onchocercomas | Skin snips (nocturnal/diurnal not relevant) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Filariasis: Nocturnal blood smear, chylous reflux, mosquito vector.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the 'filarial dance sign' can be observed, representing the movement of live adult worms within dilated lymphatic vessels. Intraoperatively, severely dilated and obstructed lymphatic channels filled with chyle may be encountered.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the Global Programme to Eliminate Lymphatic Filariasis (GPELF), updated periodically. They recommend mass drug administration (MDA) and morbidity management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is caused by a cestode worm. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is spread by one of the anopheles group of mosquito. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | can be diagnosed on a nocturnal blood smear. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | causes chylous reflux. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | causes elephantiasis neuromatosa. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) can be diagnosed on a nocturnal blood smear.\ncauses chylous reflux.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
