  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hodgkin's: The RS cell throws a party, and eosinophils always show up!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe histological hallmark of Hodgkin's lymphoma is the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells amidst a rich reactive inflammatory infiltrate. This infiltrate frequently includes eosinophils and various stromal cells, often referred to as reticulum cells, which contribute significantly to the characteristic microscopic appearance.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHodgkin's lymphoma is unique among lymphomas as the malignant cells (Reed-Sternberg cells, derived from B-lymphocytes) constitute a minority of the tumor mass. The vast majority of the tissue consists of reactive inflammatory cells, including lymphocytes, plasma cells, macrophages, and notably, eosinophils. Reed-Sternberg cells secrete various cytokines, such as IL-5, which specifically attract eosinophils, contributing to the systemic symptoms and characteristic histology. Reticulum cells, which are essentially stromal fibroblasts, are also an integral part of this reactive microenvironment, providing structural support and interacting with the inflammatory cells.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Langerhans’ cells are antigen-presenting cells found in the skin and other tissues, and their proliferation is characteristic of Langerhans cell histiocytosis, not Hodgkin's lymphoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hassall’s corpuscles are epithelial structures found in the medulla of the thymus, playing a role in T-cell education, and are not a feature of Hodgkin's lymphoma histology.\nOption E (Incorrect): Acanthotic cells refer to the thickening of the stratum spinosum of the epidermis, a dermatological term, and are unrelated to the histology of Hodgkin's lymphoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Association | Key Feature/Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| Reed-Sternberg Cell | Hodgkin Lymphoma | Malignant B-cell derivative, diagnostic hallmark (owl-eye nuclei) |\n| Eosinophils | Hodgkin Lymphoma | Reactive inflammatory cell, attracted by IL-5 from RS cells |\n| Reticulum Cells | Hodgkin Lymphoma | Stromal/fibroblastic cells, part of reactive microenvironment |\n| Langerhans' Cells | Langerhans Cell Histiocytosis | Dendritic cells with Birbeck granules |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hodgkin's lymphoma: RS cells are the stars, but eosinophils and reticulum cells are their reactive entourage.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, Hodgkin's lymphoma often presents as bulky mediastinal lymphadenopathy, sometimes with contiguous spread. Intraoperatively, affected lymph nodes may appear firm and rubbery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Classification of Tumours of Haematopoietic and Lymphoid Tissues (5th Edition, 2022). It provides the definitive diagnostic criteria and classification for Hodgkin's lymphoma, including histological features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Langerhans’ cells. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | eosinophils. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | reticulum cells. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Hassall’s corpuscles. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | acanthotic cells. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) eosinophils.\nreticulum cells.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
