  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 See it, biopsy it, stage it: The lymphoma mantra.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies procedures that have been, or in specific circumstances, continue to be helpful in the assessment of lymphoma. This includes initial imaging, historical staging procedures, and methods to evaluate organ involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA chest x-ray remains a fundamental initial screening tool for lymphoma, capable of detecting mediastinal masses, hilar adenopathy, or pulmonary infiltrates, especially in Hodgkin lymphoma. While largely superseded by CT/PET-CT, intravenous urography historically played a role in assessing retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy causing ureteral obstruction or kidney involvement. Full laparotomy, though now rare, was once the gold standard for staging Hodgkin lymphoma and can still be employed in select cases for definitive diagnosis when less invasive methods fail, or for therapeutic splenectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Tonsillectomy is a therapeutic surgical procedure for tonsillar disease, not a primary diagnostic assessment tool for lymphoma, unless a specific tonsillar biopsy is indicated. Option E (Incorrect): Block dissection of glands of the neck is a therapeutic lymphadenectomy performed for known disease, not a primary diagnostic procedure for initial lymphoma assessment. Biopsy of a single node is diagnostic, but block dissection is treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure Type | Current Role in Lymphoma Assessment | Key Finding/Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Chest X-ray** | Initial screening for mediastinal/pulmonary involvement | Mediastinal widening, hilar adenopathy, parenchymal lesions |\n| **CT/PET-CT** | Primary staging and response assessment | Metabolic activity, size, and location of lymph nodes/extranodal disease |\n| **Excisional Biopsy** | Gold standard for definitive diagnosis | Provides sufficient tissue for histopathology, immunohistochemistry, flow cytometry |\n| **Staging Laparotomy** | Rarely performed; historical gold standard | Definitive tissue diagnosis and staging (e.g., spleen, liver, lymph nodes) when non-invasive methods are inadequate |\n| **Intravenous Urography** | Largely obsolete; historical role | Indirect evidence of retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy (e.g., hydronephrosis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lymphoma assessment requires tissue diagnosis and comprehensive staging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a chest x-ray, a common finding in lymphoma is a widened mediastinum due to bulky mediastinal lymphadenopathy. During a laparotomy for lymphoma, one might observe significantly enlarged, rubbery lymph nodes in the retroperitoneum or mesentery, and often splenomegaly.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hodgkin Lymphoma and Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma (latest version) recommend PET-CT as the primary staging modality and excisional biopsy for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | chest x-ray. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | intravenous urography. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | full laparotomy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | tonsillectomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | block dissection of glands of the neck. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) chest x-ray.\nintravenous urography.\nfull laparotomy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
