  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bone healing is a symphony; infection and distraction are discordant notes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options identify key factors that impede the normal progression of fracture healing, leading to a delayed union. Delayed union occurs when a fracture takes longer than the expected time frame to heal, but still shows signs of progression towards union.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFracture healing is a complex biological process requiring adequate blood supply, stability, and a sterile environment. Compound fractures introduce contamination and significant soft tissue damage, compromising the local biology and increasing infection risk. Infection directly inhibits osteogenesis and can lead to osteomyelitis, preventing callus formation. Distraction, or excessive separation of fracture fragments, mechanically prevents the formation of a bridging callus, as osteogenic cells cannot span the gap effectively.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Ankylosis is the stiffening and immobility of a joint due to fusion of bones, not a cause of delayed fracture union. It is a joint pathology, not a factor directly impeding bone healing. \nOption D (Incorrect): While severe systemic illnesses can generally impair healing, uraemia (kidney failure) is more commonly associated with renal osteodystrophy and metabolic bone disease, affecting bone quality. It is not considered a primary, direct cause of delayed union in the same manner as local factors like infection or distraction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Delayed Union | Non-Union | Malunion |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Definition | Heals slower than expected, but will eventually heal | Permanent failure of healing, no further progression | Heals in an unacceptable anatomical or functional position |\n| Prognosis | Good with continued support/time | Requires intervention (surgery, bone graft) | May require corrective osteotomy |\n| Key Causes | Infection, distraction, poor blood supply, systemic factors | Persistent motion, infection, large gap, severe soft tissue loss | Inadequate reduction, unstable fixation, premature weight-bearing |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think local (infection, gap, blood supply) and systemic (nutrition, smoking, comorbidities) for healing issues.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, you would see a persistent fracture line with minimal or no bridging callus formation at a time when union would typically be expected. Intraoperatively, signs might include granulation tissue, pus (if infected), or an obvious gap between fragments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAOS Clinical Practice Guidelines (various years): Emphasize meticulous surgical technique, infection prevention, and stable fixation to promote timely union.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | compound fracture. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | infection. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | ankylosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | uraemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | distraction. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) compound fracture.\ninfection.\ndistraction.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
