  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out – for compartment syndrome!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A (gross swelling) and D (acute pain on employing the stretch test) are correct. Acute compartment syndrome (ACS) is a surgical emergency characterized by increased pressure within a closed osteofascial compartment, leading to compromised tissue perfusion and potential irreversible damage. Gross swelling indicates fluid accumulation and increased pressure, while pain with passive stretch is a classic and reliable early symptom of muscle ischemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute compartment syndrome arises when the interstitial pressure within a confined fascial space exceeds the capillary perfusion pressure, leading to tissue ischemia. The lower leg contains four distinct compartments, each with its own fascial boundaries. Gross swelling is a direct manifestation of increased volume within these non-distensible compartments. The hallmark symptom, acute pain on passive stretch, occurs because stretching ischemic muscle fibers exacerbates their metabolic demand and pain, often disproportionate to the injury itself. This pain is a critical early indicator, as it reflects the compromised microcirculation and impending tissue necrosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (normal pulses): Incorrect. Distal pulses are typically normal in acute compartment syndrome because arterial pressure usually exceeds compartment pressure, and major arteries often run outside or are less susceptible to compression until very late stages. Pulselessness is a very late and ominous sign.\nOption C (normal sensation distally): Incorrect. Paresthesia (numbness or tingling) is a common early sign of nerve ischemia within the affected compartment, making normal sensation unlikely.\nOption E (venous occlusion): Incorrect. While increased compartment pressure can impede venous outflow, contributing to swelling, complete venous occlusion is not a primary or defining characteristic feature of ACS. The critical issue is tissue ischemia due to compromised microcirculation, not necessarily macroscopic venous occlusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign/Symptom | Description | Relevance to ACS |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain (out of proportion) | Severe pain, especially with passive stretch | Most reliable and earliest clinical sign |\n| Paresthesia | Numbness, tingling, altered sensation | Indicates nerve ischemia, often an early sign |\n| Pallor | Pale or dusky skin | Late sign, indicates severe ischemia and poor perfusion |\n| Pulselessness | Absent distal pulses | Very late and ominous sign, often irreversible damage has occurred |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pain out of proportion and with passive stretch is the hallmark of ACS.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging is not diagnostic for ACS; direct compartment pressure measurement is key. Intraoperatively, fasciotomy reveals bulging, tense, often pale or dusky muscle that does not contract when stimulated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Acute Compartment Syndrome (2019). Recommends early diagnosis based on clinical suspicion and compartment pressure measurement, followed by emergent fasciotomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | gross swelling. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | normal pulses. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | normal sensation distally. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | acute pain on employing the stretch test. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | venous occlusion. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D) gross swelling.\nacute pain on employing the stretch test.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
