  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fractures heal, but their shadows can linger.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies hypertrophic non-union, Sudeck’s atrophy (Complex Regional Pain Syndrome Type I), and myositis ossificans as recognized late complications of fractures. These conditions represent distinct pathological processes that can significantly impair recovery long after the initial injury has occurred.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic non-union occurs when a fracture fails to heal despite an adequate biological response, often due to excessive motion at the fracture site, leading to abundant but unmineralized callus. Sudeck’s atrophy, or CRPS Type I, is a debilitating neuropathic pain syndrome characterized by autonomic dysfunction, sensory changes, and trophic changes, often triggered by extremity fractures. Myositis ossificans involves heterotopic bone formation within muscle tissue, typically following severe contusions or fractures, particularly around large joints, leading to pain and restricted range of motion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Dupuytren’s contracture is a fibromatosis of the palmar fascia, primarily idiopathic, and not a direct or recognized late complication of fractures, although trauma can sometimes be a precipitating factor in predisposed individuals.\nOption E (Incorrect): Osteitis fibrosa cystica is a skeletal manifestation of hyperparathyroidism, characterized by increased osteoclastic activity and fibrous replacement of bone, and is unrelated to fracture healing or its complications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Definition | Key Feature | Management Principle |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hypertrophic Non-union | Failure of fracture healing with abundant callus | \"Elephant's foot\" appearance on X-ray | Stabilize fracture (e.g., rigid fixation) |\n| Sudeck's Atrophy (CRPS I) | Chronic neuropathic pain syndrome after trauma | Pain out of proportion, autonomic dysfunction | Multimodal approach (PT, meds, blocks) |\n| Myositis Ossificans | Heterotopic bone formation in muscle | Pain, swelling, decreased ROM near joint | Rest, NSAIDs, surgical excision (late) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Late fracture complications span mechanical failure, neuropathic pain, and heterotopic tissue formation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, hypertrophic non-union shows a widened fracture gap with sclerotic, rounded bone ends and abundant callus. Sudeck's atrophy (CRPS) may show patchy osteopenia on X-ray. Myositis ossificans appears as a soft tissue mass with peripheral calcification on X-ray or CT, often with a lucent center in early stages.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (2018) recommends early diagnosis and multimodal treatment for CRPS, a key late complication.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dupuytrens’s contracture. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | hypertrophic non-union. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Sudeck’s atrophy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | myositis ossificans. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | osteitis fibrosa cystica. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D) hypertrophic non-union.\nSudeck’s atrophy.\nmyositis ossificans.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
