  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cartilage: once broken, forever changed.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis answer is correct because articular cartilage, being avascular and aneural, has a very limited capacity for true hyaline cartilage repair. Instead, defects are often filled with biomechanically inferior fibrocartilage, and mechanical symptoms like locking are common due to fragments or unstable flaps.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nArticular cartilage is a specialized connective tissue, primarily composed of chondrocytes embedded in an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and proteoglycans. Its avascular, aneural, and alymphatic nature severely limits its intrinsic healing potential. When injured, chondrocytes have a minimal proliferative response, and the repair tissue that forms is typically fibrocartilage, which lacks the organized structure and biomechanical properties of native hyaline cartilage, leading to progressive degeneration. Mechanical symptoms such as locking arise from unstable cartilage flaps or loose bodies interfering with joint mechanics.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Muscle wasting surrounding an injured joint is very common due to pain, disuse, and reflex inhibition, leading to arthrogenic muscle inhibition.\nOption E (Incorrect): Blood within the joint (hemarthrosis) contains clotting factors and will clot, potentially forming adhesions and contributing to joint stiffness and pain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hyaline Cartilage (Native) | Fibrocartilage (Repair) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Composition | Type II collagen, high proteoglycan content | Type I collagen, lower proteoglycan content |\n| Structure | Smooth, organized, resilient | Disorganized, less resilient |\n| Healing Potential | Very limited intrinsic repair | Forms as a repair tissue, but inferior |\n| Biomechanics | Excellent load-bearing, low friction | Poorer load-bearing, higher friction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Articular cartilage injury leads to poor healing, fibrocartilage repair, and mechanical symptoms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, articular cartilage injuries appear as focal defects or signal changes, often with associated subchondral bone edema. Arthroscopically, one would observe the cartilage defect, potentially with unstable flaps, fibrillation, or loose bodies within the joint space.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAOS Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Osteochondral Lesions of the Knee (2017) recommends considering surgical intervention for symptomatic osteochondral lesions failing conservative management, with various repair and restoration techniques available.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | true healing does not occur. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the defect is filled with fibrocartilage. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | muscle wasting surrounding the joint is unusual. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | locking can occur. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | blood within the joint will not clot. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) true healing does not occur.\nthe defect is filled with fibrocartilage.\nlocking can occur.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
