  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A wobbly joint means the rope is broken.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, mechanical instability. This is the most specific and diagnostic sign of a complete joint ligament rupture because ligaments are primary static stabilizers, and their failure directly results in abnormal joint motion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLigaments are strong, fibrous bands of connective tissue that connect bones and provide passive stability to joints by limiting excessive or abnormal movements. When a ligament is completely ruptured, its ability to restrict these movements is lost, leading to demonstrable mechanical instability. This instability can manifest as excessive translation, rotation, or gapping of the joint under stress, which is a direct functional consequence of the ligament's structural failure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Local tenderness is a general sign of injury or inflammation and is not specific to a complete ligament rupture; it can occur with sprains, contusions, or fractures.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pain when the ligament is stressed indicates injury to the ligament, but not necessarily a complete rupture. A partial tear (sprain) would also cause pain with stress, and a complete rupture might paradoxically cause less pain with stress than a partial tear due to complete disruption of nerve fibers.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bruising (ecchymosis) indicates hemorrhage, which is common with many types of trauma, including contusions, fractures, and sprains, not exclusively a ligament rupture.\nOption D (Incorrect): Local swelling (effusion or edema) is a non-specific inflammatory response to injury and can occur with any joint trauma, including minor sprains or contusions, without a complete ligament rupture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ligament Sprain (Partial Tear) | Ligament Rupture (Complete Tear) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Pain** | Often severe, especially with stress | Can be severe initially, may lessen with complete disruption |\n| **Swelling/Bruising** | Present, variable | Often more pronounced |\n| **Tenderness** | Localized | Localized |\n| **Mechanical Instability** | Absent or mild laxity | **Definitely present and demonstrable** |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Instability is the hallmark of a complete ligament rupture.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a complete ligament rupture will show discontinuity of the ligament fibers, often with surrounding edema and hemorrhage. Intraoperatively, direct visualization will reveal a completely torn or avulsed ligament, allowing for abnormal joint motion when stressed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines (e.g., for ACL Injury, 2014) emphasize clinical examination for instability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | local tenderness. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pain when ligament is stressed. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | bruising. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | local swelling. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | mechanical instability. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) mechanical instability.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
