  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Clavicle breaks: muscles pull, non-union can follow. Know your anatomy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers highlight key characteristics of midshaft clavicle fractures: significant displacement due to muscle pull and the potential for non-union. Understanding these aspects is crucial for proper diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMidshaft clavicle fractures are prone to significant displacement because the sternocleidomastoid muscle pulls the medial fragment superiorly, while the deltoid and pectoralis major muscles pull the lateral fragment inferiorly and medially. This inherent instability, combined with the clavicle's subcutaneous location and high stress, contributes to a notable incidence of non-union, particularly in cases of severe displacement, comminution, or inadequate immobilization. Non-union rates can range from 5-15% in non-operatively treated displaced fractures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The coraco-acromial ligament is part of the coracoacromial arch and is not typically ruptured in a midshaft clavicle fracture. It's more relevant to acromial fractures or severe AC joint injuries.\nOption C (Incorrect): While some clavicle fractures require reduction, not all midshaft fractures 'should' be reduced. Many non-displaced or minimally displaced fractures are successfully treated non-operatively without reduction.\nOption D (Incorrect): Malunion is actually quite common, especially with non-operative treatment of displaced fractures, leading to shortening, cosmetic deformity, and sometimes functional impairment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Non-Displaced Midshaft Clavicle Fracture | Displaced Midshaft Clavicle Fracture |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Treatment** | Often non-operative (sling, pain control) | May require operative fixation (plate/screws) |\n| **Displacement** | Minimal or none | Significant (due to muscle pull) |\n| **Non-union Risk** | Low | Higher (especially >2cm shortening, comminution) |\n| **Malunion Risk** | Low | Moderate to High (shortening, cosmetic deformity) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Clavicle fractures: think muscle pull for displacement, and non-union for complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, look for superior displacement of the medial fragment and inferior/medial displacement of the lateral fragment. Intraoperatively, achieving anatomical reduction and stable fixation is key to preventing non-union.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAOS Clinical Practice Guideline: The Treatment of Clavicle Fractures (2019). Recommends considering surgical fixation for significantly displaced midshaft clavicle fractures to improve functional outcomes and reduce non-union rates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the coraco-acromial ligament is ruptured. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | significant displacement of the bone ends is common. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | the fracture should be reduced. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | malunion is uncommon. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | non-union is possible. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, E) significant displacement of the bone ends is common.\nnon-union is possible.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
