  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial epicondyle: Don't miss the incarcerated fragment; mobilize early!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, B, D, and E accurately describe key features and management principles of a medial epicondyle fracture of the humerus. This injury is typically an avulsion, often with fragment rotation, necessitating surgical intervention for significant displacement or rotation, followed by early mobilization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMedial epicondyle fractures are classic avulsion injuries, commonly seen in children and adolescents, resulting from valgus stress or strong contraction of the forearm flexor-pronator mass. The fragment, which serves as the origin for these muscles and the ulnar collateral ligament, is frequently rotated due to muscle pull, sometimes even 180 degrees. Such significant rotation or displacement often requires operative re-attachment to restore anatomical alignment and function. Early active and passive range of motion is critical post-fixation to prevent elbow stiffness and promote optimal recovery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): The fragment of bone fortunately does not enter the elbow joint. This statement is incorrect because the medial epicondyle fragment can, and often does, become incarcerated within the elbow joint, particularly in association with an elbow dislocation. This complication is a significant indication for surgical intervention to reduce the fragment and restore joint congruity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Medial Epicondyle Fracture | Lateral Epicondyle Fracture |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Valgus stress, flexor-pronator avulsion | Varus stress, extensor avulsion (less common) |\n| Common Age | Children/Adolescents | Less common, can be associated with capitellum |\n| Fragment Rotation | Common, often significant | Less common |\n| Joint Incarceration | Frequent, especially with dislocation | Rare |\n| Nerve at Risk | Ulnar nerve | Radial nerve (less common) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial epicondyle fracture: Think avulsion, rotation, incarceration, and early motion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray (AP, lateral, and oblique views), look for displacement, rotation, and potential incarceration of the epicondyle fragment within the elbow joint, especially after reduction of a dislocation. Intraoperatively, the fragment may be found rotated 90-180 degrees, sometimes buttonholed through the joint capsule or trapped within the joint space.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Pediatric Elbow Fractures (2014, updated 2020) recommends surgical fixation for displaced (>2mm), rotated, or incarcerated medial epicondyle fractures, particularly in older children and adolescents, followed by early range of motion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | it is an avulsion injury. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the fragment of bone may be rotated. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | the fragment of bone fortunately does not enter the elbow joint. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | a rotated fragment requires operative re-attachment to the epicondyle. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | active and passive movements of the elbow joint should begin as soon as pos | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D, E) ['it is an avulsion injury.', 'the fragment of bone may be rotated.', 'a rotated fragment requires operative re-attachment to the epicondyle.', 'active and passive movements of the elbow joint should begin as soon as possible.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
