  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Elbow dislocations: common, posterolateral, check for coronoid.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the most common type of elbow dislocation and a frequently associated fracture. Elbow dislocations are typically posterolateral, and coronoid fractures are a critical associated injury that impacts stability.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nElbow dislocations most commonly occur from a fall on an outstretched hand (FOOSH) with the elbow in slight flexion and forearm supination, leading to a posterolateral rotatory mechanism. The coronoid process is a primary anterior stabilizer of the elbow; its fracture, especially larger fragments, significantly compromises stability and can lead to recurrent instability if not addressed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Falling on the point of the elbow typically causes olecranon fractures, not dislocations. Elbow dislocations are usually due to a fall on an outstretched hand (FOOSH).\nOption C (Incorrect): Divergent dislocation, where the radius and ulna separate, is extremely rare. Most dislocations involve both bones moving together relative to the humerus.\nOption E (Incorrect): While early motion is crucial, \"active exercises commenced 48 hours after reduction\" is often too aggressive. Protected range of motion or passive exercises are typically initiated early, with active exercises introduced more cautiously to prevent re-dislocation, especially in unstable injuries.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Common Elbow Dislocation | Divergent Elbow Dislocation | Associated Coronoid Fracture |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Type** | Posterolateral | Rare, radius and ulna separate | Common (up to 50%) |\n| **Mechanism** | FOOSH, valgus/supination | High-energy trauma | FOOSH, impaction |\n| **Stability Impact** | Ligamentous disruption | Severe instability | Anterior stability compromise |\n| **Management** | Closed reduction, early ROM | Often requires ORIF | Depends on fragment size/stability |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FOOSH + elbow pain = think posterolateral dislocation and associated fractures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn lateral X-ray, look for the \"dropped fat pad sign\" and disruption of the ulnohumeral articulation. Intraoperatively, assess for coronoid fracture size and stability after reduction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Elbow Dislocation (2015). Recommends early, protected range of motion after stable reduction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | occurs from falling on the point of the elbow. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is commonly a posterolateral dislocation. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can include divergent dislocation of the radius and ulna. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | can include fracture of the coronoid. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | is best managed by active exercises commenced 48 hours after reduction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D) ['is commonly a posterolateral dislocation.', 'can include fracture of the coronoid.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
