  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Colles' fracture: Dinner fork deformity, dorsally displaced and rotated.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers are A and B. A Colles' fracture is classically defined by the dorsal displacement and dorsal angulation (rotation) of the distal radial fragment. This characteristic deformity is crucial for diagnosis and understanding the injury mechanism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Colles' fracture typically results from a fall on an outstretched hand (FOOSH) with the wrist in extension. The impact causes a transverse fracture of the distal radius, usually within 2.5 cm of the articular surface. The characteristic 'dinner fork' deformity arises because the distal fragment is driven dorsally (posteriorly) and radially, and also angulates dorsally relative to the proximal fragment. This dorsal displacement and rotation are the hallmarks of the injury, distinguishing it from other distal radius fractures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): displaced medially. Colles' fractures typically involve radial displacement, not medial (ulnar) displacement.\nOption D (Incorrect): rotated medially. The rotation of the distal fragment in a Colles' fracture is dorsally (posteriorly), not medially.\nOption E (Incorrect): pronated. While the forearm might be pronated during the injury, the distal fragment itself does not characteristically pronate relative to the proximal fragment as a primary deformity in a Colles' fracture; the key rotational component is dorsal angulation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Mechanism | Distal Fragment Displacement/Angulation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Colles' | FOOSH, wrist extension | Dorsal displacement & dorsal angulation |\n| Smith's | FOOSH, wrist flexion (or direct blow to dorsum) | Volar displacement & volar angulation |\n| Barton's | Fall on extended, pronated wrist | Intra-articular, dorsal or volar rim fracture with carpal displacement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Colles' = Dorsal displacement + angulation. Smith's = Volar displacement + angulation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a lateral X-ray, you would observe the articular surface of the distal radius tilted dorsally (posteriorly) and the entire distal fragment displaced dorsally relative to the radial shaft. The radial length may also be shortened on the PA view.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Distal Radius Fractures (2017). Recommends considering surgical intervention for unstable fractures with significant displacement, angulation, or intra-articular involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | displaced dorsally. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | rotated dorsally. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | displaced medially. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | rotated medially. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | pronated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B) ['displaced dorsally.', 'rotated dorsally.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
