  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pelvic fractures: a bony break, a systemic shake.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer is ACCEPT because all listed options are well-recognized and significant complications associated with pelvic fractures. These injuries are high-energy traumas that can lead to a wide array of systemic and local sequelae, impacting multiple organ systems.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPelvic fractures often involve significant force, leading to disruption of the bony pelvis and surrounding soft tissues. This can cause massive hemorrhage from venous plexuses and arterial branches (e.g., internal iliac artery), direct injury to adjacent organs like the bladder and bowel, and create a pro-thrombotic state due to immobility and tissue damage. Long-term, improper healing can result in malunion, affecting gait and function, while bowel entrapment can occur due to fracture displacement or hematoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options (A, B, C, D, E) are correct complications of pelvic fractures. There are no incorrect options in this list.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Specific Example | Mechanism | Management Principle |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hemorrhagic | Blood loss | Disruption of venous plexuses/arteries | Resuscitation, pelvic binder, embolization, external fixation |\n| Urogenital | Bladder injuries | Direct trauma, shear forces | Foley catheter, surgical repair (if indicated) |\n| Thromboembolic | DVT | Immobility, hypercoagulability, venous stasis | Prophylaxis (pharmacologic/mechanical), early mobilization |\n| Musculoskeletal | Malunion | Inadequate reduction/fixation, poor healing | Corrective osteotomy, rehabilitation |\n| Gastrointestinal | Bowel entrapment | Fracture displacement, hematoma, adhesions | Surgical exploration, reduction/repair |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvic fractures are not just bone breaks; they're systemic threats.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, look for extravasation of contrast (active bleeding), bladder wall disruption, or bowel loops within fracture fragments. Intraoperatively, massive retroperitoneal hematoma is common.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) Guidelines, 10th Edition (2018). Recommends immediate assessment for hemorrhage, pelvic stabilization, and early identification of associated injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | blood loss. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | bladder injuries. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | DVT. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | malunion. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | bowel entrapment. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, D, E) ['blood loss.', 'bladder injuries.', 'DVT.', 'malunion.', 'bowel entrapment.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
