  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Time is hip: Reduce posterior dislocations ASAP to save the head!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key clinical features, management principles, and potential complications of posterior hip dislocation. The classic presentation involves a flexed, adducted, and internally rotated leg, and prompt reduction is crucial to minimize the risk of avascular necrosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPosterior hip dislocation, often resulting from high-energy trauma like a dashboard injury, occurs when the femoral head is driven posteriorly out of the acetabulum. The characteristic position of the limb—flexed, adducted, and internally rotated—is due to the pull of intact muscles and the position of the femoral head relative to the acetabulum. Acute, uncomplicated dislocations are often amenable to closed reduction under sedation, making reduction 'usually easy' if performed promptly. However, the blood supply to the femoral head, particularly the medial circumflex femoral artery, is vulnerable during dislocation, and prolonged ischemia due to delayed reduction significantly increases the risk of avascular necrosis, with rates approaching 50% if reduction is delayed beyond 6-12 hours.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The leg is typically adducted, not abducted, in a posterior hip dislocation due to the pull of the adductor muscles and the posterior displacement of the femoral head.\nOption C (Incorrect): The leg is typically internally rotated, not externally rotated, in a posterior hip dislocation. External rotation is characteristic of anterior hip dislocations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Posterior Hip Dislocation | Anterior Hip Dislocation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Dashboard injury, axial load on flexed hip | Abduction and external rotation force |\n| Limb Position | Flexed, adducted, internally rotated | Flexed, abducted, externally rotated |\n| Femoral Head Location | Posterior and superior to acetabulum | Anterior and inferior to acetabulum |\n| AVN Risk | High, especially with delayed reduction | Lower than posterior, but still possible |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Posterior hip = flexed, adducted, internally rotated. Reduce fast or risk AVN.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs (AP pelvis and lateral views), the femoral head will appear superior and posterior to the acetabulum, often appearing smaller due to magnification effects, and Shenton's line will be disrupted. Intraoperatively (if open reduction is needed), one might see a torn posterior capsule, labral tears, or osteochondral fragments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nOrthopaedic Trauma Association (OTA) Practice Management Guidelines for Hip Dislocation (2014). Recommends emergent reduction within 6 hours to minimize complications like avascular necrosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the leg is flexed. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the leg is abducted. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the leg is externally rotated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | reduction is usually easy. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | 50% of dislocations are followed by avascular necrosis of the femoral head  | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) ['the leg is flexed.', 'reduction is usually easy.', '50% of dislocations are followed by avascular necrosis of the femoral head if there is delay in reduction.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
