  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Intracapsular hip: Blood supply's the key, surgery's the decree.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options accurately describe key aspects of intracapsular femoral neck fractures, including their potential for impaction, classic clinical presentation when unimpacted, and the general principle of surgical management. This question tests a comprehensive understanding of these common and critical injuries.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntracapsular femoral neck fractures are notorious for their precarious blood supply, primarily from the medial and lateral circumflex femoral arteries. An unimpacted fracture severely disrupts this, leading to the classic shortened, externally rotated limb due to muscle spasm and instability. While rare, an impacted fracture in abduction can be relatively stable, sometimes allowing for non-operative consideration, though surgical fixation is still often preferred to prevent displacement and complications. Due to the high risk of avascular necrosis and non-union, surgical management is almost invariably indicated.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While intracapsular fractures are common in the elderly, they can also occur in younger individuals due to high-energy trauma, making the term \"always\" incorrect.\nOption E (Incorrect): Unimpacted intracapsular fractures are highly unstable and have a significant risk of non-union and avascular necrosis due to the severe disruption of the femoral head's blood supply.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Impacted Intracapsular | Unimpacted Intracapsular |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stability | Relatively stable (often valgus) | Unstable (displaced) |\n| Blood Supply Risk | Lower risk of complete disruption | High risk of complete disruption |\n| Clinical Presentation | Less obvious deformity, pain | Shortened, externally rotated leg |\n| Risk of Non-union/AVN | Present, but lower than unimpacted | High (up to 30-40% for AVN) |\n| Management | Often surgical fixation (screws) to prevent displacement | Surgical (ORIF, Hemiarthroplasty, THA) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unimpacted femoral neck fractures: shortened, externally rotated, and always operated.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, look for the Garden classification (I-IV) to assess displacement and guide treatment. Intraoperatively, ensure anatomical reduction before fixation with cannulated screws or consider arthroplasty based on patient age and fracture type.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults (2020). Recommends surgical treatment for most femoral neck fractures, with choice of procedure guided by fracture displacement and patient factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | always occur in elderly women and men. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | may be impacted in abduction. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | when unimpacted are recognised by a shortened leg that lies in external rot | ✅ Correct |\n| D | are invariably operated on. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | if unimpacted are unlikely to be followed by non-union. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D) ['may be impacted in abduction.', 'when unimpacted are recognised by a shortened leg that lies in external rotation.', 'are invariably operated on.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
