  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No blood, no bone: AVN is an infarct, not just a pain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the fundamental pathology of avascular necrosis (AVN) of the femoral head as bone infarction and lists common etiologies. AVN is a critical condition leading to joint destruction if not managed appropriately.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAvascular necrosis (AVN) of the femoral head results from the disruption of blood supply to the bone, leading to the death of osteocytes and marrow cells (infarction). This initial ischemic event is the defining characteristic. Systemic steroid therapy is a well-established risk factor, likely due to fat emboli, vasculitis, or altered lipid metabolism leading to vascular occlusion. Similarly, radiation therapy can cause obliterative endarteritis, damaging the blood vessels supplying the bone and leading to ischemia and subsequent necrosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While avascular necrosis often causes pain, especially with progression and subchondral collapse, the initial infarct itself may be asymptomatic. Pain is a symptom, not the primary pathological event of infarction.\nOption E (Incorrect): Early avascular necrosis is often radiographically occult. As the disease progresses, X-rays typically show increased radiodensity (sclerosis) due to dead bone and reactive new bone formation, or subchondral collapse (crescent sign), not increased radiolucency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Avascular Necrosis (AVN) | Osteoarthritis (OA) | Osteomyelitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pathology** | Ischemic death of bone | Cartilage degeneration | Bone infection |\n| **Key Causes** | Steroids, trauma, alcohol, radiation, sickle cell | Wear-and-tear, genetics, obesity, prior injury | Bacterial/fungal infection, open fractures, surgery |\n| **Imaging (X-ray)** | Sclerosis, crescent sign, collapse, normal early | Joint space narrowing, osteophytes, subchondral sclerosis | Lytic lesions, periosteal reaction, sequestrum/involucrum |\n| **Pain Onset** | Often sudden, insidious | Gradual, activity-related | Localized, acute, fever, systemic signs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: AVN = Infarction. Think steroids, trauma, alcohol, radiation as key causes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, early AVN may be normal, but later stages show increased radiodensity (sclerosis) and the classic 'crescent sign' (subchondral lucency) indicating impending collapse. MRI is the most sensitive imaging modality, showing characteristic low signal on T1-weighted images and variable signal on T2-weighted images, often with a 'double-line sign' at the interface of necrotic and viable bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines (e.g., Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults, 2021) provide recommendations for conditions that can lead to or be complicated by AVN, and general principles for hip preservation or replacement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the head has firstly been infarcted. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the infarct is painful. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | steroid therapy may be a cause. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | irradiation is a cause. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | infarction of bone shows on x-ray by increased radiolucency. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) ['the head has firstly been infarcted.', 'steroid therapy may be a cause.', 'irradiation is a cause.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
