  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Patella fractures: Don't miss the extensor mechanism!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, B, and C accurately describe common morphological classifications of patella fractures. These categories are fundamental for understanding the injury pattern and guiding appropriate treatment strategies for this critical component of the knee extensor mechanism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPatella fractures are typically classified based on their morphology, displacement, and comminution. Transverse fractures, often resulting from indirect forces like sudden quadriceps contraction, are the most common type and frequently require surgical fixation due to displacement. Vertical fractures, less common, usually result from direct trauma and are often undisplaced, amenable to conservative management. Osteochondral fractures involve articular cartilage and subchondral bone, often occurring with patellar dislocation, and require careful assessment for fragment fixation to restore joint congruity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): The Salter-Harris classification system is specifically used for fractures involving the growth plates (physes) in skeletally immature patients, which is not applicable to typical adult patella fractures. \nOption E (Incorrect): While stress fractures of the patella can occur, 'fatigue fracture' describes a mechanism of injury (overuse) rather than a primary morphological classification type for patella fractures in the same vein as transverse or vertical.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Mechanism | Key Feature | Treatment Principle |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Transverse | Indirect (quads contraction) | Most common, often displaced | ORIF (tension band wiring) |\n| Vertical | Direct trauma | Less common, often undisplaced | Conservative (immobilization) |\n| Comminuted | Direct, high-energy | Multiple fragments, complex | ORIF, partial/total patellectomy |\n| Osteochondral | Shear (dislocation) | Articular surface involvement | Fragment fixation, chondroplasty |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Patella fractures: morphology dictates management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray (AP, lateral, skyline views), assess for fragment displacement, comminution, and articular step-off. CT scans are invaluable for complex fractures, osteochondral fragments, and pre-operative planning. Intraoperatively, tension band wiring is common for transverse fractures, while screw fixation may be used for vertical or osteochondral fragments; severe comminution may necessitate partial or total patellectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nOrthopaedic Trauma Association (OTA) Classification of Patella Fractures (2018): Recommends a comprehensive classification system (e.g., 34-C) that incorporates morphology, displacement, and comminution to guide treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | undisplaced transverse. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | vertical. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | osteochondral. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | a Salter type. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a fatigue fracture. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) ['undisplaced transverse.', 'vertical.', 'osteochondral.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
