  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody knee, ACL's plea!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, haemarthrosis. A ruptured anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) is a significant intra-articular injury that typically results in immediate bleeding into the joint space, leading to haemarthrosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe ACL is richly vascularized, receiving blood supply primarily from the middle geniculate artery. When the ligament tears, these vessels are disrupted, causing blood to extravasate directly into the synovial cavity. This acute bleeding manifests as a rapid onset of joint swelling (effusion) that is bloody (haemarthrosis) within hours of the injury. The presence of haemarthrosis is a strong indicator of an intra-articular injury, and in the context of a twisting knee injury, it is highly suggestive of an ACL tear, meniscal tear, or osteochondral fracture.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): ACL tears typically cause significant, not minor, swelling due to the rapid accumulation of blood (haemarthrosis) and inflammatory exudates within the joint.\nOption B (Incorrect): An acute ACL rupture is usually a very painful injury due to the tearing of soft tissues, nerve endings, and the distension of the joint capsule by haemarthrosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Patellar dislocation is a distinct injury where the patella moves out of the trochlear groove, usually laterally. While it can occur with other knee injuries, it is not a direct feature or consequence of an isolated ACL rupture.\nOption E (Incorrect): The ACL primarily prevents excessive anterior translation of the tibia relative to the femur. Excessive posterior glide is a hallmark sign of a posterior cruciate ligament (PCL) injury, not an ACL injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | ACL Rupture                               | PCL Rupture                               |\n|---------------------|-------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|\n| Mechanism           | Twisting, hyperextension, valgus stress   | Direct blow to anterior tibia (dashboard) |\n| Primary Restraint   | Anterior tibial translation               | Posterior tibial translation              |\n| Clinical Test       | Lachman, Anterior Drawer                  | Posterior Drawer, Sag Sign                |\n| Effusion Type       | Often haemarthrosis (acute)               | Variable, less common haemarthrosis       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute knee haemarthrosis after trauma = ACL tear until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, an acute ACL tear will show discontinuity or abnormal signal within the ligament, often with associated bone bruising (kissing lesions) on the lateral femoral condyle and posterior tibia. Arthroscopically, a torn ACL will appear as frayed, discontinuous fibers with active bleeding into the joint.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Anterior Cruciate Ligament Injuries (2014). Recommends clinical examination and MRI for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | minor swelling. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | little pain. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | haemarthrosis. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | dislocation of the patella. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | excessive posterior glide. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ['haemarthrosis.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
