  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the knee locks, it's often a meniscus playing hide-and-seek.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately identifies classic clinical features associated with a torn medial meniscus: locking, McMurray's sign, and giving way. These symptoms and signs are direct manifestations of the mechanical disruption caused by a meniscal tear within the knee joint.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLocking (C) occurs when a displaced fragment of the torn meniscus becomes entrapped between the femoral condyle and tibial plateau, mechanically impeding full extension or flexion of the knee. This is a hallmark of a bucket-handle tear. McMurray’s sign (D) is a specific orthopedic maneuver designed to elicit pain or a palpable click/clunk by trapping the torn meniscal fragment between the femur and tibia during specific rotational and flexion/extension movements, indicating meniscal pathology. Giving way (E) describes a sudden, involuntary sensation of the knee buckling or collapsing, often due to pain, muscle inhibition, or mechanical instability caused by the torn meniscus interfering with normal joint mechanics and proprioception.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): swelling. While swelling (effusion) can occur with a meniscal tear, it is a non-specific symptom common to many knee injuries and not a definitive feature of a torn meniscus itself. It's often delayed or mild compared to ligamentous injuries.\nOption B (Incorrect): excessive forward glide. Excessive forward glide (anterior tibial translation) is a primary sign of an anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) tear, not a meniscal tear. A meniscal tear primarily affects rotational stability and load bearing, not typically anterior-posterior laxity in isolation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Meniscal Tear | ACL Tear | MCL Tear |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------ | :---------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- |\n| Mechanism of Injury | Twisting injury, squatting, degeneration | Pivoting, hyperextension, direct blow | Valgus stress to lateral knee |\n| Key Symptoms | Locking, catching, giving way, joint line pain | \"Pop,\" instability, giving way, rapid swelling | Medial knee pain, instability with valgus stress |\n| Key Signs | McMurray's sign, joint line tenderness | Lachman test, Anterior Drawer test | Valgus stress test at 0° and 30° flexion |\n| Swelling | Often delayed, mild effusion | Rapid, significant hemarthrosis | Variable, localized swelling |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Locking, McMurray's, and giving way are the classic triad for meniscal tears.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a meniscal tear appears as high signal intensity extending to the articular surface on T2-weighted images. Intraoperatively during arthroscopy, a torn meniscus will be directly visualized as a disruption of the meniscal cartilage, often with displaced fragments or unstable flaps.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Meniscal Tears (2014, updated 2021). It recommends surgical intervention (repair or meniscectomy) for symptomatic meniscal tears that fail conservative management, especially for mechanical symptoms like locking.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | swelling. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | excessive forward glide. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | locking. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | McMurray’s sign. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | giving way. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D, E) ['locking.', 'McMurray’s sign.', 'giving way.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
