  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 TB arthritis: Diagnose with tissue, treat with drugs and often the knife.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question addresses the comprehensive approach to tuberculous arthritis, encompassing both diagnostic and therapeutic interventions. The correct options highlight the necessity of definitive tissue diagnosis and appropriate surgical management strategies for joint preservation or stabilization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTuberculous arthritis often requires tissue diagnosis due to the slow growth of Mycobacterium tuberculosis, making lymph node biopsy (if regional nodes are involved) or direct joint biopsy via arthrotomy crucial. Arthrotomy allows for thorough debridement of infected synovium and bone, drainage of pus, and collection of samples for culture and histology. In cases of severe joint destruction or persistent infection, arthrodesis may be necessary to achieve stability and pain relief, particularly in weight-bearing joints.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Waiting for a positive culture can significantly delay treatment, leading to irreversible joint damage. Empiric antitubercular therapy is often initiated based on strong clinical suspicion and preliminary diagnostic findings.\nOption C (Incorrect): While drainage of pus is part of management, a simple \"incision to let out pus\" is often insufficient. Tuberculous arthritis typically requires thorough debridement and synovectomy, which is better achieved through an arthrotomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Method | Indication | Benefit |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lymph Node Biopsy | Regional lymphadenopathy, systemic TB suspicion | Confirms systemic TB, less invasive than joint biopsy |\n| Arthrotomy | Direct joint access, debridement, biopsy | Definitive diagnosis, therapeutic debridement/drainage |\n| Synovial Fluid Analysis | Joint effusion | Initial screening for infection, but often low yield for TB culture |\n| MRI | Joint involvement, soft tissue extent | Detects early changes, abscesses, bone destruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tissue diagnosis is paramount for TB arthritis; surgical intervention often needed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, early tuberculous arthritis may show soft tissue swelling and juxta-articular osteopenia. Later stages reveal joint space narrowing, subchondral erosions, and \"Phemister's triad\" (juxta-articular osteoporosis, peripheral erosions, gradual joint space narrowing). Intraoperatively, one might see caseous necrosis, thickened synovium, and granulomatous tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the programmatic management of drug-resistant tuberculosis (2020) recommends prompt diagnosis and initiation of appropriate antitubercular therapy, often including surgical intervention for musculoskeletal forms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | waiting for a positive culture of the tubercle bacillus before treatment is | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | biopsy of lymph nodes. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | incision to let out pus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | arthrotomy. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | arthrodesis. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D, E) ['biopsy of lymph nodes.', 'arthrotomy.', 'arthrodesis.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
