  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ewing's: Layers of bone, like an onion's mourn.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the classic radiographic appearance of Ewing's sarcoma. This tumor is well-known for inducing a specific type of periosteal reaction that is highly suggestive of its diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEwing's sarcoma, a highly malignant primary bone tumor, classically presents with a characteristic 'onion skin' or lamellated periosteal reaction on X-ray. This appearance results from the tumor's rapid growth, which lifts the periosteum in concentric layers as new bone is laid down by the irritated periosteum. This layered new bone formation is a key diagnostic feature, distinguishing it from other bone tumors and guiding further diagnostic workup, such as biopsy and immunohistochemistry.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Ewing's sarcoma is a primary malignant bone tumor, not a metastasis from thyroid carcinoma. Thyroid carcinoma metastases to bone typically present as lytic lesions.\nOption B (Incorrect): Immediate amputation is rarely the primary treatment for Ewing's sarcoma. Modern management involves neoadjuvant chemotherapy, followed by limb-sparing surgery and/or radiation, with amputation reserved for unresectable or recurrent disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): A 'soap-bubble' appearance on X-ray is characteristic of benign bone lesions like aneurysmal bone cysts or giant cell tumors, not Ewing's sarcoma.\nOption E (Incorrect): 'Sun-ray spicules' or 'sunburst' appearance is the classic radiographic sign for osteosarcoma, another primary malignant bone tumor, due to new bone formation perpendicular to the cortex.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Classic X-ray Appearance | Common Location | Age Group |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ewing's Sarcoma | Onion skin periosteal reaction | Diaphysis of long bones | Children, young adults |\n| Osteosarcoma | Sunburst/Codman's triangle | Metaphysis of long bones | Adolescents, young adults |\n| Chondrosarcoma | Popcorn calcification | Pelvis, proximal femur, humerus | Older adults |\n| Giant Cell Tumor | Soap-bubble, epiphyseal | Epiphysis of long bones | Young adults (20-40s) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ewing's = Onion skin. Osteosarcoma = Sunburst. Know your bone tumor X-rays!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, Ewing's sarcoma typically shows a permeative lytic lesion with a characteristic lamellated or 'onion skin' periosteal reaction, indicating layers of new bone formation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Bone Cancer (2023): Recommends multidisciplinary evaluation, neoadjuvant chemotherapy, local control (surgery/radiation), and adjuvant chemotherapy for Ewing's sarcoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is a metastasis from carcinoma of the thyroid. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | should be treated by immediate amputation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | looks like a cut onion on x-ray. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | has a soap-bubble appearance on x-ray. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | displays sun-ray spicules on x-ray. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ['looks like a cut onion on x-ray.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
