  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Weak abductors, dropping pelvis, lurching gait – Trendelenburg's tells the tale!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers accurately describe a positive Trendelenburg’s sign. It is a clinical finding indicating weakness of the hip abductor muscles, primarily the gluteus medius and minimus, which can be caused by conditions like coxa vara. This weakness manifests as a characteristic lurching gait where the pelvis drops on the unsupported side.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe gluteus medius and minimus muscles are crucial for stabilizing the pelvis during single-leg stance. Their contraction on the stance leg prevents the contralateral (unsupported) side of the pelvis from dropping. A positive Trendelenburg’s sign occurs when these muscles are weak or their lever arm is compromised, as seen in coxa vara where the decreased neck-shaft angle reduces the mechanical advantage of the abductors. This leads to the pelvis dropping on the side opposite to the standing leg, causing a compensatory lurch of the trunk over the stance leg to maintain balance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The pelvis *drops*, not rises, on the unsupported side during a positive Trendelenburg’s sign.\nOption B (Incorrect): Trendelenburg’s sign is due to weakness or paralysis of the hip *abductors* (gluteus medius and minimus), not the adductors.\nOption D (Incorrect): Bilateral weakness of hip abductors (bilateral Trendelenburg’s) results in a \"waddling\" or \"duck-like\" gait, which is distinctly abnormal, not normal.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Trendelenburg's Sign | Duchenne Gait (Bilateral Trendelenburg) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanism** | Weakness of hip abductors (gluteus medius/minimus) on stance leg | Bilateral weakness of hip abductors |\n| **Pelvis Movement** | Drops on the unsupported (contralateral) side | Drops bilaterally, causing a waddling motion |\n| **Compensatory Action** | Trunk lurches over the stance leg | Trunk sways side-to-side to maintain balance |\n| **Common Causes** | Superior gluteal nerve injury, hip dislocation, coxa vara, L5 radiculopathy | Muscular dystrophy, bilateral hip arthritis, severe bilateral hip pathology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvis drops on unsupported side = positive Trendelenburg.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an X-ray, coxa vara would show a decreased femoral neck-shaft angle (typically <120 degrees). Intraoperatively, during hip surgery, one might observe atrophy or fatty infiltration of the gluteus medius/minimus, or evidence of superior gluteal nerve injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip (2014) discusses gait assessment including Trendelenburg's sign.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is present when the pelvis rises on the unsupported side on walking. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | occurs with paralysis of hip adductors. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | occurs with coxa vara. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | on both sides can make the gait appear normal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | on one side causes a lurching gait downwards towards the unsupported side. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: CE) occurs with coxa vara.; on one side causes a lurching gait downwards towards the unsupported side.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
