  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Abduct and flex to save the hip, or risk a lifetime of limp.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct management for an unstable hip detected at birth is to use a splint that maintains the hip in 90° flexion and abduction. This position is crucial for reducing the hip and promoting proper acetabular development, thereby preventing persistent dislocation and long-term sequelae of developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Pavlik harness is the gold standard for treating unstable hips in neonates. It works by maintaining the hip in a position of controlled flexion (typically 90-110 degrees) and abduction (typically 40-60 degrees), which centers the femoral head within the acetabulum. This stable, reduced position allows for remodeling of the dysplastic acetabulum and prevents further dislocation. The dynamic nature of the harness allows for some movement, which stimulates acetabular development while preventing avascular necrosis of the femoral head, a risk with rigid immobilization in extreme positions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"do nothing and re-examine every six months as only a minority of hips develop into a persistent dislocation.\" This is incorrect. An unstable hip at birth requires intervention to prevent persistent dislocation and promote normal development; waiting can lead to more complex problems.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"use a splint to keep the hip joint in 45° flexion and adduction.\" Adduction is contraindicated in hip instability as it promotes dislocation and can worsen the condition. The hip needs to be abducted.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"advise operative stabilization.\" Operative stabilization is typically reserved for cases where conservative management (like a Pavlik harness) fails, or for older children with irreducible dislocations. It is not the first-line treatment for an unstable hip detected at birth.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"use a Thomas’ thigh splint.\" A Thomas' thigh splint is used for immobilization of femoral shaft fractures, not for developmental dysplasia of the hip or hip instability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Unstable Hip (Neonate) | Stable but Dysplastic Hip (Neonate) | Irreducible/Failed Pavlik (Older Infant) |\n| :-------------------- | :---------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------- |\n| **Presentation** | Positive Ortolani/Barlow | Acetabular dysplasia on US, no instability | Persistent dislocation, older age |\n| **Initial Mgmt** | Pavlik harness (flexion/abduction) | Pavlik harness (flexion/abduction) | Closed reduction + spica cast (often) |\n| **Goal** | Reduce hip, promote acetabular dev. | Promote acetabular development | Achieve and maintain reduction |\n| **Contraindicated** | Adduction, forced abduction | Adduction, forced abduction | Forced reduction without imaging |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable neonatal hip = Pavlik harness, 90° flexion, 45-60° abduction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, an unstable hip would show a shallow acetabulum (alpha angle <60 degrees) and the femoral head displacing out of the acetabulum during dynamic stress maneuvers (Barlow/Ortolani equivalent). The femoral head coverage would be reduced.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Detection and Management of Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip in Infants (2015). Recommends screening for DDH and early intervention with a Pavlik harness for unstable or dislocated hips in infants.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | do nothing and re-examine every six months as only a minority of hips devel | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | use a splint to keep the hip joint in 45° flexion and adduction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | use a splint to keep the hip joint in 90° flexion and abduction. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | advise operative stabilization. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | use a Thomas’ thigh splint. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) use a splint to keep the hip joint in 90° flexion and abduction.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
