  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vara's angle is low, but its causes are high-yield!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCoxa vara is a deformity characterized by a decreased angle between the femoral neck and the femoral shaft. This condition is associated with underlying developmental or metabolic issues that compromise the structural integrity or normal formation of the proximal femur, such as femoral dysplasia, defective endochondral ossification, and rickets.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFemoral dysplasia refers to abnormal development of the femur, which can directly lead to a varus deformity of the femoral neck. Defective endochondral ossification is critical because this process is responsible for the growth and shaping of the femoral neck; any impairment can result in a weakened or abnormally angled bone. Rickets, caused by vitamin D deficiency, leads to impaired mineralization of bone, making the bones soft and susceptible to bending under normal physiological stresses, thereby causing the femoral neck to assume a varus position.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): An increase in the angle between the femoral neck and shaft is known as coxa valga, which is the opposite of coxa vara.\nOption D (Incorrect): A fractured neck of femur is an acute traumatic event that can lead to a varus deformity if it heals improperly or is displaced, but coxa vara itself is a chronic deformity often due to developmental or metabolic conditions, not primarily a fracture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Femoral Neck-Shaft Angle (Adult) | Common Associations/Causes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Normal | 125-135 degrees | Healthy bone development |\n| Coxa Vara | < 120 degrees | Femoral dysplasia, rickets, SCFE, trauma, infection |\n| Coxa Valga | > 140 degrees | Cerebral palsy, congenital hip dislocation, Legg-Calvé-Perthes disease (late stage) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vara means less angle, Valga means more angle.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an AP pelvis X-ray, coxa vara is identified by a femoral neck-shaft angle less than 120-125 degrees, often accompanied by a shortened femoral neck and increased prominence of the greater trochanter.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nPediatric Orthopaedic Society of North America (POSNA) Clinical Practice Guidelines (various years) emphasize early diagnosis and management of pediatric hip deformities and metabolic bone diseases like rickets to prevent long-term complications and optimize outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | an increase in angle between the femoral neck and the femoral shaft. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | femoral dysplasia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | defective endochondral ossification of the head of the femur. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | fractured neck of femur. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | rickets. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCE) femoral dysplasia.; defective endochondral ossification of the head of the femur.; rickets.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
