  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Perthes: Avascular necrosis's bony tale, told on X-ray.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options accurately describe the progressive radiological changes seen in Perthes' disease, which stems from avascular necrosis of the femoral head. These features reflect the initial inflammatory response, subsequent bone death, and the body's attempt at repair and remodeling.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn enlarged joint space is an early sign, often due to synovial effusion and thickening of the articular cartilage. Epiphyseal fragmentation is a hallmark of the active disease process, where the necrotic bone of the femoral head ossific nucleus collapses and is resorbed, leading to a fragmented appearance. Lateral subluxation occurs as the weakened and deformed femoral head migrates laterally within the acetabulum, often due to collapse and remodeling, and can contribute to a poor outcome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): An enlarged ossific nucleus is incorrect. The ossific nucleus in Perthes' disease typically becomes smaller, flattened, and fragmented due to avascular necrosis, not enlarged.\nOption E (Incorrect): A horizontal growth plate is not a characteristic radiological feature of Perthes' disease. While the physis can be affected, often showing widening or irregularity, \"horizontal\" is not a specific or primary descriptor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage of Perthes' Disease | Key Radiological Features | Clinical Presentation |\n| :------------------------ | :------------------------ | :-------------------- |\n| Initial/Necrosis          | Joint space widening (effusion/cartilage), subtle sclerosis, subchondral fracture (Crescent sign) | Limp, mild pain, limited abduction/internal rotation |\n| Fragmentation             | Flattening, sclerosis, fragmentation of femoral head epiphysis, lateral subluxation | Increased pain, muscle spasm, significant ROM limitation |\n| Reossification            | New bone formation, remodeling of femoral head, continued deformity | Decreased pain, improving ROM, but residual deformity |\n| Healed                    | Residual deformity (coxa magna/plana), acetabular changes, potential degenerative arthritis | Variable function, risk of early osteoarthritis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perthes' progression: Effusion -> Fragmentation -> Subluxation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an AP pelvis X-ray, look for a smaller, denser, and fragmented femoral head epiphysis, widening of the medial joint space, and lateral displacement of the femoral head relative to the acetabulum. The \"Crescent sign\" (subchondral fracture) is an early indicator.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nPediatric Orthopaedic Society of North America (POSNA) Perthes Disease Clinical Practice Guideline (2019). Recommends initial non-operative management for most patients, with surgical options considered for those with poor containment or risk factors for poor outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | an enlarged ossific nucleus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | an enlarged joint space. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | epiphyseal fragmentation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | lateral subluxation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a horizontal growth plate. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCD) an enlarged joint space.; epiphyseal fragmentation.; lateral subluxation.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
