  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Eccentric, bi-articular muscles: prime targets for strain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights that muscles spanning two joints, those performing eccentric work, and specific examples like the rectus femoris are particularly susceptible to exercise-induced injury. This is due to the unique biomechanical stresses placed upon them during movement and contraction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMuscles that cross two joints, such as the hamstrings or rectus femoris, are subjected to greater stretch and tension across a wider range of motion, increasing their vulnerability to strain. Eccentric contractions, where the muscle lengthens under load (e.g., lowering a weight), generate higher forces and cause more microtrauma to muscle fibers compared to concentric contractions. The rectus femoris exemplifies both these risk factors, spanning the hip and knee joints and undergoing significant eccentric loading during activities like kicking or deceleration, making it a common site for muscle strains.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): While Type II fibers are involved in powerful, high-intensity movements and can be injured, their presence alone is not the primary or most significant risk factor for exercise-induced muscle injury compared to biomechanical factors like eccentric loading or multi-joint spanning.\nOption E (Incorrect): The pectoralis major, while susceptible to injury (e.g., tears during heavy lifting), does not inherently fit the general biomechanical risk categories of spanning two joints or being predominantly an eccentric worker in the same way as the rectus femoris or hamstrings.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Risk Factor | Description | Example Muscle |\n|---|---|---|\n| Spans Two Joints | Subjected to greater stretch and tension across multiple articulations. | Rectus Femoris, Hamstrings, Gastrocnemius |\n| Eccentric Work | Muscle lengthens under load, generating higher forces and microtrauma. | Quadriceps (during deceleration), Hamstrings (during running) |\n| High Force Production | Muscles involved in powerful, explosive movements. | Quadriceps, Hamstrings, Adductors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Multi-joint muscles doing eccentric work are injury magnets.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, muscle strains typically appear as areas of high signal intensity on T2-weighted images, indicating edema and hemorrhage within the muscle belly or at the myotendinous junction. Complete tears show fiber discontinuity and retraction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Sports Medicine (ACSM) Position Stands (various years): These often discuss principles of exercise prescription and injury prevention, emphasizing proper warm-up, progressive overload, and technique to minimize muscle injury risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | those that span two joints. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | those that work eccentrically. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | those that contain a high proportion of type 2 fibres. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | the rectus femoris. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | the pectoralis major. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABD) those that span two joints.; those that work eccentrically.; the rectus femoris.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
