  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Treat the bug, drain the pus, save the digit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis answer is ACCEPTED. Acute paronychia, an infection of the nail fold, requires a dual approach: antibiotics for the underlying bacterial infection and drainage if pus has accumulated, reflecting the progression from cellulitis to abscess.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute paronychia is predominantly caused by Staphylococcus aureus. Early stages, characterized by erythema and swelling without frank pus, respond well to oral antibiotics like flucloxacillin, which targets gram-positive bacteria. If an abscess forms, indicated by fluctuance, surgical drainage is paramount. Gentle elevation or stripping of the eponychium (proximal nail fold) allows for effective pus release while preserving the nail matrix, preventing further complications and promoting healing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Complete nail avulsion is an overly aggressive and unnecessary procedure for most acute paronychia cases, typically reserved for severe subungual abscesses or chronic conditions.\nOption D (Incorrect): Excision of the eponychium is not the standard treatment for acute paronychia; the goal is drainage, not tissue removal, which could lead to scarring or nail deformity.\nOption E (Incorrect): Griseofulvin is an antifungal medication. Acute paronychia is overwhelmingly bacterial, making antifungal treatment ineffective and inappropriate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Early Acute Paronychia | Abscessed Acute Paronychia | Chronic Paronychia |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Presentation | Erythema, swelling, pain | Fluctuance, pus collection | Nail dystrophy, recurrent inflammation |\n| Etiology | Bacterial (S. aureus) | Bacterial (S. aureus) | Fungal, irritant, bacterial |\n| Treatment | Warm soaks, oral antibiotics (flucloxacillin) | Incision & drainage (eponychial stripping) | Avoid irritants, topical steroids/antifungals, marsupialization |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Antibiotics for cellulitis, drainage for pus – the paronychia mantra.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, gentle elevation of the eponychium will reveal a collection of purulent material, often extending laterally along the nail fold, which can be expressed with minimal tissue disruption.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) 2014 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Skin and Soft Tissue Infections: Recommends incision and drainage for abscesses and empiric antibiotics targeting S. aureus for cellulitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | flucloxacillin. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | operative gentle stripping of eponychium to release pus. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | always avulsion of the nail. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | excision of loose eponychium. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | griseofulvin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B) flucloxacillin.\noperative gentle stripping of eponychium to release pus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
