  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bunion isn't just a bump, it's a whole foot slump!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately identifies key clinical and anatomical features directly associated with hallux valgus. This condition is characterized by a lateral deviation of the great toe and a medial prominence, leading to predictable secondary changes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHallux valgus involves a progressive deformity where the great toe deviates laterally, often leading to impingement or displacement of the second toe. This lateral deviation causes the first metatarsal head to become prominent medially, forming an adventitious bursa (bunion) which frequently becomes inflamed due to shoe wear and friction. The mechanical forces can cause the hallux to either override or underride the second toe, both common secondary deformities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Rheumatoid arthritis is a systemic condition that can *cause* or *exacerbate* hallux valgus, but hallux valgus itself is a mechanical deformity, and RA is not a defining *feature* of the deformity in all cases.\nOption E (Incorrect): The characteristic exostosis in hallux valgus occurs on the *medial* side of the head of the first metatarsal, contributing to the bunion prominence, not the lateral side.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hallux Valgus | Hallux Rigidus | Bunionette (Tailor's Bunion) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Deformity** | Lateral deviation of great toe (hallux) | Degenerative arthritis of 1st MTP joint | Lateral prominence of 5th MTP joint |\n| **Key Symptom** | Medial bunion pain, toe crowding | Dorsal MTP joint pain, stiffness, limited motion | Lateral foot pain, shoe irritation |\n| **Radiographic Findings** | Increased HVA, IMA, medial exostosis | Dorsal osteophytes, joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis | Lateral bowing of 5th metatarsal, lateral exostosis |\n| **Associated Toe Deformity** | Overriding/underriding 2nd toe | None specific to hallux rigidus | None specific to bunionette |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hallux valgus is a complex forefoot deformity, not just a medial bump.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, look for an increased Hallux Valgus Angle (HVA >15-20 degrees), increased Intermetatarsal Angle (IMA >9 degrees), and subluxation of the sesamoids. Intraoperatively, a prominent medial eminence (bunion) is resected, and a lateral soft tissue release is often performed in conjunction with an osteotomy to realign the first metatarsal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Hallux Valgus (2014, updated 2020). Recommends non-operative management as first-line, with surgery reserved for failed conservative treatment and significant symptoms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | an overriding of the second toe by the first. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | an underriding of the second toe by the first. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | rheumatoid arthritis of the first metatarsophalangeal joint. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | an inflamed adventitious bursa. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | an exostosis on the lateral side of the head of the first metatarsal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) an overriding of the second toe by the first.\nan underriding of the second toe by the first.\nan inflamed adventitious bursa.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
