  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Frataxin's fault: Friedreich's ataxia, a GAA-tastrophe of coordination.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nFriedreich's ataxia is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterized by spinocerebellar degeneration, leading to ataxia, and is associated with widespread demyelination in the central and peripheral nervous systems, often resulting in characteristic musculoskeletal deformities like bilateral pes cavus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFriedreich's ataxia is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by a trinucleotide GAA repeat expansion in the FXN gene, leading to reduced frataxin protein. This protein deficiency impairs mitochondrial function, particularly in the dorsal root ganglia, spinal cord (dorsal columns, spinocerebellar tracts), and cerebellum (dentate nucleus). The degeneration of these pathways results in progressive ataxia, dysarthria, and sensory loss. The associated patchy demyelination contributes to nerve conduction abnormalities, and the chronic neurological imbalance leads to characteristic orthopedic deformities such as pes cavus and scoliosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Friedreich's ataxia is an autosomal recessive condition, not X-linked recessive.\nOption D (Incorrect): Friedreich's ataxia typically presents in childhood or adolescence, not at maturity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Friedreich's Ataxia | Ataxia-Telangiectasia | Spinocerebellar Ataxia (SCA) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Inheritance** | Autosomal Recessive | Autosomal Recessive | Autosomal Dominant |\n| **Onset** | Childhood/Adolescence | Early Childhood | Variable (often adulthood) |\n| **Key Neurological** | Spinocerebellar ataxia, dysarthria, sensory loss, areflexia | Cerebellar ataxia, oculocutaneous telangiectasias, immunodeficiency | Cerebellar ataxia, dysarthria, nystagmus (variable) |\n| **Pathology** | Degeneration of dorsal columns, spinocerebellar tracts, dentate nucleus; demyelination | Cerebellar degeneration, immune dysfunction | Cerebellar and brainstem degeneration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Friedreich's ataxia: GAA repeat, frataxin, spinocerebellar, demyelination, pes cavus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRI of the brain and spinal cord may show atrophy of the cervical spinal cord and cerebellum, particularly the superior cerebellar peduncles. Intraoperatively, during orthopedic correction for pes cavus, one would observe the characteristic high arch, hindfoot varus, and forefoot pronation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Academy of Neurology (EAN) Guidelines on the diagnosis and management of Friedreich's ataxia (2019). Recommends multidisciplinary care, symptomatic treatment, and genetic counseling.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is an X-linked recessive condition. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | affects part of the cerebellum. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | is associated with patchy demyelination. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | presents at maturity. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | causes bilateral pes cavus. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) affects part of the cerebellum.\nis associated with patchy demyelination.\ncauses bilateral pes cavus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
