  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spinal cord injury: stabilize the spine, save the skin.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies critical components in the management of a patient with a spinal cord injury. These include meticulous prevention of secondary complications like pressure sores, active rehabilitation measures such as passive range of motion, and the appropriate role of surgical intervention for stabilization and decompression.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEffective spinal cord injury management is a multidisciplinary endeavor focused on preventing secondary injury and optimizing long-term functional outcomes. Pressure ulcer prevention is paramount due to immobility and sensory loss, necessitating meticulous skin care and frequent repositioning, often every two hours. Passive range of motion exercises are crucial to prevent joint contractures, maintain muscle length, and preserve joint integrity, facilitating future rehabilitation efforts. Surgical stabilization, frequently involving plating or other instrumentation, aims to decompress the spinal cord, restore spinal alignment, and provide stability, thereby preventing further neurological deterioration and enabling earlier mobilization.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Turning every six hours is generally insufficient for preventing pressure sores in high-risk spinal cord injury patients; turning every two hours is a more common and effective standard of care.\nOption C (Incorrect): Meteorism (paralytic ileus) is a common and serious complication of spinal cord injury that requires active management, not passive allowance, due to risks of respiratory compromise, aspiration, and discomfort.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Aspect | Rationale | Key Intervention |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pressure Ulcer Prevention | Immobility, sensory loss, poor nutrition | Frequent repositioning (q2h), specialized mattresses, skin inspection |\n| DVT Prophylaxis | Venous stasis due to immobility | Anticoagulation (LMWH), compression stockings, SCDs |\n| Bladder Management | Neurogenic bladder dysfunction | Intermittent catheterization, indwelling catheter, suprapubic cystostomy |\n| Bowel Management | Neurogenic bowel dysfunction, ileus | Bowel regimen, dietary fiber, stool softeners, manual evacuation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stabilize, decompress, prevent complications, rehabilitate.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRI, you would typically see vertebral fractures, dislocations, epidural hematomas, or cord contusions. Intraoperatively, plating involves direct visualization of the spinal column, reduction of fractures/dislocations, and placement of screws/rods for stabilization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Neurological Surgeons (AANS) / Congress of Neurological Surgeons (CNS) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Cervical Spine and Spinal Cord Injuries (2019) recommends early surgical decompression and stabilization for appropriate cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the patient should be turned every six hours. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | plaster immobilisation increases the risk of pressure sores. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | meteorism should be allowed to occur. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | passive movements of the limbs are necessary. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | operations such as plating are indicated to relieve existing damage to the  | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D, E) plaster immobilisation increases the risk of pressure sores.\npassive movements of the limbs are necessary.\noperations such as plating are indicated to relieve existing damage to the cord.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
