  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the cord's core is compromised, expect a sensory split and bladder woes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nIntramedullary spinal cord tumors arise within the parenchyma of the spinal cord, directly affecting the central gray matter and crossing long tracts. This central location dictates their characteristic clinical presentation, distinguishing them from extramedullary lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntramedullary tumors classically cause dissociated sensory loss because they preferentially affect the decussating spinothalamic fibers (pain and temperature) in the central gray matter, while sparing the more peripherally located posterior columns (proprioception, vibration, light touch). Early bladder symptoms arise from the involvement of the centrally located sacral autonomic pathways. Spasticity is an early sign due to direct disruption of the descending corticospinal tracts within the cord. A 'belt' of local sensory loss at the level of the lesion is also characteristic, reflecting involvement of the dorsal horn or ascending tracts at that specific segment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): early prominent root pain. Root pain (radicular pain) is more typical of extramedullary or intradural-extramedullary lesions that directly compress nerve roots. Intramedullary tumors primarily affect the cord parenchyma, and root pain, if present, is usually less prominent or occurs later, often due to associated syrinx formation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intramedullary Tumor | Extramedullary Tumor |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain | Dull, aching, poorly localized; later radicular pain if syrinx | Early, prominent radicular pain |\n| Sensory Loss | Dissociated (pain/temp > touch/proprioception); segmental | Non-dissociated; ascending sensory level |\n| Motor | Early spasticity, UMN signs below lesion | Weakness, LMN signs at level, UMN signs below |\n| Bladder | Early dysfunction | Later dysfunction |\n| CSF Protein | Mildly elevated | Markedly elevated (block) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intramedullary lesions cause central cord syndromes; think dissociated sensory loss and early bladder issues.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, intramedullary tumors typically appear as an expansile lesion within the cord parenchyma, often with associated cord edema and sometimes a syrinx. Intraoperatively, the cord will appear swollen, and a myelotomy may reveal a distinct tumor mass within the cord substance, often with a clear plane from normal cord.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Central Nervous System Cancers (e.g., Astrocytomas, Ependymomas) 2023. These guidelines provide recommendations for diagnosis, treatment, and surveillance of spinal cord tumors, emphasizing MRI for diagnosis and surgical resection where feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | early prominent root pain. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | dissociated sensory loss. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | early bladder symptoms. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | early spasticity. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | a belt of local sensory loss. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D, E) dissociated sensory loss.\nearly bladder symptoms.\nearly spasticity.\na belt of local sensory loss.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
