  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tic douloureux: when your face feels like a live wire.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, stating that trigeminal neuralgia is known as tic douloureux. This term, meaning \"painful tic,\" accurately describes the sudden, severe, and often spasmodic facial pain characteristic of the condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTrigeminal neuralgia is characterized by excruciating, paroxysmal, electric shock-like or stabbing pain, typically unilateral, affecting one or more divisions of the trigeminal nerve. The historical nomenclature, \"tic douloureux,\" vividly captures the involuntary facial muscle contractions or grimacing (a 'tic') that can accompany these agonizing pain attacks. This descriptive term underscores the profound and often debilitating nature of the pain, making it a clinically and historically relevant synonym.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pain is most commonly experienced in the second (maxillary, V2) and third (mandibular, V3) divisions of the trigeminal nerve, not predominantly the first (ophthalmic, V1).\nOption C (Incorrect): Rubbing or light touch to specific trigger zones (e.g., shaving, eating, talking) typically *provokes* an attack of trigeminal neuralgia, rather than providing relief.\nOption D (Incorrect): Trigeminal neuralgia is defined by its paroxysmal, episodic nature, with periods of intense pain interspersed with pain-free intervals, not as a constant pain.\nOption E (Incorrect): There is no recognized direct association between trigeminal neuralgia and migraine; they are distinct neurological conditions with different pathophysiologies and clinical presentations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Trigeminal Neuralgia (TN) | Atypical Facial Pain (AFP) | Migraine | Cluster Headache |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ | :---------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Pain Quality** | Electric shock, stabbing, lancinating | Dull, aching, burning, constant | Throbbing, pulsating | Excruciating, boring, sharp |\n| **Duration** | Seconds to minutes (paroxysmal) | Constant, persistent | 4-72 hours | 15-180 minutes (episodic) |\n| **Triggers** | Touch, chewing, talking, cold air | Often psychological, stress; less specific physical triggers | Stress, certain foods, hormones, sensory stimuli | Alcohol, strong odors, sleep deprivation |\n| **Associated Sx** | Facial grimacing (tic), no autonomic features | Often psychological distress, depression | Nausea, vomiting, photophobia, phonophobia | Ipsilateral autonomic features (lacrimation, ptosis, rhinorrhea) |\n| **Nerve Divisions** | V2, V3 most common | Diffuse, often bilateral | Unilateral (often), but not strictly nerve distribution | Periorbital, temporal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Trigeminal neuralgia is paroxysmal, shock-like pain, often triggered by light touch, and is *not* constant.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nHigh-resolution MRI (e.g., FIESTA or CISS sequences) may reveal neurovascular compression of the trigeminal nerve root entry zone, most commonly by the superior cerebellar artery. Intraoperatively during microvascular decompression (MVD), the offending vessel is identified and gently separated from the nerve using a Teflon felt pad.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) 2008 Guidelines for the management of trigeminal neuralgia recommend carbamazepine as the first-line medical treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is known as tic doloureux. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is pain mainly in the first division of the fifth nerve. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is helped by rubbing the part of the face affected. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | is a constant pain. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | has recognised association with migraine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) is known as tic doloureux.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
