  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Facial palsy: more than just Bell's, always protect the eye!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options B, C, D, and E accurately describe various aspects and consequences of a seventh nerve palsy. These options highlight the diverse etiologies, the differential diagnosis from Bell's palsy, the ominous sign of malignancy in parotid involvement, and the critical ocular complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe facial nerve (CN VII) has a complex anatomical course, traversing the cerebellopontine angle, internal auditory canal, temporal bone (including close proximity to the middle ear), and exiting via the stylomastoid foramen to innervate the muscles of facial expression within the parotid gland. This intricate path explains its vulnerability to various pathologies, from middle ear infections to parotid tumors. Its motor function for eyelid closure (orbicularis oculi) is crucial, and its loss leads to lagophthalmos and subsequent corneal exposure. Understanding the distinction between central (supranuclear) and peripheral (infranuclear) lesions is fundamental, as peripheral lesions affect the entire ipsilateral face, unlike central lesions which spare the forehead.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"if due to an infranuclear lesion fevalves only the lower half of the face.\" This is incorrect. An infranuclear (peripheral) lesion of the facial nerve affects the entire ipsilateral face, including both the upper and lower halves. It is a supranuclear (central) lesion that typically spares the upper face due to bilateral cortical innervation to the forehead muscles.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Supranuclear (Central) Palsy | Infranuclear (Peripheral) Palsy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Forehead Sparing | Yes (due to bilateral innervation) | No (entire ipsilateral face affected) |\n| Etiology | Stroke, tumor (e.g., cerebral cortex, brainstem) | Bell's palsy, trauma, infection, tumor (e.g., temporal bone, parotid) |\n| Associated Symptoms | Often hemiparesis, aphasia | Hyperacusis, taste disturbance, dry eye/mouth |\n| Corneal Ulceration Risk | Low | High (due to lagophthalmos) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Facial nerve palsy demands a thorough search for etiology beyond Bell's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRI, look for temporal bone fractures, middle ear inflammation/masses, or parotid gland tumors invading the facial nerve. Intraoperatively, the facial nerve can be seen traversing the parotid gland, and its integrity must be meticulously preserved during parotidectomy; nerve involvement by a tumor is a critical finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Bell's Palsy (2022). Recommends corticosteroids for Bell's palsy and eye protection for lagophthalmos.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | if due to an infranuclear lesion fevalves only the lower half of the face. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | can be caused by middle ear disease. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | is not always a Bell’s palsy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is an indication of malignancy when associated with a parotid tumour. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | causes corneal ulceration. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D, E) can be caused by middle ear disease.\nis not always a Bell’s palsy.\nis an indication of malignancy when associated with a parotid tumour.\ncauses corneal ulceration.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
