  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Snuff-box numbness? Think superficial radial nerve, wrist level!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E. Severance of the radial nerve at the wrist primarily affects its superficial sensory branch, which supplies sensation to the dorsum of the hand, including the anatomical snuff-box. Motor function, such as wrist extension, is preserved as the motor branches diverge more proximally.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe radial nerve divides into deep (posterior interosseous) and superficial branches in the forearm. The superficial radial nerve is purely sensory and courses distally, emerging from beneath the brachioradialis tendon to supply sensation to the dorsum of the thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring fingers, as well as the dorsal hand. The anatomical snuff-box, bounded by the extensor pollicis longus, extensor pollicis brevis, and abductor pollicis longus tendons, receives its sensory innervation from this superficial radial nerve. Therefore, injury at the wrist level specifically targets this sensory distribution, leading to anaesthesia in this characteristic area.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Main en griffe, or claw hand, is a classic sign of ulnar nerve injury, affecting the intrinsic hand muscles.\nOption B (Incorrect): Wasting of the thenar eminence is indicative of median nerve compression or injury, affecting the thenar muscles.\nOption C (Incorrect): Wrist drop is a hallmark of radial nerve injury occurring more proximally in the forearm or arm, affecting the motor branches to the wrist and finger extensors. At the wrist, the motor branches have already supplied these muscles.\nOption D (Incorrect): Trophic ulcer of the index finger is a general sign of severe sensory denervation, often seen with median nerve injuries or other conditions causing profound sensory loss, but not specific to radial nerve injury at the wrist.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve Injured | Level of Injury | Classic Sign/Symptom |\n|---|---|---|\n| Radial Nerve | Wrist | Anaesthesia in anatomical snuff-box |\n| Radial Nerve | Proximal Forearm/Arm | Wrist drop |\n| Median Nerve | Wrist (Carpal Tunnel) | Thenar atrophy, sensory loss thumb/index/middle fingers |\n| Ulnar Nerve | Wrist/Elbow | Claw hand, sensory loss ring/little fingers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Radial nerve at the wrist means sensory loss in the snuff-box, not wrist drop.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, severance of the superficial radial nerve at the wrist would reveal a transected, thin, purely sensory nerve branch lying subcutaneously, typically radial to the radial artery and emerging from under the brachioradialis tendon. Imaging like high-resolution ultrasound might show nerve discontinuity or neuroma formation in this superficial location.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) Clinical Practice Guideline for Peripheral Nerve Injuries (2016) recommends careful sensory and motor examination to localize nerve injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | main en griffe. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | wasting of the thenar eminence. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | wrist drop. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | trophic ulcer of the index finger. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | anaesthesia in the anatomical snuff-box. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) anaesthesia in the anatomical snuff-box.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
