  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ulnar nerve at the wrist: pinch weak, fingers spread, pinky numb.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, D, and E accurately describe the clinical manifestations of a complete ulnar nerve severance at the wrist. This injury impacts the nerve's distal sensory distribution and its intrinsic hand muscle innervation, leading to specific functional deficits and characteristic signs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe ulnar nerve at the wrist divides into a superficial sensory branch and a deep motor branch. The superficial branch provides sensation to the palmar and dorsal aspects of the medial one-and-a-half fingers (little finger and ulnar half of the ring finger), explaining option A. The deep motor branch innervates the hypothenar muscles, all dorsal and palmar interossei, the medial two lumbricals, and the adductor pollicis. Loss of interossei function directly causes inability to abduct or adduct the fingers (option D). Weakness of the adductor pollicis is compensated by the flexor pollicis longus (median nerve), leading to hyperflexion of the thumb IP joint during pinch, which is a positive Froment's sign (option E).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Inability to flex the terminal phalanx of the little finger is due to loss of flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) function. The ulnar nerve supplies the FDP to the ring and little fingers, but this innervation occurs in the forearm, *proximal* to the wrist. Therefore, a severance *at* the wrist spares FDP function.\nOption C (Incorrect): Flexion of the little finger at the metacarpophalangeal joint is a normal action. Ulnar nerve palsy at the wrist leads to paralysis of the interossei and medial lumbricals, which normally flex the MCP joints and extend the IP joints. Loss of these muscles results in unopposed action of the extrinsic extensors and flexors, causing *hyperextension* at the MCP joint and *flexion* at the IP joints, characteristic of an ulnar claw hand, not isolated MCP flexion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve Injury (Wrist Level) | Sensory Loss | Key Motor Deficit | Classic Sign/Deformity |\n| :------------------------ | :----------- | :---------------- | :--------------------- |\n| Ulnar Nerve               | Medial 1.5 digits | Interossei, Adductor Pollicis, Hypothenar | Froment's Sign, Ulnar Claw Hand |\n| Median Nerve              | Lateral 3.5 digits | Thenar muscles (APB, FPB, OP), Lateral Lumbricals | Ape Hand, Thenar Atrophy, Benediction Hand (proximal) |\n| Radial Nerve              | Dorsum of hand/thumb web space | None significant (primarily sensory at wrist) | None (Wrist Drop is more proximal) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ulnar nerve at wrist = sensory loss, interossei paralysis, Froment's sign.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a complete severance would show a transected nerve fascicle. On high-resolution ultrasound, a discontinuity or neuroma formation at the site of injury could be visualized, along with muscle denervation changes in the intrinsic hand muscles.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) Clinical Practice Guideline: Peripheral Nerve Injuries (2016) recommends early diagnosis and surgical repair for complete nerve lacerations to optimize functional outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | loss of sensation on the anterior and posterior aspects of the inner one-an | ✅ Correct |\n| B | inability to flex the terminal phalanx of the little finger. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | flexion of the little finger at the metacarpophalangeal joint. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | inability to abduct or adduct the fingers. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | a positive Froment’s sign. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) loss of sensation on the anterior and posterior aspects of the inner one-and-a half fingers.\ninability to abduct or adduct the fingers.\na positive Froment’s sign.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
