  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 High sciatic severance: profound paralysis, profound problems.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, B, and D. Severance of the sciatic nerve high up in the thigh or gluteal region results in significant motor and sensory deficits affecting the entire lower limb below the lesion, leading to footdrop, inability to flex the knee, and a high risk of trophic ulcers due to profound sensory loss.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe sciatic nerve, formed by L4-S3 nerve roots, is the largest nerve in the body. A high severance impacts both its major divisions: the tibial nerve and the common peroneal nerve. Motorically, this leads to paralysis of the hamstrings (responsible for knee flexion), and all muscles below the knee, resulting in footdrop (due to loss of dorsiflexion and eversion via common peroneal nerve) and inability to plantarflex or flex toes (via tibial nerve). Sensorily, there is extensive anaesthesia over the entire leg and foot, except for the medial strip supplied by the saphenous nerve. This profound sensory loss eliminates protective reflexes, making the limb highly susceptible to unnoticed trauma, pressure, and subsequent trophic ulceration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): complete stocking anaesthesia. While there is extensive sensory loss, it is not 'complete' stocking anaesthesia because the saphenous nerve (a branch of the femoral nerve) supplies sensation to the medial aspect of the leg and foot, which would be spared.\nOption E (Incorrect): meralgia paraesthetica. Meralgia paraesthetica is a condition caused by compression or entrapment of the lateral femoral cutaneous nerve, resulting in sensory symptoms (pain, numbness, tingling) on the lateral thigh, entirely unrelated to sciatic nerve injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | High Sciatic Nerve Injury                               | Common Peroneal Nerve Injury (at fibular head)          | Tibial Nerve Injury (at popliteal fossa)                 |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Motor Deficit**   | Hamstring paralysis (knee flexion), footdrop, toe paralysis | Footdrop (dorsiflexion, eversion), toe extension weakness | Plantarflexion, toe flexion weakness                     |\n| **Sensory Deficit** | Extensive below knee (except medial strip)              | Dorsum of foot, lateral leg                             | Sole of foot                                             |\n| **Key Sign**        | Footdrop, inability to flex knee, trophic ulcers        | Footdrop, steppage gait                                 | Calcaneal gait (loss of push-off), claw toes             |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High sciatic injury = hamstrings + all muscles below the knee.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a high sciatic nerve severance would present as a complete discontinuity of the nerve in the gluteal region or posterior thigh. Imaging like MRI can delineate the extent of nerve injury, identify neuromas, or detect compressive lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the Management of Traumatic Peripheral Nerve Injuries (2019). These guidelines recommend early surgical exploration and repair for complete nerve transections to optimize functional recovery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | footdrop. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | complete inability to flex the knee. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | complete stocking anaesthesia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | trophic ulcers. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | meralgia paraesthetica. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) footdrop.\ncomplete inability to flex the knee.\ntrophic ulcers.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
