  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't thin the blood or poison the brain after a head injury.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies dicoumarol and sulphonamides as substances to be avoided in head injuries. Dicoumarol, an anticoagulant, significantly increases the risk of intracranial hemorrhage, while sulphonamides can have neurotoxic effects or exacerbate cerebral edema.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDicoumarol is a vitamin K antagonist that inhibits the synthesis of clotting factors, leading to a heightened risk of bleeding. In the confined space of the cranium, any hemorrhage can rapidly increase intracranial pressure (ICP) and cause devastating neurological damage. Sulphonamides, while not as universally contraindicated as anticoagulants, can potentially increase ICP, cause neurotoxicity, or interfere with cerebral autoregulation, making them generally undesirable in patients with compromised cerebral function following head trauma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (frusemide) (Incorrect): Frusemide is a loop diuretic often used as an adjunct to mannitol to reduce intracranial pressure by decreasing cerebral edema.\nOption B (mannitol) (Incorrect): Mannitol is an osmotic diuretic and a cornerstone therapy for reducing elevated intracranial pressure in acute head injury.\nOption E (dexamethasone) (Incorrect): Dexamethasone, a corticosteroid, is generally avoided in traumatic brain injury (TBI) due to evidence of increased mortality (CRASH trial). However, it is used in other types of head injuries, such as those associated with vasogenic edema from brain tumors, making it not universally 'avoided' in all head injuries.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Substance | Role in Head Injury | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mannitol | Used | Osmotic diuretic, reduces ICP by drawing water from brain tissue |\n| Frusemide | Used (adjunct) | Loop diuretic, reduces ICP by decreasing CSF production and cerebral edema |\n| Dicoumarol | Avoided | Anticoagulant, significantly increases risk of intracranial hemorrhage |\n| Sulphonamides | Avoided | Potential for neurotoxicity, increased ICP, or drug interactions |\n| Dexamethasone | Avoided (TBI) / Used (other) | Increased mortality in TBI; used for vasogenic edema (e.g., tumors, abscesses) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anticoagulants and drugs with neurotoxic potential are contraindicated in head injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT scan, the presence of intracranial hemorrhage (e.g., epidural, subdural, intraparenchymal) would be a critical finding, especially if exacerbated by anticoagulant use. Progressive cerebral edema would also be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBrain Trauma Foundation (BTF) Guidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury (e.g., 4th Edition, 2016). These guidelines recommend against the use of corticosteroids in TBI and emphasize careful management of coagulation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | frusemide. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | mannitol. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | sulphonamides. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | dicoumarol. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | dexamethasone. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) sulphonamides.\ndicoumarol.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
