  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 SDH: The silent, fluctuating threat that can push your brain too far.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answers are C and D. Subdural haemorrhage (SDH) can indeed cause fluctuating neurological symptoms, particularly in its chronic form, and a large collection can lead to significant mass effect resulting in a midbrain pressure cone.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic subdural haematomas often present with a waxing and waning course of cognitive decline or altered mental status due to recurrent microbleeds, changes in osmotic gradients, or gradual brain compression. Furthermore, any significant intracranial mass lesion, including a large subdural haemorrhage, can exert pressure on the brainstem, leading to uncal herniation and subsequent compression of the midbrain, manifesting as a 'midbrain pressure cone' with devastating neurological consequences.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Subdural haemorrhage is significantly *more* common than extradural haemorrhage, especially in the elderly and those with brain atrophy, not less common.\nOption B (Incorrect): While possible in young individuals, subdural haemorrhage is particularly prevalent in the elderly due to fragile bridging veins and brain atrophy, making it less common in young people compared to other age groups.\nOption E (Incorrect): Papilloedema is a sign of chronic raised intracranial pressure, which can occur with subdural haemorrhage, but it is a late and inconsistent finding, not a defining characteristic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Subdural Haemorrhage (SDH) | Extradural Haemorrhage (EDH) | Subarachnoid Haemorrhage (SAH) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Between dura and arachnoid | Between dura and skull | Between arachnoid and pia |\n| Shape on CT | Crescent-shaped | Lenticular (lens-shaped) | Fills sulci/cisterns |\n| Common Cause | Tearing of bridging veins | Middle meningeal artery tear (trauma) | Aneurysm rupture |\n| Patient Group | Elderly, alcoholics | Young adults (trauma) | Any age (aneurysm), trauma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: SDH: Fluctuating symptoms, high herniation risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an acute subdural haemorrhage appears as a crescent-shaped hyperdense (bright) collection conforming to the brain's surface, often crossing suture lines but not falx/tentorium. Chronic SDH appears hypodense or isodense.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGuidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury, Brain Trauma Foundation (BTF), 2017. Recommends surgical evacuation for acute SDH >10mm thick or with >5mm midline shift.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | six times less common than extradural haemorrhage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | particularly common in young people. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | a cause of slowing of cerebration which comes and goes. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | a cause of a midbrain pressure cone. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | characterised by papilloedema. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) a cause of slowing of cerebration which comes and goes.\na cause of a midbrain pressure cone.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
