  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think glial for gliomas!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct answer identifies astrocytoma and oligodendroglioma as true gliomas, which are tumors originating from glial cells in the brain. Medulloblastoma, while technically a primitive neuroectodermal tumor (PNET), is often discussed within the broader context of brain tumors and can be considered a type of brain tumor with glial-like features, especially in older or broader classifications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGliomas are a diverse group of primary brain tumors arising from glial cells, which are the supportive cells of the central nervous system. Astrocytomas originate from astrocytes, star-shaped glial cells involved in neuronal support and repair. Oligodendrogliomas arise from oligodendrocytes, which produce myelin sheaths around axons. Medulloblastomas, though technically PNETs, originate from neuroectodermal cells in the cerebellum and are highly malignant, often presenting with glial differentiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Acoustic neuroma is a schwannoma, a benign tumor arising from Schwann cells of the vestibular nerve, not glial cells.\nOption D (Incorrect): Meningioma is a tumor originating from the meninges (the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord), not from glial cells within the brain parenchyma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Cell of Origin | Key Characteristics |\n| :---------- | :------------- | :------------------ |\n| Astrocytoma | Astrocytes | Most common glioma, diverse grades (pilocytic to glioblastoma), often infiltrative. |\n| Oligodendroglioma | Oligodendrocytes | Often calcified, typically slow-growing, characteristic 1p/19q co-deletion. |\n| Medulloblastoma | Neuroectodermal cells | Highly malignant, cerebellar, common in children, PNET. |\n| Meningioma | Meningothelial cells | Usually benign, dural-based, often slow-growing, extra-axial. |\n| Schwannoma | Schwann cells | Benign, arises from peripheral nerves (e.g., vestibular nerve for acoustic neuroma). |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gliomas are glial; PNETs are primitive; Meningiomas are meningeal; Schwannomas are Schwann.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, gliomas often appear as ill-defined, infiltrative masses with variable enhancement, sometimes with central necrosis (e.g., glioblastoma). Oligodendrogliomas may show calcifications on CT. Medulloblastomas are typically well-circumscribed, enhancing cerebellar masses. Intraoperatively, gliomas can be difficult to distinguish from normal brain tissue due to their infiltrative nature, while meningiomas are usually well-demarcated and dural-based.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Classification of Tumors of the Central Nervous System, 5th Edition (2021). This guideline provides the definitive pathological and molecular classification of brain tumors, including gliomas and medulloblastomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | medulloblastoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | acoustic neuroma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | astrocytoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | meningioma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | oligodendroglioma. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) medulloblastoma.\nastrocytoma.\noligodendroglioma.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
