  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Dural tail, bony growth, arachnoid origin: Meningioma's signature.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question accurately identifies key characteristics of meningiomas, which are among the most common primary intracranial tumors. The correct options highlight their cellular origin, epidemiological prevalence, and a distinctive imaging feature related to their interaction with bone.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeningiomas arise from arachnoid cap cells, not brain parenchyma, making them extra-axial tumors. Their slow growth and intimate association with the dura mater often induce a reactive thickening of the adjacent bone, known as hyperostosis, which is a valuable diagnostic clue on imaging. Epidemiologically, meningiomas constitute a significant proportion, approximately 18%, of all primary intracranial neoplasms, underscoring their clinical importance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"endothelioma formation\" is an outdated and inaccurate term. Meningiomas originate from arachnoid cap cells, not endothelial cells.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"flat features\" is a vague and generally incorrect descriptor. While some meningiomas can grow in an \"en plaque\" fashion, it is not a universal characteristic, and many are nodular or lobulated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Characteristic | Meningioma | Glioblastoma | Pituitary Adenoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Arachnoid cap cells | Astrocytes | Pituitary gland cells |\n| Growth Rate | Slow, mostly benign | Rapid, aggressive | Slow to moderate |\n| Common Imaging Feature | Reactive hyperostosis, dural tail | Ring enhancement, central necrosis | Sella turcica expansion |\n| Prevalence | ~18% of primary intracranial tumors | Most common primary malignant brain tumor | Common, often asymptomatic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Meningiomas: arachnoid origin, dural attachment, hyperostosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, look for a well-circumscribed, extra-axial mass often associated with reactive hyperostosis of the adjacent skull bone. On MRI, they are typically isointense to gray matter on T1, hyperintense on T2, and show strong, homogeneous enhancement with a characteristic \"dural tail\" sign. Intraoperatively, they are usually firm, well-demarcated, and arise from the dura.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 WHO Classification of Tumours of the Central Nervous System. This classification provides the definitive diagnostic criteria and grading for meningiomas, including their origin and histological features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | endothelioma formation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | flat features: | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | reactive hyperostosis. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | the fact that about 18% of intracranial tumours are meningiomas. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | an origin in the arachnoid. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D, E) reactive hyperostosis.\nthe fact that about 18% of intracranial tumours are meningiomas.\nan origin in the arachnoid.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
