  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Craniopharyngiomas: The calcified, cystic, hypothalamic headache of neurosurgery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Craniopharyngiomas are benign but locally aggressive suprasellar tumors characterized by their frequent calcification, cystic nature, tendency to grow large, and propensity to cause hydrocephalus due to their strategic location.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCraniopharyngiomas originate from Rathke's pouch remnants, explaining their typical suprasellar location. Their growth often compresses critical structures like the optic chiasm, hypothalamus, and third ventricle, leading to classic symptoms such as visual field defects, endocrine dysfunction, and obstructive hydrocephalus. The presence of calcifications and cystic components are hallmark pathological and radiological features.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"are removable.\" While surgical resection is the primary treatment, complete removal of craniopharyngiomas is often challenging and associated with significant morbidity due to their adherence to vital structures like the hypothalamus, optic chiasm, and major vessels. Maximal safe resection, rather than complete removal, is often the goal.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Craniopharyngioma | Pituitary Adenoma | Suprasellar Meningioma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Rathke's pouch remnants | Pituitary gland | Arachnoid cap cells |\n| Calcification | Common (50-80%) | Rare | Variable (often present) |\n| Cystic Component | Common (\"motor oil\" fluid) | Rare | Rare |\n| Endocrine Dysfunction | Hypothalamic/Panhypopituitarism | Hyper/Hypopituitarism | Less common, compression |\n| Typical Imaging | Heterogeneous, calcified, cystic | Homogeneous, enhancing | Homogeneous, dural tail |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Craniopharyngiomas are calcified, cystic, large, and cause hydrocephalus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a suprasellar mass with characteristic curvilinear or nodular calcifications is often seen. MRI reveals a heterogeneous mass with cystic components (T1 hypointense, T2 hyperintense fluid) and solid enhancing portions. Intraoperatively, they are often adherent, lobulated, and may contain thick, yellowish \"motor oil\" fluid within cysts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Society of Endocrinology (ESE) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Craniopharyngiomas (2021). These guidelines recommend individualized treatment strategies, often involving maximal safe surgical resection followed by radiation therapy for residual tumor, with lifelong endocrine and neurocognitive follow-up.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are calcified in 50% of cases. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | are removable. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | form large masses. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | have cystic cavities. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | cause hydrocephalus. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D, E) are calcified in 50% of cases.\nform large masses.\nhave cystic cavities.\ncause hydrocephalus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
