  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pituitary tumors: know your cells, know your hormones.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the three primary histological classifications of pituitary adenomas. These classifications are based on the staining characteristics of the tumor cells, which often correlate with the type of hormone they produce.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPituitary adenomas, which constitute the majority of pituitary tumors, are traditionally classified based on their affinity for histological stains. Basophilic cells stain with basic dyes and often produce ACTH (Cushing's disease) or TSH. Acidophilic cells stain with acidic dyes and typically produce growth hormone (acromegaly) or prolactin (prolactinoma). Chromophobe cells, which do not stain well, are often non-secretory or can produce any hormone, including gonadotropins or alpha-subunits, and represent a significant proportion of adenomas. This classification aids in understanding the tumor's biological behavior and potential hormonal syndromes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Craniopharyngiomas are benign epithelial tumors arising from remnants of Rathke's pouch, located in the suprasellar region, adjacent to but distinct from the pituitary gland itself.\nOption E (Incorrect): Neurofibromas are benign nerve sheath tumors, typically associated with peripheral nerves or cranial nerves (e.g., acoustic neuroma), and are not primary tumors of the pituitary body.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Basophil Adenoma | Acidophil Adenoma | Chromophobe Adenoma |\n| :------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- |\n| Staining | Stains with basic dyes (e.g., hematoxylin) | Stains with acidic dyes (e.g., eosin) | Does not stain well (chromophobic) |\n| Common Hormones | ACTH (Cushing's), TSH | GH (Acromegaly), Prolactin (Prolactinoma) | Non-secretory, Gonadotropins, Alpha-subunits, or others |\n| Clinical Syndromes | Cushing's disease, Hyperthyroidism (rare) | Acromegaly, Galactorrhea, Amenorrhea, Impotence | Mass effect symptoms (visual field defects, headache) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pituitary adenomas are classified by cell staining: basophil, acidophil, chromophobe.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, pituitary adenomas typically appear as a sellar or suprasellar mass, often isointense to brain on T1 and T2, with avid enhancement after gadolinium. Larger tumors can cause remodeling of the sella turcica, optic chiasm compression, or cavernous sinus invasion. Intraoperatively via transsphenoidal approach, the tumor often appears as a soft, grayish-pink, vascular mass, distinct from the firmer, yellowish normal pituitary gland.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pituitary Adenomas (e.g., 2016 for Acromegaly, 2011 for Prolactinoma) provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, treatment, and follow-up based on the specific type of pituitary adenoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | basophil. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | acidophil. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | chromophobe. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | craniopharyngiomas. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | neurofibromas. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) basophil.\nacidophil.\nchromophobe.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
