  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Worst headache of my life? Think SAH, don't delay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies sudden severe headache, sudden loss of consciousness, and oculomotor nerve palsy as characteristic clinical features of subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH). These are classic presentations that demand immediate medical attention due to the high morbidity and mortality associated with SAH.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSubarachnoid haemorrhage, often caused by a ruptured cerebral aneurysm, leads to blood spilling into the subarachnoid space. The sudden increase in intracranial pressure and irritation of the meninges by blood products cause the hallmark 'thunderclap headache.' Acute rise in ICP or direct brainstem involvement can lead to sudden loss of consciousness. Oculomotor nerve (CN III) palsy, characterized by ptosis, a dilated pupil, and a 'down and out' eye, frequently results from compression by an expanding posterior communicating artery (PComm) aneurysm, which lies in close proximity to the nerve.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Bell’s palsy) (Incorrect): Bell's palsy is an idiopathic unilateral facial nerve (CN VII) paralysis, not directly associated with the pathophysiology or presentation of SAH.\nOption E (Brown-Séquard lesion) (Incorrect): Brown-Séquard syndrome is a specific spinal cord hemisection injury, presenting with ipsilateral motor and proprioceptive loss and contralateral pain and temperature loss below the lesion. It is unrelated to intracranial haemorrhage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Clinical Features | Primary Affected System |\n|---|---|---|\n| Subarachnoid Haemorrhage (SAH) | Thunderclap headache, sudden LOC, CN III palsy | Intracranial/Vascular |\n| Bell's Palsy | Acute unilateral facial weakness/paralysis | Cranial Nerve VII |\n| Brown-Séquard Syndrome | Ipsilateral motor/proprioception loss, contralateral pain/temp loss | Spinal Cord |\n| Migraine | Unilateral throbbing headache, aura, photophobia, phonophobia | Neurological (Primary Headache) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thunderclap headache + CN III palsy = SAH until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn non-contrast head CT, SAH appears as hyperdensity (white) in the subarachnoid spaces, such as the basal cisterns, sylvian fissures, and sulci. Intraoperatively, one would observe frank blood within the subarachnoid space and the ruptured aneurysm itself, often with surrounding brain edema.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2023 AHA/ASA Guidelines for the Management of Patients With Unruptured Intracranial Aneurysms and Subarachnoid Hemorrhage recommend that noncontrast head CT should be performed immediately in patients with suspected SAH (Class I, Level of Evidence B-NR).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | sudden severe headache. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | sudden loss of consciousness. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | oculomotor nerve palsy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Bell’s palsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Brown-Séquard lesion. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) sudden severe headache.\nsudden loss of consciousness.\noculomotor nerve palsy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
