  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Image to see, meds to treat, surgery to cure.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers highlight that accurate diagnosis of epilepsy relies on MR imaging to identify structural causes, and initial management for most patients involves oral anticonvulsant therapy. These are fundamental principles in epilepsy care.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHigh-resolution brain MRI is the gold standard for identifying epileptogenic lesions such as hippocampal sclerosis, cortical malformations, or tumors, which are critical for guiding treatment decisions. Oral anticonvulsant medications work by various mechanisms, including enhancing GABAergic inhibition, blocking voltage-gated sodium channels, or modulating calcium channels, thereby stabilizing neuronal excitability and preventing seizure propagation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Epilepsy affects approximately 1% of the global population, making it a common neurological disorder, not uncommon.\nOption B (Incorrect): While ECT induces therapeutic seizures, epilepsy itself is a neurological disorder and not directly related to the *discovery* of ECT.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hippocampal sclerosis is a leading cause of medically refractory temporal lobe epilepsy and is a strong indication for resective surgery in carefully selected patients.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Modality | Primary Utility in Epilepsy | Key Findings |\n|---|---|---|\n| **EEG** | Functional assessment of brain electrical activity | Epileptiform discharges, seizure patterns, background slowing |\n| **MRI Brain** | Structural assessment of brain anatomy | Hippocampal sclerosis, cortical dysplasia, tumors, vascular malformations |\n| **PET/SPECT** | Metabolic/perfusion assessment | Hypometabolism (PET) or hypoperfusion (SPECT) in epileptogenic zone |\n| **Video-EEG Monitoring** | Correlate clinical events with EEG changes | Precise localization of seizure onset, classification of seizure type |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MRI for structure, EEG for function, meds first, surgery for refractory cases.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, look for subtle hippocampal atrophy and increased T2 signal consistent with hippocampal sclerosis, or focal cortical dysplasia. Intraoperatively, during resective surgery, the goal is to remove the identified epileptogenic focus while preserving critical neurological function.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational League Against Epilepsy (ILAE) guidelines (e.g., 2017 classification of seizures and epilepsies) recommend MRI as a key diagnostic tool and oral anticonvulsants as first-line therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is relatively uncommon in the general population. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is related to the discovery of the use of ECT. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | should be investigated by the use of MR imaging. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | requires oral anticonvulsant therapy as first line management. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | when due to hippocampal sclerosis is not an indication for surgery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) should be investigated by the use of MR imaging.\nrequires oral anticonvulsant therapy as first line management.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
