  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Leukocoria demands immediate attention; it could be retinoblastoma's red flag.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer is correct. Retinoblastoma is a highly malignant, undifferentiated tumor originating from immature retinal cells, often with a hereditary component, and is effectively managed with radiotherapy among other modalities.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRetinoblastoma is classified as a malignant undifferentiated tumor because it arises from primitive retinoblasts, which are immature retinal cells that fail to differentiate properly. Its hereditary nature stems from germline mutations in the RB1 tumor suppressor gene, making it an autosomal dominant condition in many cases. Radiotherapy is a cornerstone of treatment due to the tumor's high radiosensitivity, particularly for localized disease, allowing for globe salvage and vision preservation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Ganglioneuroma is a benign tumor of the sympathetic nervous system, entirely unrelated to the retina or retinoblastoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Retinoblastoma is a highly aggressive malignancy that can and does metastasize, primarily to the brain, bone marrow, and lymph nodes, if not diagnosed and treated early.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hereditary Retinoblastoma | Sporadic Retinoblastoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Cause** | Germline RB1 mutation | Somatic RB1 mutation |\n| **Laterality** | Often bilateral/multifocal | Usually unilateral/unifocal |\n| **Age of Onset** | Earlier (mean 12 months) | Later (mean 24 months) |\n| **Risk of Secondary Cancers** | Significantly increased | Not increased |\n| **Family History** | Often positive | Usually negative |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think RB1 gene, leukocoria, and multimodal treatment for retinoblastoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound or CT), retinoblastoma often presents with characteristic intraocular calcifications. Intraoperatively or on fundoscopic exam, the classic sign is leukocoria (white pupillary reflex), often accompanied by strabismus or inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Retinoblastoma (most recent update) provides comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment, emphasizing a multidisciplinary approach.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is a type of ganglioneuroma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is a malignant undifferentiated tumour. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can be hereditary. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | does not metastasise. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | can be treated by radiotherapy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) is a malignant undifferentiated tumour.\ncan be hereditary.\ncan be treated by radiotherapy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
