  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Red eye, red flag: Don't let the gut distract from the globe!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies crucial diagnostic and clinical features in the differential diagnosis of acute red eye. Fluorescein is a vital tool for corneal assessment, conjunctivitis typically spares visual acuity, and the systemic symptoms of acute glaucoma can be highly misleading.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFluorescein dye, a hydrophilic molecule, stains exposed corneal stroma where epithelial cells are absent, making corneal abrasions or ulcers visible under cobalt blue light. Conjunctivitis, an inflammation of the conjunctiva, primarily affects the superficial vascularized membrane, leaving the cornea and deeper visual pathways unaffected. The severe pain and rapid rise in intraocular pressure during acute angle-closure glaucoma can trigger a strong vagal response, leading to nausea and vomiting, which can unfortunately mimic acute abdominal pathology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Steroid drops are generally contraindicated in infectious keratitis (e.g., herpes simplex) as they can suppress the immune response, worsen the infection, and lead to corneal melting or perforation. Their use requires careful diagnosis and specialist supervision.\nOption D (Incorrect): An exudate in the anterior chamber (hypopyon) is characteristic of severe intraocular inflammation or infection (e.g., endophthalmitis, severe uveitis), not acute glaucoma. In acute angle-closure glaucoma, the pupil is typically mid-dilated and fixed, not 'notched,' which might suggest iris atrophy or previous trauma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Conjunctivitis | Keratitis | Acute Angle-Closure Glaucoma | Anterior Uveitis |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Vision | Normal | Reduced | Markedly reduced | Reduced |\n| Pain | Gritty/Irritation | Moderate to Severe | Severe | Moderate |\n| Pupil | Normal | Normal | Mid-dilated, fixed | Small, irregular |\n| Discharge | Watery/Purulent | Minimal | None | None |\n| Fluorescein | Negative | Positive (if ulcer) | Negative | Negative |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't miss acute glaucoma; it's an ocular emergency with systemic mimics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn slit lamp examination, acute angle-closure glaucoma presents with corneal edema, a shallow anterior chamber, and a mid-dilated, fixed pupil. Gonioscopy would reveal angle closure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Patterns (PPP) for Acute Angle-Closure Glaucoma (2020) recommends immediate intraocular pressure reduction and referral.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a drop of fluorescein will show up corneal ulceration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | conjunctivitis does not affect vision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | steroid drops are used for keratitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | there is an exudate in the anterior chamber and the pupil is notched in gla | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | the vomiting in glaucoma can be mistaken as a symptom of an acute abdominal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABE) a drop of fluorescein will show up corneal ulceration.; conjunctivitis does not affect vision.; the vomiting in glaucoma can be mistaken as a symptom of an acute abdominal emergency.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
