  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keratitis: When the cornea cries, look for the dendrite's lies.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nKeratitis, an inflammation of the cornea, is frequently caused by viral infections, particularly herpes simplex virus (HSV) and varicella-zoster virus (VZV). Herpes simplex keratitis classically presents with a pathognomonic dendritic ulcer, while herpes zoster ophthalmicus can also lead to corneal involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHerpes simplex virus (HSV) is a neurotropic virus that can reactivate in the trigeminal ganglion, leading to corneal infection. The characteristic dendritic ulcer, a branching epithelial lesion, is formed by active viral replication and epithelial cell destruction, staining with fluorescein. Herpes zoster ophthalmicus (HZO), caused by varicella-zoster virus (VZV) reactivation in the trigeminal ganglion, can also involve the cornea, often presenting with pseudodendrites or stromal keratitis, especially if the nasociliary nerve (Hutchinson's sign) is involved.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Vitreous detachment is a separation of the posterior vitreous cortex from the retina, typically age-related or due to trauma, and is not a direct consequence or presentation of keratitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): While allergic reactions to penicillin can occur, direct keratitis from a penicillin injection is not a recognized complication. Ocular side effects from systemic medications are rare and typically not direct keratitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Herpes Simplex Keratitis (HSK) | Herpes Zoster Keratitis (HZK) | Bacterial Keratitis | Fungal Keratitis |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------- | :---------------------------- | :------------------ | :--------------- |\n| **Etiology** | HSV-1, HSV-2 | Varicella-Zoster Virus (VZV) | Bacteria (e.g., Pseudomonas, Staph) | Fungi (e.g., Fusarium, Aspergillus) |\n| **Lesion Type** | Dendritic ulcer, geographic ulcer | Pseudodendrites, stromal keratitis | Ulcer, infiltrates, hypopyon | Feathery borders, satellite lesions |\n| **Associated Signs**| Recurrent, unilateral | Skin rash (dermatomal), Hutchinson's sign | Rapid onset, severe pain, discharge | Often post-trauma (vegetable matter) |\n| **Treatment** | Antivirals (topical/oral) | Antivirals (oral), steroids | Topical antibiotics | Topical antifungals |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Dendritic ulcers = HSV keratitis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn slit lamp examination, a classic dendritic ulcer will appear as a branching, linear epithelial defect that stains brightly with fluorescein and has terminal bulbs. Stromal involvement may present as edema or infiltrates.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Herpes Simplex Virus Keratitis (2021). It recommends topical and/or oral antiviral therapy for active epithelial keratitis and prophylactic oral antivirals for recurrent disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is associated with herpes simplex infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | can follow herpes zoster. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | causes vitreous detachment. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | can present as a dendritic ulcer. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | can be caused by an injection of penicillin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABD) is associated with herpes simplex infection.; can follow herpes zoster.; can present as a dendritic ulcer.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
