  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let one eye's trauma blind the other's future.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer correctly identifies sympathetic ophthalmia as an autoimmune reaction. This rare, bilateral granulomatous panuveitis occurs following trauma or surgery to one eye, leading to an immune attack on the uninjured, 'sympathizing' eye.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSympathetic ophthalmia is a delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction. Trauma or surgery to the 'exciting' eye exposes normally sequestered uveal antigens (e.g., S-antigen, interphotoreceptor retinoid-binding protein) to the immune system. This triggers a T-cell mediated autoimmune response, where the immune system subsequently attacks similar antigens in the uninjured 'sympathizing' eye. This leads to chronic inflammation, characterized by granulomatous panuveitis, and can result in severe vision loss or blindness in both eyes if not promptly treated with immunosuppression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Conjunctivitis is superficial inflammation of the conjunctiva, not a deep, bilateral autoimmune panuveitis affecting the uveal tract.\nOption B (Incorrect): Subconjunctival hemorrhage is bleeding under the conjunctiva, often benign, and not an autoimmune disease. A fractured base of skull can cause periorbital ecchymosis but is unrelated to sympathetic ophthalmia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Infective conjunctivitis is an infection, not an autoimmune process, and typically does not lead to the severe, bilateral, vision-threatening inflammation seen in sympathetic ophthalmia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Horner’s syndrome is a neurological condition involving miosis, ptosis, and anhidrosis due to sympathetic nerve damage, entirely unrelated to the autoimmune pathology of sympathetic ophthalmia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Cause | Key Features | Affected Eye(s) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Sympathetic Ophthalmia | Autoimmune reaction to uveal antigens after penetrating trauma/surgery to one eye | Bilateral granulomatous panuveitis, Dalen-Fuchs nodules, choroidal thickening | Both (exciting and sympathizing) |\n| Endophthalmitis | Infection (bacterial/fungal) inside the eye | Severe pain, vision loss, hypopyon, vitritis | Usually unilateral (injured/post-op eye) |\n| Panuveitis | Inflammation of all parts of the uvea (iris, ciliary body, choroid) | Vision loss, pain, photophobia, floaters | Unilateral or bilateral |\n| Conjunctivitis | Inflammation of the conjunctiva (viral, bacterial, allergic) | Redness, discharge, itching/grittiness | Unilateral or bilateral |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Injured eye excites, uninjured eye suffers autoimmune attack.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, OCT may reveal Dalen-Fuchs nodules (collections of epithelioid cells and lymphocytes between Bruch's membrane and the RPE), choroidal thickening, and serous retinal detachments. Fluorescein angiography often shows multiple pinpoint leaks at the RPE level. Histopathology of the exciting eye (if enucleated) demonstrates diffuse granulomatous inflammation of the uveal tract with lymphocytes, epithelioid cells, and giant cells, typically sparing the choriocapillaris and retina.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Uveitis (latest edition): Recommends early recognition and aggressive immunosuppression (corticosteroids, immunomodulators) to preserve vision. Enucleation of the severely damaged exciting eye within 10-14 days of injury is considered preventative but is controversial if any vision is salvageable.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | conjunctivitis in both eyes due to injury. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | subconjunctival haemorrhage due to a fractured base of skull. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | infective (contagious) conjunctivitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | an autoimmune reaction causing blindness in a normal eye following injury o | ✅ Correct |\n| E | part of Horner’s syndrome. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) an autoimmune reaction causing blindness in a normal eye following injury of the other eye.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
