  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Painless lip ulcer? Think syphilis, not just a sore.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options B, C, and D accurately describe the clinical presentation of a primary syphilitic chancre of the lip. A chancre is typically a painless, indurated ulcer that leads to regional lymphadenopathy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA primary chancre, characteristic of primary syphilis, is caused by *Treponema pallidum*. It typically presents as a solitary, firm, painless ulcer with a clean base and raised, indurated borders. The induration imparts a 'button-like' or 'cartilaginous' feel upon palpation. Regional lymphadenopathy, often bilateral, firm, discrete, and non-tender ('shotty'), develops within a week of the chancre's appearance due to the lymphatic spread of the spirochete.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Bluish-black spots are not characteristic of a primary chancre; this description might be more aligned with conditions like Kaposi's sarcoma or certain vascular lesions.\nOption E (Incorrect): Perleche (angular cheilitis) is an inflammatory condition affecting the corners of the mouth, often due to fungal or bacterial infection, and is distinct from a syphilitic chancre.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Primary Syphilitic Chancre (Lip) | Herpes Labialis (Cold Sore) | Aphthous Ulcer (Canker Sore) |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------- | :-------------------------- | :--------------------------- |\n| **Etiology** | *Treponema pallidum* | Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV) | Unknown, immune dysregulation |\n| **Pain** | Painless | Painful | Painful |\n| **Appearance** | Firm, indurated, clean ulcer | Vesicles -> crusts | Shallow, white/yellow base, red halo |\n| **Lymphadenopathy** | Hard, shotty, non-tender | Variable, often tender | Rare |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Painless, indurated ulcer with shotty nodes = chancre until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., ultrasound) of the neck might show enlarged, hypoechoic, well-defined lymph nodes with preserved fatty hilum, consistent with reactive lymphadenopathy, but is not typically used for diagnosis of chancre itself. Diagnosis is clinical and serological.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Sexually Transmitted Infections Treatment Guidelines 2021 recommends penicillin G for syphilis treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | appears first as bluish-black spots. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | develops as a painless clean ulcer. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | imparts a button-like sensation to the examining fingers. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | produces hard shotty submandibular lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is also known as perleche. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCD) develops as a painless clean ulcer.; imparts a button-like sensation to the examining fingers.; produces hard shotty submandibular lymph nodes.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
