  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stomatitis: More than just a sore mouth, it's a systemic red flag.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies vitamin B deficiency, lichen planus, and kwashiorkor as conditions associated with stomatitis. Stomatitis, or inflammation of the oral mucosa, is a common manifestation of various systemic diseases, nutritional deficiencies, and immune-mediated conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVitamin B deficiencies (e.g., B2, B3, B6, B12) impair cellular metabolism and epithelial integrity, leading to mucosal inflammation. Lichen planus is a T-cell mediated autoimmune disorder targeting basal keratinocytes, causing chronic inflammatory lesions in the mouth. Kwashiorkor, severe protein-energy malnutrition, results in impaired tissue repair, mucosal atrophy, and increased susceptibility to inflammation and infection, manifesting as stomatitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Lupus vulgaris is a form of cutaneous tuberculosis primarily affecting the skin, not typically a direct cause of stomatitis, although oral tuberculosis can occur. Option D (Incorrect): Lead poisoning can cause a 'lead line' on the gums (Burton's line) and a metallic taste, but stomatitis is not a primary or direct manifestation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Etiology | Key Oral Manifestations |\n|---|---|---|\n| Vitamin B Deficiency | Nutritional (e.g., B2, B3, B12) | Stomatitis, glossitis, angular cheilitis, cheilosis |\n| Lichen Planus | Autoimmune (T-cell mediated) | Reticular white lesions, erosions, pain, burning sensation |\n| Kwashiorkor | Protein-energy malnutrition | Stomatitis, glossitis, angular cheilitis, mucosal atrophy, impaired healing |\n| Oral Candidiasis | Fungal infection (Candida albicans) | White pseudomembranous plaques, erythema, burning |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stomatitis is a red flag for nutritional, autoimmune, or systemic issues.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinical oral examination reveals erythematous, ulcerative, or white reticular lesions. Biopsy may be indicated for persistent or atypical lesions (e.g., lichen planus) to confirm diagnosis and rule out malignancy. Blood tests are crucial for diagnosing nutritional deficiencies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines on the management of severe malnutrition (2013) emphasize addressing nutritional deficiencies to prevent and treat associated oral manifestations like stomatitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | vitamin B deficiency. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | lupus vulgaris. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | lichen planus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | lead poisoning | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | kwashiorkor. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) vitamin B deficiency.; lichen planus.; kwashiorkor.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
