  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just treat the mouth; look for the systemic root!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer BCDE accurately reflects the diverse clinical presentations and systemic associations of aphthous stomatitis. This condition encompasses various ulcer types, including large/deep and herpetiform lesions, and can be a manifestation of systemic diseases like Behcet's and Reiter's syndromes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAphthous stomatitis, or recurrent aphthous ulcers (RAU), is characterized by painful, recurrent oral ulcers. While minor aphthae are most common, major aphthae (Sutton's disease) present as larger (>1 cm), deeper, and longer-lasting ulcers that can lead to scarring, validating option B. Herpetiform aphthae, though not viral, manifest as numerous small (1-3 mm) ulcers that coalesce into crops, supporting option C. Furthermore, RAU can be a significant component of systemic inflammatory conditions; Behcet's syndrome classically includes oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis (option D), and Reiter's syndrome (now reactive arthritis) can also feature oral lesions alongside arthritis, urethritis, and conjunctivitis (option E).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Telangiectasia, which refers to dilated small blood vessels, is not a characteristic feature of aphthous stomatitis. It is typically associated with conditions like hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia or chronic sun damage, not recurrent oral ulcers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Minor Aphthous Ulcers | Major Aphthous Ulcers | Herpetiform Aphthous Ulcers | Behcet's Syndrome |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Size | <1 cm | >1 cm | 1-3 mm | Variable, often multiple |\n| Depth | Shallow | Deep | Shallow | Deep |\n| Number | 1-5 | 1-3 | Numerous (10-100) | Multiple |\n| Location | Non-keratinized mucosa | Any oral site | Any oral site | Any oral site |\n| Healing | 7-14 days, no scar | Weeks to months, often scars | 7-10 days, no scar | Recurrent, can scar |\n| Associations | Stress, trauma | HIV, nutritional def. | None specific | Oral, genital ulcers, uveitis, skin lesions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Aphthous ulcers are diverse; consider systemic causes for severe or recurrent cases.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn clinical examination, aphthous ulcers appear as painful, round or oval lesions with a yellow-gray fibrinoid center and an erythematous halo. Biopsy, if performed to rule out other conditions, would show non-specific inflammation with a mixed infiltrate of lymphocytes, plasma cells, and neutrophils, without viral inclusions or granulomas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Oral Medicine (AAOM) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Recurrent Aphthous Stomatitis (2020). These guidelines recommend a thorough history and physical examination to differentiate between simple and complex aphthosis, and to screen for underlying systemic conditions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | telangiectasia occurs. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | ulcers can be large and deep. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | herpetiform ulcers appear in crops. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Behcet’s syndrome can be present. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Reiter’s syndrome can be present. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCDE) ulcers can be large and deep.; herpetiform ulcers appear in crops.; Behcet’s syndrome can be present.; Reiter’s syndrome can be present.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
