  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get thrushed by *Candida*'s many disguises!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct answer accurately identifies the three primary clinical forms of oral *Candida albicans* infection: pseudomembranous, atrophic, and hyperkeratotic. These represent distinct clinical manifestations of fungal overgrowth in the oral cavity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOral candidiasis, caused by the opportunistic fungus *Candida albicans*, manifests in several ways depending on host factors and the chronicity of the infection. Pseudomembranous candidiasis (thrush) is characterized by removable white plaques, often seen in immunocompromised patients. Atrophic candidiasis often presents as erythematous patches, commonly seen under dentures (denture stomatitis) or as angular cheilitis. Hyperkeratotic candidiasis (candidal leukoplakia) appears as non-removable white lesions, often with a more chronic course and potential for dysplasia, requiring biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Herpes labialis is caused by the Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV), not *Candida albicans*. It presents as vesicular lesions, typically on the lips.\nOption E (Incorrect): Herpangina is a viral illness caused by Coxsackievirus, characterized by painful ulcers and vesicles in the posterior oropharynx, distinct from fungal infections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Form of Candidiasis | Appearance | Common Sites | Key Feature/Associated Factor |\n| :----------------- | :--------- | :----------- | :---------------------------- |\n| Pseudomembranous   | Removable white plaques | Buccal mucosa, tongue, palate | Most common, easily scraped off |\n| Atrophic (Erythematous) | Red, inflamed areas | Palate (under dentures), tongue, angular cheilitis | Often associated with denture use or antibiotic therapy |\n| Hyperkeratotic (Chronic Hyperplastic) | Non-removable white patches | Buccal mucosa, tongue | Chronic, can be mistaken for leukoplakia, potential for dysplasia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Oral candidiasis isn't just thrush; recognize its pseudomembranous, atrophic, and hyperkeratotic forms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinical examination reveals characteristic white plaques (pseudomembranous), erythematous patches (atrophic), or non-removable white lesions (hyperkeratotic). Microscopic examination of a potassium hydroxide (KOH) smear from a lesion will show hyphae and pseudohyphae, confirming the fungal etiology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Candidiasis (2016) recommends fluconazole as the primary treatment for most forms of oral candidiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the hyperkeratotic. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | the atrophic. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the pseudomembranous. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | herpes labialis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | herpangina. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABC) the hyperkeratotic.; the atrophic.; the pseudomembranous.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
