  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 White patch? Biopsy it, don't just watch it.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT because all listed options are indeed recognized causes or significant contributing factors to the development of oral leukoplakia. Leukoplakia is a clinical diagnosis of exclusion for a white patch that cannot be scraped off and cannot be classified as any other disease, often resulting from chronic irritation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeukoplakia represents a spectrum of epithelial changes, from hyperkeratosis to severe dysplasia, often induced by chronic irritation. Chemical irritants like those in tobacco (smoking) and alcohol (spirit drinking), as well as mechanical trauma from sharp teeth or ill-fitting dentures, stimulate epithelial hyperplasia and hyperkeratosis, leading to the characteristic white appearance. Certain practices like spice chewing (e.g., betel quid) combine both chemical and mechanical irritation. Additionally, chronic candidiasis can present as a white patch that may be clinically indistinguishable from other forms of leukoplakia and can sometimes be a co-factor or precursor to dysplastic changes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options (A, B, C, D, E) are recognized causes or contributing factors to leukoplakia. There are no incorrect options in this question.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Leukoplakia | Erythroplakia | Oral Candidiasis (Pseudomembranous) |\n| :---------------- | :---------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------ |\n| **Appearance** | White patch, non-scrapable | Red patch, velvety | White patches, *scrapable* |\n| **Malignant Risk**| 5-20% (higher for non-homogenous) | 50-90% (very high) | Low (unless underlying immunosuppression) |\n| **Etiology** | Chronic irritation (smoking, alcohol, trauma, spices), candidiasis | Chronic irritation (smoking, alcohol) | Immunosuppression, antibiotics, steroids, xerostomia |\n| **Management** | Biopsy, cessation of irritants, excision | Biopsy, excision, close follow-up | Antifungals (topical/systemic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Leukoplakia: think chronic irritation and rule out malignancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn intraoperative examination, leukoplakia appears as a persistent white patch or plaque. The key intraoperative step is a biopsy (incisional or excisional) to determine the presence and degree of dysplasia or malignancy, as visual inspection alone is unreliable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Classification of Head and Neck Tumours (5th Ed, 2022). It defines leukoplakia as a 'white plaque of questionable risk having excluded (other) known diseases or disorders that carry no increased risk for cancer,' emphasizing the need for histological assessment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | smoking. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | sharp edges of teeth. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | spirit drinking. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | spice chewing. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | candidiasis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABCDE) smoking.; sharp edges of teeth.; spirit drinking.; spice chewing.; candidiasis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
