  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 AOM: Don't just look in the ear, look at the whole child!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAcute otitis media (AOM) is a common pediatric infection with a varied clinical presentation, extending beyond localized ear symptoms. It can also lead to significant local complications if left untreated or if severe.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAOM, particularly in younger children, can manifest with non-specific systemic symptoms like vomiting, diarrhea, and poor feeding, due to systemic inflammation and potential vagal nerve irritation. Furthermore, the inflammatory process and pus accumulation within the middle ear can increase pressure on the tympanic membrane, leading to spontaneous perforation and subsequent otorrhea, which often provides symptomatic relief from pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): AOM does not inevitably cause acute mastoiditis; mastoiditis is a serious but uncommon complication. Most cases of AOM resolve without this progression.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Telephonist's ear' is a historical term for ear discomfort or otitis externa related to prolonged telephone use, not synonymous with acute otitis media, which is a middle ear infection.\nOption E (Incorrect): Myringotomy is not inevitably required for AOM. It is reserved for specific indications such as severe pain, bulging tympanic membrane unresponsive to antibiotics, or complications, not routine management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Otitis Media (AOM) | Otitis Media with Effusion (OME) | Acute Mastoiditis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pathophysiology | Bacterial/viral infection of middle ear | Fluid in middle ear without acute infection | Infection of mastoid air cells |\n| Key Symptoms | Ear pain, fever, irritability, vomiting | Hearing loss, ear fullness, no acute pain/fever | Postauricular pain/swelling, fever, ear protrusion |\n| Tympanic Membrane | Bulging, erythematous, decreased mobility | Retracted or neutral, fluid level, decreased mobility | Often normal or signs of AOM |\n| Treatment | Antibiotics, analgesics | Watchful waiting, sometimes tubes | IV antibiotics, mastoidectomy if needed |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: AOM is more than just ear pain; consider systemic symptoms and potential complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn otoscopy, a bulging, erythematous, and poorly mobile tympanic membrane is characteristic of AOM. In cases of perforation, a visible hole with purulent discharge may be seen. For suspected mastoiditis, a CT scan would show opacification and possible coalescence of mastoid air cells.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Acute Otitis Media (2013, reaffirmed 2016). This guideline recommends observation for certain cases, antibiotics for others, and emphasizes pain management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | can present with vomiting. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | inevitably causes acute mastoiditis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | causes perforation of the eardrum. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is synonymous with ‘telephonist’s ear’. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | inevitably requires myringotomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) can present with vomiting.\ncauses perforation of the eardrum.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
