  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let your patients get 'surgical mumps' – hydrate them!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAcute parotitis is a common condition that can arise from various etiologies, including bacterial infection and as a complication in the postoperative period. The correct options highlight these two significant aspects of its presentation and cause.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPostoperative parotitis, often referred to as 'surgical mumps,' is typically a non-specific bacterial infection, most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus. It arises from salivary stasis due to dehydration, NPO status, and anticholinergic medications, which allows for the retrograde ascent of oral flora into the parotid duct. This mechanism explains why it is a likely occurrence following major surgery, especially in elderly or debilitated patients, and why it is due to a non-specific bacterial infection rather than a unique pathogen.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Coxsackie A virus is primarily associated with hand-foot-and-mouth disease, not acute parotitis. The classic viral cause of parotitis is the mumps virus.\nOption D (Incorrect): Acute parotitis is initially managed conservatively with hydration, antibiotics, and sialogogues. Immediate incision and drainage are reserved for confirmed abscess formation, not for the initial presentation of parotitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Early acute parotitis presents with diffuse, firm, and tender swelling. Fluctuance is a late sign, indicating the development of an abscess, and is not immediately present upon onset.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Bacterial Parotitis | Viral Parotitis (Mumps) | Chronic Sialadenitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | S. aureus, oral flora | Mumps virus | Recurrent obstruction, autoimmune |\n| Onset | Acute, often post-op | Acute, prodromal symptoms | Recurrent, waxing/waning |\n| Symptoms | Unilateral, painful swelling, fever, purulent discharge | Bilateral, painful swelling, fever, malaise | Recurrent swelling, pain, often after meals |\n| Treatment | Hydration, antibiotics, sialogogues; I&D for abscess | Supportive care, analgesics | Address obstruction, antibiotics for flares, sialogogues |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-op parotitis = bacterial, dehydration, stasis. Hydrate your patients!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or ultrasound, acute parotitis appears as diffuse glandular enlargement with heterogeneous enhancement and periglandular inflammatory changes. Abscess formation would show a well-defined, hypoechoic or low-attenuation collection with peripheral enhancement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThere isn't a single, universally adopted clinical practice guideline specifically for acute parotitis. However, management principles are derived from general surgical practice and infectious disease recommendations, such as those from the Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) for soft tissue infections, which guide antibiotic selection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | may be due to non-specific Beeteral infection. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | may be due to the Coxsackie A virus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is likely in the postoperative period following major surgery. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | requires immediate incision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | with pus formation is immediately fluctuant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) may be due to non-specific Beeteral infection.\nis likely in the postoperative period following major surgery.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
