  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Submandibular stones: easy access, happy patient.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because submandibular duct stones (sialoliths) are typically located in Wharton's duct, which opens onto the floor of the mouth. This anatomical accessibility allows for a transoral approach to remove the stone, a procedure known as sialolithotomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe transoral approach for submandibular duct stones leverages the superficial location of Wharton's duct on the floor of the mouth, particularly anteriorly. Under local anesthesia, an incision can be made directly over the palpable stone, allowing for its extraction while preserving the duct and gland function. This minimally invasive technique avoids external incisions and associated risks, making it the preferred method for accessible ductal stones.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Submandibular stones in the gland often require gland excision (sialadenectomy) if symptomatic and not amenable to transoral removal, which is typically performed via a neck incision. Simple extraction of a stone from within the gland via a neck incision is not the standard approach.\nOption C (Incorrect): Submandibular calculi are significantly more common than parotid calculi, accounting for approximately 80-90% of all salivary gland stones.\nOption D (Incorrect): Salivary stones are primarily composed of calcium phosphate (hydroxyapatite), not calcium carbonate.\nOption E (Incorrect): A parotid duct stone causes obstruction, leading to pain, swelling, and potential infection (sialadenitis), but typically does not cause true cysts of the parotid gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Submandibular Gland/Duct |\n|---|---|\n| Duct Name | Wharton's Duct |\n| Duct Opening | Floor of mouth (sublingual papilla) |\n| Stone Prevalence | ~80-90% of all salivary stones |\n| Stone Composition | Calcium phosphate (hydroxyapatite) |\n| Surgical Approach (Duct Stone) | Transoral sialolithotomy (floor of mouth) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Submandibular stones: \"Wharton's on the floor, so go through the door.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain film (occlusal view), submandibular stones are often radiopaque. CT scan is highly sensitive for detecting stones, showing hyperdense foci within the duct or gland. Intraoperatively, a palpable stone in Wharton's duct can be milked anteriorly, and a small incision made directly over it.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2016). This guideline recommends transoral removal for accessible submandibular duct stones and considers sialendoscopy for diagnosis and treatment of salivary gland obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | submandibular stones in the duct are removed via the floor of the mouth. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | submandibular stones in the gland are extracted from the gland through an i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | parotid calculi are more common than submandibular calculi. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | -ssalivary stones contain calcium carbonate. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a parotid duct stone causes cysts of the parotid. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) submandibular stones in the duct are removed via the floor of the mouth.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
