  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duct stone out, gland stays stout!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is to remove the stone by making an opening in the duct. This approach directly addresses the obstruction caused by the submandibular calculus, allowing for its extraction while preserving the salivary gland's function. It is the most appropriate and least invasive surgical intervention for a stone located within the duct.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis surgical approach, known as sialolithotomy, involves a precise incision over the palpable stone in the floor of the mouth, directly into Wharton's duct. The anatomical proximity of Wharton's duct to the lingual nerve and sublingual gland necessitates careful dissection to avoid injury. By directly incising the duct and extracting the calculus, salivary flow is restored, alleviating symptoms of pain, swelling, and infection, and preventing further gland damage. This method is preferred for accessible stones, as it avoids the morbidity associated with gland excision.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Dilation is ineffective for a solid calculus; it might temporarily relieve some pressure but will not remove the obstruction.\nOption C (Incorrect): Slitting the papilla is insufficient as the calculus is typically located further within the duct, not just at the orifice.\nOption D (Incorrect): Removing the gland is an overly aggressive procedure for an isolated ductal stone and is reserved for recurrent stones, chronic sialadenitis, or malignancy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ligating the duct would cause permanent obstruction, leading to gland atrophy, pain, and potential infection, exacerbating the problem rather than solving it.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment | Indication | Mechanism | Outcome |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Conservative | Small, distal stones; mild symptoms | Hydration, massage, sialogogues | Spontaneous passage, symptom relief |\n| Sialolithotomy | Palpable ductal stones | Surgical incision over stone, extraction | Stone removal, duct patency, gland preservation |\n| Sialendoscopy | Smaller, non-palpable ductal stones; diagnostic | Endoscopic visualization, basket/forceps extraction | Stone removal, duct patency, minimally invasive |\n| Gland Excision | Recurrent stones, chronic sialadenitis, large/proximal stones, malignancy | Surgical removal of entire gland | Definitive treatment, loss of gland function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ductal stone = ductal incision for removal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an occlusal radiograph or CT scan, a submandibular calculus typically appears as a radiopaque lesion within the course of Wharton's duct. Intraoperatively, the stone is often palpable in the floor of the mouth, and after a mucosal incision, it can be directly visualized and extracted from the opened duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2016) recommends sialolithotomy for accessible stones in the submandibular duct.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | dilate the duct. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | remove the stone by making an opening in the duct. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | slit open the duct at the papilla. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | remove the gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | ligature the duct. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) remove the stone by making an opening in the duct.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
