  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let Sjögren's dry up your diagnostic acumen!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the hallmark sicca symptoms of Sjögren's syndrome (dry eyes and dry mouth) and its common association with other autoimmune conditions, specifically rheumatoid arthritis. Sjögren's is a chronic autoimmune disease primarily affecting exocrine glands.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSjögren's syndrome is characterized by lymphocytic infiltration and destruction of exocrine glands, particularly the lacrimal and salivary glands. This leads to xerophthalmia (dry eyes) and xerostomia (dry mouth), which are the primary diagnostic features. It is frequently a secondary condition, occurring in conjunction with other systemic autoimmune diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis (RA) or systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), indicating a shared underlying autoimmune predisposition and pathogenesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Psoriasis is a chronic autoimmune skin condition characterized by scaly plaques, and while it is an autoimmune disease, it is not a recognized feature or common direct association of Sjögren's syndrome.\nOption D (Incorrect): Proptosis, or exophthalmos, is the bulging of the eye, most commonly associated with Graves' ophthalmopathy (thyroid eye disease), not Sjögren's syndrome. Sjögren's causes ocular dryness, not protrusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Manifestation | Key Associated Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sjögren's Syndrome | Dry eyes (xerophthalmia), dry mouth (xerostomia) | Rheumatoid Arthritis, SLE, B-cell lymphoma risk |\n| Graves' Disease | Hyperthyroidism | Proptosis, pretibial myxedema, thyroid acropachy |\n| Psoriasis | Erythematous, scaly skin plaques | Psoriatic arthritis, nail changes, metabolic syndrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sjögren's: dry eyes, dry mouth, often RA's autoimmune friend.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, salivary gland scintigraphy may show decreased uptake and excretion in Sjögren's. Biopsy of minor salivary glands (e.g., labial) can reveal focal lymphocytic sialadenitis, a key diagnostic finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2016 American College of Rheumatology/European League Against Rheumatism (ACR/EULAR) classification criteria for primary Sjögren's Syndrome recommend evaluating ocular and oral symptoms, objective tests (ocular staining score, unstimulated whole salivary flow), and serology (anti-Ro/SSA antibodies).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | dry eyes. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | rheumatoid arthritis. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | psoriasis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | proptosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a dry mouth. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) dry eyes.\nrheumatoid arthritis.\na dry mouth.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
