  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Smoking + Supraglottic = Bad News Larynx.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are B and D. Malignant laryngeal tumors are indeed strongly associated with smoking, and supraglottic tumors are known for their propensity for early metastasis due to rich lymphatic drainage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe vast majority of laryngeal cancers are squamous cell carcinomas, directly linked to chronic exposure to carcinogens in tobacco smoke. The supraglottic larynx possesses an extensive and interconnected lymphatic network, allowing for rapid and often bilateral spread to cervical lymph nodes, even with relatively small primary tumors. This contrasts sharply with the glottic larynx, which has a sparse lymphatic supply, delaying metastatic spread and often leading to a better prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Laryngeal cancers are overwhelmingly squamous cell carcinomas, not columnar-celled. Columnar cells are typically found in glandular tissues.\nOption C (Incorrect): Glottic tumors generally carry the *best* prognosis among laryngeal subsites. Their early symptom (hoarseness) and limited lymphatic drainage lead to earlier detection and less metastatic spread compared to supraglottic or subglottic tumors.\nOption E (Incorrect): Early-stage laryngeal squamous cell carcinomas, particularly glottic ones, are highly radiosensitive, and radiation therapy is a cornerstone of treatment, often preserving voice function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Glottic Larynx | Supraglottic Larynx | Subglottic Larynx |\n| :--------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | True vocal cords | Epiglottis, aryepiglottic folds, false vocal cords | Below vocal cords to cricoid cartilage |\n| **Lymphatics** | Sparse | Rich, bilateral | Moderate, to paratracheal nodes |\n| **Presentation** | Early hoarseness | Dysphagia, odynophagia, neck mass, muffled voice | Stridor, dyspnea, hoarseness (late) |\n| **Prognosis** | Best (early symptoms, late metastasis) | Worst (early metastasis, often advanced at Dx) | Intermediate/Poor (often advanced at Dx) |\n| **Radiosensitivity** | High | High | High |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Smoking fuels laryngeal cancer; supraglottic spreads fast.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRI, look for cartilage invasion, especially of the thyroid cartilage, and evaluate for cervical lymphadenopathy, particularly in levels II, III, and IV. Endoscopy will reveal the primary tumor's extent and vocal cord mobility.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (e.g., 2024). These guidelines recommend a multidisciplinary approach, emphasizing accurate staging and tailored treatment plans involving surgery, radiation, and/or chemotherapy based on tumor location and stage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are characteristically columnar-celled. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | are associated with smoking. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | if glottic carry the worst prognosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | if supraglottic metastasise early. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | are not radiosensitive. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D) are associated with smoking.\nif supraglottic metastasise early.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
