  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Classical neck dissection: No pain, no gain... for the tumor!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Classical block dissection of the neck, also known as Radical Neck Dissection (RND), is a comprehensive oncologic procedure performed to remove metastatic lymph nodes from the neck, often in conjunction with primary tumor resection like laryngectomy. The correct options accurately describe key components of this extensive surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nClassical Radical Neck Dissection (RND) is characterized by the en bloc removal of lymph node levels I through V, along with the sternocleidomastoid muscle (SCM), internal jugular vein (IJV), and spinal accessory nerve (SAN). Removing a length of the IJV is standard to ensure complete clearance of lymph nodes within the carotid sheath. Detaching the SCM from its lower attachment provides wide surgical access to the deeper structures of the neck, facilitating thorough lymphadenectomy, and it is subsequently resutured. The contents of the supraclavicular triangle, which include lymph node levels IV and V, are routinely removed to achieve comprehensive oncologic clearance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Partial thyroidectomy is not a standard component of the neck dissection itself. While a laryngectomy may involve a total thyroidectomy if the tumor extends to the thyroid, partial thyroidectomy is not inherently part of the neck dissection.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ligation of the common carotid artery is a catastrophic event leading to severe cerebral ischemia and is never a planned part of a neck dissection. The carotid artery is meticulously preserved.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Classical Radical Neck Dissection (RND) | Modified Radical Neck Dissection (MRND) | Selective Neck Dissection (SND) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lymph Node Levels Removed** | I, II, III, IV, V | I, II, III, IV, V | Specific levels (e.g., I-III, II-IV) |\n| **Sternocleidomastoid Muscle (SCM)** | Removed | Preserved | Preserved |\n| **Internal Jugular Vein (IJV)** | Removed | Preserved | Preserved |\n| **Spinal Accessory Nerve (SAN)** | Removed | Preserved | Preserved |\n| **Indications** | Extensive nodal disease, extracapsular spread | Nodal disease without extensive involvement of non-lymphatic structures | Clinically N0 neck or limited nodal disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Classical RND sacrifices SCM, IJV, SAN for oncologic clearance.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, classical radical neck dissection involves identifying and sacrificing the sternocleidomastoid muscle, internal jugular vein, and spinal accessory nerve to achieve en bloc removal of lymph node levels I-V.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (2023): Provides comprehensive recommendations for surgical management, including indications and techniques for neck dissection in conjunction with laryngectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a length of the internal jugular vein is removed. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | partial thyroidectomy may have to be included. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the sternomastoid is detached from its lower attachment and resutured at th | ✅ Correct |\n| D | the common carotid artery is ligated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | the contents of the supraclavicular triangle should be removed. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) a length of the internal jugular vein is removed.\nthe sternomastoid is detached from its lower attachment and resutured at the end of the operation.\nthe contents of the supraclavicular triangle should be removed.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
