  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be a couch potato, know your neck masses!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, sternomastoid muscle. The term 'potato' tumour of the neck colloquially refers to fibromatosis colli, a benign fibrous mass found within the sternocleidomastoid muscle, typically in infants.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibromatosis colli, also known as congenital muscular torticollis, presents as a firm, non-tender, fusiform mass within the sternocleidomastoid muscle, usually appearing 2-4 weeks after birth. It is thought to result from birth trauma or intrauterine malposition leading to muscle ischemia and fibrosis. The mass is typically located in the lower to middle third of the muscle and is associated with head tilt and limited range of motion. It is benign and often resolves spontaneously with physical therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Carotid body tumors (paragangliomas) are neuroendocrine tumors located at the carotid bifurcation, typically pulsatile and mobile side-to-side but not vertically (positive Fontaine's sign). They are not described as 'potato' tumors.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thyroid gland nodules are within the thyroid, move with swallowing, and are not typically referred to as 'potato' tumors.\nOption D (Incorrect): Parotid gland tumors are located in the preauricular or angle of mandible region, distinct from the sternocleidomastoid muscle.\nOption E (Incorrect): Parathyroid gland adenomas are small, deep, and rarely palpable as a distinct mass, let alone a 'potato' tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Neck Mass | Location | Characteristics | Age Group |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Fibromatosis Colli | Sternocleidomastoid muscle | Firm, non-tender, fusiform mass, associated with torticollis | Infants (2-4 weeks) |\n| Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Midline, moves with tongue protrusion | Smooth, cystic, moves with swallowing and tongue | Any age, often childhood |\n| Branchial Cleft Cyst | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM | Soft, fluctuant, often presents with infection | Children/Young adults |\n| Cervical Lymphadenopathy | Various, often posterior triangle | Mobile, rubbery, can be tender if inflammatory | Any age, common in children |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: 'Potato' tumor = Fibromatosis Colli = Sternocleidomastoid muscle = Infant torticollis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, fibromatosis colli appears as a fusiform, hyperechoic or heterogeneous enlargement of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, often with increased vascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Congenital Muscular Torticollis (2018). Recommends early physical therapy as the primary treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | sternomastoid muscle. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | carotid body. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | thyroid gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | parotid gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | parathyroid gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) sternomastoid muscle.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
