  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 TB lymphadenitis: The neck's silent, matted menace.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options C, D, and E accurately describe key features of tuberculous lymphadenitis of the neck. This condition, often referred to as scrofula, is a classic manifestation of extrapulmonary tuberculosis with distinct clinical and pathological characteristics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTuberculous lymphadenitis is a chronic granulomatous inflammatory process. The 'matting together' of nodes (D) results from periadenitis and inflammation spreading beyond the capsule, fusing adjacent nodes. A 'collar stud abscess' (E) is pathognomonic, forming when a cold abscess erodes through the deep cervical fascia into the subcutaneous tissue, creating a dumbbell-shaped collection. While often localized, a 'primary focus in the lungs may be present' (C) because TB is a systemic disease, and lymphatic spread from a pulmonary focus is a common pathway for extrapulmonary manifestations.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While TB lymphadenitis can occur at any age, it is more commonly seen in younger adults, children, or immunocompromised individuals, not specifically elderly women. The age and gender are not characteristic defining features. \nOption B (Incorrect): The vast majority of human tuberculous lymphadenitis cases are caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis (human type). Mycobacterium bovis (bovine type) is a less common cause, typically associated with consumption of unpasteurized dairy products.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Tuberculous Lymphadenitis | Acute Bacterial Lymphadenitis | Metastatic Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Insidious, chronic | Acute, rapid | Progressive, often painless |\n| Consistency | Firm, rubbery, matted | Tender, warm, fluctuant | Hard, fixed, non-tender |\n| Abscess | Cold abscess, collar-stud | Hot abscess, purulent | Rare, central necrosis |\n| Systemic Sx | Fever, night sweats, weight loss (variable) | Fever, malaise, leukocytosis | Variable, weight loss, fatigue |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Matted nodes, cold abscess, and collar-stud formation scream TB lymphadenitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or ultrasound, you would typically see enlarged, often centrally necrotic lymph nodes with peripheral enhancement, sometimes with calcifications. Intraoperatively, expect matted nodes, caseous material, and thick, fibrotic capsules, making dissection challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the programmatic management of drug-resistant tuberculosis (2020) recommend specific regimens for extrapulmonary TB, including lymphadenitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the patient may be an elderly woman. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | the bovine bacillus is mostly responsible. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | a primary focus in the lungs may be present. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | the nodes tend to be matted together. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | a collar stud abscess may form. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D, E) a primary focus in the lungs may be present.\nthe nodes tend to be matted together.\na collar stud abscess may form.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
