  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ignore a lump in the neck; FNAC is your friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, B, and E accurately define types of thyroid nodules and the essential initial investigation. Understanding the terminology for discrete thyroid swellings and the role of fine needle aspiration cytology (FNAC) is fundamental to thyroid pathology and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOption A correctly defines an 'isolated' thyroid nodule as a single palpable lesion within an otherwise impalpable or normal-feeling thyroid gland. Option B accurately describes a 'dominant' nodule as a prominent swelling within a gland that exhibits generalized nodularity, often seen in multinodular goiter. Option E highlights the critical role of FNAC, which is the cornerstone investigation for any clinically significant thyroid nodule to assess its malignant potential and guide further management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): 'are rarely malignant if isolated.' This is false. Isolated thyroid nodules have a malignancy risk similar to or even slightly higher than dominant nodules in a multinodular gland, typically ranging from 5-15%. The term 'isolated' does not imply benignity.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'if ‘hot’ on isotope scanning are invariably malignant.' This is profoundly false and a common misconception. 'Hot' (hyperfunctioning) nodules on isotope scanning are almost invariably benign (<1% malignancy risk) and are typically associated with hyperthyroidism. Malignant thyroid nodules are almost always 'cold' (non-functioning) on isotope scanning.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nodule Type | Definition | Malignancy Risk | Key Investigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Isolated Nodule | Single palpable nodule in an otherwise impalpable gland | ~5-15% | Ultrasound, FNAC |\n| Dominant Nodule | Most prominent nodule in a gland with generalized nodularity | ~5-15% | Ultrasound, FNAC |\n| 'Hot' Nodule (on scan) | Hyperfunctioning on isotope scan | <1% (almost always benign) | TSH, Isotope Scan |\n| 'Cold' Nodule (on scan) | Non-functioning on isotope scan | ~5-15% | Ultrasound, FNAC |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: All discrete thyroid nodules require ultrasound and FNAC for risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a discrete thyroid swelling appears as a focal lesion with varying echogenicity, margins, and vascularity. Intraoperatively, it presents as a palpable, distinct mass within the thyroid parenchyma, which may be encapsulated or infiltrative depending on its nature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015) recommend ultrasound and FNAC as the primary tools for risk stratification of thyroid nodules.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are termed isolated if in an otherwise impalpable gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | are termed dominant if in a gland of generalised nodularity. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | are rarely malignant if isolated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | if ‘hot’ on isotope scanning are invariably malignant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | should be investigated by FNAC. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABE) are termed isolated if in an otherwise impalpable gland.\nare termed dominant if in a gland of generalised nodularity.\nshould be investigated by FNAC.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
