  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thyroid cancer: It's mostly papillary and follicular, but don't forget the rare squamous!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the primary malignant tumors of the thyroid, including papillary, follicular, and the less common primary squamous cell carcinoma. These represent distinct histological types originating within the thyroid gland, crucial for accurate diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPapillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) and follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) arise from thyroid follicular cells and constitute the vast majority of thyroid malignancies, with PTC being the most prevalent. Primary squamous cell carcinoma of the thyroid, though extremely rare, is a distinct and aggressive entity originating from metaplastic squamous epithelium within the thyroid or from thyroglossal duct remnants. Understanding these primary types is fundamental for surgical oncologists.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Columnar cell carcinoma is a rare histological variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma, not a distinct primary tumor type itself.\nOption E (Incorrect): Basaloid carcinoma is a type of carcinoma typically found in other organs like the lung, salivary glands, or skin, and is not recognized as a primary malignant tumor of the thyroid gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Thyroid Cancer | Origin | Prevalence | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Papillary | Follicular cells | Most common (80-85%) | Orphan Annie eye nuclei, psammoma bodies |\n| Follicular | Follicular cells | Second most common (10-15%) | Capsular/vascular invasion for diagnosis |\n| Medullary | Parafollicular C cells | Rare (1-2%) | Calcitonin production, MEN syndromes |\n| Anaplastic | Follicular cells (dedifferentiated) | Very rare (<1%) | Highly aggressive, rapidly growing mass |\n| Squamous | Metaplastic squamous epithelium | Extremely rare | Aggressive, often presents with local invasion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the common follicular cell cancers (papillary, follicular) and the rare but primary squamous.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, papillary carcinomas often appear as hypoechoic, solid nodules with irregular margins, microcalcifications, and taller-than-wide shape. Follicular carcinomas are typically solid, iso- or hyperechoic, and may be difficult to distinguish from benign adenomas preoperatively, often requiring surgical excision for definitive diagnosis. Intraoperatively, papillary tumors may be firm and gritty, while follicular tumors can be encapsulated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015 (updated 2023). The ATA guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the management of thyroid nodules and differentiated thyroid cancer, including diagnostic workup, surgical extent, and adjuvant therapies based on risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | squamous. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | papillary. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | columnar. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | follicular. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | basaloid. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABD) squamous.\npapillary.\nfollicular.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
