  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hyperparathyroidism: When your calcium's high, your mind might fly!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer is correct. Personality changes, including depression, anxiety, and cognitive dysfunction, are well-documented neuropsychiatric manifestations of hypercalcemia, a hallmark of hyperparathyroidism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary hyperparathyroidism leads to excessive parathyroid hormone (PTH) secretion, causing hypercalcemia. Elevated calcium levels disrupt neuronal function, leading to a spectrum of central nervous system symptoms, often summarized as \"psychiatric overtones.\" Beyond the CNS, hypercalcemia also impacts renal function (stones), bone metabolism (bones), and gastrointestinal motility (groans), contributing to the classic mnemonic \"stones, bones, abdominal groans, and psychiatric overtones.\"\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Risus sardonicus is a characteristic facial spasm seen in tetanus or strychnine poisoning, not hyperparathyroidism.\nOption B (Incorrect): Tetany is a sign of hypocalcemia, characterized by involuntary muscle contractions, which is the opposite of hypercalcemia.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Lumpy and bumpy lips\" is not a recognized clinical sign associated with hyperparathyroidism or any specific medical condition.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hypothermia is not a feature of hyperparathyroidism; severe hypercalcemia can sometimes lead to hyperthermia, but hypothermia is incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hypercalcemia (Hyperparathyroidism) | Hypocalcemia |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Neurological** | Personality changes, lethargy, confusion, weakness | Tetany, paresthesias, seizures, Chvostek's/Trousseau's signs |\n| **Musculoskeletal** | Bone pain, fractures, osteitis fibrosa cystica | Muscle cramps, spasms |\n| **Gastrointestinal** | Nausea, vomiting, constipation, pancreatitis | Abdominal pain |\n| **Renal** | Polyuria, polydipsia, nephrolithiasis, renal insufficiency | Renal osteodystrophy (chronic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Stones, bones, groans, moans, and psychiatric overtones\" for hyperparathyroidism.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a Sestamibi scan or ultrasound may localize a parathyroid adenoma. Intraoperatively, a single enlarged, discolored parathyroid gland is often identified and excised.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Primary Hyperparathyroidism (2016). Recommends surgical parathyroidectomy for symptomatic patients and those meeting specific criteria.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | risus sardonicus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | tetany. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | personality changes. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | lumpy and bumpy lips. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | hypothermia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) personality changes.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
