  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let hypercalcemia's causes calcify your brain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, C, and E, representing primary hyperparathyroidism, malignancy-associated hypercalcemia, and granulomatous disease, respectively. These are three of the most common and distinct etiologies of elevated serum calcium encountered in clinical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary hyperparathyroidism, often due to a parathyroid adenoma, causes autonomous overproduction of parathyroid hormone (PTH), leading to increased bone resorption, renal calcium reabsorption, and enhanced vitamin D activation. Multiple myeloma causes hypercalcemia primarily through osteolytic bone destruction mediated by local cytokine release (e.g., osteoclast activating factors) from plasma cells. Sarcoidosis, a granulomatous disease, leads to unregulated extra-renal production of 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D by activated macrophages within granulomas, increasing intestinal calcium absorption.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Acute pancreatitis typically causes hypocalcemia, not hypercalcemia, due to the saponification of calcium in areas of fat necrosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): While phaeochromocytoma can be associated with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2A (MEN 2A), which includes primary hyperparathyroidism (a cause of hypercalcemia), the phaeochromocytoma itself does not directly cause hypercalcemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Hypercalcemia | Primary Mechanism | Key Biochemical Feature |\n| :--------------------- | :---------------- | :---------------------- |\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Excess PTH secretion | High PTH, High Ca |\n| Malignancy (e.g., Myeloma) | Osteolysis / PTHrP | Low/Normal PTH, High Ca |\n| Granulomatous Disease (e.g., Sarcoidosis) | Unregulated 1,25-Vit D | Low PTH, High Ca, High 1,25-Vit D |\n| Acute Pancreatitis | Calcium saponification | Low Ca (Hypocalcemia) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hypercalcemia's top three: PTH, malignancy, granulomas.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor parathyroid adenoma, a Sestamibi scan (SPECT/CT) is crucial for localization preoperatively, showing a focal area of increased uptake. Intraoperatively, the adenoma appears as an enlarged, often darker, parathyroid gland. Multiple myeloma may show characteristic \"punched-out\" lytic lesions on skeletal surveys or CT scans. Sarcoidosis often presents with bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy and pulmonary infiltrates on chest imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Primary Hyperparathyroidism (2016) recommends surgical parathyroidectomy for symptomatic patients and asymptomatic patients meeting specific criteria.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | parathyroid adenoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | acute pancreatitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | multiple myeloma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | phaeochromocytoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | sarcoidosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) parathyroid adenoma.\nmultiple myeloma.\nsarcoidosis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
