  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adrenal cortex: GFR for Salt, Sugar, Sex.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Options A, C, and D are correct. The adrenal cortex is a vital endocrine gland composed of distinct zones, each responsible for producing specific steroid hormones, including mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids, and androgens.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe adrenal cortex is anatomically divided into three distinct layers: the outermost zona glomerulosa, the middle zona fasciculata, and the innermost zona reticularis. The zona glomerulosa primarily produces mineralocorticoids like aldosterone. The zona fasciculata is responsible for glucocorticoid production, mainly cortisol. The zona reticularis, as correctly identified, is the primary site for adrenal androgen synthesis, such as dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) and androstenedione.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The acanthotic layer refers to the stratum spinosum of the epidermis, a layer of the skin, not a component of the adrenal cortex.\nOption E (Incorrect): Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) is a pituitary hormone that stimulates, rather than inhibits, the adrenal cortex, particularly the zona fasciculata and reticularis, to produce cortisol and androgens.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Cortex Zone | Location | Primary Hormone(s) | Regulation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Zona Glomerulosa | Outermost | Mineralocorticoids (Aldosterone) | Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System (RAAS), K+ |\n| Zona Fasciculata | Middle | Glucocorticoids (Cortisol) | ACTH |\n| Zona Reticularis | Innermost | Androgens (DHEA, Androstenedione) | ACTH |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"GFR\" (Glomerulosa, Fasciculata, Reticularis) for \"Salt, Sugar, Sex\" (Mineralocorticoids, Glucocorticoids, Androgens).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, the adrenal glands appear as small, Y or V-shaped structures superior to the kidneys. Intraoperatively, they are yellowish-brown, retroperitoneal organs, often surrounded by fat, with the right gland typically more superior and posterior to the IVC, and the left gland more medial to the spleen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Incidentalomas (2016) recommends evaluation for hormonal overproduction and malignancy in incidentally discovered adrenal masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | contains the glomerular zone. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | contains the acanthotic layer. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | contains the reticular zone. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | makes androgens. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is inhibited by ACTH. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACD) contains the glomerular zone.\ncontains the reticular zone.\nmakes androgens.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
