  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cortex loves ACTH, Medulla loves catecholamines!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are D (ACTH) and E (SYNACTHEN). Both of these substances are directly involved in stimulating or assessing the function of the adrenal cortex, making them key tests for adrenocortical activity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdrenocorticotropic Hormone (ACTH) is a polypeptide hormone produced by the anterior pituitary gland that stimulates the adrenal cortex to produce and secrete glucocorticoids (like cortisol), mineralocorticoids, and adrenal androgens. Synacthen, also known as cosyntropin, is a synthetic analogue of the first 24 amino acids of human ACTH. It is widely used in the ACTH stimulation test (or Synacthen test) to evaluate the functional reserve of the adrenal cortex, particularly in diagnosing primary or secondary adrenal insufficiency. This direct stimulatory action on the adrenal cortex is the physiological basis for their use in assessing adrenocortical activity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (VMA) (Incorrect): Vanillylmandelic acid is a metabolite of catecholamines (epinephrine and norepinephrine) and is primarily used in the diagnosis of pheochromocytoma and neuroblastoma, which are tumors of the adrenal medulla or sympathetic nervous system, not the cortex.\nOption B (MIBG) (Incorrect): Metaiodobenzylguanidine (MIBG) scanning is a nuclear medicine imaging technique used to localize neuroendocrine tumors, especially pheochromocytomas and paragangliomas, which originate from chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla or sympathetic ganglia.\nOption C (ERE) (Incorrect): ERE is not a recognized standard medical abbreviation for a test related to adrenocortical activity. It serves as a distractor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test/Substance | Primary Use                                     | Adrenal Gland Region Assessed |\n| :------------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------- |\n| ACTH           | Pituitary hormone stimulating adrenal cortex   | Cortex                        |\n| Synacthen      | Synthetic ACTH for adrenal stimulation test     | Cortex                        |\n| VMA            | Metabolite of catecholamines                    | Medulla                       |\n| MIBG Scan      | Imaging for pheochromocytoma/neuroblastoma      | Medulla                       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ACTH and Synacthen test the adrenal cortex; VMA and MIBG test the medulla.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), adrenocortical activity may manifest as normal-sized glands, atrophy (in primary adrenal insufficiency), or hyperplasia/adenoma (in Cushing's syndrome or congenital adrenal hyperplasia). Intraoperatively, the adrenal gland's size, color, and texture can indicate underlying pathology, such as a cortical adenoma or diffuse hyperplasia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society's 2016 Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Primary Adrenal Insufficiency recommends the ACTH (cosyntropin) stimulation test as the primary diagnostic tool.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | VMA. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MIBG. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ERE. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | ACTH. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | SYNACTHEN. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: DE) ACTH.\nSYNACTHEN.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
