  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Aldosterone: The salt-saver, potassium-purger.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies aldosterone as a mineralocorticoid, which is its primary classification and function. Aldosterone is a steroid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex, essential for regulating electrolyte balance and blood pressure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAldosterone's role as the principal mineralocorticoid is to act on the renal distal convoluted tubules and collecting ducts. Here, it promotes the reabsorption of sodium (Na+) and water, while simultaneously stimulating the excretion of potassium (K+) and hydrogen ions (H+). This action is critical for maintaining extracellular fluid volume, blood pressure, and acid-base balance, making it a key component of the Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System (RAAS).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While aldosterone indirectly affects water balance by promoting sodium reabsorption, its primary direct action is on electrolytes. Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) directly regulates water balance.\nOption C (Incorrect): Aldosterone stimulates sodium *reabsorption*, not excretion. It conserves sodium in the body.\nOption D (Incorrect): Aldosterone stimulates potassium *excretion*, not retention. It helps rid the body of excess potassium.\nOption E (Incorrect): Glucocorticoids, such as cortisol, are primarily responsible for facilitating gluconeogenesis, not mineralocorticoids like aldosterone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Class | Primary Action | Key Effect |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Aldosterone | Mineralocorticoid | Na+ reabsorption, K+ excretion | Regulates blood pressure & electrolytes |\n| Cortisol | Glucocorticoid | Glucose metabolism, anti-inflammatory | Stress response, immune modulation |\n| ADH (Vasopressin) | Peptide hormone | Water reabsorption | Regulates plasma osmolality |\n| Parathyroid Hormone | Peptide hormone | Ca2+ reabsorption, PO4 excretion | Regulates calcium homeostasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Aldosterone: Na+ in, K+ out, H2O follows.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, an adrenal adenoma (Conn's syndrome) may be seen as a well-circumscribed mass in the adrenal gland, often unilateral. Intraoperatively, this would appear as a distinct nodule within the adrenal cortex, which, if resected, can cure primary hyperaldosteronism.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Primary Aldosteronism (2016) recommends screening for primary aldosteronism in patients with hypertension and specific risk factors, such as spontaneous hypokalemia or resistant hypertension.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is a mineralocorticoid. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | regulates water balance. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | stimulates sodium excretion. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | stimulates potassium retention. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | facilitates gluconeogenesis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) is a mineralocorticoid.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
