  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Addison's: When your adrenals take a permanent vacation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are C, D, and E. Addison's disease, or primary adrenal insufficiency, is characterized by deficient production of cortisol, aldosterone, and adrenal androgens. This leads to a constellation of symptoms including hyperpigmentation, muscle weakness, and in females, loss of body hair.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe characteristic pigmentation (E) seen in Addison's disease is due to the loss of negative feedback from cortisol, leading to increased ACTH secretion. ACTH shares a common precursor with melanocyte-stimulating hormone (MSH), thus stimulating melanocytes. Muscular weakness (D) arises from the combined effects of cortisol deficiency (general malaise, fatigue) and aldosterone deficiency, which causes hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypovolemia. Loss of body hair (C) in females is a direct consequence of reduced adrenal androgen production, as these are significant contributors to pubic and axillary hair.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (hyperglycaemia): Incorrect. Cortisol is a glucocorticoid that promotes gluconeogenesis. Its deficiency in Addison's leads to hypoglycaemia, especially during fasting or stress.\nOption B (hypertension): Incorrect. Aldosterone is a mineralocorticoid that promotes sodium and water retention. Its deficiency in Addison's leads to hypotension due to hypovolemia and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Addison's Disease (Primary Adrenal Insufficiency) | Cushing's Syndrome (Hypercortisolism) | Conn's Syndrome (Primary Hyperaldosteronism) |\n| :---------------- | :------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------- |\n| **Cortisol** | Low | High | Normal |\n| **Aldosterone** | Low | Normal/High | High |\n| **ACTH** | High (Primary) | Low (Adrenal) / High (Pituitary) | Normal |\n| **Blood Pressure**| Hypotension | Hypertension | Hypertension |\n| **Glucose** | Hypoglycemia | Hyperglycemia | Normal |\n| **Potassium** | Hyperkalemia | Hypokalemia | Hypokalemia |\n| **Pigmentation** | Hyperpigmentation (due to high ACTH) | No pigmentation | No pigmentation |\n| **Body Hair** | Loss (females) | Hirsutism (females) | Normal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Addison's 'adds' pigmentation and weakness, but 'subtracts' blood pressure and glucose.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRI, autoimmune Addison's typically shows small, atrophic adrenal glands. If due to infection (e.g., TB) or metastatic disease, enlarged or nodular adrenals may be seen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Primary Adrenal Insufficiency (2016) recommends specific diagnostic criteria and lifelong hormone replacement therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | hyperglycaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | hypertension. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | loss of body hair. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | muscular weakness. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | pigmentation of the mouth. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: CDE) loss of body hair.\nmuscular weakness.\npigmentation of the mouth.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
