  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cushing's: When cortisol runs wild, the body pays the price.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer correctly identifies kyphoscoliosis, limb muscle atrophy, acne, and glycosuria as clinical features of Cushing's disease. This condition, caused by chronic hypercortisolism, manifests with a wide array of systemic effects due to cortisol's pervasive influence on metabolism, musculoskeletal, and integumentary systems.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic excess cortisol leads to protein catabolism, causing limb muscle atrophy and thinning of the skin, which can contribute to striae and easy bruising. Bone demineralization from increased osteoclast activity and decreased osteoblast function results in osteoporosis, predisposing to vertebral compression fractures and kyphoscoliosis. Hypercortisolism also induces insulin resistance and increased gluconeogenesis, leading to hyperglycemia and often glycosuria. Furthermore, increased adrenal androgen production contributes to skin manifestations like acne and hirsutism.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (kyphoscoliosis): Correct. Result of osteoporosis and vertebral compression fractures from chronic hypercortisolism. \nOption B (limb muscle atrophy): Correct. Due to protein catabolism and muscle wasting. \nOption C (acne): Correct. Caused by increased adrenal androgen production. \nOption D (glycosuria): Correct. A consequence of hyperglycemia due to insulin resistance and increased gluconeogenesis. \nOption E (Hippocratic facies): Incorrect. Hippocratic facies, characterized by sunken eyes and emaciation, is associated with severe dehydration or prolonged illness, not the plethoric 'moon facies' seen in Cushing's disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cushing's Disease | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Body Habitus** | Central obesity, 'moon facies', 'buffalo hump' | Fat redistribution, fluid retention |\n| **Musculoskeletal** | Proximal muscle weakness, limb atrophy, osteoporosis, kyphosis | Protein catabolism, bone resorption |\n| **Skin** | Thin skin, easy bruising, purple striae, acne, hirsutism | Collagen breakdown, androgen excess |\n| **Metabolic** | Hyperglycemia, glycosuria, hypertension | Insulin resistance, gluconeogenesis, mineralocorticoid effects |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cushing's: too much cortisol, too many systemic problems.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPituitary MRI is crucial for identifying the microadenoma in Cushing's disease; adrenal CT for adrenal adenomas in Cushing's syndrome.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis of Cushing's Syndrome (2008, updated 2015) recommends initial screening with 24-hour urinary free cortisol, late-night salivary cortisol, or low-dose dexamethasone suppression test.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | kyphoscoliosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | limb muscle atrophy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | acne. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | glycosuria. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hippocratic facies. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABCD) kyphoscoliosis.\nlimb muscle atrophy.\nacne.\nglycosuria.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
