  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Breast imaging: X-rays for calcifications, sound for solids vs. fluid.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Options A and C are correct. Mammography utilizes high amperage X-rays for imaging, and ultrasonography is highly effective in differentiating cystic from solid breast lesions due to its physical principles.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMammography relies on an X-ray tube where a high voltage accelerates electrons from a cathode to an anode. The current (amperage) flowing through the filament determines the number of electrons, which in turn dictates the quantity of X-rays produced, impacting image quality and dose. Ultrasonography, conversely, uses high-frequency sound waves. These waves reflect differently off fluid-filled structures (cysts, appearing anechoic) compared to solid tissues (tumors, appearing hypoechoic or complex), allowing for clear differentiation without ionizing radiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Ductography involves injecting contrast into a duct and can be uncomfortable or painful, often requiring local anesthesia. It is a useful diagnostic tool for specific nipple discharge but not universally painless.\nOption D (Incorrect): While FNAC with a 23-gauge needle is generally well-tolerated, describing it as \"painless without anesthesia\" is an overstatement. Patient discomfort varies, and local anesthesia is frequently used or offered to ensure patient comfort and cooperation.\nOption E (Incorrect): FNAC is a valuable diagnostic tool but is not \"totally reliable.\" It has limitations, including potential for false negatives (sampling error, insufficient cells) and false positives, and often requires correlation with imaging and sometimes subsequent core biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Principle | Primary Use | Key Feature |\n| :------- | :-------- | :---------- | :---------- |\n| Mammography | X-rays | Screening, calcifications | Ionizing radiation |\n| Ultrasonography | Sound waves | Cyst vs. solid, dense breasts | No radiation, real-time |\n| MRI | Magnetic fields, radio waves | Staging, high-risk screening | High sensitivity, contrast |\n| Ductography | Contrast injection | Nipple discharge etiology | Invasive, specific |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ultrasound differentiates fluid from solid; mammography finds calcifications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple cyst appears anechoic with posterior acoustic enhancement. A solid mass appears hypoechoic with irregular margins and possibly posterior shadowing. Mammography can show spiculated masses, architectural distortion, or suspicious microcalcifications.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Breast Cancer Screening (2023) recommends annual mammography for average-risk women starting at age 40, with supplemental screening (ultrasound or MRI) for those with dense breasts or high risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | mammography submits the breast to high amperage x-rays. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | ductography is a painless and useful imaging technique. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ultrasonography can distinguish cystic from solid tumours. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | cytology derived from multiple passes of a 23 gauge needle with syringe suc | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | FNAC is totally reliable. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) mammography submits the breast to high amperage x-rays., ultrasonography can distinguish cystic from solid tumours.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
