  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the nipple weeps red, think papilloma ahead!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is duct papilloma. This is a benign, friable growth within the mammary ducts, making it the most common cause of spontaneous, unilateral, bloody nipple discharge. Its delicate, vascularized nature within the duct leads to bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuct papillomas are small, wart-like growths that develop within the milk ducts, often close to the nipple. Their delicate, vascularized structure makes them prone to micro-trauma and subsequent bleeding into the ductal system, which then presents as a blood-stained discharge from the nipple. This intraductal location is key to their presentation, as the blood has a direct path to exit the nipple.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Breast abscess typically presents with purulent (pus-filled) discharge, pain, redness, and warmth, not blood-stained discharge.\nOption B (Incorrect): Fibroadenomas are benign solid tumors of glandular and stromal tissue. They rarely cause nipple discharge, and if they do, it's typically not bloody.\nOption D (Incorrect): Duct ectasia involves dilation of the subareolar ducts, often leading to a thick, sticky, multi-colored (green, brown, black) discharge, but rarely bloody discharge.\nOption E (Incorrect): Fat necrosis is a benign inflammatory process resulting from trauma or surgery. It typically presents as a firm mass with skin dimpling or retraction, not nipple discharge.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause | Type of Discharge | Associated Symptoms | Malignancy Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Duct Papilloma | Bloody, serosanguinous, unilateral, spontaneous | Often none, sometimes palpable mass | Low (but can be associated with atypical hyperplasia or carcinoma) |\n| Duct Ectasia | Thick, sticky, multi-colored (green, brown, black) | Nipple retraction, subareolar mass, burning pain | Very low |\n| Intraductal Carcinoma | Bloody, serous, unilateral, spontaneous | May be associated with a mass, skin changes | High |\n| Breast Abscess | Purulent (pus) | Pain, redness, warmth, fever | None (infectious) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody nipple discharge = think papilloma first, but always rule out cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, papillomas may be occult or present as a small mass or calcifications. Ultrasound can show an intraductal mass. Ductography (galactography) is the most definitive imaging, showing a filling defect within the duct. Intraoperatively, excision of the involved duct (microdochectomy) reveals the small, friable lesion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Nipple Discharge (2019). It recommends evaluation of pathologic nipple discharge (spontaneous, unilateral, persistent, from a single duct, or bloody/serous) with imaging (mammogram, ultrasound) and consideration of ductography or MRI, followed by surgical excision for definitive diagnosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the likely presence of breast abscess. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | fibroadenoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | duct papilloma. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | duct ectasia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | fat necrosis of the breast. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) duct papilloma.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
