  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duct ectasia: not cancer, but a pain in the nipple!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct associations with mammary duct ectasia are plasma cell mastitis, retraction of the nipple, and bacterial infection. Mammary duct ectasia involves dilation of the subareolar ducts, leading to inflammation, fibrosis, and potential infection, which can manifest as nipple retraction and plasma cell infiltration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMammary duct ectasia is a benign condition characterized by dilation and inflammation of the major subareolar ducts. The stagnant secretions within these dilated ducts can lead to chronic inflammation, often with a prominent plasma cell infiltrate, hence 'plasma cell mastitis'. The periductal fibrosis and inflammation can cause shortening of the ducts, pulling the nipple inward, resulting in 'retraction of the nipple'. Secondary 'bacterial infection' can occur due to the altered ductal environment and stasis, leading to acute mastitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): blue domed cysts. Blue domed cysts are characteristic of fibrocystic changes, a different benign breast condition, not specifically mammary duct ectasia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Paget’s disease of the nipple. Paget's disease is a rare form of breast cancer involving the nipple epidermis, distinct from the benign inflammatory process of duct ectasia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Features | Etiology/Pathology | Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mammary Duct Ectasia | Dilated subareolar ducts, periductal inflammation, fibrosis | Stasis of secretions, chronic inflammation | Nipple discharge (multi-colored), nipple retraction, subareolar mass, pain, potential infection |\n| Fibrocystic Changes | Cysts, fibrosis, adenosis, apocrine metaplasia | Hormonal fluctuations | Lumpy, painful breasts, often bilateral, blue domed cysts |\n| Paget's Disease | Intraepithelial adenocarcinoma of nipple | Underlying ductal carcinoma in situ or invasive carcinoma | Eczematous changes of nipple/areola, itching, burning, ulceration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duct ectasia: inflammation, retraction, infection – a triad of trouble.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, dilated ducts, rod-like calcifications, or a subareolar mass may be seen. Ultrasound can confirm dilated ducts and periductal inflammation. Intraoperatively, dilated ducts with thick, often colored, secretions and surrounding fibrosis are characteristic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Benign Breast Disease (2016): Recommends conservative management for symptomatic duct ectasia, with surgery reserved for persistent symptoms or suspicion of malignancy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | blue domed cysts. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | plasma cell mastitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | retraction of the nipple. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | bacterial infection. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Paget’s disease of the nipple. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D) plasma cell mastitis., retraction of the nipple., bacterial infection.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
