  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fibrocystic changes: benign, common, and hormonally driven.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The term 'mammary dysplasia' historically encompassed a spectrum of benign breast changes, now more accurately referred to as fibrocystic changes or fibrocystic condition. The correct options (cyst formation, epitheliosis, and adenosis) represent the key histological features associated with this common benign breast alteration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibrocystic changes are a very common benign breast condition, often influenced by hormonal fluctuations. They are characterized by a combination of stromal fibrosis, cyst formation (dilated terminal duct-lobular units), epithelial hyperplasia (epitheliosis), and proliferation of glandular elements (adenosis). These changes can lead to palpable lumps, pain, and tenderness, and while generally benign, some forms of epithelial hyperplasia (e.g., atypical ductal hyperplasia) can slightly increase the future risk of breast cancer, necessitating careful pathological evaluation and follow-up.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Metaplasia refers to the reversible replacement of one differentiated cell type with another mature differentiated cell type. While apocrine metaplasia can occur within breast cysts, 'metaplasia' alone is too broad and not a primary defining feature of mammary dysplasia in the same way as the other options.\nOption C (Incorrect): Leucoplakia is a white patch on a mucous membrane, typically associated with chronic irritation or inflammation, and is primarily seen in oral or genital mucosa, not breast tissue. It has no relevance to mammary dysplasia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cyst Formation | Dilated terminal duct-lobular units filled with fluid. | Most common cause of breast lumps, often painful; typically benign. |\n| Epitheliosis | Proliferation of epithelial cells lining ducts or lobules. | Can be usual ductal hyperplasia (no increased risk) or atypical (increased risk for cancer). |\n| Adenosis | Increase in the number and size of glandular acini. | Can be sclerosing adenosis, which may mimic malignancy on imaging and palpation. |\n| Fibrosis | Increase in fibrous connective tissue. | Contributes to palpable lumpiness and firmness, often associated with pain.\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mammary dysplasia = fibrocystic changes: cysts, epitheliosis, adenosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, cysts appear as anechoic, well-circumscribed lesions with posterior acoustic enhancement. Fibrocystic changes can present as diffuse nodularity, microcysts, or areas of increased echogenicity. Mammography may show diffuse increased density, scattered calcifications, or circumscribed masses, often requiring further workup to rule out malignancy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (5th Edition, 2013). This atlas provides standardized terminology for reporting mammography, ultrasound, and MRI findings, including those related to fibrocystic changes, to guide appropriate management and follow-up.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | cyst formation. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | metaplasia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | leucoplakia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | epitheliosis. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | adenosis. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) cyst formation., epitheliosis., adenosis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
