  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, biopsy the nipple out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answers are B and C. Eczema of the nipple is often associated with irritant factors like lactation and characteristically presents with vesicles, distinguishing it from Paget's disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEczema is an inflammatory skin condition, and acute forms are classically characterized by erythema, papules, and vesicles, which can rupture and crust. Nipple eczema, particularly in lactating individuals, can be a form of irritant contact dermatitis due to friction, moisture, or allergic reactions to topical products. This direct association with lactation and the presence of vesicles are key clinical differentiators from Paget's disease, which is an intraepithelial adenocarcinoma and typically presents with persistent, scaly, erythematous lesions, often without prominent vesiculation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Both eczema and Paget's disease can present unilaterally. While Paget's is almost exclusively unilateral, eczema can also affect one nipple, making this an unreliable distinguishing feature.\nOption D (Incorrect): Eczema typically responds to simple treatments like topical corticosteroids and emollients. It is Paget's disease that characteristically does not respond to such treatments, prompting further investigation.\nOption E (Incorrect): This statement describes Paget's disease of the nipple, which is a manifestation of an underlying ductal carcinoma in situ or invasive breast cancer. Eczema is an inflammatory skin condition, not a malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Eczema of Nipple | Paget's Disease of Nipple |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Inflammatory, irritant, allergic | Intraepithelial adenocarcinoma |\n| Association | Lactation, atopy | Underlying breast carcinoma |\n| Vesicles | Common, especially acutely | Rare or absent |\n| Response to Tx | Responds to topical steroids | Does not respond to topical steroids |\n| Unilaterality | Can be uni- or bilateral | Almost always unilateral |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Persistent 'eczema' of the nipple that fails to respond to treatment is Paget's until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor Paget's disease, mammography or ultrasound may reveal an underlying breast mass, architectural distortion, or microcalcifications in up to 90% of cases. Biopsy (punch or shave) is diagnostic, showing Paget cells (large, pale, vacuolated cells) within the epidermis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology: Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend biopsy for any suspicious nipple lesion not responding to conservative management to rule out Paget's disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is unilateral. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is related to lactation. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | manifests vesicles. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | does not respond to simple treatment. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is associated with a minute duct carcinoma within the breast. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) is related to lactation., manifests vesicles.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
