  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ignore the subtle whispers; early detection saves lives.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A, a prickling sensation in a breast lump, is the correct answer. This symptom, while non-specific, can be an early indicator of a developing breast carcinoma, prompting timely investigation. The other options represent signs of locally advanced or metastatic disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEarly breast cancer often presents subtly, with a palpable lump being the most common initial sign. A prickling sensation, pain, or tenderness within a new or existing breast lump can arise from the tumor's growth irritating local nerve endings or rapidly expanding tissue. While not pathognomonic for cancer, any new or persistent sensory change associated with a breast mass should raise suspicion and trigger prompt diagnostic workup, as early detection significantly improves prognosis and treatment outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Peau d’orange is a sign of advanced breast cancer, indicating widespread dermal lymphatic invasion, often seen in inflammatory breast cancer. It is not an early diagnostic sign.\nOption C (Incorrect): Brawny arm refers to lymphedema of the arm, typically a complication of axillary lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or advanced lymphatic obstruction by tumor. It is a late-stage complication or iatrogenic effect, not an early diagnostic sign of the primary tumor.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cancer en cuirasse is a very late and aggressive manifestation of breast cancer where the skin of the chest wall becomes thickened and indurated, resembling a breastplate, due to extensive dermal lymphatic invasion. It is far from an early sign.\nOption E (Incorrect): Palpable axillary nodes usually indicate regional metastasis, meaning the cancer has already spread beyond the breast. While crucial for staging, it's generally not considered an *early* diagnostic sign of the primary tumor itself, but rather a sign of regional spread.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Stage | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Prickling sensation/new lump | Early | Subtle sensory change, palpable mass, warrants investigation |\n| Palpable axillary nodes | Intermediate/Late | Regional metastasis to lymph nodes, indicates spread |\n| Peau d'orange | Late | Skin edema, dimpling, orange peel appearance due to lymphatic obstruction |\n| Cancer en cuirasse | Very Late | Diffuse skin induration, 'breastplate' appearance, extensive dermal invasion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Any new breast symptom, however subtle, demands investigation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, early breast cancer may appear as microcalcifications, architectural distortion, or a spiculated mass. Ultrasound often reveals an irregular, hypoechoic mass. Intraoperatively, early cancers are typically firm, irregular, and non-encapsulated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer, Version 1.2024: Recommends prompt evaluation of any new breast symptom, including palpable masses or skin changes, with imaging (mammography, ultrasound) and biopsy as indicated.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a prickling sensation in a breast lump. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | peau d’orange. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | brawny arm. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | cancer en cuirasse. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | palpable axillary nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) a prickling sensation in a breast lump.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
