  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tethered skin means the tumor's got a grip, and it's T2!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, as skin tethering is a defining characteristic of a T2 tumor in the TNM classification for breast carcinoma. This indicates local invasion of the tumor into the dermal structures, which is a critical component of tumor staging beyond just size.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe TNM (Tumor, Node, Metastasis) staging system is fundamental for breast cancer management. The 'T' component describes the primary tumor's size and local extent. While T2 often refers to tumors between 2 cm and 5 cm, it also includes tumors of any size with direct extension to the skin (e.g., tethering, dimpling, ulceration, or edema/peau d'orange) or chest wall (excluding pectoralis muscle invasion). Skin tethering occurs when the tumor invades and shortens Cooper's ligaments, pulling the skin inward, signifying local advancement of the disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A tumor more than 5 cm in diameter would be classified as T3, not T2.\nOption C (Incorrect): Palpable but movable axillary nodes describe N1, which is the nodal component of the staging, not the primary tumor (T) component.\nOption D (Incorrect): Oedema of the arm is typically a sign of advanced nodal involvement (N3) or lymphedema, not a direct descriptor of a T2 primary tumor.\nOption E (Incorrect): 'No metastases' describes M0, which is the distant metastasis component of the staging, not the primary tumor (T) component.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| TNM Component | Description for Breast Cancer |\n|---|---|\n| **T1** | Tumor ≤ 2 cm in greatest dimension |\n| **T2** | Tumor > 2 cm but ≤ 5 cm, OR tumor of any size with direct extension to skin (tethering, dimpling, ulceration, edema) or chest wall (excluding pectoralis muscle invasion) |\n| **T3** | Tumor > 5 cm in greatest dimension |\n| **T4** | Tumor of any size with direct extension to chest wall (including pectoralis muscle invasion), skin ulceration, ipsilateral satellite nodules, or inflammatory carcinoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: T in TNM isn't just size; it's local invasion too!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography or ultrasound, skin tethering would appear as architectural distortion or retraction of the skin overlying the mass. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would observe the tumor directly adherent to the dermis, requiring careful dissection to achieve clear margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 8th Edition (2017). This manual provides the definitive criteria for TNM staging across various cancers, including breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the tumour is more than 5 cm in diameter. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | skin is tethered to the tumour. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | axillary nodes are palpable but movable. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | there is oedema of the arm. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | there are no metastases. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) skin is tethered to the tumour.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
