  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Patey: When you need to go big, but not *too* big.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately identifies the key anatomical structures removed en bloc during a Patey type of modified radical mastectomy. This procedure is designed for comprehensive tumor removal while preserving certain muscle groups compared to a classic radical mastectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Patey mastectomy, a form of modified radical mastectomy, involves the en bloc removal of the entire breast, including the nipple-areola complex, the pectoralis major muscle, and the clavipectoral fascia. This extensive resection ensures adequate oncological clearance, particularly when there is concern for tumor involvement of the pectoral fascia or muscle, or extensive lymphatic spread requiring thorough axillary dissection. The preservation of the pectoralis minor muscle distinguishes it from a Halsted radical mastectomy, aiming to reduce post-operative morbidity while maintaining oncologic efficacy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption E (Incorrect): 'the third and fourth anterior intercostal lymph nodes.' While axillary lymph node dissection is a component of a Patey mastectomy, specific anterior intercostal lymph nodes are not routinely included in the *en bloc* tissue removal. Their removal is not a defining characteristic of this procedure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Mastectomy Type | Breast Tissue | Pectoralis Major | Pectoralis Minor | Axillary LND |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Radical (Halsted)** | Whole Breast + Nipple | YES | YES | YES |\n| **Modified Radical (Patey)** | Whole Breast + Nipple | YES | NO (fascia removed) | YES |\n| **Modified Radical (Auchincloss)** | Whole Breast + Nipple | NO | NO | YES |\n| **Simple/Total** | Whole Breast + Nipple | NO | NO | NO (sentinel node only) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Patey removes breast, nipple, pectoralis major, clavipectoral fascia, and axillary nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after skin flap elevation, the pectoralis major muscle is clearly visible. Its removal exposes the pectoralis minor muscle and the clavipectoral fascia, which is then meticulously dissected to access the axillary contents for lymph node removal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (latest version) recommend various mastectomy types based on tumor characteristics, patient factors, and oncological principles.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | whole breast. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the nipple. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | the pectoralis major. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | the clavipectoral fascia. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | the third and fourth anterior intercostal lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, D) whole breast., the nipple., the pectoralis major., the clavipectoral fascia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
