  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your lung cancer types; they're not all created equal!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the primary histological classifications of bronchial carcinoma, which are crucial for diagnosis, prognosis, and treatment planning. These types represent the vast majority of lung cancers encountered clinically.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSquamous cell carcinoma typically arises from bronchial epithelium, often centrally, and is strongly linked to smoking. Adenocarcinoma, the most common type, originates from glandular cells, often peripherally, and can occur in non-smokers. Small cell lung carcinoma, also known as oat cell carcinoma, is a highly aggressive neuroendocrine tumor characterized by rapid growth and early metastasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Round-celled\" is a descriptive term but not a specific, recognized histological classification for bronchial carcinoma. While small cell carcinoma cells can appear round, \"oat-celled\" is the more precise and commonly used pathological term.\nOption D (Incorrect): Transitional cell carcinoma is a type of cancer primarily found in the urinary tract (e.g., bladder, renal pelvis) and is not a primary histological type of bronchial carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) | Adenocarcinoma (ADC) | Small Cell Lung Carcinoma (SCLC) |\n| :--------------- | :---------------------------- | :-------------------------- | :------------------------------- |\n| **Prevalence** | ~25-30% of NSCLC | ~40-50% of NSCLC | ~10-15% of all lung cancers |\n| **Origin** | Bronchial epithelium | Glandular cells | Neuroendocrine cells |\n| **Location** | Often central | Often peripheral | Central |\n| **Key Features** | Keratinization, intercellular bridges | Gland formation, mucin production | Small cells, scant cytoplasm, high mitotic rate |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lung cancer histology dictates prognosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, SCC often presents as a central mass with cavitation, while adenocarcinoma is more commonly a peripheral nodule or mass. SCLC typically presents as a large central mass with extensive mediastinal lymphadenopathy. Bronchoscopy may reveal an endobronchial lesion for SCC or SCLC, while ADC might require peripheral biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Classification of Tumours of the Lung, Pleura, Thymus and Heart (5th Edition, 2021) provides the definitive histological classification for these tumors. NCCN Guidelines for Lung Cancer (latest version) recommend treatment based on these classifications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | round-celled. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | squamous-celled. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | columnar-celled. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | transitional-celled. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | oat-celled. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) squamous-celled., columnar-celled., oat-celled.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
