  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lung cancer: a master of disguise, affecting systems far and wide.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights that bronchus carcinoma can manifest through various paraneoplastic syndromes, affecting systems distant from the primary tumor. These manifestations are often due to ectopic hormone production or autoimmune responses triggered by the cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEpileptiform fits can occur due to paraneoplastic limbic encephalitis (often associated with small cell lung cancer, SCLC) or severe hyponatremia secondary to SIADH (Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone secretion), also common in SCLC. Gynaecomastia can result from ectopic production of human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) or aromatase activity by the tumor, leading to increased estrogen levels. Peripheral neuropathy, such as Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome (LEMS) or sensory neuropathies, is a well-recognized paraneoplastic syndrome, particularly with SCLC, caused by autoantibodies targeting neuronal structures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Systemic sclerosis is an autoimmune connective tissue disease and is not a direct manifestation or common paraneoplastic syndrome of bronchus carcinoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hypocalcaemia is rare in bronchus carcinoma. Hypercalcaemia, often due to ectopic parathyroid hormone-related peptide (PTHrP) production, is a much more common paraneoplastic syndrome, especially with squamous cell carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Paraneoplastic Syndrome | Associated Lung Cancer Type | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| SIADH (Hyponatremia) | Small Cell Lung Cancer (SCLC) | Ectopic ADH production |\n| Hypercalcaemia | Squamous Cell Carcinoma | Ectopic PTHrP production |\n| Lambert-Eaton Myasthenic Syndrome (LEMS) | Small Cell Lung Cancer (SCLC) | Autoantibodies against presynaptic voltage-gated calcium channels |\n| Gynaecomastia | Large Cell Carcinoma, Adenocarcinoma | Ectopic hCG or aromatase production |\n| Limbic Encephalitis (Epileptiform fits) | Small Cell Lung Cancer (SCLC) | Autoimmune response (e.g., anti-Hu antibodies) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Paraneoplastic syndromes are diverse; think beyond direct tumor effects.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn chest CT, a primary lung mass, often with mediastinal lymphadenopathy, would be visible. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the primary tumor, assess resectability, and look for local or regional spread, which might be the underlying cause of these systemic manifestations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (2024) and Small Cell Lung Cancer (2024) provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and management, including recognition of paraneoplastic syndromes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | systemic sclerosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | epileptiform fits. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | gynaecomastia. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | hypocalcaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | peripheral neuropathy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) epileptiform fits., gynaecomastia., peripheral neuropathy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
