  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anterior mediastinum: Think '4 Ts' and surgical access.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe anterior mediastinum is a common site for various tumors and masses, and the correct options represent classic examples. Retrosternal goitre, teratoma, and thymic tumors all originate from or extend into this specific anatomical compartment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anterior mediastinum is defined as the space anterior to the pericardium and great vessels, extending from the sternum to the anterior aspect of the pericardium. It primarily contains the thymus, lymph nodes, and fat. Thymic tumors (thymoma, thymic carcinoma) arise directly from the thymus. Teratomas are germ cell tumors, often originating from pluripotent cells that migrate to this region during embryogenesis. Retrosternal goitre represents an extension of the cervical thyroid gland, which can descend into the anterior mediastinum due to its embryological origin and anatomical proximity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Neurofibromas are neurogenic tumors, typically arising from nerve sheaths, and are characteristic of the posterior mediastinum.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pleuropericardial cysts are congenital cysts typically found in the middle mediastinum, often at the cardiophrenic angle, not the anterior compartment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Mediastinal Compartment | Common Tumors/Masses |\n|---|---|\n| Anterior | Thymoma, Teratoma, Thyroid (retrosternal goitre), Lymphoma ('4 Ts') |\n| Middle | Bronchogenic cyst, Pericardial cyst, Lymphadenopathy, Tracheal tumors, Esophageal tumors |\n| Posterior | Neurogenic tumors (e.g., Neurofibroma, Schwannoma), Enteric cysts, Meningocele |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The 4 Ts of the anterior mediastinum are Thymoma, Teratoma, Thyroid, and 'Terrible' Lymphoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, retrosternal goitre appears as a heterogeneously enhancing mass continuous with the cervical thyroid. Teratomas often show fat, fluid, and calcifications. Thymic tumors are typically solid, well-circumscribed masses in the prevascular space. Intraoperatively, these masses are found anterior to the pericardium and great vessels, often requiring sternotomy for access.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Thymomas and Thymic Carcinomas (e.g., 2023) recommend complete surgical resection as the primary treatment for resectable disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | retrosternal goitre. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | teratoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | neurofibroma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | pleuropericardial cyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | thymic tumours. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) retrosternal goitre., teratoma., thymic tumours.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
