  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sarcoidosis: Granulomas gone wild, but not infectious.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key clinical associations with Boeck's sarcoidosis, a systemic granulomatous disease. These options highlight common immunological features and organ involvement characteristic of the condition. Understanding these manifestations is crucial for diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSarcoidosis is fundamentally an immune-mediated disorder, often leading to acquired immune dysfunction, particularly T-cell anergy, despite systemic inflammation. Erythema nodosum is a classic acute cutaneous manifestation, representing an inflammatory reaction in the subcutaneous fat, frequently seen in sarcoidosis. Enlarged parotids (parotid gland involvement) are also a recognized feature, sometimes part of Heerfordt's syndrome (uveoparotid fever), indicating glandular involvement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): \"pulmonary infiltration followed by hilar adenopathy.\" This describes the typical progression of tuberculosis, not sarcoidosis. In sarcoidosis, hilar adenopathy often precedes or occurs concurrently with pulmonary infiltrates, or can even be isolated.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"secondary infections.\" While chronic diseases can sometimes predispose to infections, secondary infections are not a primary or defining clinical association of sarcoidosis itself. The immune dysfunction in sarcoidosis is more complex than simple susceptibility to secondary infections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| System | Common Manifestations |\n|---|---|\n| Pulmonary | Hilar lymphadenopathy, interstitial infiltrates |\n| Cutaneous | Erythema nodosum, lupus pernio |\n| Glandular | Parotid enlargement, lacrimal gland enlargement |\n| Immune | Acquired immune dysfunction (anergy), hypercalcemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sarcoidosis: \"Anergy\" and \"non-caseating granulomas\" are key.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn chest X-ray or CT, bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy is a hallmark, often described as \"potato nodes.\" Pulmonary infiltrates can range from ground-glass opacities to reticulonodular patterns and fibrosis. Biopsy (e.g., transbronchial, lymph node) reveals non-caseating granulomas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thoracic Society (ATS) 2020 Clinical Practice Guideline: An Official ATS Clinical Practice Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Sarcoidosis. It provides comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment of sarcoidosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | acquired immune dysfunction. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | erythema nodosum. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | pulmonary infiltration followed by hilar adenopathy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | secondary infections. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | enlarged parotids. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) ['acquired immune dysfunction.', 'erythema nodosum.', 'enlarged parotids.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
