  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Left lung segments: Know them cold, or your patient might get cold.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe left lung is divided into two lobes: upper and lower. The upper lobe contains the apicoposterior, anterior, superior lingular, and inferior lingular segments. The lower lobe contains the superior, anteromedial basal, lateral basal, and posterior basal segments. Therefore, 'anterior upper,' 'superior lingular,' and 'lateral basal' are all valid segments of the left lung.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBronchopulmonary segments are the fundamental anatomical and functional units of the lung, each supplied by its own tertiary bronchus and pulmonary artery branch. This segmental organization is critical for surgical planning, allowing for precise segmentectomies to preserve lung parenchyma while removing localized pathology, such as early-stage lung cancer or localized infections. Accurate identification of these segments preoperatively via CT and intraoperatively is paramount for successful lung-sparing surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): The azygos lobe is an anatomical variant, typically found in the right upper lobe, not a standard segment of the left lung.\nOption D (Incorrect): The medial (cardiac) basal segment (S7) is a segment of the right lower lobe; the left lung typically has an anteromedial basal segment (S7+8) or lacks a distinct S7.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Segment Name | Left Lung | Right Lung | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Apicoposterior | Yes (S1+2) | Yes (S1, S2) | Upper Lobe |\n| Anterior | Yes (S3) | Yes (S3) | Upper Lobe |\n| Superior Lingular | Yes (S4) | N/A | Upper Lobe (Left only) |\n| Medial (Cardiac) Basal | No (often fused) | Yes (S7) | Lower Lobe |\n| Lateral Basal | Yes (S9) | Yes (S9) | Lower Lobe |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Left lung has 2 lobes, Right lung has 3 lobes; know their segments.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scans with 3D reconstruction clearly delineate bronchopulmonary segments, crucial for surgical planning. Intraoperatively, inflation/deflation techniques or indocyanine green (ICG) can help identify segmental planes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Society of Thoracic Surgeons (STS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Lung Cancer (2021) emphasize precise anatomical resection for optimal oncologic outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | anterior upper. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | superior lingular. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | azygos. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | medial (cardiac). | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | lateral basal. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) ['anterior upper.', 'superior lingular.', 'lateral basal.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
