  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bypass the block, relieve the pain, live to graft another day!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. This question accurately identifies key aspects of aortocoronary bypass grafting (CABG), including its primary indication, necessary anatomical prerequisites, expected symptomatic relief, and the common need for multiple grafts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCABG is a cornerstone of revascularization for severe coronary artery disease. Its main indication is often refractory angina, aiming to restore blood flow to ischemic myocardium. Successful grafting relies on identifying a significant stenosis proximally and a healthy, patent vessel distally to ensure adequate outflow and graft patency. The procedure typically offers excellent symptomatic relief, with a high percentage of patients experiencing freedom from angina. Given the diffuse nature of atherosclerosis, it is common for patients to have multi-vessel disease, necessitating the placement of multiple bypass grafts to revascularize all affected territories.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Lengths of femoral vein are not typically used for CABG. The most common venous conduit is the great saphenous vein, while arterial conduits like the internal mammary artery and radial artery are preferred for their superior long-term patency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Graft Type | Source | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n| :--------- | :----- | :--------- | :------------ |\n| Internal Mammary Artery (IMA) | Thoracic wall | Excellent long-term patency, arterial flow | Limited length, single vessel use |\n| Great Saphenous Vein (GSV) | Leg | Easily harvested, long lengths, multiple grafts | Poorer long-term patency than IMA, prone to intimal hyperplasia |\n| Radial Artery | Forearm | Good patency, arterial flow, less spasm than vein | Potential for forearm ischemia, spasm risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CABG success hinges on good targets, good conduits, and good indications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn coronary angiography, you would see significant stenoses (e.g., >70%) in major coronary arteries and patent distal vessels suitable for anastomosis. Intraoperatively, the surgeon identifies these target vessels, harvests conduits (e.g., LIMA, saphenous vein), and performs distal and proximal anastomoses under cardioplegic arrest or on-pump.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization. It recommends CABG for patients with severe angina refractory to medical therapy, left main coronary artery disease, or multi-vessel disease with reduced left ventricular function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the main indication is angina that cannot be controlled by medical means. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | coronary arteriography must show a blocked or stenosed coronary artery with | ✅ Correct |\n| C | lengths of femoral vein are used to bypass a narrowed artery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 80-90% can obtain relief from angina. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | more than one graft may be required. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D, E) ['the main indication is angina that cannot be controlled by medical means.', 'coronary arteriography must show a blocked or stenosed coronary artery with a normal vessel beyond.', '80-90% can obtain relief from angina.', 'more than one graft may be required.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
