  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Choose your suture wisely; some stay, some go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies materials that are designed to be broken down and absorbed by the body over time. This property is crucial for surgical applications where temporary tissue approximation is needed without leaving a permanent foreign body.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbsorbable sutures lose their tensile strength and are eventually metabolized by the body. Synthetic absorbable sutures, such as polymers of glycolide (e.g., polyglactin 910/Vicryl) and homopolymers of polydioxanone (PDS), are primarily broken down by hydrolysis, a predictable chemical process. Natural absorbable sutures like collagen (e.g., surgical gut/catgut) are degraded by enzymatic proteolysis, which can be less predictable due to individual patient factors. These materials are essential for internal closures where long-term foreign body presence is undesirable, allowing the tissue to heal and assume its own strength.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (polyamide) (Incorrect): Polyamide, commonly known as nylon, is a synthetic monofilament suture that is non-absorbable. It retains its tensile strength for extended periods and is used when permanent tissue support is needed.\nOption D (polypropylene) (Incorrect): Polypropylene, known by the trade name Prolene, is a synthetic monofilament suture that is non-absorbable. It is known for its inertness and long-term tensile strength, making it ideal for cardiovascular and permanent tissue approximation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Suture Type | Examples | Absorption Mechanism | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Absorbable Synthetic | Polyglactin 910 (Vicryl), Polydioxanone (PDS), Polyglycolic Acid (Dexon) | Hydrolysis | Predictable absorption, good initial tensile strength, minimal tissue reaction |\n| Absorbable Natural | Surgical Gut (Catgut) | Enzymatic degradation | Less predictable absorption, higher tissue reaction, rapid loss of tensile strength |\n| Non-absorbable Synthetic | Polypropylene (Prolene), Polyamide (Nylon), Polyester (Ethibond) | None | Permanent tissue support, minimal tissue reaction, retains tensile strength indefinitely |\n| Non-absorbable Natural | Silk, Cotton | None (encapsulated) | Loses tensile strength over time, higher tissue reaction, multifilament |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Absorbable sutures disappear; non-absorbable sutures stay.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, absorbable sutures are chosen for deep tissue layers, fascial closures that will heal, or ligatures where long-term strength isn't needed. They are often dyed violet or green for visibility. Non-absorbable sutures are typically used for skin closure (removed later), vascular anastomoses, or prosthetic fixation where permanent support is required.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) \"Surgical Knot Tying and Suture Selection\" (updated periodically). It recommends selecting suture material based on tissue type, wound healing characteristics, and desired duration of wound support, emphasizing absorbable sutures for temporary support and non-absorbable for permanent.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | polyamide. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | polymers of glycolide. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | homopolymer of polydioxanone. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | polypropylene. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | collagen. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) ['polymers of glycolide.', 'homopolymer of polydioxanone.', 'collagen.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
