  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anastomoses heal, but not always perfectly; vigilance is key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are haemorrhage and stenosis. These represent common and direct complications arising from the surgical creation and healing process of an intestinal anastomosis, reflecting both immediate technical issues and longer-term healing responses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHaemorrhage is an immediate complication, often due to inadequate hemostasis at the anastomotic line or disruption of small vessels during the surgical procedure. Stenosis, or stricture, is a later complication resulting from excessive fibrosis and scar tissue formation during the healing process, or from technical errors like an inverted anastomosis or excessive tension. Both are well-recognized sequelae that can significantly impact patient recovery and require further intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Diverticular formation is a chronic condition of the bowel wall, typically unrelated to the acute or subacute complications of an intestinal anastomosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Atresia is a congenital absence or closure of a normal body opening or tubular organ, not a complication that develops after an intestinal anastomosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Intussusception, while a possible post-operative complication, is less directly a complication of the anastomosis itself compared to bleeding or stenosis. It typically involves telescoping of one segment of bowel into another, often due to altered motility or a lead point, rather than a direct failure of the anastomotic healing.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Early (within 30 days) | Late (after 30 days) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Anastomotic Leak** | Yes | No |\n| **Haemorrhage** | Yes | No (unless chronic ulceration) |\n| **Stenosis/Stricture** | Less common early, more common late | Yes |\n| **Abscess/Fistula** | Yes | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think acute and chronic surgical healing issues for anastomotic complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, haemorrhage is directly visible and requires immediate control. Post-operatively, a CT scan with oral and IV contrast is the gold standard for evaluating anastomotic complications like leaks (extravasation of contrast), abscesses, or early signs of stricture (luminal narrowing).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anastomotic Leak Following Colorectal Surgery (2020) recommends early recognition and appropriate management strategies for anastomotic leaks, a severe complication often associated with other issues like hemorrhage or infection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | haemorrhage. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | diverticular formation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | stenosis. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | atresia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | intussusception. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) ['haemorrhage.', 'stenosis.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
