  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Reflux burns, hernias churn, oesophagus learns.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies acid reflux, alkaline reflux, and hiatus hernia as clinical associations with oesophagitis. Oesophagitis is inflammation of the oesophagus, primarily caused by chemical irritation from gastric or duodenal contents, often exacerbated by anatomical defects.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOesophagitis results from direct chemical injury to the esophageal mucosa. Acid reflux, involving gastric acid and pepsin, is the most common cause, leading to gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). Alkaline reflux, involving bile and pancreatic enzymes, can occur after gastric surgery or with pyloric dysfunction. A hiatus hernia, an anatomical defect where part of the stomach protrudes through the diaphragm, compromises the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) function, thereby predisposing individuals to both acid and alkaline reflux.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Scalds refer to thermal burns, which can cause acute esophageal injury but are not typically considered a chronic 'clinical association' in the same pathophysiological context as reflux. They represent a direct, acute trauma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Anaemia can be a *consequence* of chronic oesophagitis (e.g., from chronic blood loss due to erosions or ulcers), but it is not a *cause* or a direct *association* that leads to oesophagitis itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Oesophagitis | Primary Cause | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Reflux Oesophagitis | Gastric acid, pepsin, bile | Heartburn, regurgitation, dysphagia, often associated with GERD and hiatus hernia |\n| Eosinophilic Oesophagitis | Allergic reaction | Dysphagia, food impaction, often seen in atopic individuals, characteristic endoscopic rings |\n| Infectious Oesophagitis | Candida, Herpes Simplex Virus, CMV | Odynophagia, dysphagia, immunocompromised patients |\n| Pill-Induced Oesophagitis | Direct mucosal injury from medications | Acute onset odynophagia, typically localized, often due to NSAIDs, bisphosphonates, antibiotics |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Reflux is the primary cause of oesophagitis; anatomical defects exacerbate it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, oesophagitis appears as mucosal erythema, friability, erosions, or ulcers. Chronic reflux can lead to strictures or Barrett's oesophagus. A barium swallow may demonstrate reflux episodes or the presence of a hiatus hernia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of GERD (2022). These guidelines recommend lifestyle modifications, proton pump inhibitors (PPIs), and surgical intervention (e.g., fundoplication) for refractory cases or complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | scalds. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | acid reflux. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | alkaline reflux. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | anaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | hiatus hernia. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) ['acid reflux.', 'alkaline reflux.', 'hiatus hernia.']** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
