  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GDA: The common hepatic's first major split, crucial for foregut flow.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, hepatic artery. The gastroduodenal artery (GDA) is a direct and significant branch of the common hepatic artery, which itself originates from the celiac axis. This anatomical relationship is fundamental to understanding the vascular supply of the foregut.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe common hepatic artery arises from the celiac trunk. It then gives off the gastroduodenal artery (GDA) before continuing as the proper hepatic artery. The GDA descends posterior to the first part of the duodenum, supplying the pylorus, proximal duodenum, and head of the pancreas via its branches, including the superior pancreaticoduodenal arteries and the right gastroepiploic artery. This branching pattern is critical in surgical procedures like pancreaticoduodenectomy (Whipple procedure) and in managing upper gastrointestinal bleeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (coeliac axis.): Incorrect. The celiac axis is the origin of the common hepatic artery, which then gives rise to the GDA. The GDA is not a direct branch of the celiac axis itself.\nOption C (superior mesenteric artery.): Incorrect. The superior mesenteric artery (SMA) primarily supplies the midgut structures, not the foregut structures supplied by the GDA.\nOption D (_sgastroepiploic artery.): Incorrect. The right gastroepiploic artery is a branch of the gastroduodenal artery, not the other way around.\nOption E (splenic artery.): Incorrect. The splenic artery is another major branch of the celiac axis, supplying the spleen, greater curvature of the stomach, and pancreas, but it does not give rise to the GDA.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Origin | Major Branches | Primary Supply |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Celiac Axis | Abdominal Aorta (T12/L1) | Common Hepatic, Splenic, Left Gastric | Foregut (stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas, duodenum to ampulla) |\n| Common Hepatic Artery | Celiac Axis | Gastroduodenal, Proper Hepatic | Liver, Gallbladder, Stomach, Duodenum, Pancreas |\n| Gastroduodenal Artery | Common Hepatic Artery | Right Gastroepiploic, Superior Pancreaticoduodenal | Pylorus, Duodenum, Pancreatic Head, Greater Curvature of Stomach |\n| Superior Mesenteric Artery | Abdominal Aorta (L1) | Inferior Pancreaticoduodenal, Jejunal, Ileal, Ileocolic, Right Colic, Middle Colic | Midgut (duodenum distal to ampulla, jejunum, ileum, cecum, ascending colon, proximal 2/3 transverse colon) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Celiac trunk branches: Left Gastric, Splenic, Common Hepatic. GDA from Common Hepatic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, the GDA can be clearly visualized arising from the common hepatic artery, especially when evaluating for GI bleeding or planning complex pancreaticobiliary surgery. Intraoperatively, during a pancreaticoduodenectomy, the GDA is a key landmark, typically ligated and divided as it runs posterior to the first part of the duodenum, marking the plane for pancreatic head resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSabiston Textbook of Surgery (21st Edition, 2021) recommends a thorough understanding of foregut arterial anatomy for safe and effective abdominal surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | coeliac axis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | hepatic artery. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | superior mesenteric artery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | _sgastroepiploic artery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | splenic artery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) hepatic artery.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
