  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: When the olive is ripe, it's time to operate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answers, C and E, highlight the two classic physical examination findings that are the cornerstones for diagnosing hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (HPS) in infants: visible peristalsis and a palpable pyloric mass (the 'olive'). These signs directly reflect the underlying anatomical obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic pyloric stenosis involves a thickened pyloric muscle, leading to gastric outlet obstruction. The stomach attempts to overcome this obstruction with forceful contractions, which become visible as peristaltic waves across the epigastrium, moving from left to right. The hypertrophied pyloric muscle itself can often be palpated in the right upper quadrant as a firm, mobile, olive-shaped mass, especially after vomiting or feeding, making it a definitive diagnostic sign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Bile-stained vomit is not typical for HPS. The obstruction is at the pylorus, proximal to the ampulla of Vater, so bile does not usually reflux into the stomach. Vomit is typically non-bilious and projectile.\nOption B (Incorrect): Diarrhoea is not a symptom of HPS. Infants with HPS often have infrequent stools due to poor intake and dehydration from vomiting.\nOption D (Incorrect): Loss of weight is a consequence of chronic vomiting and poor feeding in HPS, not a primary diagnostic pillar. The pillars are direct physical signs of the obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | Malrotation with Volvulus | Gastroesophageal Reflux (GER) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vomit Character** | Non-bilious, projectile | Bilious, acute onset | Non-bilious, non-projectile |\n| **Physical Exam** | Visible peristalsis, palpable olive | Abdominal distension, tenderness | Normal exam |\n| **Metabolic Derangement** | Hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis | Metabolic acidosis (late) | Usually none |\n| **Timing of Onset** | 3-6 weeks of age | Any age, often first month | First few weeks of life |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Projectile vomit, palpable olive, and visible peristalsis are the classic triad of HPS.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging: Abdominal ultrasound is the gold standard, showing a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm) and an elongated pyloric channel (>14-17 mm). Intraoperative: Ramstedt pyloromyotomy involves longitudinal incision of the pyloric muscle down to the mucosa, relieving the obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) consensus recommendations (e.g., 2019) emphasize ultrasound as the primary diagnostic tool and pyloromyotomy as the definitive treatment for HPS.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | bile-stained vomit. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | diarrhoea. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | visible peristalsis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | loss of weight. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | presence of a lump. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: CE) visible peristalsis.\npresence of a lump.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
