  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Acute ulcers: Stressful, NSAID-induced, and prone to bleed!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, C, and E. Acute peptic ulcers are typically stress-induced or drug-induced lesions that can occur throughout the stomach, frequently present with bleeding, and are strongly associated with NSAID ingestion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute peptic ulcers, often termed stress ulcers or NSAID-induced ulcers, arise from a disruption of the gastric mucosal barrier. Stress ulcers (e.g., Curling's in burns, Cushing's in head injury) result from splanchnic vasoconstriction and ischemia, while NSAIDs inhibit cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1), reducing protective prostaglandin synthesis. These ulcers can develop rapidly, are often superficial erosions but can penetrate deeper, leading to hemorrhage (Option C). Their distribution is not limited to specific areas and can be diffuse throughout the stomach (Option A). The strong causal link with NSAID use is a well-established clinical fact (Option E).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): seldom invade the muscle layer. While many acute ulcers are superficial erosions, they can and often do invade the muscularis propria, especially when presenting with hemorrhage or perforation. NSAID-induced ulcers, in particular, can be quite deep.\nOption D (Incorrect): are rarely multiple. Acute peptic ulcers, especially stress-related mucosal disease or NSAID gastropathy, are frequently multiple, affecting various areas of the gastric mucosa. This contrasts with chronic peptic ulcers, which are more often solitary.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Peptic Ulcer | Chronic Peptic Ulcer |\n| :-------------- | :----------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Etiology** | Stress (shock, burns, trauma), NSAIDs, steroids | H. pylori, NSAIDs, Zollinger-Ellison syndrome |\n| **Location** | Anywhere in stomach (fundus, body, antrum), duodenum | Duodenum (90%), lesser curvature of stomach |\n| **Depth** | Often superficial erosions, but can be deep | Typically deep, extending into muscularis propria |\n| **Multiplicity**| Often multiple | Usually solitary |\n| **Presentation**| Hemorrhage (common), pain (less prominent) | Epigastric pain (classic), hemorrhage, perforation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute ulcers: stress, NSAIDs, bleed, multiple, anywhere.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, acute peptic ulcers often appear as superficial erosions or discrete ulcers, sometimes multiple, with a clean base or signs of recent/active bleeding (e.g., oozing, visible vessel, adherent clot). They typically lack the fibrotic base or heaped-up margins characteristic of chronic ulcers.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Prevention and Treatment of NSAID-Induced Ulcers (2009). Recommends risk stratification and prophylactic strategies for patients on NSAIDs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | can occur anywhere in the stomach. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | seldom invade the muscle layer. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | present with haemorrhage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | are rarely multiple. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | are associated with ingestion of NSAIDS. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) can occur anywhere in the stomach.\npresent with haemorrhage.\nare associated with ingestion of NSAIDS.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
