  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 H. pylori and smoking: the dynamic duo of duodenal destruction.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question correctly identifies two major associations with chronic duodenal ulcers: smoking and Helicobacter pylori infection. These are the most prevalent and well-established risk factors for peptic ulcer disease, particularly in the duodenum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHelicobacter pylori is a gram-negative bacterium that colonizes the gastric mucosa, leading to chronic inflammation, increased gastrin release, and subsequent hyperacidity, which overwhelms the duodenal mucosal defenses. Smoking exacerbates ulcer formation and impairs healing by reducing mucosal blood flow, decreasing prostaglandin synthesis, inhibiting bicarbonate secretion, and increasing acid production. Together, these factors significantly compromise the integrity of the duodenal mucosa, predisposing it to chronic ulceration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (blood group B. Incorrect): Blood group O is associated with a slightly higher risk of duodenal ulcers, not blood group B.\nOption B (non-f cell tumour. Incorrect): F-cell tumors (gastrinomas, part of Zollinger-Ellison syndrome) cause severe peptic ulcers due to excessive gastrin production, not 'non-f cell' tumors.\nOption E (alkaline gastric mucosa. Incorrect): Duodenal ulcers are associated with increased acid exposure to the duodenum, often due to hypersecretion or impaired duodenal bicarbonate secretion, not an alkaline gastric environment which would be protective.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Duodenal Ulcer | Gastric Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Location | Duodenal bulb (D1) | Antrum, lesser curvature |\n| H. pylori | ~90-95% | ~70-80% |\n| NSAIDs | Common cause | Common cause |\n| Pain | Relieved by food | Worsened by food |\n| Malignancy | Very rare | ~5-10% risk |\n| Acid Secretion | Often increased | Often normal/decreased |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: H. pylori and smoking are the primary culprits in chronic duodenal ulcer disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy is the gold standard, revealing a discrete, often punched-out lesion, typically in the duodenal bulb. Biopsies are taken to rule out malignancy (though rare in duodenal ulcers) and to test for H. pylori.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Treatment of Helicobacter pylori Infection (2017) recommends eradication therapy for all patients with active peptic ulcer disease and H. pylori infection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | blood group B. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | non-f cell tumour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | smoking. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Helicobacter pylorii infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | alkaline gastric mucosa. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: CD) smoking.\nHelicobacter pylorii infection.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
