  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duodenal ulcers: Food's friend, pain's foe, a cyclical show.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies heartburn and well-marked periodicity as key features of a duodenal ulcer. Heartburn, or pyrosis, is a common symptom due to acid reflux, while periodicity refers to the characteristic cyclical nature of ulcer symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal ulcers typically result from an imbalance between aggressive factors (acid, pepsin, H. pylori, NSAIDs) and protective factors (mucus, bicarbonate, prostaglandins) in the duodenal bulb. The pain, often described as burning or gnawing epigastric discomfort, is classically relieved by food and recurs 2-3 hours post-prandially or nocturnally. Heartburn can be an associated symptom due to acid reflux. The 'well-marked periodicity' is a hallmark, where symptoms flare for weeks, then remit for months, often with seasonal variations, reflecting the dynamic nature of mucosal healing and breakdown.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Duodenal ulcer pain is typically relieved by food, not worsened soon after eating. Gastric ulcer pain is often exacerbated by food. Lying down can sometimes worsen reflux, but it's not a defining feature of duodenal ulcer pain.\nOption B (Incorrect): Considerable vomiting is not a primary feature of uncomplicated duodenal ulcers. It may indicate complications like pyloric outlet obstruction, but not a general characteristic.\nOption C (Incorrect): Anorexia nervosa is an eating disorder, not a symptom or feature of a duodenal ulcer. While some patients might experience decreased appetite due to pain, this option refers to a specific psychiatric diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Duodenal Ulcer | Gastric Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain relation to food | Relieved by food | Worsened by food |\n| Pain timing | 2-3 hours after meals, nocturnal | Soon after meals |\n| Weight | Gain or stable | Loss |\n| Malignancy risk | Very low | Higher (biopsy all) |\n| Periodicity | Well-marked | Less marked |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Food soothes duodenal ulcers, but irritates gastric ulcers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a duodenal ulcer appears as a discrete mucosal break, typically in the duodenal bulb, often with a clean base or fibrin. Biopsies are taken to confirm H. pylori and exclude malignancy (rare in duodenum). In the OR, a perforated duodenal ulcer presents with free air under the diaphragm on X-ray and localized inflammation/peritonitis around the duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017). Recommends H. pylori testing and eradication, NSAID cessation, and proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy for ulcer healing.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | pain soon after eating but not when lying down. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | considerable vomiting. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | anorexia nervosa. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | heartburn. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | well-marked periodicity. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: DE) heartburn.\nwell-marked periodicity.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
