  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gastrectomy: A surgical fix with long-term digestive and cancer risks.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct options (A, C, E) accurately describe common and significant long-term sequelae following partial gastrectomy. These complications arise directly from the altered anatomy, physiology, and digestive processes after removal of part of the stomach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiarrhea (A) is often due to rapid gastric emptying (dumping syndrome), malabsorption, or bacterial overgrowth in the afferent loop. Carcinoma of the gastric remnant (C) is a well-recognized late complication, particularly after Billroth II reconstruction, attributed to chronic bile reflux and inflammation. Megaloblastic anemia (E) results from reduced intrinsic factor production by parietal cells in the remaining stomach, leading to vitamin B12 malabsorption, with stores typically depleting over 1-3 years.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): There is no specific or common association between partial gastrectomy and the reactivation of previous tuberculous disease. While any major surgery can be a stressor, this is not a recognized specific complication.\nOption D (Incorrect): While bilious vomiting can occur due to bile reflux, especially after Billroth II, the description 'intermittent rather than with every meal' is not a universally accurate or defining characteristic. It can be frequent and often related to meals, and other options represent more common and significant sequelae.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Onset | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Dumping Syndrome | Rapid gastric emptying, osmotic shift | Early post-op | Dietary modification, acarbose, octreotide |\n| Remnant Carcinoma | Chronic bile reflux, inflammation | Late (10-20+ years) | Endoscopic surveillance, surgical resection |\n| Megaloblastic Anemia | Vitamin B12 malabsorption (lack of intrinsic factor) | 1-3 years post-op | Parenteral B12 supplementation |\n| Iron Deficiency Anemia | Reduced acid for iron absorption, blood loss | Variable | Oral/IV iron supplementation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Post-gastrectomy: Think DUMPING, CANCER, and ANEMIAS (B12, Iron).\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy is crucial for surveillance of the gastric remnant for carcinoma, looking for mucosal changes, ulcers, or masses. Barium studies can demonstrate rapid emptying in dumping syndrome or afferent loop dilation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2024) recommend long-term follow-up for nutritional deficiencies and endoscopic surveillance for remnant cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | diarrhoea is common, episodic and troublesome. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | previous tuberculous disease may be reactivated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | carcinoma of the stomach may occur in the gastric remnant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | bilious vomiting is intermittent rather than with every meal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | megaloblastic anaemia is common and appears about a year after the operatio | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) diarrhoea is common, episodic and troublesome.\ncarcinoma of the stomach may occur in the gastric remnant.\nmegaloblastic anaemia is common and appears about a year after the operation.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
