  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stop the bleed, fill the tank, then look inside.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers reflect immediate priorities in managing acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding: stabilizing hemodynamics and preparing for definitive diagnosis/treatment. Rapid blood transfusion addresses hypovolemia, while NPO prevents further gastric irritation and allows for endoscopy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute upper GI bleeding from a duodenal ulcer can lead to significant blood loss and hypovolemic shock. Rapid intravenous fluid resuscitation and blood product transfusion are critical to restore circulating volume, maintain organ perfusion, and prevent irreversible shock. Keeping the patient NPO is essential to minimize gastric acid secretion, prevent further irritation of the ulcer bed, and ensure the stomach is empty for potential emergent endoscopy or surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Allowing ambulation risks syncope, falls, and increased bleeding in an unstable patient with active GI hemorrhage. Strict bed rest is indicated.\nOption B (Incorrect): Morphine 15 mg IM regularly is a high dose that can mask symptoms, cause respiratory depression, and is generally avoided in unstable patients due to unpredictable absorption and potential for hematoma. IV titration is preferred if pain control is necessary.\nOption E (Incorrect): An enema is not a standard diagnostic tool for melaena and could exacerbate bleeding or discomfort. Melaena is typically identified by stool inspection or rectal exam.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Aspect | Acute Bleeding Duodenal Ulcer | Non-Bleeding Duodenal Ulcer |\n| :---------------- | :----------------------------- | :-------------------------- |\n| **NPO Status**    | Essential                      | Not typically required      |\n| **Fluid Resuscitation** | Rapid IV fluids, blood products | Oral hydration              |\n| **PPI Therapy**   | High-dose IV continuous infusion | Oral daily                   |\n| **Endoscopy**     | Emergent/Urgent (within 24h)   | Elective/Diagnostic         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: In acute GI bleed, stabilize first: Resuscitate, NPO, then scope.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal an ulcer with stigmata of recent hemorrhage (e.g., active spurting, non-bleeding visible vessel, adherent clot) or a clean-based ulcer. In the OR, a duodenotomy might reveal the ulcer on the posterior wall, often involving the gastroduodenal artery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). It recommends early risk stratification, prompt resuscitation, and urgent endoscopy (within 24 hours) for most patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | allowed to go to the toilet. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | given morphine 15 mg i.m. regularly. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | given a rapid blood transfusion. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | allowed nothing by mouth. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | given a small enema to see if he has melaena. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: CD) given a rapid blood transfusion.\nallowed nothing by mouth.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
