  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duodenal ulcers: small lesion, big trouble.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The recognized complications of a duodenal ulcer include pyloric stenosis, penetration, and, albeit rarely, carcinoma. These represent the most significant clinical sequelae of chronic duodenal ulceration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic inflammation and scarring from a duodenal ulcer, particularly if located near the pylorus, can lead to fibrosis and narrowing, causing pyloric stenosis and gastric outlet obstruction. Penetration occurs when the ulcer erodes through the duodenal wall into adjacent organs like the pancreas or liver, leading to severe pain and potential fistulae. While much less common than with gastric ulcers, chronic duodenal ulcers, especially those associated with H. pylori, are recognized to have a rare but definite potential for malignant transformation, typically adenocarcinoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): hour-glass stomach. This is a complication of chronic gastric ulcers, not duodenal ulcers, where scarring causes a central constriction of the stomach.\nOption E (Incorrect): leather bottle stomach. This term (Linitis Plastica) describes a diffuse infiltrative gastric carcinoma, which is a type of gastric cancer, not a direct complication arising from a duodenal ulcer itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Duodenal Ulcer | Gastric Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bleeding | Common | Common |\n| Perforation | Common | Common |\n| Obstruction (Pyloric Stenosis) | Common | Less common (can cause GOO) |\n| Penetration | Common | Common |\n| Malignancy | Rare | Higher risk |\n| Hour-glass stomach | No | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think GOO, bleed, perf, and rarely cancer for duodenal ulcers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy is key, revealing an ulcer crater, often with surrounding inflammation or scarring. In pyloric stenosis, the endoscope may not pass through the narrowed pylorus. Penetration might be suspected if the ulcer base appears deep or if adjacent organ involvement is seen on cross-sectional imaging (CT).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline on the Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017). It recommends H. pylori eradication and NSAID cessation as primary management, and addresses the diagnosis and treatment of complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | pyloric stenosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | penetration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | hour-glass stomach. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | leather bottle stomach. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABC) pyloric stenosis.\npenetration.\ncarcinoma.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
