  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When connecting stomach to gut, watch for leaks and wrong turns.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, C, and D. These complications are directly related to the altered anatomy and surgical manipulation inherent in performing a gastroenterostomy, involving either anastomotic integrity, altered flow dynamics, or direct injury to adjacent structures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA duodenal fistula (A) can arise from a leak at the duodenal stump (e.g., after Billroth II gastrectomy) or from the duodenal side of the gastrojejunal anastomosis. A gastrocolic fistula (C) is a rare but serious complication, often resulting from a marginal ulcer eroding into the adjacent colon, or direct surgical injury. Cholangitis (D) can occur due to altered biliary drainage, particularly in cases of afferent loop syndrome where stasis and bacterial overgrowth in the bypassed duodenal/jejunal loop lead to ascending infection into the biliary tree.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pancreatitis is a general post-operative complication that can occur after any abdominal surgery due to manipulation or ischemia, but it is not specific to the unique anatomical changes of a gastroenterostomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Polycythaemia is a hematological disorder characterized by an increase in red blood cell mass and has no direct or specific association with gastroenterostomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Key Diagnostic Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Duodenal Fistula | Leak from duodenal stump or anastomosis | Extravasation on contrast study, high-output bile-stained drainage |\n| Gastrocolic Fistula | Marginal ulcer erosion into colon | Feculent emesis, diarrhea, contrast passage on imaging |\n| Cholangitis | Afferent loop stasis, bacterial overgrowth | Fever, jaundice, dilated bile ducts on imaging |\n| Pancreatitis | General surgical trauma, inflammation | Elevated amylase/lipase, characteristic imaging findings |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastroenterostomy complications: Think leaks, fistulas, and altered flow dynamics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor a duodenal fistula, a contrast study (e.g., gastrografin swallow) would show extravasation of contrast. A gastrocolic fistula would be visualized on an upper GI series or barium enema as contrast passing directly between the stomach and colon, or via endoscopy. Cholangitis might show dilated bile ducts on ultrasound or CT, and potentially stones or strictures on MRCP/ERCP.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe World Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Anastomotic Leaks (2017) provide recommendations for diagnosis and management of gastrointestinal leaks, including those that could lead to duodenal or gastrocolic fistulas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | duodenal fistula. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pancreatitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | gastrocolic fistula. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | cholangitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | polycythaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACD) duodenal fistula.\ngastrocolic fistula.\ncholangitis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
