  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gastric cancer: a silent killer with tell-tale signs.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key clinical signs and pathological manifestations directly linked to gastric carcinoma. These options represent either metastatic spread or specific histological types of the disease, which are crucial for diagnosis and staging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric carcinoma is a malignant neoplasm of the stomach. Its advanced stages often present with specific metastatic patterns. Troisier's sign (Virchow's node) indicates lymphatic spread to the left supraclavicular fossa. Krukenberg's tumors are ovarian metastases, typically from signet-ring cell gastric adenocarcinoma, characterized by mucin-producing cells. Linitis plastica is a diffuse infiltrative gastric adenocarcinoma, causing a rigid, \"leather bottle\" stomach due to extensive submucosal and muscular layer infiltration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Blood group A, not O, is associated with an increased risk of gastric carcinoma.\nOption E (Incorrect): Gastric volvulus is a mechanical condition where the stomach twists on its axis. While a mass could potentially predispose to it, it is not a recognized direct association or manifestation of gastric carcinoma itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Association Type | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Troisier's Sign** | Enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node (Virchow's node) | Sign of advanced abdominal malignancy, often gastric cancer |\n| **Linitis Plastica** | Diffuse infiltrative gastric adenocarcinoma | Poor prognosis, rigid stomach, difficult to resect |\n| **Krukenberg's Tumors** | Ovarian metastases from gastric cancer | Indicates advanced disease, typically signet-ring cell histology |\n| **Blood Group A** | Genetic predisposition | Increased risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastric cancer spreads widely; know its classic metastatic signs.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, linitis plastica appears as diffuse, concentric wall thickening with loss of normal rugal folds and minimal luminal distension. Krukenberg's tumors are typically bilateral, solid ovarian masses with cystic components. Endoscopy for linitis plastica may show subtle mucosal changes, but biopsies are crucial, often requiring deep or multiple samples due to submucosal infiltration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment, including recognition of metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | blood group:O. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Troisier’s sign. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | linitis plastica. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Krukenberg’s tumours. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | volvulus of the stomach. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCD) Troisier’s sign.\nlinitis plastica.\nKrukenberg’s tumours.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
