  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the stomach swells, the body fails.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the classic triad of symptoms for postoperative acute gastric dilatation: effortless, dark watery vomiting, and shock. These signs reflect massive gastric distension and its severe systemic consequences.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPostoperative acute gastric dilatation results from gastric atony or mechanical obstruction, leading to rapid accumulation of swallowed air, gastric secretions, and ingested fluids. This massive distension causes effortless overflow vomiting, often dark due to stagnant blood or bile. The severe distension elevates the diaphragm, impairs venous return, and can trigger a vagal response, culminating in hypovolemic or obstructive shock.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hiccups are a non-specific symptom often related to diaphragmatic irritation and are not indicative of acute gastric dilatation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Considerable flatus indicates active bowel peristalsis and gas passage, which is contrary to the gastric stasis and obstruction seen in acute gastric dilatation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Gastric Dilatation | Paralytic Ileus | Small Bowel Obstruction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vomiting** | Effortless, dark watery, large volume | Nausea, non-bilious/bilious, variable | Bilious, feculent (late), often projectile |\n| **Abdominal Distension** | Marked epigastric, can be generalized | Generalized, diffuse | Localized initially, then generalized |\n| **Bowel Sounds** | Absent or markedly diminished | Absent or markedly diminished | High-pitched, tinkling (early); absent (late) |\n| **Systemic Effects** | Shock, hypovolemia, respiratory distress | Mild dehydration, discomfort | Dehydration, electrolyte imbalance, sepsis (late) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Effortless dark vomit + shock = think acute gastric dilatation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPlain abdominal X-ray or CT will show a massively distended stomach with air-fluid levels. Intraoperatively, the stomach will be grossly enlarged and tense.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEnhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) Society Guidelines (e.g., 2021 for colorectal surgery) emphasize early mobilization, early oral feeding, and judicious use of opioids to prevent postoperative ileus and gastric stasis, which can predispose to acute gastric dilatation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | hiccups | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | effortless vomit. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | dark watery vomit. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | considerable flatus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | shock. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCE) effortless vomit.\ndark watery vomit.\nshock.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
