  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duodenal leaks burn skin, not bridges to recovery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies two key aspects of duodenal fistulas: their etiology and their characteristic local effect. Duodenal fistulas frequently arise from trauma or iatrogenic injury to the duodenum, and the highly enzymatic nature of duodenal contents causes severe skin excoriation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal fistulas are often a consequence of direct injury to the duodenum, whether from blunt or penetrating trauma, or iatrogenic damage during complex abdominal surgeries like gastrectomy or pancreaticoduodenectomy. The duodenum's retroperitoneal location makes it vulnerable. The fluid leaking from a duodenal fistula is particularly caustic due to its high concentration of pancreatic enzymes (amylase, lipase, proteases) and bile. When this enzymatic fluid comes into contact with the skin, it rapidly digests the superficial layers, leading to severe inflammation, pain, and excoriation, which is a hallmark clinical sign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A gastrostomy creates an opening into the stomach, not the duodenum. While complications like gastric fistula can occur, a duodenal fistula is not a direct or common complication of a gastrostomy.\nOption C (Incorrect): A right hemicolectomy involves resection of the right colon. The duodenum is retroperitoneal and generally not directly involved in this procedure, making a duodenal fistula an extremely rare and unexpected complication.\nOption E (Incorrect): While duodenal fistulas can cause significant fluid and electrolyte imbalances requiring aggressive management, immediate operation is often not the first line of treatment. Many fistulas are managed non-operatively with fluid resuscitation, electrolyte correction, nutritional support (TPN), and somatostatin analogs, with surgery reserved for failed conservative management or specific complications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fistula Type | Common Causes | Output Characteristics | Skin Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Duodenal | Trauma, iatrogenic injury, pancreatitis | High enzyme content (bile, pancreatic enzymes) | Severe excoriation, digestion |\n| Gastric | Gastrostomy, anastomotic leak, ulcer perforation | Acidic, low enzyme content | Chemical irritation, mild excoriation |\n| Small Bowel | Crohn's disease, anastomotic leak, radiation | High volume, electrolyte-rich | Maceration, moderate irritation |\n| Colonic | Diverticulitis, anastomotic leak, malignancy | Feculent, bacterial load | Maceration, infection, mild irritation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duodenal fistulas: trauma, enzymes, excoriation, often non-operative management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT with oral contrast, extravasation of contrast material from the duodenum into the peritoneal cavity or adjacent tissues would be seen. Intraoperatively, bile-stained fluid leaking from a duodenal defect is the definitive finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for Nutrition Support in Adult Patients with Enterocutaneous Fistulas (2016) recommend early and aggressive nutritional support, often with total parenteral nutrition, as a cornerstone of non-operative management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is a complication of trauma to the duodenum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is a complication of gastrostomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | can follow a right hemicolectomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | causes excoriation of the skin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | requires immediate operation to prevent dehydration and hypoproteinaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: AD) is a complication of trauma to the duodenum.\ncauses excoriation of the skin.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
