  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let varices burst your patient's chances!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict correctly identifies multiple accurate statements regarding oesophageal varices. These statements highlight key aspects of their diagnosis, underlying etiology, and treatment, which are crucial for managing this life-threatening complication of portal hypertension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOesophageal varices are dilated submucosal veins in the distal oesophagus, a direct consequence of portal hypertension, most commonly stemming from liver cirrhosis. Their presence signifies a high risk of life-threatening haemorrhage. Endoscopy (oesophagoscopy) is the gold standard for diagnosis, allowing direct visualization and grading. Imaging techniques like CT or MRI angiography, and historically splenic-portography, can also demonstrate these collateral vessels. Crucially, varices are treatable, with endoscopic injection sclerotherapy being a primary method for acute bleeding control and prevention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Varices are not restricted to the oesophagus. Portal hypertension can lead to varices in other locations such as the stomach (gastric varices), duodenum, or rectum, as well as caput medusae on the abdominal wall.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Aspect | Oesophageal Varices |\n|---|---|\n| **Primary Cause** | Portal hypertension (most commonly cirrhosis) |\n| **Gold Standard Diagnosis** | Upper endoscopy (oesophagoscopy) |\n| **Imaging Diagnosis** | CT/MRI angiography, splenic-portography (historical) |\n| **Acute Bleed Treatment** | Endoscopic band ligation, sclerotherapy, vasoactive drugs (octreotide), TIPS |\n| **Prophylaxis** | Non-selective beta-blockers, endoscopic band ligation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Varices are a hallmark of portal hypertension, primarily due to cirrhosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, oesophageal varices appear as dilated, tortuous, bluish veins protruding into the oesophageal lumen, often with 'red wale signs' indicating high risk of rupture. On CT angiography, they are seen as enhancing, tortuous collateral vessels surrounding the oesophagus, draining into systemic circulation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance on the Management of Varices in Cirrhosis (2021). Recommends screening endoscopy for all patients with cirrhosis and outlines strategies for primary and secondary prophylaxis, and management of acute variceal bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are restricted to the oesophagus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | can be demonstrated by splenic-portography. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can always be demonstrated by oesophagoscopy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | can be treated by injection. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | relate to cirrhosis of the liver. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D, E) can be demonstrated by splenic-portography.\ncan always be demonstrated by oesophagoscopy.\ncan be treated by injection.\nrelate to cirrhosis of the liver.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
