  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Liver cancer: it's not just for grandpa, and it loves to make fluid!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies two key aspects of primary liver carcinoma: its bimodal age distribution and a common presenting symptom. Primary liver cancers encompass both adult hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) and pediatric hepatoblastoma, while ascites is a frequent sign of advanced disease or underlying cirrhosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary liver carcinoma is a broad term. In adults, hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is the most common primary liver malignancy, typically arising in the context of chronic liver disease and cirrhosis, affecting older individuals. In contrast, hepatoblastoma is the most common primary malignant liver tumor in children, usually presenting before age three. The development of ascites in patients with primary liver carcinoma, particularly HCC, often signifies advanced disease, portal hypertension due to underlying cirrhosis, or tumor invasion of the portal vein, leading to fluid accumulation in the peritoneal cavity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pel-Ebstein fever is a classic symptom of Hodgkin's lymphoma, not primary liver carcinoma. \nOption C (Incorrect): While CEA can be elevated in some malignancies, alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is the primary and most specific tumor marker for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). \nOption D (Incorrect): Multiphasic CT scanning is a cornerstone for the diagnosis, staging, and surveillance of primary liver carcinoma, particularly HCC, often demonstrating characteristic enhancement patterns.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Marker | Associated Cancer/Condition | Clinical Utility |\n|---|---|---|\n| Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC), Germ Cell Tumors | Diagnosis, surveillance, prognosis |\n| Carcinoembryonic Antigen (CEA) | Colorectal Cancer, Pancreatic, Gastric, Lung | Surveillance for recurrence, prognosis |\n| CA 19-9 | Pancreatic Cancer, Cholangiocarcinoma | Diagnosis, prognosis, monitoring treatment |\n| CA 125 | Ovarian Cancer | Diagnosis, monitoring treatment response |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think bimodal age for primary liver cancer: kids and older adults.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn multiphasic CT, HCC typically shows arterial phase hyperenhancement followed by venous phase washout, a hallmark for diagnosis in cirrhotic patients.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance 2023: Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma recommends multiphasic imaging (CT or MRI) for diagnosis and surveillance in at-risk patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | tends to occur in children and older people. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | causes a Pel-Ebstein type of fever. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | causes the CEA level in the plasma to be raised. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | cannot be diagnosed by CT scanning. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is associated with ascites in about 40% of patients at the time of first ex | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, E) tends to occur in children and older people.\nis associated with ascites in about 40% of patients at the time of first examination.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
