  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spleen's burst? Blood's dispersed! Look for distension and guarding.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies abdominal distension, guarding, and sighing respiration as clinical features of a ruptured spleen. These signs collectively point towards intra-abdominal hemorrhage and peritoneal irritation, which are the primary consequences of splenic rupture.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA ruptured spleen leads to hemoperitoneum, where blood accumulates in the peritoneal cavity. This free blood causes peritoneal irritation, manifesting as abdominal guarding and tenderness. Significant blood accumulation can lead to abdominal distension. Furthermore, hypovolemia from blood loss can cause systemic signs, and pain from peritoneal irritation or diaphragmatic irritation (Kehr's sign, though not an option here) can alter respiratory patterns, including sighing respiration as a non-specific sign of discomfort or impending shock.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A 'ladder pattern' refers to distended loops of small bowel visible through the abdominal wall, typically seen in small bowel obstruction, not splenic rupture.\nOption C (Incorrect): Boas’s sign is referred pain to the right subscapular region, characteristic of acute cholecystitis or peptic ulcer disease, not splenic rupture. Splenic rupture can cause Kehr's sign (referred pain to the left shoulder).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Condition | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Abdominal Distension | Splenic Rupture, Bowel Obstruction, Ascites | Fluid/gas accumulation |\n| Guarding | Peritonitis (e.g., ruptured spleen, appendicitis) | Involuntary muscle spasm due to peritoneal irritation |\n| Kehr's Sign | Splenic Rupture, Ectopic Pregnancy | Referred pain to left shoulder from diaphragmatic irritation |\n| Boas's Sign | Cholecystitis | Referred pain to right scapula from diaphragmatic irritation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ruptured spleen = hemorrhage + peritoneal irritation. Look for signs of both.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan with IV contrast, a ruptured spleen will show perisplenic fluid (hemoperitoneum), splenic lacerations, subcapsular hematoma, and potentially active extravasation of contrast. Intraoperatively, free blood in the peritoneal cavity and a lacerated or fragmented spleen are evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Splenic Injury Scale (2018). This scale classifies splenic injuries from Grade I to V, guiding management decisions for non-operative management versus splenectomy or splenorrhaphy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | abdominal distension. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | ladder pattern. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Boas’s sign. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | guarding. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | sighing respiration. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) abdominal distension.\nguarding.\nsighing respiration.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
