  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Blood in the belly means trouble, and the spleen's often the culprit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, the provided answer correctly identifies key radiological signs of a ruptured spleen. These features primarily reflect the presence of blood or fluid in the abdominal cavity or irritation of adjacent structures due to hemorrhage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA ruptured spleen leads to hemorrhage, which manifests radiologically. Elevation of the left hemidiaphragm (B) occurs due to irritation from subphrenic blood or a hematoma pushing it upwards. Obliteration of the psoas shadow (C) indicates retroperitoneal fluid accumulation, which can occur with significant splenic bleeding extending posteriorly. Free fluid between gas-filled coils of intestine (E) is a direct sign of intraperitoneal hemorrhage, a hallmark of splenic rupture, as blood collects in dependent areas.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Subdiaphragmatic gas shadows indicate free air, typically from a perforated hollow viscus (e.g., stomach, intestine), not a ruptured solid organ like the spleen.\nOption D (Incorrect): Eventration of the diaphragm is a congenital or acquired thinning and upward displacement of the diaphragm, a chronic condition unrelated to acute splenic rupture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Radiological Sign | Associated Condition | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Elevated Left Diaphragm | Ruptured Spleen | Subphrenic hematoma/irritation |\n| Obliterated Psoas Shadow | Retroperitoneal Hemorrhage (e.g., splenic, renal) | Fluid accumulation obscuring muscle outline |\n| Free Fluid (Intraperitoneal) | Ruptured Spleen, Liver Laceration, Ectopic Pregnancy | Hemorrhage into peritoneal cavity |\n| Subdiaphragmatic Gas | Perforated Viscus | Free air from GI tract |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blood irritates, displaces, and fills; air perforates.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain X-ray, look for left upper quadrant haziness, gastric bubble displacement, or pleural effusion. CT scan with IV contrast is the gold standard, showing perisplenic or diffuse hemoperitoneum, splenic lacerations, or active extravasation. Intraoperatively, frank blood in the peritoneal cavity and a lacerated spleen are evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends focused assessment with sonography for trauma (FAST) or CT scan for evaluating blunt abdominal trauma, including splenic injury, based on patient stability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | subdiaphragmatic gas shadows. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | elevation of the left side of the diaphragm. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | obliteration of the psoas shadow. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | eventration of the diaphragm. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | free fluid between gas-filled coils of intestine. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) elevation of the left side of the diaphragm.\nobliteration of the psoas shadow.\nfree fluid between gas-filled coils of intestine.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
