  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ITP: Platelets plummet, bleeding blooms.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nIdiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is an autoimmune disorder characterized by isolated thrombocytopenia, leading to an increased risk of bleeding. The correct options highlight various clinical manifestations and potential complications of severe thrombocytopenia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nITP results from immune-mediated destruction of platelets, leading to a low platelet count. This impairs primary hemostasis, causing spontaneous bleeding. Manifestations range from petechiae and purpura (large areas of bruising) to more severe internal bleeding. Hematuria is a common mucosal bleeding site. Intussusception, though rare, can occur due to intramural hematoma acting as a lead point, particularly in pediatric patients with severe thrombocytopenia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Correct): Intussusception can be a rare but serious complication of ITP, especially in children, where intramural hematoma in the bowel wall can serve as a lead point.\nOption B (Correct): Hematuria is a common bleeding manifestation in ITP due to the low platelet count leading to microvascular bleeding in the urinary tract.\nOption C (Correct): Large areas of bruising (ecchymoses, purpura) are classic clinical signs of thrombocytopenia, including ITP, resulting from spontaneous bleeding into the skin.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Rumpel-Leede test (tourniquet test) assesses capillary fragility and platelet function, but it is not a confirmatory test for ITP. ITP diagnosis relies on isolated thrombocytopenia after excluding other causes.\nOption E (Incorrect): ITP is an autoimmune disorder, not caused by vitamin B deficiency. While vitamin B12 or folate deficiency can cause thrombocytopenia (megaloblastic anemia), this is a distinct etiology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Idiopathic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (ITP) | Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP) | Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome (HUS) |\n|---------------------|-------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|---------------------------------|\n| Pathophysiology     | Autoimmune platelet destruction           | ADAMTS13 deficiency (platelet aggregation)| Shiga toxin (endothelial damage) |\n| Platelet Count      | Low                                       | Low                                       | Low                             |\n| RBCs                | Normal (unless significant bleeding)      | Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia         | Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia |\n| Renal Involvement   | Rare                                      | Common                                    | Prominent                       |\n| Neurological Sx     | Rare                                      | Common                                    | Rare                            |\n| Treatment           | Steroids, IVIG, splenectomy               | Plasma exchange                           | Supportive, plasma exchange (severe) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ITP = low platelets, high bleeding risk, autoimmune.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., ultrasound or CT), intussusception in ITP may show a 'target sign' or 'pseudokidney sign' with an identifiable intramural hematoma as the lead point. Intraoperatively, diffuse petechiae or ecchymoses on serosal surfaces may be noted.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2018 Guidelines for ITP. Recommends initial treatment with corticosteroids or IVIG for newly diagnosed ITP with bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a cause of intussusception. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | a cause of haematuria. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | manifests as large areas of bruising. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | confirmed by the appearance of petechiae after a sphygmomanometer cuff is i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | due to vitamin B deficiency. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) a cause of intussusception.\na cause of haematuria.\nmanifests as large areas of bruising.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
