  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 AIHA: When your immune system goes rogue on your red cells, sometimes the spleen's the target.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key aspects of acquired autoimmune haemolytic anaemia (AIHA), including its potential triggers, common associations, and fundamental pathophysiology. AIHA is characterized by the immune system mistakenly attacking and destroying the body's own red blood cells, leading to anaemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcquired AIHA is an immune-mediated disorder where autoantibodies (IgG or IgM) bind to antigens on the red blood cell surface, leading to their premature destruction. This can be triggered by various mechanisms, including drug-induced hapten formation or immune complex deposition, as well as being a secondary manifestation of systemic autoimmune diseases like systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). The binding of these antibodies marks the red cells for destruction, primarily by macrophages in the spleen (extravascular hemolysis) or via complement activation (intravascular hemolysis), thus directly damaging the red cell surface.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Cystine stones are caused by a genetic defect in renal tubular transport of certain amino acids, including cystine, leading to their accumulation and stone formation, which is entirely unrelated to haemolytic anaemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Splenectomy is a well-established treatment for refractory AIHA, particularly warm AIHA, as the spleen is a primary site for antibody-coated red cell sequestration and destruction, making it a therapeutic intervention rather than a contraindication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of AIHA | Cause/Association | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Warm AIHA | Idiopathic, SLE, CLL, drugs | Corticosteroids, Rituximab, Splenectomy |\n| Cold AIHA | Mycoplasma, EBV, Lymphoproliferative disorders | Avoid cold, Rituximab, Plasmapheresis |\n| Drug-induced AIHA | Penicillins, Cephalosporins, Methyldopa | Discontinue drug, Corticosteroids |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: AIHA is immune-mediated RBC destruction, often secondary, and splenectomy is a treatment option.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., ultrasound, CT) may reveal splenomegaly due to increased red cell sequestration. Intraoperatively during splenectomy, an enlarged, congested spleen would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBritish Society for Haematology (BSH) Guidelines for the investigation and management of autoimmune haemolytic anaemia (2017). These guidelines recommend corticosteroids as first-line treatment, with rituximab or splenectomy for refractory cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | can be due to a drug reaction. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is associated with systemic lupus erythematosus. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | is associated with damage to the surface of the red cell. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is a cause of cystine stones. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | is a contraindication to splenectomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) can be due to a drug reaction.\nis associated with systemic lupus erythematosus.\nis associated with damage to the surface of the red cell.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
