  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get trapped: splenic cysts are true or traumatic.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies dermoid and traumatic cysts as types of splenic cysts. Splenic cysts are broadly categorized into true cysts (like dermoid/epidermoid) and pseudocysts (most commonly traumatic).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic cysts are relatively rare, with pseudocysts accounting for 75-80% of cases, primarily resulting from trauma or infarction. These lack an epithelial lining. True cysts, such as epidermoid or dermoid cysts, are congenital, lined by squamous or cuboidal epithelium, and may contain sebaceous material or hair. Parasitic cysts, predominantly echinococcal, are also true cysts. Understanding this distinction between congenital/true and acquired/pseudocysts is crucial for diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Choledochal cysts are congenital dilatations of the bile ducts, not found in the spleen.\nOption C (Incorrect): Aneurysmal bone cysts are benign, expansile osteolytic lesions of bone, unrelated to splenic pathology.\nOption E (Incorrect): While lymphangiomas (a type of lymphatic malformation) can occur in the spleen, \"lymphatic cyst\" is not a standard primary classification for splenic cysts in the same way dermoid or traumatic are. Splenic cysts are typically classified as true (epidermoid, parasitic) or pseudocysts (traumatic, inflammatory).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | True Splenic Cysts | Pseudocysts of Spleen |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Congenital (epidermoid, dermoid), Parasitic (echinococcal) | Acquired (trauma, infarction, inflammation) |\n| **Lining** | Epithelial lining (squamous, cuboidal) | No epithelial lining (fibrous capsule) |\n| **Contents** | Serous fluid, sebaceous material, hair (dermoid) | Blood, necrotic debris, serous fluid |\n| **Incidence** | Less common (20-25%) | More common (75-80%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Splenic cysts are either true (lined) or pseudocysts (unlined, often traumatic).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or ultrasound, splenic cysts appear as well-defined, anechoic or hypodense lesions. Pseudocysts may show internal septations or debris, while true cysts are often unilocular. Calcification can be seen in chronic pseudocysts or hydatid cysts. Intraoperatively, they present as a palpable, often tense, cystic mass on the splenic surface or within its parenchyma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Splenic Injury Scale (2018). While not directly about cysts, it guides management of splenic trauma, which is the leading cause of pseudocysts. It recommends non-operative management for most low-grade injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | dermoid. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | choledochal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | aneurysmal bone. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | traumatic. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | lymphatic. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D) dermoid.\ntraumatic.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
