  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No spleen, no problem? Think again: OPSI is real!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies multiple systemic effects of splenectomy, highlighting the spleen's diverse physiological roles. Removing the spleen impacts hematopoiesis, immune function, and compensatory mechanisms throughout the body.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen is a vital organ involved in blood filtration, immune surveillance, and hematopoiesis. Post-splenectomy, the bone marrow undergoes compensatory changes to manage blood cell production and destruction, as the spleen's role in filtering old cells is lost. Accessory spleens (splenunculi) often hypertrophy to attempt to take over some of the lost splenic function. The absence of the spleen's filtering and immune functions can lead to a transient or persistent eosinophilia and, critically, a state of immunodeficiency, particularly against encapsulated bacteria, due to impaired antibody production and opsonization.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Leucopenia is incorrect. Splenectomy typically leads to a transient leukocytosis (increased white blood cell count) rather than leucopenia, as the spleen normally sequesters a portion of the circulating white blood cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Effect | Pre-Splenectomy | Post-Splenectomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Immunity** | Robust against encapsulated bacteria | Increased susceptibility to OPSI |\n| **Platelets** | Normal count | Often thrombocytosis |\n| **RBCs** | Normal lifespan/clearance | Howell-Jolly bodies, target cells |\n| **Accessory Spleens** | Usually quiescent | Hypertrophy to compensate |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always vaccinate post-splenectomy patients for encapsulated bacteria.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or during surgery, always meticulously search for and remove any accessory spleens (splenunculi), as they can hypertrophy and negate the therapeutic effect of splenectomy for certain hematologic conditions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC/ACIP Guidelines for Immunization of Persons with Asplenia (e.g., 2013 ACIP recommendations): Recommends vaccination against Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae type b, and Neisseria meningitidis for all asplenic patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | changes in the bone marrow. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | hypertrophy of any splenunculi. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | eosinophilia. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | leucopenia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | immunodeficiency. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, E) changes in the bone marrow.\nhypertrophy of any splenunculi.\neosinophilia.\nimmunodeficiency.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
