  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just take the spleen, take the whole splenic family!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct options highlight two critical aspects of elective splenectomy: early vascular control and thorough search for accessory spleens. These steps are fundamental to ensuring a safe and effective procedure with minimal complications and preventing disease recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOpening the lesser sac provides direct access to the splenic artery and vein, allowing for early ligation before extensive splenic mobilization. This 'hilar first' approach significantly reduces intraoperative blood loss and improves surgical field visibility. Furthermore, identifying and removing splenunculi (accessory spleens), which occur in 10-30% of individuals, is paramount, especially in cases of hematologic disorders like ITP or hereditary spherocytosis, to prevent disease relapse or treatment failure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A Morris incision is typically used for kidney surgery, not splenectomy. Splenectomy usually employs a left subcostal, midline, or paramedian incision.\nOption B (Incorrect): Passing a hand to avulse adhesions as the 'first step' is generally discouraged. Early mobilization without prior vascular control can lead to significant hemorrhage. Ligation of splenic vessels usually precedes extensive mobilization, and adhesions should be carefully divided, not avulsed, to prevent capsular tears.\nOption E (Incorrect): Routine wound drainage after splenectomy is not recommended. Drains can increase the risk of infection and are generally reserved for specific indications such as pancreatic injury or significant contamination.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Aspect | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Early Vascular Control** | Ligation of splenic artery/vein via lesser sac access. | Reduces blood loss, improves visibility, safer procedure. |\n| **Splenunculi** | Accessory spleens, found in 10-30% of population. | Must be removed in hematologic indications to prevent recurrence. |\n| **Incision Types** | Left subcostal, midline, paramedian. | Chosen based on patient habitus, surgeon preference, and pathology. |\n| **Post-op Drainage** | Generally not routine. | Increases infection risk; reserved for specific indications. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early vascular control and accessory spleen removal are non-negotiable in elective splenectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after spleen removal, a meticulous search for splenunculi should be performed along the splenic hilum, gastrosplenic ligament, greater omentum, and tail of the pancreas. On pre-operative CT, splenunculi appear as small, round, enhancing nodules with similar attenuation to the main spleen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2019 Guidelines for Immune Thrombocytopenia (ITP) recommend splenectomy for refractory cases, emphasizing the need for accessory spleen removal.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a Morris iricision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | as the first step to pass a hand round the outer surface of the spleen to a | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the lesser sac between stomach, colon and spleen being opened to give acces | ✅ Correct |\n| D | looking for splenunculi. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | wound drainage even if haemostasis is satisfactory. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) the lesser sac between stomach, colon and spleen being opened to give access to the splenic vessels.\nlooking for splenunculi.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
