  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 IOC: Your ductal GPS and stone detector in one shot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPeroperative cholangiography, typically performed as an intraoperative cholangiogram (IOC), is a critical diagnostic tool during biliary surgery. It is correctly indicated for revealing common bile duct stones, confirming the precise anatomy of the biliary tree, and assessing the patency of the sphincter of Oddi.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraoperative cholangiography provides real-time radiographic visualization of the biliary system, allowing surgeons to identify choledocholithiasis that might otherwise be missed, thus preventing retained stones. Furthermore, it meticulously maps the complex and often variable anatomy of the bile ducts, safeguarding against iatrogenic injury to critical structures like the common bile duct. By demonstrating free flow of contrast into the duodenum, it confirms the functional integrity of the distal biliary system, ensuring no distal obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Peroperative cholangiography visualizes the bile ducts, not the arterial supply to the gallbladder or liver. Arterial anatomy is assessed visually or with other imaging modalities if necessary.\nOption E (Incorrect): Peroperative cholangiography during cholecystectomy is typically performed via the cystic duct (intraoperative cholangiogram). The transhepatic route (percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography) is a separate procedure, usually performed pre- or post-operatively for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes, not routinely as a 'peroperative' step during cholecystectomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intraoperative Cholangiography (IOC) | Percutaneous Transhepatic Cholangiography (PTC) | Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Route** | Via cystic duct (during surgery) | Percutaneous, through liver parenchyma | Endoscopic, via ampulla of Vater |\n| **Timing** | During cholecystectomy | Pre- or post-operative | Pre- or post-operative |\n| **Primary Use** | Detect CBD stones, map anatomy, assess patency | Diagnose/treat biliary obstruction (proximal), drainage | Diagnose/treat CBD stones, strictures, sphincterotomy |\n| **Complications** | Bile leak, duct injury, pancreatitis | Hemorrhage, bile leak, peritonitis, sepsis | Pancreatitis, perforation, bleeding, cholangitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: IOC: Stones, Structure, Sphincter.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn the fluoroscopy screen, you would see contrast filling the cystic duct, common hepatic duct, common bile duct, and flowing into the duodenum, outlining the biliary tree and revealing any filling defects (stones) or strictures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guideline for the Surgical Treatment of Gallstone Disease 2020: Recommends selective use of intraoperative cholangiography based on pre-operative risk assessment for choledocholithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | reveals the presence of gall-stones in the common hepatic duct. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | confirms the anatomy of the ducts. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | confirms the patency of the duodenal papilla. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | confirms the anatomy of the arterial supply to the gall bladder and liver. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | has to be performed by the transhepatic route. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) reveals the presence of gall-stones in the common hepatic duct.\nconfirms the anatomy of the ducts.\nconfirms the patency of the duodenal papilla.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
