  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Not all GB issues are stones; know your cholecystoses!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question correctly identifies several key features and complications associated with cholecystoses, which are a group of non-inflammatory, degenerative, or proliferative conditions of the gallbladder. The correct options accurately describe the pathology of cholesterolosis and adenomyomatosis, their imaging characteristics, and potential complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholesterolosis, or 'strawberry gallbladder,' is characterized by the deposition of cholesterol esters within the lamina propria of the gallbladder wall, giving it a speckled, strawberry-like appearance. Adenomyomatosis, also known as cholecystitis glandularis proliferans, involves hyperplasia of the muscularis propria and invagination of the mucosa into the muscular layer, forming Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (intramural diverticula). These sinuses can be visualized on imaging and, in severe cases, can lead to complications like biliary fistula. Gallbladder polyps, while a distinct entity, are often considered within the broader context of gallbladder lesions and can be detected by cholecystography or ultrasound.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption E (Incorrect): Squamous metaplasia is a change in the epithelial lining of the gallbladder, often a response to chronic irritation or inflammation, and is not typically classified as one of the cholecystoses, which are primarily degenerative or hyperplastic conditions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cholecystosis Type | Key Pathological Feature | Imaging Findings | Potential Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cholesterolosis (Strawberry GB) | Cholesterol ester deposition in lamina propria | US: non-shadowing polyps/deposits | Biliary colic (rare), usually asymptomatic |\n| Adenomyomatosis (Cholecystitis glandularis proliferans) | Hyperplasia of muscularis propria, Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (intramural diverticula) | US: focal/diffuse wall thickening, intramural diverticula, comet-tail artifact | Biliary fistula, stone formation, rarely malignancy |\n| Gallbladder Polyps | Mucosal projections | US: non-shadowing, fixed lesions | Malignant potential (size-dependent) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cholecystoses are non-inflammatory GB conditions with distinct pathological and imaging features.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, cholesterolosis appears as multiple small, non-shadowing polyps or diffuse mucosal speckling. Adenomyomatosis shows focal or diffuse wall thickening with intramural diverticula (Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses) and characteristic 'comet-tail' artifacts. Cholecystography (though less common now) could demonstrate contrast filling these sinuses.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Acute Cholecystitis (2021). While primarily focused on acute cholecystitis, it guides the initial imaging workup for gallbladder pathology, recommending ultrasound as the primary modality, which often identifies cholecystoses incidentally.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the strawberry gall bladder is so called because of the subserous collectio | ✅ Correct |\n| B | polyposis is evident on cholecystography. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | intramural diverticulosis occurs with cholecystitis glandularis proliferans | ✅ Correct |\n| D | biliary fistula is a recognised complication of cholecystitis glandularis p | ✅ Correct |\n| E | squamous metaplasia is included as one of these. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, D) the strawberry gall bladder is so called because of the subserous collections of cholesterol.\npolyposis is evident on cholecystography.\nintramural diverticulosis occurs with cholecystitis glandularis proliferans.\nbiliary fistula is a recognised complication of cholecystitis glandularis proliferans.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
