  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstone colic: a dance of pain, not a statue of suffering.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options B, C, and E accurately describe the characteristic presentation of gallstone colic. This condition typically manifests as severe, visceral pain that causes patients to be restless, often doubling over or moving to find relief, with pain localized to the upper abdomen.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone colic arises from the temporary obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone, leading to increased intraluminal pressure and distension of the gallbladder. This visceral pain is often intense, spasmodic, and poorly localized, typically felt in the epigastrium or right upper quadrant. Unlike somatic pain, which is exacerbated by movement, visceral pain often prompts patients to writhe, roll, or double up in an attempt to alleviate discomfort, reflecting the body's response to severe, cramping pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"lies still, afraid to move.\" This describes somatic pain, such as that seen in peritonitis or appendicitis, where movement aggravates the inflamed parietal peritoneum. Gallstone colic is visceral pain, which often leads to restlessness.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"has pain in the tip of the left shoulder.\" Referred pain to the shoulder tip in gallbladder pathology is typically to the *right* shoulder, due to irritation of the diaphragm and phrenic nerve. Left shoulder pain is more commonly associated with splenic issues or cardiac events.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Type of Pain | Patient Behavior | Pain Location/Radiation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gallstone Colic | Visceral, severe, cramping | Restless, writhing, doubled up | Epigastric/RUQ, may radiate to back/right shoulder |\n| Peritonitis/Appendicitis | Somatic, severe, constant | Lies still, guarding, avoids movement | Localized (e.g., RLQ for appendicitis), rebound tenderness |\n| Renal Colic | Visceral, severe, spasmodic | Restless, writhing, unable to find comfortable position | Flank, radiating to groin/genitalia |\n| Myocardial Infarction | Visceral, crushing, pressure | Anxious, may be still or restless | Chest, radiating to left arm/jaw/back |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Visceral pain makes you move; somatic pain makes you still.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones within the gallbladder lumen are typically seen as echogenic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing. During an intraoperative cholecystectomy, the gallbladder would appear distended, and stones would be palpable within its lumen or the cystic duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the management of acute calculous cholecystitis 2018. These guidelines recommend ultrasound as the primary diagnostic imaging modality and emphasize early cholecystectomy for definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | lies still, afraid to move. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is doubled up. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | may roll on the floor. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | has pain in the tip of the left shoulder. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | has pain across the upper abdomen. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) is doubled up.\nmay roll on the floor.\nhas pain across the upper abdomen.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
