  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Choledochal cysts: Congenital, female, jaundice, cancer risk. Excise!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCholedochal cysts are congenital anomalies of the biliary tree characterized by cystic dilation. This malformation often leads to impaired bile flow, causing cholestasis and clinically manifesting as jaundice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThese rare developmental defects are typically diagnosed in childhood but can present in adulthood. The abnormal anatomy, particularly the long common channel between the pancreatic and bile ducts, is thought to contribute to reflux of pancreatic enzymes into the bile duct, leading to inflammation and dilation. The resulting bile stasis and obstruction are the direct cause of jaundice, and the chronic inflammation significantly increases the risk of cholangiocarcinoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Choledochal cysts are congenital malformations, not caused by parasitic infections. While parasites like Clonorchis sinensis can cause biliary disease, they do not cause choledochal cysts.\nOption C (Incorrect): Choledochal cysts are significantly more common in females, with a female-to-male ratio of approximately 3-4:1.\nOption D (Incorrect): The lining of a choledochal cyst is typically columnar biliary epithelium. Squamous metaplasia can occur in response to chronic inflammation, but it is not the primary or normal lining.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Todani Classification Type | Description | Management Principle | Malignancy Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Type I | Fusiform or saccular dilation of the extrahepatic CBD | Excision + Roux-en-Y Hepaticojejunostomy | High |\n| Type II | Diverticulum protruding from the CBD | Local excision | Low |\n| Type III | Choledochocele (dilation of intraduodenal CBD) | Endoscopic sphincterotomy or transduodenal excision | Low |\n| Type IV | Multiple intra- and/or extrahepatic cysts | Complex, often excision + liver resection | High |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Congenital biliary cysts: Jaundice, female, malignancy risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging: Ultrasound is often the initial screening tool, showing a dilated common bile duct. MRCP is the gold standard for defining the anatomy and extent of the cyst. Intraoperative: A visibly dilated, often fusiform or saccular, extrahepatic bile duct requiring complete excision and reconstruction, typically with a Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) Consensus Statement (2017): Recommends complete excision of extrahepatic choledochal cysts due to the significant risk of malignant transformation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | congenital. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | parasitic. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | more common in males than in females. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | lined by squamous epithelium. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a cause of jaundice. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, E) congenital.\na cause of jaundice.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
