  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Marseilles classifies the 'what,' not the 'why' of pancreatitis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies the key categories included in the Marseilles classification of pancreatitis. This historical classification system primarily categorizes pancreatitis based on its clinical course and presentation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Marseilles classification, first established in 1963 and later revised in 1984, was a foundational attempt to standardize the nomenclature and understanding of pancreatitis. It distinguished between acute pancreatitis (including relapsing acute), chronic pancreatitis (including relapsing chronic), and also acknowledged idiopathic forms where no clear etiology was identified. This system was crucial for clinicians to categorize patients based on the disease's progression and recurrence patterns, guiding early management and research efforts before more detailed severity or etiological classifications emerged.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption E (Incorrect): Alcoholic pancreatitis describes an etiology or cause of pancreatitis, not a primary classification category within the Marseilles system itself. The Marseilles classification focuses on the clinical course (e.g., acute, chronic, relapsing) rather than the specific trigger, although alcoholism is a major cause of both acute and chronic forms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Classification System | Primary Focus | Key Categories/Criteria |\n|---|---|---|\n| Marseilles (1963/1984) | Clinical Course | Acute, Relapsing Acute, Chronic, Relapsing Chronic, Idiopathic |\n| Atlanta (1992/2012) | Severity of Acute Pancreatitis | Mild, Moderately Severe, Severe (based on organ failure, local complications) |\n| TIGAR-O (2001) | Etiology of Chronic Pancreatitis | Toxic-metabolic, Idiopathic, Genetic, Autoimmune, Recurrent Acute, Obstructive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Marseilles: Clinical course. Atlanta: Severity. TIGAR-O: Etiology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRCP), acute pancreatitis typically shows pancreatic edema and peripancreatic fluid collections, while chronic pancreatitis often reveals ductal dilation, calcifications, and glandular atrophy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013) and AGA Institute Guidelines on the Diagnosis and Management of Chronic Pancreatitis (2020). These guidelines utilize and build upon the historical understanding provided by classifications like Marseilles, focusing on current diagnostic and therapeutic approaches.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | relapsing acute pancreatitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | idiopathic pancreatitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | chronic pancreatitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | relapsing chronic pancreatitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | alcoholic pancreatitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, D) relapsing acute pancreatitis.\nidiopathic pancreatitis.\nchronic pancreatitis.\nrelapsing chronic pancreatitis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
