  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatitis: When your own enzymes turn against you.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies fat necrosis, cholelithiasis, and mumps as recognized associations with acute pancreatitis. These choices accurately reflect both common causes and direct pathological sequelae of the disease process.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis is primarily caused by premature activation of digestive enzymes within the pancreas. Cholelithiasis is a leading cause, where gallstones obstruct the pancreatic duct or ampulla, leading to enzyme reflux and autodigestion. Mumps, a viral infection, can directly inflame pancreatic acinar cells. Fat necrosis is a hallmark pathological finding, resulting from activated lipases digesting peripancreatic adipose tissue, leading to saponification.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Acute pancreatitis typically presents with leukocytosis due to the systemic inflammatory response, not leucopenia. \nOption E (Incorrect): Sulphaemoglobinaemia is a rare blood disorder caused by certain drug exposures and has no direct association with acute pancreatitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Etiology/Feature | Description | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cholelithiasis | Gallstones obstructing the ampulla of Vater or pancreatic duct. | Most common cause of acute pancreatitis. |\n| Alcohol | Direct toxic effect on acinar cells, sphincter of Oddi spasm. | Second most common cause, often chronic. |\n| Mumps | Viral infection causing direct pancreatic inflammation. | Less common, but a recognized infectious cause. |\n| Fat Necrosis | Enzymatic digestion of peripancreatic fat by activated lipases. | Pathognomonic sign, indicates severity, can lead to hypocalcemia. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember 'GET SMASHED' for common causes of acute pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, peripancreatic fat stranding and fluid collections are characteristic. Intraoperatively, saponification (chalky white deposits) in the omentum or mesentery indicates fat necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018) recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration and identifies gallstones and alcohol as the most common etiologies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | fat necrosis. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | cholelithiasis. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | mumps. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | leucopenia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | sulphaemoglobinaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) fat necrosis.\ncholelithiasis.\nmumps.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
