  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatitis: a fiery organ, a systemic storm.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies 'third space' collection, hypoxia, and pseudocyst as complications of acute pancreatitis. Acute pancreatitis is a severe inflammatory process that can lead to both local and systemic sequelae, impacting multiple organ systems.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis triggers a systemic inflammatory response, increasing capillary permeability and leading to significant 'third space' fluid shifts into the retroperitoneum, peritoneal cavity (ascites), and pleural spaces (effusions). This fluid loss contributes to hypovolemia and can cause hypoxia through pleural effusions, diaphragmatic splinting, atelectasis, and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). A pseudocyst is a common late local complication, representing a walled-off collection of pancreatic fluid, necrotic debris, and inflammatory exudate, typically forming 4-6 weeks after an acute attack.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Acute pancreatitis typically causes hypocalcaemia, not hypercalcaemia, due to the saponification of fat by lipase, which binds calcium. Option D (Incorrect): Patients with severe acute pancreatitis often develop hypotension due to significant third-space fluid loss and systemic vasodilation from inflammatory mediators, not hypertension.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Example | Timing | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Early Systemic | Hypoxia | Within days | ARDS, pleural effusion, atelectasis |\n| Early Local | Third-space fluid | Within days | Increased capillary permeability, fluid extravasation |\n| Late Local | Pseudocyst | Weeks to months | Walled-off collection of fluid and debris |\n| Metabolic | Hypocalcemia | Early | Fat saponification binding calcium |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pancreatitis complications span fluid shifts, respiratory compromise, and delayed collections.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, one would typically see peripancreatic fluid collections, ascites, pleural effusions, and potentially pancreatic necrosis. A pseudocyst appears as a well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection, often adjacent to the pancreas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013) recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration and monitoring for systemic complications like ARDS and organ failure.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ‘third space’ collection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | hypoxia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | hypercalcaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | hypertension. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | pseudocyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABE) ‘third space’ collection.; hypoxia.; pseudocyst.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
