  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic head cancer: Jaundice, palpable gallbladder, pale stools – a classic triad!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, B, and C accurately describe key clinical and pathological features of pancreatic carcinoma. Pancreatic head tumors are the most common and often present with obstructive jaundice, leading to characteristic physical exam findings and stool changes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic adenocarcinoma predominantly arises in the head of the gland, accounting for 70-80% of cases. Tumors in this location frequently compress the common bile duct, leading to biliary obstruction. This obstruction manifests clinically as painless jaundice and, according to Courvoisier's Law, a palpable, distended gallbladder. The absence of bile in the intestinal lumen due to this obstruction results in pale, acholic stools, sometimes described as 'aluminium' or clay-colored.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Pancreatic cancer is strongly related to diabetes; it can both be a risk factor for and a consequence of the malignancy, often presenting as new-onset diabetes.\nOption E (Incorrect): Mucoviscidosis is another term for Cystic Fibrosis, a genetic disorder. Pancreatic carcinoma does not cause mucoviscidosis, although both can lead to pancreatic exocrine insufficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pancreatic Head Cancer | Pancreatic Body/Tail Cancer | Cholangiocarcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Presentation** | Jaundice, weight loss, abdominal pain, Courvoisier's sign | Abdominal pain, weight loss, back pain, often late presentation | Jaundice, pruritus, weight loss, cholangitis |\n| **Location** | Head of pancreas (70-80%) | Body/tail of pancreas (20-30%) | Biliary tree (intrahepatic, perihilar, distal) |\n| **Courvoisier's Sign** | Often present (painless jaundice + palpable gallbladder) | Absent | May be present with distal CBD obstruction |\n| **Stool Color** | Acholic (pale, 'aluminium') | Normal (unless very advanced with biliary obstruction) | Acholic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Jaundice + palpable gallbladder = Courvoisier's Law, think pancreatic head mass.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a hypodense mass in the pancreatic head with upstream dilation of the pancreatic and common bile ducts (double duct sign) is highly suggestive. Intraoperatively, a firm, often ill-defined mass in the pancreatic head obstructing the bile duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). They recommend multidisciplinary evaluation, staging with cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), and consideration of neoadjuvant therapy for borderline resectable disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | occurs mostly in the head of the gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is associated with a distended gall bladder. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | can cause the passage of ‘aluminium’ stools. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | is not related to diabetes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | causes mucoviscidosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABC) occurs mostly in the head of the gland.; is associated with a distended gall bladder.; can cause the passage of ‘aluminium’ stools.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
