  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer: a silent killer with tell-tale signs.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies key features associated with pancreatic carcinoma. Most pancreatic cancers are adenocarcinomas of ductal origin, and specific complications like gallbladder distension (Courvoisier's sign) and splenic vein thrombosis are well-recognized manifestations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic adenocarcinoma, primarily arising from ductal cells, accounts for the vast majority of pancreatic malignancies. Courvoisier's law, stating that a palpable, non-tender gallbladder in a jaundiced patient suggests obstruction distal to the cystic duct (often pancreatic head or ampullary tumor), is a classic clinical sign. Splenic vein thrombosis is a significant complication, particularly with tumors in the body or tail of the pancreas, due to direct tumor invasion or compression of the splenic vein, leading to portal hypertension and gastric varices.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Jaundice is a common symptom of pancreatic head and ampullary carcinomas, but it is not synonymous with ampullary carcinoma alone. Many other conditions can cause jaundice, and not all ampullary tumors present with jaundice early. Pancreatic head tumors are a more frequent cause of obstructive jaundice than ampullary tumors.\nOption C (Incorrect): A palpable liver (hepatomegaly) typically indicates metastatic disease, which is a late-stage finding. It is not present in 80% of all pancreatic cancer cases, many of which are diagnosed at earlier stages or without overt liver metastases.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pancreatic Head/Ampullary Carcinoma | Pancreatic Body/Tail Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Common Presentation | Jaundice, Courvoisier's sign, weight loss | Back pain, weight loss, splenic vein thrombosis, gastric varices |\n| Tumor Type | Ductal adenocarcinoma (most common) | Ductal adenocarcinoma (most common) |\n| Surgical Resectability | Often higher if diagnosed early due to jaundice | Often lower due to late presentation and vascular involvement |\n| Associated Complications | Obstructive jaundice, cholangitis | Splenic vein thrombosis, portal hypertension, gastric outlet obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pancreatic cancer = ductal adeno, Courvoisier's, splenic vein thrombosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, look for a pancreatic mass, pancreatic duct dilation, common bile duct dilation, and signs of vascular involvement (e.g., splenic vein thrombosis, encasement of superior mesenteric artery/vein). Intraoperatively, a hard, irregular mass in the pancreas, often with dilated upstream ducts and a distended gallbladder (Courvoisier's), would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (latest version): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and management, emphasizing multidisciplinary care and surgical resection for resectable disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | most cases are adenocarcinomas of cell duct origin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | jaundice is synonymous with ampullary carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the liver is palpable in 80% of cases. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | the gall bladder is distended in 50% of ampullary tumours. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | splenic vein thrombosis is an associated feature. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ADE) most cases are adenocarcinomas of cell duct origin.; the gall bladder is distended in 50% of ampullary tumours.; splenic vein thrombosis is an associated feature.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
