  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer: silent killer, loud paraneoplastic signs.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies thrombophlebitis migrans, new-onset diabetes, and pancreatic calcinosis as potential indicators of pancreatic carcinoma. These represent paraneoplastic phenomena, metabolic disturbances, and chronic inflammatory changes, respectively, all associated with the disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThrombophlebitis migrans (Trousseau's syndrome) is a classic paraneoplastic syndrome, where the tumor secretes procoagulant factors (e.g., mucins, tissue factor) leading to a hypercoagulable state and migratory venous thrombosis. New-onset diabetes mellitus, particularly in older, non-obese individuals, can be an early manifestation due to tumor-induced destruction of islet cells or systemic insulin resistance. Pancreatic calcinosis, typically a sign of chronic pancreatitis, is a significant risk factor for pancreatic adenocarcinoma, and its presence can therefore indicate an increased likelihood or co-existence of malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): The 'ordinary three sign' is not a recognized radiological sign for pancreatic carcinoma. Historically, the 'inverted 3 sign' or 'Frostberg's sign' on barium studies was associated with pancreatic head masses, but this option is inaccurately phrased.\nOption E (Incorrect): The triple response of Lewis is a physiological reaction of the skin to injury (redness, flare, wheal) and has no association with pancreatic carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Trousseau's Syndrome (Thrombophlebitis Migrans) | New-Onset Diabetes Mellitus | Pancreatic Calcinosis (Chronic Pancreatitis) |\n| :---------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- |\n| **Mechanism** | Paraneoplastic hypercoagulability               | Islet cell destruction/dysfunction          | Chronic inflammation, duct obstruction       |\n| **Association with PC** | Strong, often early indicator                   | Can be early sign, especially in elderly    | Significant risk factor, can coexist         |\n| **Clinical Relevance**  | Unexplained migratory thrombosis warrants cancer workup | Unexplained new DM in non-obese/elderly warrants PC consideration | Indicates underlying chronic pancreatitis, increasing PC risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unexplained migratory thrombosis or new-onset diabetes in elderly demands pancreatic cancer workup.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRI, a pancreatic mass, often with ductal dilation (e.g., 'double duct sign' with dilated common bile duct and pancreatic duct), and atrophy of the distal pancreas are common findings. Intraoperatively, a hard, irregular, often desmoplastic mass is typically encountered.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023) recommend comprehensive workup for suspected pancreatic cancer, including imaging and consideration of paraneoplastic syndromes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | thrombophlebitis migrans. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | diabetes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | pancreatic calcinosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | the ordinary three sign on a barium meal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | the triple response of Lewis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABC) thrombophlebitis migrans.; diabetes.; pancreatic calcinosis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
