  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer: image early, biopsy definitively, and don't forget the ducts!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options highlight a range of investigations, from initial screening to more invasive diagnostic and therapeutic procedures, all useful in evaluating suspected pancreatic carcinoma. These methods help visualize the pancreas, detect masses, and assess ductal involvement, guiding further management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic ultrasound serves as a non-invasive initial screening tool, identifying masses or ductal dilation. ERCP provides direct visualization of the ampulla, allows for cannulation of the pancreatic and bile ducts, contrast injection for fluoroscopic imaging, and enables tissue sampling (brush cytology) or therapeutic stenting for obstructive jaundice. A hypotonic duodenogram, while less common now, historically provided valuable information by relaxing the duodenum to better visualize extrinsic compression or infiltration by pancreatic head masses, indicating tumor presence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (gastrin assay) (Incorrect): This test is specific for gastrinomas, a rare neuroendocrine tumor, and is not a primary investigation for pancreatic adenocarcinoma.\nOption E (fasting blood sugar) (Incorrect): While new-onset diabetes can be associated with pancreatic cancer, it is a non-specific finding and not a direct diagnostic tool for the cancer itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Role in Pancreatic Cancer | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pancreatic Ultrasound | Initial screening, guiding biopsy | Non-invasive, widely available, no radiation | Operator-dependent, limited by bowel gas/obesity |\n| CT Scan (multiphasic) | Staging, resectability assessment | High resolution, good for vascular invasion | Radiation exposure, contrast nephrotoxicity |\n| MRI/MRCP | Detailed soft tissue, ductal imaging | No radiation, better for cystic lesions | Cost, availability, patient tolerance (claustrophobia) |\n| ERCP | Diagnostic (ductal imaging, cytology), therapeutic (stenting) | Direct visualization, tissue sampling, therapeutic intervention | Invasive, risk of pancreatitis, perforation, bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Initial imaging, then advanced imaging/biopsy for pancreatic cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ERCP, a classic finding in pancreatic head cancer is a \"double duct sign\" – simultaneous dilation of both the common bile duct and the pancreatic duct due to obstruction by the tumor. On ultrasound, a hypoechoic mass within the pancreatic parenchyma may be seen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). They recommend multiphasic CT or MRI/MRCP as primary imaging for diagnosis and staging, with EUS-guided FNA for tissue diagnosis. ERCP is primarily for therapeutic intervention (stenting) in obstructive jaundice, though it can be diagnostic.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | hypotonic duodenogram. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pancreatic ultrasound. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ERCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | gastrin assay. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | fasting blood sugar. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABC) hypotonic duodenogram.; pancreatic ultrasound.; ERCP** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
