  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When ulcers go south, think ZES.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately identifies jejunal ulceration as a hallmark of Zollinger-Ellison syndrome (ZES) due to excessive acid production. It also correctly includes antral G-cell hyperplasia, a condition that mimics ZES, and Whipple's triad, which is associated through the common link of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 1 (MEN1).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nZES is caused by a gastrin-secreting tumor (gastrinoma), leading to profound hypergastrinemia and massive gastric acid hypersecretion. This overwhelms the duodenum's neutralizing capacity, resulting in severe, often refractory, peptic ulcers frequently found in atypical locations like the distal duodenum or jejunum. Antral G-cell hyperplasia is a rare cause of hypergastrinemia that can clinically mimic ZES, requiring careful differentiation. Whipple's triad (symptoms of hypoglycemia, low plasma glucose, and symptom relief with glucose administration) is characteristic of insulinoma, another neuroendocrine tumor often found in MEN1, which also predisposes to ZES.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Carcinoid tumors secrete serotonin and other vasoactive substances, causing carcinoid syndrome, not ZES. While both are neuroendocrine tumors, they have distinct clinical presentations.\nOption D (Incorrect): ZES is associated with severe diarrhea due to acid inactivation of pancreatic enzymes and mucosal damage, which can lead to hypokalemia, not hyperkalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome | Antral G-cell Hyperplasia | Insulinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cause | Gastrinoma (NET) | Excessive G-cell proliferation in antrum | Insulin-secreting NET |\n| Hormone | Gastrin | Gastrin | Insulin |\n| Key Clinical | Severe PUD, diarrhea, jejunal ulcers | PUD, hypergastrinemia (mimics ZES) | Hypoglycemia, Whipple's triad |\n| Association | MEN1 | No MEN1 association | MEN1 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ZES: Gastrinoma, hyperacidity, jejunal ulcers, MEN1.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy typically reveals multiple, large, or atypical ulcers (distal duodenum, jejunum) and prominent gastric folds. Imaging (CT/MRI/Somatostatin Receptor Scintigraphy) aims to localize the gastrinoma, often small and located in the pancreas or duodenum. Intraoperatively, careful palpation of the pancreas and duodenum is crucial for identifying small tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNorth American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumors (2020) recommend surgical resection for localized gastrinomas and emphasize biochemical testing for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | antral G-cell hyperplasia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | carcinoid tumour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | jejunal ulceration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | hyperkalaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Whipple’s triad. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ACE) antral G-cell hyperplasia.; jejunal ulceration.; Whipple’s triad.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
