  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wait for silent bowels; peritonitis screams early.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer BCD accurately identifies initial clinical features of diffuse peritonitis. Vomiting, guarding (fear of coughing), and initially present bowel sounds are characteristic early responses to widespread peritoneal inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiffuse peritonitis, an inflammation of the entire peritoneal cavity, triggers a systemic response. Visceral irritation leads to reflex nausea and vomiting via vagal pathways. The inflamed parietal peritoneum is highly sensitive to stretch and movement, causing severe pain exacerbated by coughing or movement, leading to voluntary guarding and rigidity. Initially, the bowel attempts to respond to inflammation, so sounds may be present, albeit often diminished. As inflammation progresses, paralytic ileus develops, leading to absent bowel sounds.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hippocratic facies is a sign of severe, prolonged illness and dehydration, not an initial feature of peritonitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): While fever is common, hyperpyrexia (very high fever) is typically seen in advanced sepsis or severe, late-stage peritonitis, not initially.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Initial Peritonitis | Late Peritonitis |\n| :------------------ | :------------------ | :------------------ |\n| Pain | Localized/Diffuse, sharp | Widespread, severe |\n| Bowel Sounds | Present, often diminished | Absent (paralytic ileus) |\n| Vomiting | Common | Persistent, bilious/feculent |\n| Guarding/Rigidity | Voluntary/Involuntary | Board-like rigidity |\n| Facies | Normal/Anxious | Hippocratic facies |\n| Fever | Low-grade to moderate | High-grade, hyperpyrexia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peritonitis starts with pain and guarding; silent bowels and shock come later.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, free fluid, bowel wall thickening, and inflammatory stranding are common. Intraoperatively, purulent exudate, fibrin deposits, and inflamed, edematous bowel loops are characteristic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Intra-abdominal Infections 2017. These guidelines provide recommendations for diagnosis, source control, and antimicrobial therapy for peritonitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hippocratic facies. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | vomiting. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | a patient who is afraid to cough. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | the presence of bowel sounds. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | hyperpyrexia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCD) vomiting.; a patient who is afraid to cough.; the presence of bowel sounds.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
