  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 UC's reach extends far beyond the colon's walls.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Options B, C, and E are correct. These represent common extra-intestinal manifestations (EIMs) of ulcerative colitis, which are systemic complications occurring outside the gastrointestinal tract due to the underlying inflammatory process.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUlcerative colitis is a chronic inflammatory condition primarily affecting the colon, but its systemic nature leads to a variety of extra-intestinal manifestations. These EIMs are thought to arise from shared immunological pathways, genetic predispositions, and the systemic inflammatory burden. For instance, circulating immune complexes, T-cell activation, and cytokine release can target distant organs, leading to conditions like iritis (ocular inflammation), aphthous stomatitis (oral ulcers), and various dermatological conditions such as erythema nodosum or pyoderma gangrenosum.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Neuropathic joints (Charcot joints) are a consequence of severe peripheral neuropathy, leading to joint destruction, and are not a direct complication or extra-intestinal manifestation of ulcerative colitis.\nOption D (Incorrect): While there can be an increased risk of renal calculi in inflammatory bowel disease, it is more commonly associated with Crohn's disease due to fat malabsorption leading to increased oxalate absorption, rather than a primary or common complication of ulcerative colitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| System | Ulcerative Colitis (Common EIMs) | Crohn's Disease (Common EIMs) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ocular | Iritis, Uveitis, Episcleritis | Iritis, Uveitis, Episcleritis |\n| Cutaneous | Erythema Nodosum, Pyoderma Gangrenosum | Erythema Nodosum, Pyoderma Gangrenosum |\n| Articular | Peripheral Arthritis, Spondyloarthritis | Peripheral Arthritis, Spondyloarthritis |\n| Oral | Aphthous Stomatitis | Aphthous Stomatitis, Oral granulomas |\n| Hepatobiliary | Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) | Gallstones, Fatty liver |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think beyond the gut; UC's systemic inflammation causes diverse extra-intestinal manifestations.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, ulcerative colitis typically presents with continuous inflammation starting from the rectum and extending proximally, characterized by erythema, friability, loss of vascular pattern, erosions, and pseudopolyps. For iritis, slit-lamp examination would reveal inflammatory cells in the anterior chamber. Skin lesions like erythema nodosum appear as tender, red nodules, often on the shins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines: Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019). These guidelines recommend screening for and managing extra-intestinal manifestations as part of comprehensive UC care, noting their impact on patient quality of life and disease activity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | neuropathic joints. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | stomatitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | iritis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | renal calculi. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | skin lesions. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCE) stomatitis.; iritis.; skin lesions.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
