  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Crohn's: A full-thickness problem with systemic reach.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, B, and C. These features – faecal fistula, steatorrhoea, and cholangitis – are all well-established manifestations or associations of Crohn's disease, reflecting its transmural nature, common sites of involvement, and systemic impact.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCrohn's disease is characterized by transmural inflammation, which can lead to the formation of fistulas (e.g., enteroenteric, enterocutaneous, perianal, or faecal fistulas) as the inflammation extends through all layers of the bowel wall. Involvement of the terminal ileum, a common site for Crohn's, impairs bile salt reabsorption, leading to fat malabsorption and subsequent steatorrhoea. Furthermore, Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) is a recognized extraintestinal manifestation of inflammatory bowel disease, particularly ulcerative colitis, but also associated with Crohn's disease, causing inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Calcified lymph nodes are not a typical feature of Crohn's disease. While Crohn's is a granulomatous disease, calcified lymph nodes are more commonly associated with other granulomatous conditions like tuberculosis or sarcoidosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): An 'apple core' filling defect on barium enema is a classic radiographic sign highly suggestive of colorectal carcinoma, indicating an annular constricting lesion, and is not characteristic of Crohn's disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Crohn's Disease | Ulcerative Colitis | Colorectal Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Transmural Inflammation | Yes | No (mucosal only) | N/A |\n| Fistula Formation | Common | Rare | Rare (unless advanced/perforated) |\n| Steatorrhoea | Common (due to ileal involvement) | Rare | Rare |\n| Apple Core Lesion | No | No | Yes |\n| Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis | Yes (less common than UC) | Yes (more common than CD) | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Crohn's: transmural, skip, fistulas, malabsorption, extraintestinal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., barium studies, CT enterography), Crohn's disease can manifest as skip lesions, cobblestoning, strictures, and fistulas. Intraoperatively, one might observe creeping fat, thickened bowel wall, mesentery inflammation, and visible fistulous tracts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines: Management of Crohn's Disease in Adults (2018) provides comprehensive recommendations on diagnosis, medical, and surgical management, including recognition of extraintestinal manifestations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | faecal fistula. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | steatorrhoea. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | cholangitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | calcified lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | apple core filling defect of a colonic lesion on barium enema. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABC) faecal fistula.; steatorrhoea.; cholangitis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
