  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be anemic to the signs of colon cancer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, \"causes anaemia.\" This is a classic and often early presentation of colon carcinoma, particularly for right-sided lesions, due to chronic, occult blood loss from friable tumors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColon adenocarcinomas, especially those in the right colon, tend to be exophytic and friable. As stool passes over these lesions, microscopic bleeding occurs. This chronic blood loss, often unnoticed by the patient, leads to iron deficiency anemia over time. The larger luminal diameter and more liquid stool in the right colon allow tumors to grow quite large before causing obstructive symptoms, making anemia an early and often the only presenting symptom.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (spreads to inguinal lymph nodes): Incorrect. Inguinal lymph node spread is rare for colon cancer, typically only seen with very distal rectal cancers involving the perianal skin or extensive local invasion. Colon cancer primarily spreads to regional mesenteric lymph nodes.\nOption B (is transitional celled): Incorrect. The vast majority (over 95%) of colon cancers are adenocarcinomas, arising from the glandular epithelium of the colon. Transitional cell carcinoma is characteristic of the urinary tract.\nOption C (presents early when on the right side): Incorrect. Right-sided colon cancers often present late because the larger luminal diameter and more liquid stool allow tumors to grow to a significant size before causing obstructive symptoms. They are more likely to present with anemia or a palpable mass. Left-sided cancers, with a smaller lumen and more solid stool, tend to present earlier with obstructive symptoms or altered bowel habits.\nOption D (is markedly radiosensitive): Incorrect. Colon adenocarcinoma is generally considered radioresistant. While radiation therapy can be used in specific contexts (e.g., neoadjuvant/adjuvant for rectal cancer, palliative for metastatic disease), it is not a primary curative modality for colon cancer due to its inherent radioresistance.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right-sided Colon Cancer | Left-sided Colon Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Presentation | Anemia, fatigue, palpable mass, occult bleeding | Change in bowel habits, obstruction, hematochezia, tenesmia |\n| Tumor Morphology | Exophytic, polypoid, larger lumen | Annular, \"apple-core\" lesion, smaller lumen |\n| Stool Consistency | Liquid | Solid |\n| Common Symptom | Anemia | Obstruction, bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right colon bleeds, left colon obstructs.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, a friable, often fungating or ulcerated mass would be seen. CT imaging might show a thickened bowel wall, a mass, or signs of metastatic disease (e.g., liver lesions). Intraoperatively, a firm, often exophytic mass would be palpable, potentially with enlarged regional lymph nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2024). These guidelines detail screening, diagnosis, staging, and treatment, including the workup for anemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | spreads to inguinal lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is transitional celled. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | presents early when on the right side. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | is markedly radiosensitive. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | causes anaemia. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) causes anaemia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
