  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A happy stoma is pink and proud, not blue and bowed!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies stenosis, prolapse, and necrosis as common complications of colostomies. These issues arise due to factors like surgical technique, blood supply, and abdominal wall dynamics, directly impacting stoma function and patient well-being.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStenosis often results from inadequate fascial opening, excessive tension, or chronic inflammation at the mucocutaneous junction. Prolapse occurs when the bowel telescopes through the stoma, frequently due to a large fascial defect, inadequate fixation, or increased intra-abdominal pressure. Necrosis is a critical complication caused by compromised blood supply to the stoma, which can be due to excessive tension on the mesentery, inadequate mobilization, or vascular injury during creation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Atresia refers to the congenital absence or abnormal narrowing of a body opening or tube, typically seen in conditions like intestinal atresia, not as a complication of a surgically created colostomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Desmoid formation, or aggressive fibromatosis, is a rare benign but locally invasive soft tissue tumor. While it can occur in surgical scars, it is not a typical or common complication directly associated with colostomy creation or function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Description | Common Cause | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Stenosis | Narrowing of the stoma opening | Inadequate fascial opening, ischemia, inflammation | Local revision, stoma dilation, re-siting |\n| Prolapse | Bowel telescoping through the stoma | Large fascial defect, increased intra-abdominal pressure | Manual reduction, surgical revision, stoma support |\n| Necrosis | Tissue death of the stoma | Compromised blood supply (tension, ischemia) | Urgent surgical revision, re-siting |\n| Retraction | Stoma pulls back below skin level | Excessive tension, inadequate mobilization | Surgical revision, re-siting |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Stenosis, prolapse, and necrosis are the 'big three' colostomy complications.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn examination, a necrotic stoma appears dusky or black. Intraoperatively, compromised blood supply to the stoma is evident by lack of bleeding from the stoma edge or a non-viable appearance of the bowel. Imaging like CT may show bowel wall thickening or edema in cases of inflammation or early ischemia, or a dilated proximal bowel in stenosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Ostomy Surgery (2019). These guidelines recommend careful patient selection, optimal stoma site marking, and meticulous surgical technique to minimize complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | atresia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | stenosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | prolapse. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | necrosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | desmoid formation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCD) stenosis.; prolapse.; necrosis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
