  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just chew your food, know your bolus risks!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, B, and C accurately identify diverse etiologies of bolus obstruction. This condition refers to mechanical blockage of the gastrointestinal tract by an intraluminal mass, which can be food, a gallstone, or other foreign material, often exacerbated by underlying anatomical or physiological abnormalities.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFood bolus obstruction (A) commonly occurs in the esophagus or stomach, particularly with poorly chewed fibrous foods like unripe apples, especially in patients with esophageal strictures, motility disorders, or poor dentition. Post-gastrectomy states (B) predispose to bolus obstruction due to altered anatomy (e.g., anastomotic strictures, afferent loop syndrome) or impaired gastric emptying and food breakdown. Gallstone ileus (C) is a specific form of mechanical small bowel obstruction caused by a large gallstone that has eroded through a cholecystoenteric fistula, typically impacting in the terminal ileum.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Enemas are primarily used for distal colonic or rectal obstruction and are ineffective for bolus obstructions, which typically occur in the upper GI tract or small bowel. Treatment often involves endoscopic removal or surgical intervention.\nOption E (Incorrect): An emergency barium meal is generally contraindicated in suspected complete bowel obstruction or perforation due to the risk of aspiration and the potential for barium to obscure endoscopic or surgical views. CT scan with IV contrast is the preferred imaging modality for acute bowel obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Bolus Obstruction | Common Location | Key Predisposing Factors | Management Approach |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Food Bolus Impaction | Esophagus, Stomach | Poor dentition, strictures, motility disorders, rapid eating | Endoscopic removal, glucagon |\n| Gallstone Ileus | Terminal Ileum | Cholecystoenteric fistula, large gallstone | Surgical removal of stone (enterolithotomy) |\n| Bezoar | Stomach, Small Bowel | Gastric dysmotility, prior gastric surgery, psychiatric conditions | Endoscopic fragmentation/removal, enzymatic dissolution, surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bolus obstruction etiologies span food, stones, and surgical sequelae.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, gallstone ileus classically presents with Rigler's triad: pneumobilia, ectopic gallstone, and small bowel obstruction. Endoscopy is crucial for diagnosing and often treating esophageal or gastric food bolus impaction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guideline for the management of ingested foreign bodies and food impactions (2023) recommends prompt endoscopic removal for esophageal food impactions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | can follow eating unripe apples. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is a complication after partial gastrectomy. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can be caused by a gall-stone. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is treated by enemas. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | should be investigated by an emergency barium meal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) can follow eating unripe apples.\nis a complication after partial gastrectomy.\ncan be caused by a gall-stone.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
