  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keep the NGT flowing, watch that belly grow (or shrink!).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers are B and D. In the management of paralytic ileus, a nasogastric tube (NGT) is used for decompression and should not be clamped, and daily measurement of abdominal girth is crucial for monitoring the patient's progress.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nParalytic ileus is characterized by decreased or absent bowel motility, leading to accumulation of gas and fluid. An NGT provides continuous gastric decompression, preventing further distension, nausea, vomiting, and aspiration. Clamping the NGT (spiggotting) would negate its purpose, allowing gastric contents to accumulate. Abdominal girth measurement offers an objective, reproducible way to track abdominal distension, a primary sign of ileus, and helps assess the effectiveness of interventions or resolution of the condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Morphine and other opioids decrease gut motility and can worsen paralytic ileus, so they are generally avoided or used with extreme caution. However, stating they are \"strictly contraindicated\" might be an overstatement in all clinical scenarios, especially for severe pain.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hypokalemia (low serum potassium) can cause or exacerbate paralytic ileus by impairing smooth muscle function. Therefore, a lowering of serum potassium would be a detrimental sign, not a welcome one.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hunger pains or the return of bowel sounds typically indicate the recovery of gut motility, which is a sign of improvement and resolution of the ileus, not a worsening of the problem.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Paralytic Ileus                                  | Mechanical Obstruction                               |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|\n| Bowel Sounds        | Absent or hypoactive                             | High-pitched, tinkling, then absent                  |\n| Abdominal Pain      | Diffuse, constant, mild                          | Colicky, intermittent, severe                        |\n| Distension          | Generalized, often significant                   | Localized or generalized, depending on obstruction    |\n| Vomiting            | Bilious, non-feculent, less severe               | Feculent (late), more severe                         |\n| Imaging             | Diffusely dilated loops, air-fluid levels        | Dilated loops proximal to obstruction, transition zone |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Decompress and monitor. NGT open, girth measured.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-rays, you would typically see diffusely dilated loops of both small and large bowel with air-fluid levels, without a clear transition point. Intraoperatively, the bowel would appear distended, flaccid, and lack peristaltic activity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of acute colonic pseudo-obstruction and ileus (2017) recommend conservative management including NGT decompression and careful fluid/electrolyte balance.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | morphine is strictly contraindicated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | a nasogastric tube should not be spiggotted. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | lowering of the serum potassium level is a welcome sign. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | daily measurement of the abdominal girth is mandatory. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | hunger pains indicate worsening of the probiem. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D) a nasogastric tube should not be spiggotted.\ndaily measurement of the abdominal girth is mandatory.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
