  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the rectum's upset, the whole system's a mess.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options (A, C, D, E) represent a range of common symptoms associated with various rectal pathologies, including functional disturbances, structural issues, and sensory complaints. These symptoms directly reflect the rectum's role in defecation and its susceptibility to local irritation and structural changes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSpurious diarrhea often indicates fecal impaction, where liquid stool bypasses a hardened fecal mass in the rectum. Pruritus ani, or anal itching, is a common symptom of local irritation, poor hygiene, or underlying rectal conditions like hemorrhoids or fissures. Rectal prolapse is the protrusion of the rectal wall through the anus, a clear structural defect. Hesitancy in defecation can stem from outlet obstruction, such as a rectocele or intussusception, or pelvic floor dyssynergia, all involving rectal function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Strangury refers to painful, frequent urination, which is a symptom of lower urinary tract irritation or bladder pathology, not typically a primary manifestation of rectal disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom | Associated Rectal Pathology | Mechanism/Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Spurious Diarrhea | Fecal Impaction | Liquid stool bypasses hardened fecal mass |\n| Pruritus Ani | Hemorrhoids, Fissures, Poor Hygiene | Local irritation, inflammation, or infection |\n| Rectal Prolapse | Weakened Pelvic Floor, Chronic Straining | Full-thickness protrusion of rectal wall |\n| Hesitancy | Obstructed Defecation, Dyssynergia | Difficulty initiating or completing bowel movement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rectal symptoms are diverse, affecting both bowel function and sensation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn defecography, one might observe rectal prolapse, rectocele, or intussusception during straining. Endoscopy can reveal mucosal inflammation, masses, or internal prolapse.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Rectal Prolapse (2017) recommends surgical repair for symptomatic full-thickness rectal prolapse.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | spurious diarrhoea. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | strangury. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | pruritus. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | prolapse. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | hesitancy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D, E) spurious diarrhoea.\npruritus.\nprolapse.\nhesitancy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
