  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Proctitis: Don't just treat the pain, find the flame!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nProctitis, inflammation of the rectum, can arise from diverse etiologies including infectious, inflammatory, and sexually transmitted causes. The correct options represent various conditions that directly cause or are characterized by rectal inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPseudomembranous colitis, typically caused by C. difficile, induces toxin-mediated inflammation of the colonic and rectal mucosa. Amoebic granuloma results from chronic Entamoeba histolytica infection leading to a mass-like inflammatory lesion in the colon or rectum. Crohn's disease is a chronic, transmural inflammatory bowel disease frequently affecting the rectum. Granuloma inguinale, a bacterial STD caused by Klebsiella granulomatis, causes chronic granulomatous inflammation in the anogenital region, including the rectum.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Proctalgia fugax is a benign, episodic, severe rectal pain caused by muscle spasm, not an inflammatory condition of the rectal mucosa. It does not cause proctitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Etiology | Pathophysiology | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pseudomembranous Colitis | Toxin-mediated inflammation (C. difficile) | Diarrhea, abdominal pain, fever, pseudomembranes on endoscopy |\n| Amoebic Granuloma | Chronic parasitic infection (Entamoeba histolytica) | Rectal mass, dysentery, abdominal pain, often travel history |\n| Crohn's Disease | Immune-mediated transmural inflammation | Abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, perianal disease, skip lesions |\n| Granuloma Inguinale | Bacterial infection (Klebsiella granulomatis) | Painless, progressive ulcerative lesions, beefy red appearance, STD |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Proctitis: Always consider infectious, inflammatory, and autoimmune causes.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy reveals erythematous, friable, and often ulcerated rectal mucosa; pseudomembranes are characteristic of C. difficile. Biopsies are crucial for definitive diagnosis, showing granulomas in Crohn's or specific pathogens like Donovan bodies in granuloma inguinale.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Crohn's Disease in Adults (2018) recommends endoscopy with biopsy for diagnosis and assessment of disease activity, including rectal involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | proctalgia fugax. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pseudomembranous colitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | amoebic granuloma. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Crohn’s disease. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | granuloma inguinale. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D, E) pseudomembranous colitis.\namoebic granuloma.\nCrohn’s disease.\ngranuloma inguinale.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
