  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Not all rectal bumps are bad, but biopsy is key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT as pseudopolyps, villous adenomas, endometriomas, and fibromas are all recognized benign lesions that can occur in the rectum. This question tests the breadth of knowledge regarding non-malignant rectal pathologies, encompassing inflammatory, neoplastic, and ectopic origins.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBenign rectal lesions encompass a spectrum from non-neoplastic inflammatory processes to true neoplastic growths and ectopic tissue. Pseudopolyps are inflammatory mucosal tags, often seen in inflammatory bowel disease, and are not neoplastic. Villous adenomas are neoplastic epithelial growths with significant malignant potential, but are histologically benign until invasive carcinoma develops. Endometriomas represent ectopic endometrial tissue, which can infiltrate the rectal wall, causing symptoms but remaining benign. Fibromas are benign mesenchymal tumors composed of fibrous connective tissue.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Keratoacanthoma is a rapidly growing, benign epithelial tumor primarily found on sun-exposed skin, such as the face, hands, and arms, and is not a lesion typically found in the rectum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lesion Type | Nature | Malignant Potential | Common Presentation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pseudopolyp | Inflammatory (non-neoplastic) | None | Mucosal tags, often with IBD |\n| Villous Adenoma | Neoplastic (epithelial) | High (pre-malignant) | Velvety, broad-based, often large polyp |\n| Endometrioma | Ectopic tissue | None | Submucosal nodule, often with pelvic pain |\n| Fibroma | Neoplastic (mesenchymal) | None | Firm, well-circumscribed submucosal mass |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Benign rectal lesions are diverse: inflammatory, neoplastic, or ectopic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, pseudopolyps appear as irregular, often multiple, inflamed mucosal projections. Villous adenomas typically present as broad-based, velvety, friable, and often large polyps. An endometrioma may appear as a bluish or purplish submucosal nodule, sometimes with surrounding fibrosis. A fibroma would likely be seen as a firm, well-circumscribed submucosal mass, often covered by normal-appearing mucosa.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guidelines 2020: Recommendations for the management of colorectal polyps. These guidelines provide detailed recommendations for surveillance and management of various types of colorectal polyps, including adenomas, based on their malignant potential.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | keratoacanthoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pseudopolyps. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | villous adenoma. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | endometrioma. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | fibroma. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, D, E) pseudopolyps.\nvillous adenoma.\nendometrioma.\nfibroma.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
