  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Blackcurrant lump, acute pain, external thrombosed gain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct. A thrombosed external haemorrhoid presents as a sudden, painful perianal lump, and its characteristic appearance, due to clotted blood beneath the anoderm, is often described as a purplish-blue, firm nodule, much like a semi-ripe blackcurrant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExternal haemorrhoids arise from the inferior haemorrhoidal plexus, located distal to the dentate line and covered by anoderm. When a vein in this plexus thromboses, it leads to acute distension and discoloration of the overlying skin. The anoderm is richly innervated by somatic nerves, which accounts for the severe pain associated with this condition. The dark, firm appearance is a direct result of the trapped blood clot, making the 'semi-ripe blackcurrant' analogy highly accurate and clinically descriptive.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Thrombosed external haemorrhoids are typically acutely and severely painful due to the rapid distension of the richly innervated anoderm.\nOption C (Incorrect): This describes a different pathology. A thrombosed external haemorrhoid is a distinct entity arising from the inferior haemorrhoidal plexus, whereas a prolapsed strangulated internal haemorrhoid originates from the superior plexus and is covered by mucosa.\nOption D (Incorrect): While perianal disease is common in Crohn's disease, thrombosed external haemorrhoids are not a specific or defining feature of Crohn's; they are a common condition in the general population.\nOption E (Incorrect): Sclerotherapy with agents like ethanoleate is a treatment for internal haemorrhoids, primarily to fix them to the underlying muscle, not for acutely thrombosed external haemorrhoids. Treatment for the latter often involves conservative management or surgical excision.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Internal Haemorrhoid | External Haemorrhoid | Thrombosed External Haemorrhoid |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Superior haemorrhoidal plexus | Inferior haemorrhoidal plexus | Inferior haemorrhoidal plexus |\n| **Covering** | Mucosa | Anoderm | Anoderm |\n| **Pain** | Usually painless (unless prolapsed/strangulated) | Painless (unless thrombosed) | Acutely painful |\n| **Appearance** | Prolapsing tissue, bright red bleeding | Skin tag, rarely visible unless thrombosed | Firm, purplish-blue lump (blackcurrant-like) |\n| **Innervation** | Visceral (above dentate line) | Somatic (below dentate line) | Somatic (below dentate line) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute anal pain + purple lump = thrombosed external haemorrhoid.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, you would see a firm, exquisitely tender, purplish-blue, ovoid mass at the anal verge, often covered by stretched, edematous anoderm. Incision typically reveals a dark, clotted blood mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). They recommend excision within 72 hours of onset for symptomatic relief of acutely thrombosed external hemorrhoids, otherwise conservative management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | not unlike a semi-ripe blackcurrant in appearance. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | painless. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | a prolapsed strangulated internal haemorrhoid. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | a feature of Crohn’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | best treated by injection of ethanoleate. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) not unlike a semi-ripe blackcurrant in appearance.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
