  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 An itchy bum demands a thorough look, from worms to lumps!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies common causes of pruritus ani, which is a symptom rather than a diagnosis. It highlights that local anorectal conditions, mechanical irritants, and parasitic infections are frequent culprits leading to perianal itching.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPruritus ani often stems from irritation or inflammation of the perianal skin. Piles (hemorrhoids) can cause discharge and moisture, leading to maceration and itching. A polypus, especially if prolapsing or causing incomplete evacuation, can lead to irritation and discharge. Parasites, particularly pinworms (Enterobius vermicularis), directly cause intense perianal itching, especially at night, due to their migratory habits and egg-laying around the anus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Gonorrhoea primarily causes proctitis with symptoms like discharge, pain, and tenesmus, but pruritus ani is not its typical or primary presentation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Entamoeba histolytica causes amoebic dysentery or colitis, leading to abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea. While it's an intestinal parasite, it does not directly cause pruritus ani.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Examples | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anorectal Conditions | Hemorrhoids, Fissures, Fistulas, Polyps | Discharge, irritation, incomplete hygiene |\n| Infections | Pinworms, Fungi (Candida), Bacteria | Direct irritation, inflammatory response |\n| Dermatologic | Eczema, Psoriasis, Contact dermatitis | Skin inflammation, allergic reaction |\n| Systemic | Diabetes, Liver disease, Thyroid disease | Metabolic changes, dry skin, neuropathy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Pruritus ani: Always consider local, infectious, and systemic etiologies.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn anoscopy or colonoscopy, one might visualize internal hemorrhoids, a prolapsing polyp, or signs of proctitis. Microscopic examination of a perianal swab (scotch tape test) is diagnostic for pinworm eggs.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Pruritus Ani (e.g., 2021). Recommends a thorough history, physical examination, and targeted investigations to identify underlying causes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | piles. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | gonorrhoea. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | parasites. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Entamoeba histolytica. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a polypus. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) piles.\nparasites.\na polypus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
