  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a belly ache fool you; sometimes it's just a bloody muscle!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are B, C, and E. Tearing of the inferior epigastric artery, leading to a rectus sheath hematoma, commonly occurs in situations of increased intra-abdominal pressure or sudden muscle contraction, such as in muscular men and pregnant women, and often presents as a palpable mass.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe inferior epigastric artery runs within the rectus sheath. In muscular men, sudden, forceful contraction of the rectus abdominis muscle (e.g., coughing, straining, heavy lifting, exercise) can lead to shearing forces that tear the artery, especially if the muscle is taut. Pregnant women are susceptible due to increased intra-abdominal pressure, stretching and thinning of the abdominal wall muscles, and hormonal changes that can increase vascular fragility. A rectus sheath hematoma typically presents as a painful, palpable mass, often below the umbilicus, but can sometimes be less painful, especially if the bleeding is slow or contained within the sheath.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While elderly individuals can develop rectus sheath hematomas, often due to anticoagulation, 'elderly women' are not specifically predisposed to tearing of the artery due to muscle contraction in the same way as muscular men or pregnant women.\nOption D (Incorrect): The inferior epigastric artery enters the rectus sheath below the arcuate line and ascends. While tearing can occur anywhere along its course within the rectus sheath, 'at the level of the arcuate line' is not a uniquely or predominantly susceptible location for injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Muscular Men | Pregnant Women | Elderly/Anticoagulated |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Cause** | Sudden, forceful rectus muscle contraction (cough, strain, exercise) | Increased intra-abdominal pressure, muscle stretching, vascular fragility | Anticoagulation, minor trauma, muscle strain |\n| **Risk Factors** | Intense physical activity, chronic cough, constipation | Multiparity, late-term pregnancy, pre-eclampsia | Advanced age, polypharmacy, falls, coagulopathies |\n| **Presentation** | Acute abdominal pain, palpable mass, ecchymosis | Acute abdominal pain, palpable mass, uterine irritability | Abdominal pain, palpable mass, often insidious onset |\n| **Location** | Typically below umbilicus, within rectus sheath | Typically below umbilicus, within rectus sheath | Anywhere along rectus sheath, often below umbilicus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rectus sheath hematoma: think muscular men, pregnant women, and anticoagulation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, a rectus sheath hematoma appears as a hyperdense collection within the rectus abdominis muscle or between the muscle and its sheath, often with active extravasation visible in arterial phase. Intraoperatively, a contained hematoma within the rectus sheath will be seen, and the bleeding inferior epigastric artery may need ligation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Emergency Physicians (ACEP) Clinical Policy: Critical Issues in the Evaluation and Management of Adult Patients Presenting to the Emergency Department with Acute Abdominal Pain (2019). Recommends CT imaging for evaluation of acute abdominal pain when rectus sheath hematoma is suspected, especially in patients on anticoagulation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | in elderly women. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | in muscular men. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | in pregnant women. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | at the level of the arcuate line. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | as a painless lump just below the umbilicus. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) in muscular men.\nin pregnant women.\nas a painless lump just below the umbilicus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
