  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Drainage is key; choose your path wisely, internal or external!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that options A, B, C, and E are correct statements regarding renal drainage and stone management. These options accurately describe common and accepted techniques for managing obstructive uropathy and ureteral stones, reflecting current urological practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPercutaneous nephrostomy (PCN) provides direct renal drainage, typically performed in the lateral position for optimal access to the kidney's posterior calyx. Ureteral stents (J-stents) offer internal drainage, placed either retrogradely via cystoscopy or antegrade through a PCN tract, bypassing ureteral obstruction. Dormia baskets are essential tools for endoscopic stone retrieval, particularly effective for lower ureteral calculi, demonstrating the versatility of minimally invasive approaches in urology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Open nephrostomy, while less common than percutaneous, is still indicated in specific complex cases where percutaneous access is difficult or contraindicated, such as severe coagulopathy or failed percutaneous attempts. Therefore, it is not true that it \"need never be performed nowadays.\"\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Approach | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Percutaneous Nephrostomy (PCN) | Upper tract obstruction, temporary drainage | Antegrade, percutaneous | Lateral/prone position, direct renal access |\n| Ureteral Stent (J-stent) | Ureteral obstruction, internal drainage | Retrograde (cystoscopy) or Antegrade (PCN) | Bypasses obstruction, allows urine flow to bladder |\n| Dormia Basket | Ureteral stone retrieval | Retrograde (ureteroscopy/cystoscopy) | Endoscopic tool for stone extraction |\n| Open Nephrostomy | Complex cases, failed PCN, specific surgical needs | Open surgical incision | Direct surgical access to kidney, rarely performed for drainage alone |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know your drainage routes: internal (stent) vs. external (nephrostomy), and their access methods.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn fluoroscopy during PCN, a guidewire is advanced into the renal collecting system, followed by dilators and catheter placement, confirming urine flow. During cystoscopy for J-stent placement, the ureteral orifice is cannulated, and the stent is advanced under fluoroscopic guidance, coiling in the renal pelvis and bladder.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Ureteral Calculi (2023) recommends various approaches for stone management, including endoscopic retrieval and drainage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | percutaneous nephrostomy is carried out with the patient in the lateral pos | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the ureter can be drained by insertion of a J-stent via cystoscopy. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | a J-stent can be inserted via a nephrostomy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | open nephrostomy need never be performed nowadays. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | stones in the lower ureter can be removed with the aid of a Dormia basket. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, E) percutaneous nephrostomy is carried out with the patient in the lateral position.\nthe ureter can be drained by insertion of a J-stent via cystoscopy.\na J-stent can be inserted via a nephrostomy.\nstones in the lower ureter can be removed with the aid of a Dormia basket.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
