  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ADPKD: Cysts everywhere, kidneys fail, transplant awaits.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options accurately describe Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease (ADPKD), the most common form of congenital cystic kidney disease in adults. It is a hereditary condition with systemic manifestations, prone to complications like pyelonephritis, and frequently progresses to end-stage renal disease requiring transplantation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nADPKD is an inherited disorder primarily caused by mutations in the PKD1 or PKD2 genes, leading to the development of numerous fluid-filled cysts in both kidneys. This genetic basis explains its hereditary nature. The disease is systemic, often involving other organs such as the liver (cysts), pancreas, and lungs, and is associated with intracranial aneurysms. The complex cyst architecture and impaired urinary flow predispose patients to recurrent infections like pyelonephritis, hemorrhage, and pain. Ultimately, progressive cyst enlargement and renal parenchymal destruction lead to chronic kidney disease and end-stage renal disease, making renal transplantation a common and necessary intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Congenital cystic kidney diseases, particularly ADPKD, are characteristically bilateral, affecting both kidneys. Unilateral involvement is more typical of conditions like multicystic dysplastic kidney (MCDK), which has a different pathophysiology and prognosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease (ADPKD) | Autosomal Recessive Polycystic Kidney Disease (ARPKD) | Multicystic Dysplastic Kidney (MCDK) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Inheritance | Autosomal Dominant (PKD1/PKD2) | Autosomal Recessive (PKHD1) | Sporadic |\n| Presentation | Adults (often 30s-40s), hypertension, pain, hematuria | Neonates/Infants, severe renal failure, pulmonary hypoplasia | Usually detected prenatally, often asymptomatic |\n| Kidney Involvement | Bilateral, numerous large cysts, progressive enlargement | Bilateral, small cysts, dilated collecting ducts, enlarged kidneys | Unilateral, non-functional kidney replaced by multiple cysts |\n| Extra-renal | Liver cysts, intracranial aneurysms, pancreatic cysts | Congenital hepatic fibrosis, portal hypertension | None |\n| Prognosis | Progressive ESRD, requires dialysis/transplant | High neonatal mortality, survivors require transplant | Often involutes, contralateral kidney compensates |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ADPKD is bilateral, systemic, and a common path to ESRD.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, kidneys appear markedly enlarged and replaced by innumerable, variably sized, anechoic or fluid-filled cysts, often distorting the normal renal architecture. Liver cysts are also frequently seen. Intraoperatively, the kidneys are massively enlarged, nodular, and feel like a \"bag of grapes.\"\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO (Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Evaluation and Management of Polycystic Kidney Disease (2014). It recommends screening for intracranial aneurysms in high-risk patients and managing hypertension aggressively.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a hereditary disease transmitted by either parent. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | recognised to be associated with similar disease in the pancreas and lung. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | usually unilateral. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | commonly complicated by pyelonephritis. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | a likely indication for renal transplantation. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D, E) a hereditary disease transmitted by either parent.\nrecognised to be associated with similar disease in the pancreas and lung.\ncommonly complicated by pyelonephritis.\na likely indication for renal transplantation.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
