  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be sour, keep your urine pH in check for stone prevention!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers are calcium oxalate and urates. These stone types are well-known to precipitate and form in an acidic urinary environment, making them the primary constituents of calculi found under such conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalcium oxalate stones, the most common type, can form across a range of pH but are particularly prone to precipitation in acidic urine due to decreased solubility of calcium salts. Urate (uric acid) stones are almost exclusively formed in acidic urine (pH < 5.5) because uric acid is poorly soluble in acidic conditions, leading to supersaturation and crystallization. This understanding is crucial for both medical management and dietary recommendations aimed at altering urinary pH.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Triple phosphate (struvite) stones form in alkaline urine, typically due to urease-producing bacterial infections that raise urinary pH.\nOption D (Incorrect): Citrate is a natural inhibitor of stone formation, not a stone component. Low urinary citrate levels, often associated with acidic urine, *promote* stone formation, but citrate itself does not form calculi.\nOption E (Incorrect): Bilirubin stones are primarily found in the gallbladder as gallstones, not in the urinary tract as kidney stones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Typical pH | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Calcium Oxalate | Acidic to Neutral | Most common, radiopaque, often jagged |\n| Uric Acid (Urats) | Acidic (<5.5) | Radiolucent (pure), often associated with gout/high purine diet |\n| Struvite (Triple Phosphate) | Alkaline (>7.0) | Associated with UTI (urease-producing bacteria), staghorn calculi, radiopaque |\n| Cystine | Acidic | Genetic defect (cystinuria), hexagonal crystals, mildly radiopaque |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acidic urine favors uric acid and calcium oxalate stones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, calcium oxalate stones are highly radiopaque, appearing bright white. Uric acid stones are typically radiolucent on plain X-ray but are visible on CT. Intraoperatively, calcium oxalate stones are often dark and hard, while uric acid stones can be yellowish-brown and friable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline for the Medical Management of Kidney Stones (2019) recommends urine pH modification as a key strategy for preventing recurrent stone formation, particularly for uric acid stones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | calcium oxalate. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | triple phosphate. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | urates. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | citrates. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | bilirubin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) calcium oxalate.\nurates.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
