  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hexagonal cystine: a genetic stone, not a calcium clone.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key characteristics of cystine calculi, which are a distinct type of kidney stone. These stones are directly linked to a specific genetic metabolic disorder, exhibit unique crystal morphology, and possess particular physical properties, all of which are accurately described by options A, B, C, and E.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCystine calculi arise from cystinuria, an autosomal recessive inborn error of metabolism affecting the renal tubular and intestinal transport of dibasic amino acids (cystine, ornithine, lysine, arginine). Due to impaired reabsorption, cystine accumulates in the urine, and its low solubility, especially in acidic conditions, leads to precipitation and stone formation. The characteristic hexagonal shape of cystine crystals on urinalysis is pathognomonic, and the stones themselves are often described as soft and waxy, resembling beeswax.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Cystine stones are indeed mildly radio-opaque, often described as having a 'ground glass' appearance on X-ray, but this opacity is due to the sulfur content of cystine, not calcium. They are significantly less opaque than calcium-containing stones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Composition | Radio-opacity (X-ray) | Crystal Shape | Associated Condition/Cause |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Cystine** | Cystine | Mildly opaque ('ground glass') | Hexagonal | Cystinuria (inborn error of metabolism) |\n| Calcium Oxalate | Calcium oxalate monohydrate/dihydrate | Highly opaque | Envelope (dihydrate), Dumbbell (monohydrate) | Hypercalciuria, hyperoxaluria, malabsorption |\n| Struvite | Magnesium ammonium phosphate | Moderately opaque | Coffin-lid | Chronic UTIs with urea-splitting bacteria (e.g., Proteus) |\n| Uric Acid | Uric acid | Radiolucent (invisible) | Rhomboid, barrel | Gout, hyperuricemia, acidic urine |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cystine stones are hexagonal, soft, genetic, and mildly radio-opaque.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain film X-ray, cystine stones appear as faintly radio-opaque, often described as 'ground glass.' On CT, they are typically visible. Urinalysis reveals characteristic hexagonal crystals. Intraoperatively, they are often yellowish, soft, and waxy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Medical Management of Kidney Stones (2014, amended 2019) recommends high fluid intake, urinary alkalinization (target pH 7.0-7.5), and in refractory cases, thiol-binding agents (e.g., tiopronin, D-penicillamine) for cystine stone prevention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are likely to appear in the urinary tract of patients with cystinuria. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | are due to an inborn error of metabolism. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | contain crystals that are hexagonal. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | are radio-opaque owing to the calcium they contain. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | are soft, like beeswax. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, E) are likely to appear in the urinary tract of patients with cystinuria.\nare due to an inborn error of metabolism.\ncontain crystals that are hexagonal.\nare soft, like beeswax.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
