  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Plain films can deceive; when in doubt, get a CT.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies common radiopaque structures that can be found in the abdominal or pelvic region and thus be mistaken for a renal or ureteral calculus on plain film X-ray. Differentiating these mimics from true stones is crucial for accurate diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe principle behind these correct answers lies in their inherent radiopacity and anatomical location. Phleboliths are calcified venous thrombi, frequently found in pelvic veins, and often exhibit a characteristic lucent center. Calcified lymph nodes, particularly in the retroperitoneum or pelvis, can appear as irregular radiopacities. Fersolate (iron) tablets are highly radiopaque due to their iron content and, if ingested or retained, can be visible on X-ray, potentially in the vicinity of the urinary tract.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Pure cholesterol gallstones are typically radiolucent and therefore not visible on plain X-ray. Only gallstones with significant calcium content (mixed or pigmented) are radiopaque.\nOption E (Incorrect): Tietze’s disease is an inflammatory condition affecting the costochondral junctions of the chest wall, characterized by pain and swelling. It does not involve calcifications that would simulate a renal calculus on an abdominal X-ray.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Mimic | Description | Typical Location | Differentiating Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Phlebolith | Calcified venous thrombus | Pelvic veins | Often has a lucent center, outside urinary tract on CT |\n| Calcified Lymph Node | Calcified lymphatic tissue | Retroperitoneum, pelvis | Irregular shape, often outside urinary tract on CT |\n| Pure Cholesterol Gallstone | Gallstone without calcium | Gallbladder | Radiolucent on plain X-ray, visible on ultrasound |\n| Renal Calculus | Calcified stone in urinary tract | Kidney, ureter, bladder | Within urinary tract lumen on CT, often causes hydronephrosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Not all radiopacities near the kidney are stones; consider mimics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain film, phleboliths often have a target-like appearance with a lucent center. On CT, phleboliths can be differentiated from ureteral stones by tracing the ureter and noting the phlebolith's location outside the ureteral lumen, often within a pelvic vein. Calcified lymph nodes are typically irregular and also outside the urinary tract. Pure cholesterol gallstones are best visualized on ultrasound.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on the Management of Ureteral Calculi (2023) recommend CT scan as the primary imaging modality for diagnosis of urolithiasis to differentiate from mimics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | phleboliths. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | calcified lymph nodes. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | pure cholesterol gallstones. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | fersolate tablets. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Tietze’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) phleboliths.\ncalcified lymph nodes.\nfersolate tablets.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
