  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just sit there; move it or lose it... your kidneys!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Paraplegia is a well-recognized risk factor for urinary stone formation due to a combination of factors including prolonged immobility, bone demineralization, and urinary stasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nImmobility in paraplegic patients leads to increased bone resorption and subsequent hypercalciuria, a primary driver for calcium stone formation. Furthermore, neurogenic bladder dysfunction often results in urinary stasis, incomplete bladder emptying, and a higher incidence of recurrent urinary tract infections, which can contribute to struvite (infection) stone formation. The combination of increased calcium load and altered urinary dynamics significantly elevates the risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Myasthenia gravis is an autoimmune neuromuscular disorder and has no direct association with urinary stone formation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hypercholesterolemia is a risk factor for cardiovascular disease and gallstones, not typically urinary stones.\nOption D (Incorrect): Primary aldosteronism causes hypertension and hypokalemia but is not directly associated with increased urinary stone risk. Primary hyperparathyroidism, however, is a strong risk factor.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hypoparathyroidism leads to hypocalcemia and hyperphosphatemia, which would decrease the risk of calcium-containing urinary stones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Mechanism of Stone Formation | Stone Type Often Associated |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paraplegia | Immobility, hypercalciuria, urinary stasis, infection | Calcium, Struvite |\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Hypercalcemia, hypercalciuria | Calcium oxalate/phosphate |\n| Renal Tubular Acidosis | Distal RTA: hypocitraturia, alkaline urine, hypercalciuria | Calcium phosphate |\n| Crohn's Disease | Enteric hyperoxaluria (fat malabsorption) | Calcium oxalate |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Immobility + Hypercalciuria + Stasis = Stones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn KUB or CT, one might see multiple, often large, staghorn calculi filling the renal collecting system, particularly in patients with chronic neurogenic bladder and recurrent UTIs.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Medical Management of Kidney Stones (2019) recommends metabolic evaluation for recurrent stone formers, including those with predisposing conditions like immobility.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | paraplegia. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | myasthenia gravis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | hypercholesteraemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | primary aldosteronism. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | hypoparathyroidism. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) paraplegia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
