  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stone + infection = surgical emergency.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nUreteric calculi are a common cause of acute flank pain and represent a significant urological challenge. The correct options highlight critical aspects of their clinical presentation and management, emphasizing both symptomatic relief and urgent intervention when necessary.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUreteric calculi cause severe, colicky pain (renal colic) due to obstruction and distension of the collecting system, often accompanied by ureteral spasm. NSAIDs are the first-line treatment for renal colic as they reduce prostaglandin-mediated inflammation and ureteral smooth muscle contraction, providing effective pain relief. Stones located in the distal ureter can irritate the bladder, leading to irritative voiding symptoms such as strangury. Crucially, an obstructing ureteric calculus in the presence of infected urine is a urological emergency requiring prompt drainage and often stone removal to prevent sepsis and preserve renal function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While many small stones pass spontaneously, expectant management is not universal. Larger stones, those causing significant obstruction, intractable pain, or infection require active intervention.\nOption D (Incorrect): Renal colic is notoriously severe, often considered one of the most excruciating pains a human can experience, frequently surpassing the pain associated with appendicitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ureteric Calculus | Appendicitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain Character | Colicky, severe, radiating to groin/genitalia | Periumbilical, then localized to RLQ, constant |\n| Associated Symptoms | Hematuria, dysuria, nausea/vomiting | Nausea/vomiting, anorexia, fever |\n| First-line Pain Tx | NSAIDs | Opioids (after diagnosis) |\n| Emergency Indication | Obstructing stone with infection | Perforation, peritonitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Obstructing stone + infection = urological emergency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT KUB, a hyperdense calculus is typically seen within the ureter, often with associated hydronephrosis and perinephric stranding. Intraoperatively, a ureteroscope can visualize the stone, allowing for fragmentation (lithotripsy) or basket extraction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline for the Management of Ureteral Calculi (2023). It recommends NSAIDs as first-line for acute renal colic and urgent decompression for obstructing stones with infection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | can Cause strangury. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is normally treated expectantly. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | causing colic is treated with NSAIDs. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | usually causes less pain than appendicitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | should be removed if the urine is infected. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) can Cause strangury.\ncausing colic is treated with NSAIDs.\nshould be removed if the urine is infected.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
