  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Straddle injury? Think suprapubic, not blind catheter.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key signs and appropriate surgical management principles for a ruptured bulbous urethra. The correct options highlight the immediate clinical presentation and crucial steps in definitive repair and wound care.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRupture of the bulbous urethra, often from a straddle injury, typically presents with urinary retention due to obstruction and pain, along with blood at the meatus and a perineal hematoma (butterfly hematoma). Primary repair by sutures is the gold standard for clean, sharp transections or partial tears to restore urethral continuity and prevent stricture. Furthermore, perineal wounds in this context, especially if contaminated by urine extravasation or hematoma, are best managed by packing rather than primary closure to allow for drainage, reduce infection risk, and facilitate secondary healing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Encouraging the patient to pass urine is contraindicated as it can lead to further extravasation of urine and blood into the perineal tissues, worsening contamination and hematoma formation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Blind catheterization on the spot is absolutely contraindicated in suspected urethral injury. It can convert a partial tear into a complete one, create a false passage, or introduce infection, significantly increasing morbidity. A suprapubic catheter is the appropriate initial urinary diversion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Bulbous Urethral Rupture Management |\n|---|---|\n| **Key Signs** | Urinary retention, blood at meatus, perineal hematoma |\n| **Initial Diversion** | Suprapubic catheter (never blind urethral catheter) |\n| **Surgical Repair** | Primary end-to-end anastomosis (if feasible) |\n| **Wound Management** | Perineal packing, delayed closure (not primary stitching) |\n| **Contraindications** | Encouraging voiding, blind urethral catheterization |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Never blind catheterize a suspected urethral injury; always consider suprapubic diversion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA retrograde urethrogram (RUG) is crucial for diagnosis, showing extravasation of contrast. Intraoperatively, the torn ends of the urethra are identified, debrided, and primarily anastomosed. The perineal wound may show significant hematoma and urine extravasation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urethral Trauma (2020) recommends immediate urinary diversion, preferably via suprapubic catheter, and primary repair for most bulbous urethral injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | retention of urine is one of the signs. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | the patient should be encouraged to pass urine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | if he cannot pass urine the patient should be catheterised on the spot. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | the urethra should be completely repaired by sutures. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | the perineal wound, if an operation is performed, is packed not stitched. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) retention of urine is one of the signs.\nthe urethra should be completely repaired by sutures.\nthe perineal wound, if an operation is performed, is packed not stitched.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
