  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Decompress first, diagnose next, definitive last. No 'always' in acute retention!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that all provided options are incorrect. The management of acute urinary retention requires immediate decompression, but the subsequent steps and methods are nuanced and not accurately reflected in any single option.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute urinary retention is a urological emergency requiring prompt decompression of the bladder to prevent renal damage, relieve pain, and reduce the risk of infection. The primary goal is to restore urine flow, typically via urethral catheterization. If urethral access is impossible or contraindicated, suprapubic cystostomy is the next appropriate step. Subsequent management involves identifying and treating the underlying cause, which may range from benign prostatic hyperplasia to neurological conditions or urethral strictures. Definitive treatment, such as prostatectomy, is rarely an immediate intervention for the acute episode itself.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Relief by catheterization is almost always necessary, but the term 'catheterisation' broadly refers to drainage. While urethral catheterization is first-line, suprapubic cystostomy is an alternative when urethral access fails or is contraindicated, so 'always' being urethral catheterization is too absolute.\nOption B (Incorrect): Admission to hospital after relief is not always necessary. Many patients can be safely discharged with an indwelling catheter and outpatient follow-up, especially if the cause is clear and no immediate complications are present.\nOption C (Incorrect): Self-retainment of a catheter is achieved by the balloon of a Foley catheter. A Fogarty catheter is a balloon-tipped catheter primarily used in vascular surgery for embolectomy or occlusion, not for indwelling urinary drainage.\nOption D (Incorrect): Suprapubic puncture (cystostomy) is not contraindicated; it is a vital alternative when urethral catheterization is unsuccessful, impossible, or contraindicated (e.g., severe urethral trauma, stricture, or infection).\nOption E (Incorrect): Immediate prostatectomy is not performed for acute urinary retention. The immediate management is bladder decompression. Prostatectomy is an elective surgical procedure to treat the underlying cause (e.g., BPH) after the acute episode has been managed and the patient has been stabilized and optimized.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drainage Method | Indication | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Urethral Catheterization | First-line for acute retention | Most common, least invasive initial approach |\n| Suprapubic Cystostomy | Failed urethral catheterization, urethral trauma/stricture, long-term drainage | Percutaneous bladder access, avoids urethra |\n| Intermittent Catheterization | Neurogenic bladder, post-op, patient preference | Patient-controlled, reduces infection risk vs. indwelling |\n| Alpha-blockers (e.g., Tamsulosin) | Medical management of BPH | Relaxes smooth muscle in prostate/bladder neck, improves flow |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute retention demands immediate drainage; definitive treatment is rarely acute.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a distended, anechoic bladder with a thin wall is characteristic of acute retention. Post-void residual volume is key.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (2021). Recommends immediate bladder decompression for acute urinary retention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | relief by catheterisation is always necessary. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | admission to hospital after relief is always necessary. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | self-retainment of a catheter is by the use of the Fogarty type. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | suprapubic puncture is contraindicated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | immediate prostatectomy can be performed in cases of enlarged prostate. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: NONE) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
