  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Oxalate stones: the dark, dense majority, not the smooth, white minority.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question is flawed as none of the provided options accurately describe oxalate calculi. Calcium oxalate stones are the most common type of kidney stone, known for their radiopacity and formation in acidic to neutral urine.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalcium oxalate stones, comprising both monohydrate (COM) and dihydrate (COD) forms, account for approximately 75-80% of all renal calculi. COM stones are typically hard, dark brown to black, and can be smooth or irregular, while COD stones are often spiculated and lighter brown. A key characteristic is their high radiopacity due to their calcium content, making them easily visible on plain radiographs and CT scans. They typically form in urine with a pH range of 5.5-6.8, not alkaline urine.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"grow rapidly.\" While oxalate stones can grow, \"rapidly\" is more characteristic of struvite stones, which can form large staghorn calculi quickly.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"have a smooth, rounded surface.\" Calcium oxalate dihydrate stones are often spiculated, and many calcium oxalate monohydrate stones are irregular, not universally smooth and rounded.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"are primarily white in colour.\" Oxalate stones are typically dark brown to black. White stones are more characteristic of calcium phosphate or struvite calculi.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"form in an alkaline urine.\" Calcium oxalate stones typically form in acidic to neutral urine (pH 5.5-6.8). Alkaline urine promotes the formation of struvite and calcium phosphate stones.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"are radiolucent.\" Calcium oxalate stones are highly radiopaque due to their calcium content, making them easily visible on X-rays and CT scans. Radiolucent stones are typically uric acid or xanthine.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Radiopacity | Typical pH | Appearance | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Calcium Oxalate | Highly Radiopaque | Acidic-Neutral (5.5-6.8) | Dark brown/black, irregular/spiculated | Most common type |\n| Struvite (MgNH4PO4) | Moderately Radiopaque | Alkaline (>7.0) | White/grey, friable, often staghorn | Infection-related |\n| Uric Acid | Radiolucent | Acidic (<5.5) | Yellow/orange, smooth | Associated with gout/high purine diet |\n| Calcium Phosphate | Moderately Radiopaque | Alkaline (>7.0) | White/grey, amorphous | Less common, often mixed |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Oxalate stones: dark, dense, common, radiopaque, acidic urine.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain X-ray or CT, oxalate stones appear as dense, bright white opacities. Intraoperatively, they are typically dark brown to black, hard, and can have irregular or spiculated surfaces.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines for the Management of Kidney Stones (2024) recommend metabolic evaluation for recurrent stone formers and emphasize prevention strategies tailored to stone composition.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | grow rapidly. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | have a smooth, rounded surface. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | are primarily white in colour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | form in an alkaline urine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | are radiolucent. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: NONE) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
