  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Diverticula: silent pouches, loud complications if ignored.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately describes key characteristics of bladder diverticula: their histological lining, potential for asymptomatic presentation, and common diagnostic imaging. This demonstrates a solid understanding of their pathology and clinical assessment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBladder diverticula are outpouchings of the bladder wall. True diverticula, whether congenital or acquired (pulsion), are indeed lined by bladder mucosa, often with submucosa and sometimes muscle. Many small diverticula can remain asymptomatic, discovered incidentally during imaging for other reasons. Ultrasound is a highly effective, non-invasive, and readily available imaging modality for visualizing bladder anatomy, including the presence and characteristics of diverticula, by identifying an anechoic or hypoechoic outpouching from the bladder wall.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Most bladder diverticula, particularly in adults, are acquired (pulsion diverticula) due to increased intravesical pressure from bladder outlet obstruction, not usually congenital. Congenital diverticula are less common.\nOption D (Incorrect): While the full extent of a diverticulum might be outside the bladder, the opening (neck) of a bladder diverticulum into the bladder lumen is typically identifiable during cystoscopy, making its presence obvious.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | True Diverticulum | Pseudodiverticulum (Pulsion) |\n| :------------------ | :---------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Lining** | All bladder layers (mucosa, submucosa, muscle) | Mucosa and submucosa only (herniates through muscle) |\n| **Etiology** | Congenital (rare) | Acquired (most common, due to outlet obstruction) |\n| **Contractility** | May contract (contains muscle) | Does not contract (lacks muscle) |\n| **Clinical Impact** | Less common, but can cause stasis/infection | More common, associated with stasis, infection, stones, malignancy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bladder diverticula are usually acquired, lined by mucosa, and often silent.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a bladder diverticulum appears as an anechoic or hypoechoic outpouching connected to the bladder lumen, often with a narrow neck. During cystoscopy, the ostium (opening) of the diverticulum into the bladder is typically visible, and a catheter can sometimes be passed into it.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (2018). Recommends evaluating for bladder diverticula in patients with BPH symptoms, as they can indicate chronic outlet obstruction and contribute to complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is usually congenital in origin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is lined by bladder mucosa. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can be symptomless. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is not always obvious on cystoscopy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | can be demonstrated by ultrasound. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) is lined by bladder mucosa.\ncan be symptomless.\ncan be demonstrated by ultrasound.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
