  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hunner's: The painful, linear lesion that's all about inflammation, not cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers are B and D. Hunner's ulcer is a distinct subtype of interstitial cystitis/bladder pain syndrome, characterized by a specific appearance on cystoscopy and a characteristic histological profile of chronic inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHunner's ulcer is a classic finding in a subset of patients with interstitial cystitis. Grossly, these lesions are typically linear, reddened, and friable, often bleeding upon hydrodistension or biopsy. Histologically, they demonstrate chronic inflammation with significant lymphocytic and mast cell infiltration, granulation tissue, and often denuded urothelium. This inflammatory process contributes to the characteristic pain and bleeding associated with the condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hunner's ulcer, like interstitial cystitis, predominantly affects women, not men. \nOption C (Incorrect): Hunner's ulcer and interstitial cystitis typically lead to a stiff, contracted, and often small-capacity bladder due to chronic inflammation and fibrosis, not a flaccid bladder. \nOption E (Incorrect): Hunner's ulcer is an inflammatory condition and is not considered premalignant; it does not increase the risk of bladder cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hunner's Ulcer | Non-Hunner's IC/BPS | Bladder Cancer (Urothelial Carcinoma) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appearance (Cystoscopy) | Linear, friable, bleeding lesion; often with glomerulations | Glomerulations (petechial hemorrhages) after hydrodistension; no distinct ulcer | Papillary or sessile mass; often with necrosis or ulceration |\n| Histology | Chronic inflammation, mast cells, lymphocytic infiltration, granulation tissue | Mast cell infiltration, edema, fibrosis; no distinct ulcer | Malignant urothelial cells, invasion |\n| Gender Predominance | Predominantly female | Predominantly female | Predominantly male |\n| Malignant Potential | None | None | High (if untreated or advanced) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hunner's: linear, bleeding, lymphocytic, female, no cancer risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cystoscopy, after hydrodistension, Hunner's ulcers appear as reddened, friable, often linear lesions that bleed upon distension or biopsy, frequently associated with glomerulations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Interstitial Cystitis/Bladder Pain Syndrome (2022). The AUA guideline recommends cystoscopy with hydrodistension and biopsy for diagnosis and classification of Hunner's lesions, distinguishing them from non-Hunner's IC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is a male complaint. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is characteristically a linear bleeding ulcer. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | results in a flaccid bladder. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | is associated with lymphocytic infiltration. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | is premalignant. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D) is characteristically a linear bleeding ulcer.\nis associated with lymphocytic infiltration.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
