  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bladder malignancy: Ulcer, salt, and friends, not just one!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options C, D, and E accurately describe characteristic features of malignant villous tumours of the bladder. Malignant lesions are prone to ulceration and secondary encrustation, and multifocality is a strong indicator of malignancy in bladder tumours.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant villous tumours, particularly high-grade urothelial carcinomas, often exhibit aggressive growth patterns leading to mucosal ulceration due to rapid cell turnover and invasion. This ulceration can expose the underlying stroma to urine, promoting the deposition of urinary salts and encrustation. The presence of multiple synchronous or metachronous tumours in the bladder is a well-recognized feature of urothelial carcinoma, reflecting the field effect or intraluminal seeding, and is a significant indicator of malignancy and recurrence risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While villous tumours have elongated villi, this description is more characteristic of benign villous adenomas or low-grade papillary urothelial carcinomas, not specifically malignant features. Malignant villi might be irregular but not necessarily \"like a sea anemone\" as a defining malignant feature.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pedunculated growth is common in both benign and low-grade malignant papillary lesions. Malignant tumours, especially high-grade ones, are often sessile or broad-based, indicating deeper invasion, rather than pedunculated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Villous Adenoma | Low-Grade Papillary Urothelial Carcinoma | High-Grade Papillary Urothelial Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Growth Pattern | Often pedunculated, delicate villi | Pedunculated, orderly villi | Sessile or broad-based, irregular/fused villi |\n| Ulceration | Rare | Rare | Common |\n| Encrustation | Rare | Rare | Common |\n| Multifocality | Less common | Common | Common |\n| Invasion | Absent | Superficial lamina propria | Deep lamina propria or muscularis propria |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ulceration, encrustation, and multifocality scream malignancy in bladder lesions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cystoscopy, malignant villous tumours may appear as irregular, friable, often broad-based lesions with areas of necrosis or white encrustation. Ulceration might be visible as a break in the mucosal surface. Imaging (CT Urogram/MRI) might show a mass with irregular enhancement, potentially with associated wall thickening or hydronephrosis if invasive.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAUA/SUO Guideline on Non-Muscle Invasive Bladder Cancer (2023). It recommends cystoscopy with biopsy/TURBT for diagnosis and staging, emphasizing the importance of multifocality in treatment planning and surveillance.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the villi are elongated like a sea anemone. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | the growth tends to be predunculated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the growth may ulcerate. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | the growth may become encrusted with urinary salts. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | if two tumours are present it is a sure sign of malignancy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D, E) the growth may ulcerate.\nthe growth may become encrusted with urinary salts.\nif two tumours are present it is a sure sign of malignancy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
