  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Prostatectomy: A delicate balance between relief and regret.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options (A, C, D, E) represent well-known and specific complications associated with prostatectomy procedures, whether for benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) or prostate cancer. These complications arise from the anatomical alterations, surgical technique, or physiological responses to the intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWater intoxication, or TURP syndrome, results from the absorption of hypotonic irrigation fluid (e.g., glycine) through open prostatic venous sinuses during transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP), leading to dilutional hyponatremia, cerebral edema, and cardiovascular compromise. Bladder neck contracture is a fibrotic narrowing at the bladder neck, often a consequence of ischemia, infection, or excessive electrocautery during the procedure. Retrograde ejaculation occurs due to the disruption of the internal urethral sphincter mechanism, allowing semen to enter the bladder during orgasm. Urethral stricture is scarring within the urethra, commonly caused by instrumentation trauma, prolonged catheterization, or thermal injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Bacteremia is a potential risk with any surgical procedure, particularly those involving the urinary tract, and is typically mitigated by prophylactic antibiotics. However, it is not considered a specific or unique complication of prostatectomy in the same manner as the other listed options, which are direct anatomical or physiological sequelae of the prostatectomy itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Timing | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Water Intoxication (TURP Syndrome) | Absorption of hypotonic irrigation fluid (e.g., glycine) | Intraoperative/Early Post-op | Fluid restriction, diuretics, hypertonic saline, ICU support |\n| Bladder Neck Contracture | Fibrosis at bladder neck (ischemia, infection, cautery) | Late Post-op (weeks-months) | Endoscopic incision/resection, dilation |\n| Retrograde Ejaculation | Disruption of internal urethral sphincter | Immediate/Late Post-op | Patient counseling, fertility options |\n| Urethral Stricture | Urethral trauma, prolonged catheterization, thermal injury | Late Post-op (weeks-months) | Dilation, internal urethrotomy, urethroplasty |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prostatectomy complications: Think fluid, flow, and function.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring cystoscopy, a bladder neck contracture appears as a tight, fibrotic ring at the bladder outlet, while a urethral stricture is visualized as a focal or diffuse narrowing of the urethral lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAUA Guideline on the Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (2021): This guideline details the potential complications of surgical therapies for BPH, including bladder neck contracture, retrograde ejaculation, and urethral stricture.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | water intoxication. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | bacteriaemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | bladder neck contracture. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | retrograde ejaculation. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | urethral stricture. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D, E) water intoxication.\nbladder neck contracture.\nretrograde ejaculation.\nurethral stricture.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
