  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stage it right, treat it tight: Prostate cancer demands precision.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that treatment for prostate carcinoma is highly stage-dependent, with early-stage disease amenable to curative radical therapies, while advanced or symptomatic disease requires palliative or systemic approaches. It highlights the diverse modalities available, from local ablative treatments to hormonal manipulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadical radiotherapy is a well-established curative option for localized prostate cancer (T1/T2), aiming to eradicate the tumor while preserving organ function. A Transurethral Resection of the Prostate (TURP) is a crucial palliative intervention for patients experiencing bladder outlet obstruction (BOO) due to prostate cancer, improving quality of life by relieving symptoms. Aminoglutethimide, by inhibiting adrenal androgen synthesis, serves as a valuable hormonal therapy in advanced prostate cancer, particularly when primary androgen deprivation therapies become insufficient, demonstrating the importance of targeting androgen pathways.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Radical prostatectomy is generally reserved for localized (T1/T2) prostate cancer. T3/T4 tumors involve extracapsular extension or seminal vesicle invasion, making surgery alone less likely to be curative and often requiring multimodal therapy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Radiotherapy, both external beam and brachytherapy, is a cornerstone of prostate cancer treatment, used for curative intent in localized disease and for palliation in advanced or metastatic settings. Therefore, stating it is 'unhelpful' is incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage/Presentation | Treatment Modality | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| T1/T2 Localized Disease | Radical Prostatectomy / Radical Radiotherapy | Curative intent for organ-confined disease |\n| T3/T4 Locally Advanced Disease | Multimodal (e.g., ADT + Radiation) | Address extracapsular extension; surgery in selected T3a |\n| Bladder Outlet Obstruction (BOO) | Transurethral Resection of Prostate (TURP) | Palliative relief of obstructive symptoms |\n| Advanced/Metastatic Disease | Androgen Deprivation Therapy (ADT), Chemotherapy, Aminoglutethimide | Systemic control, hormonal blockade, symptom management |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Prostate cancer treatment is dictated by stage and patient-specific factors.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a T3 tumor might show capsular bulging or invasion into the seminal vesicles. During a TURP, the surgeon resects prostatic tissue obstructing the urethra, creating a clear channel for urine flow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (2024). Recommends risk-stratified treatment approaches, including active surveillance, radical prostatectomy, and radiation therapy for localized disease, and systemic therapies for advanced disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | radical prostatectomy is suitable for T3/T4 (TNM) tumours. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | radical radiotherapy is applicable for T1/T2 tumours. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | general radiotherapy is unhelpful. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | a T.U.R.P. is applicable if there is associated BOO. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | aminoglutethimide is applicable in advanced cases as it inhibits androgens. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D, E) radical radiotherapy is applicable for T1/T2 tumours.\na T.U.R.P. is applicable if there is associated BOO.\naminoglutethimide is applicable in advanced cases as it inhibits androgens.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
