  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chronic prostatitis: a pain in the pelvis, not just the prostate.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, B, C, and E accurately identify key features indicative of chronic prostatitis. These encompass characteristic pain patterns, potential involvement of adjacent structures, specific diagnostic test findings, and direct endoscopic observations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic prostatitis, often presenting as chronic pelvic pain syndrome, is characterized by persistent discomfort that can radiate, such as referred pain down the legs, due to nerve irritation. Inflammation can extend to adjacent structures like the seminal vesicles. The 'three-glass test' is crucial for localization, with threads or leukocytes in the third (post-massage) urine specimen pointing to prostatic involvement. Urethroscopy can visually confirm inflammation, revealing an enlarged, oedematous verumontanum, a key anatomical landmark within the prostatic urethra.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Hematuria obtained by a catheter specimen of urine is not a specific or primary indicator of chronic prostatitis. While inflammation can cause microscopic hematuria, it is more commonly associated with other conditions like urinary tract infections, stones, or malignancy, and a catheter specimen itself can sometimes induce microscopic hematuria, making it less diagnostic for prostatitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Chronic Prostatitis | Acute Prostatitis | Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) | Prostatic Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Pain | Chronic pelvic pain, referred pain (e.g., down legs) | Acute, severe perineal/suprapubic pain | Lower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS), no significant pain | Often asymptomatic, bone pain with metastases |\n| Fever | Absent or low-grade | High fever, chills, malaise | Absent | Absent |\n| Urinalysis | Pyuria, bacteriuria (if bacterial) in EPS/VB3 | Pyuria, bacteriuria | Normal or microscopic hematuria | Normal or microscopic hematuria |\n| DRE | Tender, boggy, or normal | Exquisitely tender, warm, swollen | Smooth, enlarged | Nodular, firm, asymmetric |\n| Verumontanum | Enlarged, oedematous (urethroscopy) | Not typically assessed acutely | Normal | Normal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic prostatitis is a chronic pain syndrome with specific localization findings.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUrethroscopy would reveal an enlarged, hyperemic, and oedematous verumontanum, often with inflamed prostatic ducts or diffuse erythema of the prostatic urethra.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Chronic Prostatitis/Chronic Pelvic Pain Syndrome (2014) recommends a comprehensive history, physical exam, and urine studies including post-massage urine analysis for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | referred pain down the legs. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | infected seminal vesicles. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | in the three glass test, prostatitis is present if threads are seen in the  | ✅ Correct |\n| D | haematuria obtained by a catheter specimen of urine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | an enlarged oedematous verumontanum revealed by urethroscopy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, E) referred pain down the legs.\ninfected seminal vesicles.\nin the three glass test, prostatitis is present if threads are seen in the last glass.\nan enlarged oedematous verumontanum revealed by urethroscopy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
