  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let gonorrhea go unnoticed; it's a systemic spreader!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are B and C. Gonorrhoea, caused by *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, is a sexually transmitted infection that can disseminate to cause acute suppurative arthritis and can infect various mucosal surfaces, including the anus and rectum, due to direct inoculation during sexual activity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\n*Neisseria gonorrhoeae* is a highly adaptable bacterium that primarily infects columnar epithelial cells. While commonly associated with genitourinary infections, it can spread hematogenously, particularly in disseminated gonococcal infection (DGI), leading to septic arthritis, tenosynovitis, and dermatitis. The rectum, pharynx, and conjunctiva are common extragenital sites of infection due to direct inoculation during sexual contact, as these areas also contain susceptible columnar or transitional epithelium.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* is a gram-negative diplococcus, not gram-positive.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gonorrhea typically infects the urethra in males, not primarily the stratified squamous epithelium of the glans penis.\nOption E (Incorrect): While urethritis can cause dysuria, acute urinary retention is not a characteristic or common presentation of uncomplicated gonorrhoea.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* | *Chlamydia trachomatis* | *Staphylococcus aureus* (Septic Arthritis) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gram Stain | Gram-negative diplococcus | Obligate intracellular bacterium | Gram-positive cocci in clusters |\n| Common Sites | Urethra, cervix, rectum, pharynx, joints | Urethra, cervix, rectum, conjunctiva | Skin, soft tissue, joints, heart valves |\n| Arthritis | Septic arthritis (DGI) | Reactive arthritis (Reiter's syndrome) | Septic arthritis |\n| Treatment | Ceftriaxone + Azithromycin/Doxycycline | Azithromycin or Doxycycline | Varies (e.g., Vancomycin, Nafcillin) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gonorrhea: Gram-negative, disseminated, and loves columnar epithelium.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor septic arthritis, joint aspiration would show purulent fluid with elevated WBCs and potentially gram-negative diplococci on Gram stain. X-rays might show soft tissue swelling and joint effusions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC 2021 STI Treatment Guidelines: The CDC recommends dual therapy for uncomplicated gonococcal infections (e.g., ceftriaxone 500 mg IM single dose plus doxycycline 100 mg orally twice daily for 7 days if chlamydial infection has not been excluded).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is due to a gram-positive diplococcus. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | can cause acute suppurative arthritis. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | can occur in the anus and rectum. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | begins by penetration by the gonococcus of the epithelium of the glans peni | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | characteristically presents as acute retention of urine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) can cause acute suppurative arthritis.\ncan occur in the anus and rectum.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
