  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Reiter's: When your body reacts badly to a bug.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies key clinical manifestations of Reiter's disease, now known as Reactive Arthritis. This condition is characterized by a classic triad of conjunctivitis, arthritis, and urethritis, along with other mucocutaneous findings.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nReactive Arthritis is a seronegative spondyloarthropathy triggered by a preceding infection, most commonly genitourinary (e.g., Chlamydia trachomatis) or gastrointestinal (e.g., Salmonella, Shigella). The hallmark triad is urethritis, conjunctivitis, and arthritis ('Can't pee, can't see, can't climb a tree'). Acute hydrarthrosis, or joint effusion, is a direct manifestation of the inflammatory arthritis. Keratoderma blennorrhagicum, a psoriaform skin lesion often affecting the palms and soles (including the heel), is a characteristic mucocutaneous finding, along with circinate balanitis and oral ulcers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): A urethral smear revealing streptococci is not characteristic of the pathogens typically associated with Reactive Arthritis, which are primarily Chlamydia or certain enteric bacteria.\nOption E (Incorrect): While urethritis is part of the triad, a urethral smear revealing gonococci indicates gonococcal infection, which can cause septic arthritis but is distinct from the sterile inflammatory arthritis of Reactive Arthritis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Reactive Arthritis (Reiter's) | Gonococcal Arthritis | Psoriatic Arthritis |\n| :------------------ | :---------------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Trigger** | Preceding GU (Chlamydia) or GI (enteric bacteria) infection | Neisseria gonorrhoeae infection | Psoriasis (skin/nail) |\n| **Joints** | Asymmetric oligoarthritis, lower limbs, sacroiliitis | Migratory polyarthralgia, then septic mono/oligoarthritis | Asymmetric oligoarthritis, DIP joints, dactylitis |\n| **Extra-articular** | Urethritis, conjunctivitis, keratoderma blennorrhagicum | Tenosynovitis, dermatitis (pustules) | Psoriatic skin/nail changes, enthesitis, uveitis |\n| **Pathogen** | Sterile joint fluid (no live bacteria) | Septic joint fluid (N. gonorrhoeae present) | Sterile joint fluid |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the classic triad: 'Can't pee, can't see, can't climb a tree'.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (X-ray/MRI) may show sacroiliitis, enthesitis, periostitis, or erosions in chronic cases. Joint aspiration reveals inflammatory, sterile fluid.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) guidelines for spondyloarthritis management (e.g., 2015 ACR/Spondylitis Association of America/Spondyloarthritis Research and Treatment Network recommendations for the treatment of ankylosing spondylitis and nonradiographic axial spondyloarthritis).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | conjunctivitis occurs. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | acute hydrarthrosis is present. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | a urethral smear reveals streptococci. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | keratoderma blenorrhagicum of the heel is a concurrent manifestation. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | a urethral smear reveals gonococci. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) conjunctivitis occurs.\nacute hydrarthrosis is present.\nkeratoderma blenorrhagicum of the heel is a concurrent manifestation.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
