  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gonorrhea: a double threat to women and their newborns.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answers are A and C. Gonorrhea, caused by *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, is a sexually transmitted infection that can directly infect the Bartholin's glands in females, leading to bartholinitis, and can be vertically transmitted during childbirth, causing ophthalmia neonatorum in the newborn.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\n*Neisseria gonorrhoeae* is a gram-negative diplococcus with a predilection for columnar epithelial cells, which are abundant in the endocervix, urethra, and Bartholin's glands. Infection of the Bartholin's glands can lead to inflammation (bartholinitis) or abscess formation, presenting as a painful, unilateral labial mass. During vaginal delivery, an infected mother can transmit the bacteria to the neonate's eyes, resulting in severe purulent conjunctivitis known as ophthalmia neonatorum, which can cause corneal scarring and blindness if not promptly treated. This highlights the direct infectious potential and the significant vertical transmission risk of gonorrhea.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (vulval warts) (Incorrect): Vulval warts are caused by the Human Papillomavirus (HPV), not *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*.\nOption D (ureterocele) (Incorrect): A ureterocele is a congenital anomaly of the ureter, characterized by a cystic dilation of the distal ureter, and is unrelated to infectious processes like gonorrhea.\nOption E (Reiter’s disease) (Incorrect): Reiter's disease, now known as reactive arthritis, is typically triggered by gastrointestinal or genitourinary infections, most commonly *Chlamydia trachomatis*, but *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* is a less common trigger and it is a systemic inflammatory response, not a direct local infection or vertical transmission manifestation in the female.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Etiology | Key Features | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gonococcal Bartholinitis | *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* | Painful, unilateral labial swelling; abscess formation | Incision & drainage (Word catheter), appropriate antibiotics |\n| Ophthalmia Neonatorum | *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* | Purulent conjunctivitis 2-5 days post-birth; corneal ulceration | Topical erythromycin/tetracycline, systemic ceftriaxone |\n| Vulval Warts | Human Papillomavirus (HPV) | Papillomatous, verrucous lesions on vulva | Excision, cryotherapy, topical imiquimod/podofilox |\n| Reactive Arthritis | *Chlamydia*, GI pathogens (e.g., *Salmonella*) | Urethritis, arthritis, conjunctivitis (can't see, can't pee, can't climb a tree) | NSAIDs, DMARDS, antibiotics for underlying infection if present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gonorrhea in females: think Bartholin's gland infection and neonatal eye disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively for a Bartholin's abscess, a fluctuant, tender mass in the posterior labia majora would be incised and drained, often followed by marsupialization or Word catheter placement to prevent recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Sexually Transmitted Infections Treatment Guidelines 2021. Recommends dual therapy (ceftriaxone plus azithromycin or doxycycline) for uncomplicated gonococcal infections and erythromycin ophthalmic ointment for ophthalmia neonatorum prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bartholinitis. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | vulval warts. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ophthalmia neonatorum. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | ureterocele. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Reiter’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) Bartholinitis.\nophthalmia neonatorum.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
