  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HPV: The root of all warts, not just the genital kind!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCondylomata acuminata, commonly known as genital warts, are unequivocally caused by various types of human papillomavirus (HPV). This answer correctly identifies the viral etiology of this common sexually transmitted infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHuman papillomavirus (HPV) is a non-enveloped DNA virus with a predilection for squamous epithelial cells. Specific low-risk HPV types, primarily HPV-6 and HPV-11, are responsible for over 90% of condylomata acuminata. These viruses infect basal epithelial cells through microabrasions, leading to cellular proliferation and the characteristic verrucous, exophytic lesions. The viral DNA integrates into the host cell genome, driving the expression of viral oncoproteins (E6 and E7) that interfere with cell cycle regulation, promoting uncontrolled growth and wart formation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Condylomata acuminata are highly contagious and are primarily transmitted through sexual contact, making them a classic sexually transmitted infection (STI).\nOption B (Incorrect): Psoriasis is a chronic autoimmune inflammatory skin condition, distinct in its etiology and pathogenesis from viral-induced warts.\nOption C (Incorrect): Chlamydia trachomatis is a bacterial infection causing urethritis, cervicitis, and lymphogranuloma venereum, not condylomata acuminata.\nOption E (Incorrect): Condylomata acuminata occur in both men and women, affecting any anogenital or oropharyngeal squamous epithelium exposed to the virus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Condylomata Acuminata | Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV) | Syphilis (Secondary) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | HPV (DNA virus) | HSV-1, HSV-2 (DNA virus) | Treponema pallidum (Spirochete) |\n| Lesion Type | Verrucous, exophytic papules/plaques | Painful vesicles, ulcers | Maculopapular rash, condyloma lata |\n| Transmission | Sexual contact | Sexual contact, direct contact | Sexual contact |\n| Treatment | Excision, cryotherapy, topical agents | Antivirals (acyclovir, valacyclovir) | Penicillin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Genital warts = HPV. Always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn gross inspection, condylomata acuminata appear as flesh-colored to brownish, soft, exophytic, cauliflower-like lesions, often multiple and clustered in anogenital regions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC 2021 Sexually Transmitted Infections Treatment Guidelines. These guidelines recommend various treatment modalities for external genital warts, including patient-applied and provider-administered therapies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are not sexually transmitted. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | are associated with psoriasis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | are caused by chlamydia infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | are caused by varieties of human papilloma virus. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | occur only in men. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) are caused by varieties of human papilloma virus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
