  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Beaded vas, craggy feel – TB epididymitis is real!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately identifies key clinical features of tuberculous epididymitis. This condition is a chronic granulomatous inflammation that presents with distinct palpable characteristics, crucial for diagnosis and differentiation from other scrotal pathologies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTuberculous epididymitis typically originates in the globus major (head of the epididymis), often due to hematogenous spread from a primary pulmonary focus. The chronic inflammatory process leads to fibrosis and granuloma formation, resulting in the characteristic firm and craggy texture upon palpation. Furthermore, the vas deferens, being part of the spermatic cord and susceptible to retrograde spread or direct extension, often becomes thickened and nodular, giving it a classic 'beaded' feel. These findings are pathognomonic for chronic inflammation, specifically tuberculosis, in the epididymis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Early involvement of the testis is uncommon. Tuberculous infection typically begins in the epididymis and may spread secondarily to the testis (epididymo-orchitis) in later stages, but the epididymis is the primary site of involvement.\nOption E (Incorrect): While theoretically possible, semen culture for tubercle bacilli is not a reliable or primary diagnostic method for genitourinary tuberculosis. Urine culture (specifically first-void morning urine) is far more sensitive and commonly used for diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Tuberculous Epididymitis | Acute Bacterial Epididymitis | Testicular Tumor |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Insidious, chronic | Acute, sudden, painful | Insidious, often painless |\n| Palpation | Firm, craggy, beaded vas | Tender, swollen, boggy | Firm, smooth, painless mass |\n| Location | Globus major, spreads | Diffuse, often unilateral | Testis itself |\n| Systemic | Constitutional symptoms possible | Fever, dysuria, urethral discharge | Usually none initially |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic, firm, craggy epididymis with a beaded vas points to TB.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, tuberculous epididymitis often appears as an enlarged, heterogeneous epididymis with hypoechoic areas, sometimes with calcifications or abscess formation. Intraoperatively, the epididymis would be indurated, nodular, and potentially adherent to surrounding structures, with caseous material if an abscess is present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Guidelines for the programmatic management of drug-resistant tuberculosis (2020) - Recommends standard anti-TB drug regimens for extrapulmonary TB, including genitourinary forms, based on drug susceptibility testing.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | involvement of the globus major. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | firm and craggy nature. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | a thickened ‘beaded’ vas. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | early involvement of the testis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | the semen yielding tubercle bacilli on culture. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) involvement of the globus major.\nfirm and craggy nature.\na thickened ‘beaded’ vas.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
