  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Seminoma: Lymphatic spread is its game, retroperitoneum its fame.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options (A, C, E) accurately reflect common presentations of testicular seminoma, encompassing both primary tumor symptoms and metastatic disease. An upper abdominal mass indicates retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy, while a left supraclavicular swelling points to distant lymphatic spread. A painful scrotal swelling, though less common than painless, can still be the initial presentation of the primary tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular seminomas typically spread via the lymphatic system, following the testicular vessels to the retroperitoneal lymph nodes, primarily around the renal hilum. From there, further lymphatic spread can occur to mediastinal and supraclavicular nodes, with Virchow's node (left supraclavicular) being a classic sign of advanced abdominal malignancy. While often painless, the primary tumor can cause discomfort or pain due to rapid growth, hemorrhage, or epididymitis, making a painful scrotal swelling a possible, albeit less common, initial presentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Hirsutism is associated with androgen-producing tumors, which are exceedingly rare in the testis and not characteristic of seminoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): While seminoma can metastasize to bone, these metastases are typically osteolytic (bone destruction), not osteosclerotic (bone formation). Osteosclerotic metastases are more characteristic of prostate cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Seminoma | Non-Seminoma Germ Cell Tumor (NSGCT) |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------ |\n| **Age** | 30s-40s | 20s-30s |\n| **Markers** | Elevated hCG (sometimes), normal AFP | Elevated AFP, hCG (often), LDH |\n| **Metastasis** | Lymphatic (retroperitoneal, supraclavicular) | Hematogenous (lung, liver, brain, bone) |\n| **Radiosensitivity**| Highly radiosensitive | Less radiosensitive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think retroperitoneal nodes and Virchow's for seminoma spread.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, a seminoma typically appears as a hypoechoic, homogeneous mass within the testis. CT imaging of the abdomen/pelvis and chest would reveal retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy (often bulky) and potentially mediastinal or supraclavicular lymph nodes, or lung metastases. Intraoperatively, after inguinal orchiectomy, the resected testis would show a firm, often lobulated, tan-white mass replacing testicular parenchyma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (2023). Recommends initial inguinal orchiectomy for diagnosis and staging, followed by imaging (CT chest/abdomen/pelvis) and tumor markers (AFP, hCG, LDH) for all patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | an upper abdominal mass. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | hirsutism. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | a left supraclavicular swelling. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | osteosclerotic metastases. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | a painful swelling in the scrotum. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) an upper abdominal mass.\na left supraclavicular swelling.\na painful swelling in the scrotum.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
