  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Testicular cancer: Don't delay orchiectomy, but always stage first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct actions to be taken when a clinical diagnosis of testicular neoplasm is made include a chest x-ray, orchiectomy (or exploration), and radiotherapy. This reflects the multi-modal approach to diagnosis, staging, and treatment of testicular cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular cancer management begins with definitive diagnosis and local control via high inguinal orchiectomy. Concurrently, systemic staging with a chest x-ray is critical to detect common lung metastases, which occur via lymphatic spread to retroperitoneal nodes and subsequent hematogenous dissemination. Radiotherapy serves as an important adjuvant treatment for specific histologies or stages, targeting residual disease or nodal basins to improve outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Dissection of inguinal lymph nodes is generally not indicated for primary testicular cancer, as lymphatic drainage is primarily to the retroperitoneal nodes, not the inguinal nodes, unless there is scrotal invasion or prior scrotal surgery.\nOption D (Incorrect): Vasectomy on the contralateral side has no therapeutic, diagnostic, or prophylactic role in the management of testicular neoplasm.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Step | Action | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Initial Diagnosis & Staging | Scrotal Ultrasound, Tumor Markers (AFP, hCG, LDH), Chest X-ray, CT Abdomen/Pelvis | Confirm mass, assess metastatic spread, baseline markers |\n| Primary Treatment | Radical Inguinal Orchiectomy | Definitive diagnosis (histology), local disease control, prevent tumor dissemination |\n| Adjuvant/Systemic Therapy | Chemotherapy, Radiotherapy, RPLND | Address micrometastases, treat residual disease, manage nodal spread based on stage and histology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Testicular cancer: Orchiectomy first, then stage, then treat.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a chest x-ray might reveal pulmonary nodules (cannonball metastases). Intraoperatively, a high inguinal orchiectomy involves ligating the spermatic cord at the internal ring to prevent tumor cell dissemination into the systemic circulation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (latest version) recommend radical inguinal orchiectomy for diagnosis and local control, followed by comprehensive staging including tumor markers, chest imaging, and abdominal/pelvic CT, to guide adjuvant therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | a chest x-ray. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | orchiectomy (or exploration). | ✅ Correct |\n| C | dissection of inguinal lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | vasectomy on the contralateral side. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | radiotherapy. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, E) a chest x-ray.\norchiectomy (or exploration).\nradiotherapy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 1001 MCQs**\n",
